<HEADLINE>
YOUTH SHOULD NOT BE SERVED BY SOARING SALARIES 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The issue of youth has arisen again in the NBA. David
Stern, the usually perceptive commissioner, wants to establish an
age limit. Billy Hunter, the usually perceptive head of the players
association, says no one is forcing the teams to draft the
youngsters.
</P>
<P>
   Why are these otherwise astute men unable or unwilling to deal
with the transparently obvious problem? It's about the money, guys.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to stop the influx of unprepared kids, all you have
to do is get back in the bargaining room and stop guaranteeing them
all that money. Go back and make rookies' salaries non-guaranteed.
Even better, scale the salaries back to the point at which a player
who stays in college for four years gets more money, while a high
schooler gets the minimum wage.
</P>
<P>
   Stern often likes to use other sports as examples to show the
NBA is no different, but in fact, he's dead wrong. It is very, very
different from tennis, baseball, golf, football, hockey, soccer,
you name it. In no other sport that I can think of, let alone any
other means of livelihood, are unproven and untried individuals
guaranteed three years of lavish money whether they can play or
not, whether they can contribute or not, whether they even belong
in the business or not.
</P>
<P>
   Setting an age limit is simplistic. All it means is that kids
will spend a couple of years in college and then come out and make
all that guaranteed money. Ignoring them, as Hunter would like the
NBA to do, is, of course, nonsense. There are underclassmen who can
play. We know that. Team A can't afford to be high and mighty when
teams B-Z are getting down and dirty.
</P>
<P>
   So take away the guarantees and see what happens. Here are a
couple of other suggestions:
</P>
<P>
   --Scale the salaries to reward staying in college to the point
at which only a senior would step into what is now the rookie
scale. High school players and college freshmen would come into the
league playing for the CBA rate. A sophomore would get slightly
more, a junior slightly more. In no instance should those salaries
be even close to the NBA minimum, and of course, all should be
non-guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
   --Why do all first-round picks have to be guaranteed three
years? If you're not going to attack the root of the problem, at
least attack the branches. Make picks 1-10 guaranteed for three
years, picks 11-20 guaranteed for two, and everyone else be on
their own. Why should Leon Smith, at No. 29, receive the same
guarantees as Elton Brand at No. 1? And why should Smith get three
years and No. 30 get nothing?
</P>
<P>
   --Establish a two-way contract, as in hockey, in which a player
earns one wage if he's on the team and another if he's in the CBA.
</P>
<P>
   None of these ideas will be instituted, of course, because they
involve removing money from players' pockets. We can just hear
Patrick Ewing saying the league wants to go back to the horse and
buggy. But by making it less attractive for a player to leave
school, you are doing a service to both the NBA and the NCAA.
Players stay in school and are at least more mature when they enter
the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   That should be a win-win for all involved.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here's a scary scenario, courtesy of Spurs coach Gregg Popovich:
he feels his team may, by the middle of next season, actually be
executing the way he wants it to. ``We're not there yet with the
likes of Utah,'' Popovich said. ``I think it'll take a while, maybe
half a season for us. But I think once we do get it where we want
it, we'll be pretty good.'' The Spurs have three free agents _
Jaren Jackson, Will Perdue, and Malik Rose. Popovich says he'd like
to be able to retain two, which sounds a lot like Perdue might be
working elsewhere next season . . . 76ers coach Larry Brown says he
considered making a deal to draft Smith, the aforementioned Chicago
high school star who threw a williwaw in Dallas last week when
asked to do extra laps. Brown said he talked to some buddies in
Chicago and was told Smith had done this sort of thing before,
including refusing to come out of games by sitting at half court.
Brown did say he thought coaching Smith would be a challenge. Asked
about the league going more athletic with the impending rule
changes, Brown said, ``It will help if the kid is athletic and can
play. I've seen a lot of athletes who can't play a lick.'' Brown
was asked about a more deliberate, unathletic team like Miami
surviving in this new world. ``Miami can win if they stay
healthy,'' he said. ``Those guys know how to play. So many of these
young kids are athletic, but have no idea how to play. (Vince)
Carter is an exception. (Paul) Pierce is an exception. You surround
Alonzo (Mourning) with healthy players, they're right there.
Athletes are fine, but I'd rather have guys who know how to play
the game.'' . . . Several coaches were on hand last week to watch
the Olympic team scrimmage. It wasn't a walkover, either. The
opponents were a frontline group of Orlando Magic players (Nick
Anderson, Bo Outlaw, Matt Harpring, Michael Doleac, Darrell
Armstrong) along with a dazzling walk-on named Jason Williams.
Still, new Orlando coach Doc Rivers had to laugh every time he saw
Brown bark out a play for the Yanks. ``Does it even matter?
Wherever you throw it, it's going to be to a great player. It's
going to work.'' Rivers said he was happy to see the US field a
strong team, recalling his memories of USA Basketball when
collegians literally carried the ball. ``We'd see these Yugoslav
players pull up to the hotel in their Mercedes and get out. They'd
have their wives with them and their kids, and they'd go right for
the pool. I'm 19, on per diem, and I'm thinking, `This is not
fair.' You know what? We beat 'em anyway. But I still didn't think
it was fair.'' . . . Jerry Sichting, former Celtic and current
Timberwolves assistant, thinks the Cavaliers got a good coach in
Randy Wittman. ``He can be tough on guys, but he's also very
positive,'' Sichting said. ``I think he's got a chance to be a real
good one.'' So, too, does Minnesota coach Flip Saunders. ``He's
been around a lot of coaches, both as a player and a coach. That's
always a benefit,'' Saunders said. ``It's a great situation for
him.'' With Wittman's hiring, all vacancies are now filled. Of the
five openings, three were filled by first-time head coaches
(Wittman, Rivers, Gar Heard in Washington). Another went to an
interim (Don Casey in New Jersey), and the last went to Big Chief
Triangle himself, Phil Jackson (Lakers).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So what to make of the Celtics and Ron Mercer? Are they
lowballing him, or does Mercer have an inflated opinion of himself?
We know Rick Pitino didn't hesitate to shell out more than $50
million for Travis Knight and Chris Mills. We know he didn't
hesitate to re-sign Walter McCarty for $8.4 million. When he
acquired Kenny Anderson, Pitino said one of the undeniable benefits
was that Anderson was locked in long-term. We know only recently,
Pitino said, ``I think, possibly, we can make (Mercer) a real good
offer that he'll be happy with.'' Not. If there is a budget crunch,
as Pitino insists, why should Mercer have to pay for all the
previous signings? ``I can tell you this. Ron is disgusted with the
way management has handled this,'' said Mercer's agent, Tevester
Scott. ``You can't punish him because of what you did before. What
they offered him is embarrassing. We're not even in the same state.
When he called me and told me what it was, we both fell out of our
chairs laughing.'' Well, whether the Celtics' offer amounts to
punishment or insult is, of course, relative. ``We're at the
beginning of the process here,'' said general manager Chris
Wallace. ``I'll leave it at that.'' But after Antoine Walker ($9
million) and Anderson ($6.68 million), the next highest salary
belongs to Vitaly Potapenko ($3.81 million). In other words, the
Celtics may have cap woes, but it's because of a lot of ``average''
salaries doled out to the likes of Greg Minor and Pervis Ellison
(both M.L. Carr signings), as well as Popeye Jones, McCarty and,
incredibly, Dwayne Schintzius. (Why Schintzius was given $2.8
million over two years should warrant a Spotlight Team
investigation. It's not like he had any leverage.) The Celtics can
pay Mercer whatever they want up to the $71 million limit that they
gladly and without hesitation gave Walker. ``Seventy-one million?
Well, that's not close,'' Scott said. ``Let's just say if $71
million is on one side of the mountain, we're not to the point
where we can even see it from the other side.'' . . . Steve Smith
is hoping this Olympic experience is better than his last trip with
USA Basketball. He was a rarely-used 11th man on the 1994 team,
averaging 3 points a game for the team that won the gold medal at
the World Championships in Canada. He's also seeing this summer's
experience as a chance to distance himself from what's going on
with his Atlanta Hawks. They already have traded Mookie Blaylock _
``It came as a surprise to me,'' Smith said _ and rumors abound
that Smith himself may be on the block. ``It's nice to be here and
away from all that,'' Smith said recently in Orlando, the site of
the qualifying team's practices. ``I'm not expecting to be traded,
but nothing would surprise me. This is a business. All I can say is
that we had a lot of injuries when the playoffs came, and to break
us up because of that? I don't approve of it. But I'm not the GM or
the president.'' Smith insists he was not hurt during the Knicks
series, although he looked anything but well. ``I was dead tired,''
he said. ``That's why I didn't play well. I had to go 48 minutes in
the last two Detroit (playoff) games, and then I had to check Allan
Houston and try to stay with Latrell Sprewell. It was fatigue.''
But what about that odious Atlanta offense? ``We lost all our
scorers, except me,'' he said. ``Alan (Henderson), LaPhonso
(Ellis), and Chris (Crawford) all got hurt. They were hurt. I was
tired. And New York played very smart.'' . . . An interesting name
has popped up on the Magic's summer league entry _ Monty Williams.
Had things broken differently, he might have an NBA championship
ring. He was on the Spurs last year but was waived prior to the
season because San Antonio needed perimeter shooters. ``He was a
hard, hard worker,'' Popovich said. ``There wasn't a place for him,
that's all.'' Williams landed briefly in Denver and was also cut by
the Nuggets. He relocated to Orlando and stayed there for the rest
of the season. Williams, of course, had a heart problem in college
while at Notre Dame that has been controlled . . . So, Tim Duncan,
what exactly have you been doing, besides playing for USA
Basketball, since winning the championship? ``Sleeping,'' he said.
``I'm just trying to get my body to recover. I haven't had that
much time to enjoy it. But it was definitely a great honor, and
it's great to see the whole city excited.'' . . . The Celtics open
their California Summer League schedule Sunday night in Long Beach
against Portland. An NBA team can have three roster players, and
participating for Boston will be Tony Battie, Pierce, and
Potapenko. Also on the roster are Eric Riley, Bruce Bowen, and
Marlon Garnett, all free agents, as well as rookies Wayne Turner,
Kevin Ollie, Kris Clack and four others, the most notable being CBA
MVP Adrian Griffin. The team will play eight games in nine days,
returning on the 19th.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
