</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-CUP-KEISSER-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANY HEROINES FOR U.S.
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA _ By the time America is finished enjoying the history
that was made at the Rose Bowl Saturday, savoring it the way a wine
connoisseur might a Merlot, a thousand different storylines will
extend well into the next century.
</P>
<P>
   But the one that stands out most happens to be the simplest of
them all. On the biggest day in the history of women's team sports
in America, the U.S. soccer team won the Women's World Cup because
it played like a team.
</P>
<P>
   America didn't win because Mia Hamm escalated her game to a
Jordan-esque level. It didn't win because goalkeeper Briana Scurry
stood on her head like Dominik Hasek.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. won because they played like the best teams do, with a
collective ego, not 11 disparate ones. There was no singular hero,
just many heroines. I can think of several local professional male
athletes that would benefit from a sermon on team play from these
ladies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The courage of this team ... They didn't allow themselves to
lose,'' said coach Tony DiCicco. ``They epitomized what America is
all about. It was a storybook ending for a team that has its place
in history.''
</P>
<P>
   There were heroines everywhere you looked.
</P>
<P>
   Most obviously, there was Brandi Chastain, the defender from San
Jose, who netted the fifth and final shootout kick that gave the
U.S. the win and ignited a cheer from 90,185 as loud as any ever
heard on New Year's Day.
</P>
<P>
   In a game against China in a tournament earlier this year,
Chastain missed a penalty kick in an eventual 2-1 loss. Maybe 1,000
people attended that game in Portugal. The interest and scope
Saturday was significantly greater.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to thank Tony for allowing me to take that kick, after
missing one in that loss to China,'' said Chastain. DiCicco said he
was under orders from CBS host and bandwagoner David Letterman to
let her take a shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being (the) fifth (shooter), there was a lot of pressure. But
I felt very calm. I didn't look at Gao (Hong, the Chinese
goalkeeper). She likes to stare you down and then smile. I didn't
let her.''
</P>
<P>
   And after her shot found net? ``I lost my mind.'' Chastain
doffed her shirt and tossed it into the air, and then was mobbed.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-five feet away, a separate mob was hugging goalkeeper
Scurry. The 28-year-old goalkeeper gave Chastain the opportunity to
win it by laying out to block China's third kick in the shootout,
by Liu Ying. Scurry played every shot the same way, aggressively
leaving the stripe toward the shooter and then committing right or
left.
</P>
<P>
   ``She hit it hard, but she didn't place it very well,'' said
Scurry, whose play in the semi against Brazil got the U.S. to the
finals. ``I knew if I could stop one, we'd win, because I was so
confident we'd make all of our shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``You go on instinct. I was aggressive because even if I had a
stop called back, it would be an advantage. (Goalkeepers aren't
supposed to leave the line until the shot is airborne.) I was
confident I could stop at least one.''
</P>
<P>
   Scurry and DiCicco hugged for the longest time after the game.
``I told her before the shootout that all she could be was a hero,
because there are no goats in shootouts.''
</P>
<P>
   There were heroines before the game reached the shootout. Nine
minutes into the first overtime, China sent a corner kick across
the goal mouth that found the head of Fan Yunije. Scurry had moved
out to contest the pass and Fan sent the ball whizzing past her
only to find Kristine Lilly on the goal line, who headed it right
back out.
</P>
<P>
   As far as Lilly is concerned, she only did what she was supposed
to do hug the post, move with the ball and defend the goal line
behind Scurry.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's my job,'' she said. ``I shifted as Briana moved, and
the ball came right at me. I really didn't think at all about what
I did. It happened so fast. All I could think of was running out to
cover another shot.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Kristine is always finding and creating new ways to win
games,'' said DiCicco. ``Scoring goals, making great crosses, clear
midfield, and today standing her line.
</P>
<P>
   China dominated that overtime, in large part because the
ultimate warrior on the U.S. team, Michelle Akers, had left the
field from exhaustion and a headache earned when she dove into a
retaining fence.
</P>
<P>
   Akers, the 33-year-old midfielder who is dogged by Chronic
Fatigue Syndrome, dominated China like a warlord. For all 90
minutes of regulation, the middle of the field was off limits to
China. She bottled up midfield so well that China stopped trying.
</P>
<P>
   Akers was so spent that she barely made it back to the field for
the medal ceremony, and skipped the postgame media sessions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very difficult playing without her,'' said captain
Carla Overbeck. ``They got their best chances in that first
overtime. She covers so much ground defensively. Our strategy was
to make China play in small spaces, and we did when Michelle was in
the game.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no way I could ever not give 100 percent knowing what
she goes through just to play,'' said defender Kate Sobrero.
</P>
<P>
   That essentially was the team's mentality for the balance of the
game. Physically and mentally tired, they were down to their last
minutes of World Cup soccer, and they were going to leave it on the
field.
</P>
<P>
   ``The team captains pulled us together,'' said Chastain. ``They
said our hearts are too big for our chests to get tired now. This
was the last 15 minutes of the World Cup. Why save anything?''
</P>
<P>
   ``You just tell your legs that they're not tired,'' said
Overbeck. ``Don't let the dream end here.''
</P>
<P>
   (ital) They (end ital) didn't. And as a result, the dream will
last forever.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
