<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-11 00:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5842 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-CUP-KRIKORIAN-COL     07-11 1132
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-CUP-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN--LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. HAS DAY IN THE SUN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA _ Amid an almost surrealistic pageantry of riveting
emotion, patriotic fervor and fierce athletic competitiveness, the
women soccer teams of the United States of America and the People's
Republic of China Saturday staged a compelling show of epic
grandeur at the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, there was no scoring in the 90 minutes of regulation and 30
minutes of overtime, and the outcome of this World Cup championship
match was decided in favor of the Americans because they happened
to make all five of their penalty kicks and China blew one.
</P>
<P>
   But so what?
</P>
<P>
   What distinguished this event and made it so memorable and
perhaps a watershed moment in women athletics considering the
estimated four or five billion people around the world who viewed
it on television was the passionate resilience and relentless
resourcefulness of the combatants.
</P>
<P>
   There still might be a few male spoilsports who sniff derisively
at women athletics, but even the most cynical type had to be
impressed by the competitive ferocity displayed by the participants
throughout the proceedings that unfolded in sweltering conditions.
</P>
<P>
   For a game to be decided in such an unseemly manner as a penalty
kick it's like baseball settling a tie with a home-run hitting
duel, or basketball turning to a free-throw shooting contest was
unfortunate in light of the heroics being dispensed by performers
on both sides throughout the grueling afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   They were like Ali and Frazier in that classic Thrilla in
Manila, bitter adversaries with unshakable wills who were resolved
to settle their differences to the final gasp of breath, or rather,
alas, final penalty kick.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know if this was a game for the ages because neither
side could penetrate the other with a goal, but it certainly was
one that that boosted immeasurably the stature of women athletics.
</P>
<P>
   Never again can even your most enfeebled Male Chauvinistic Pig
sneer at the heart and courage and durability of female jocks
without being hooted into silence by those 90,185 fans in the
Arroyo Seco who saw both the American and Chinese players flash
these qualities in incredible abundance on a humid, draining
86-degree day.
</P>
<P>
   And when it counted most, when the Americans were called on to
attempt their dramatic kicks, when the pressure on this glamorous,
crazily-hyped, wildly-admired group had to be staggering, when they
were without their best penalty kicker, Michelle Akers, Carla
Overbeck, Joy Fawcett, Kristine Lilly, Mia Hamm and Brandi Chastain
coolly and calmly stepped up and fired every shot past China's
goalkeeper, Gao Hong, to the thunderous cheers of the
skimpily-attired audience.
</P>
<P>
   And when Akers went to the sidelines suffering from heat
exhaustion near the end of regulation time and when the Chinese
quickly took advantage of her absence and her midfield artistry in
the first overtime with several charges at the U.S. goal, the
Americans reacted by making one gallant defensive stand after
another including a game-saving header by Kristine Lilly.
</P>
<P>
   As evenly matched as these teams were and the differences
between them were imperceptible it's unfortunate that the outcome
would hinge on one penalty kick miss, even unfortunate that one
team left the Rose Bowl in a state of deep despondency.
</P>
<P>
   But in athletics, as in life itself, the maddening fickleness of
fate so often decides one's destiny and China's destiny was sealed
when Liu Ying's ill-starred penalty kick was flagged down in the
net by Briana Scurry.
</P>
<P>
   If Scurry didn't make her diving stop, this story might not have
made those early Saturday night deadlines because these teams might
have debated the issue well into the late evening.
</P>
<P>
   And, if Eddie Futch didn't throw in the towel for Joe Frazier
against Muhammad Ali, who knows what would have happened had the
two unyielding men resumed hostilities in the 15th round?
</P>
<P>
   ``We were starting to run out of gas in the first overtime,''
said Tony DiCicco, the American coach. ``We'd lost Michelle Akers,
and I think we were a little fatigued. But we came back in the
second overtime, and then we made all our penalty kicks. We never
quit and never gave an inch and were able to overcome adversity. I
think what we did out there epitomized what being an American is
all about.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the same can be said about the doughty Chinese ladies
one must be reminded that, after all, it was only one misguided
penalty kick that separated these teams but DiCicco can be excused
for such jingoism in the flushed heat of victory.
</P>
<P>
   There were distinct political overtones not so far beneath the
surface in this match, considering the tragic incident that
happened on May 8 when the U.S. mistakenly bombed the Chinese
embassy in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   The two nations have had strained relations since, but that
didn't keep this country's sterling commander and chief of the
armed forces, President Bill Clinton, from taking in the
festivities.
</P>
<P>
   The fact he was 30 minutes late, kept several thousand fuming
fans from reaching their seats in time for the start of the game,
and tied up the pressbox elevators for an hour was quite irrelevant
since the legendary victor over Yugoslavia was able to make it for
his three-minute halftime interview on ABC with Robin Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   And the smiling Prez also made it into the dressing room
afterward of both teams, offering his heartfelt congratulations to
the Americans and his heartfelt sympathies to the Chinese in a
stirring display of his fabled triangulations.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton wasn't the only big name on the premises. Natch, Jack
Nicholson was present, and I almost bumped into Big Daddy himself,
Adam Sandler, before the game near the FIFA headquarters outside
the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   It seems as though everyone who's anyone is now warmly embracing
these American gals, who have created quite a stir across the
country with their extraordinary skills, toughness and elan.
</P>
<P>
   And the fact that they didn't fail in their greatest challenge,
and performed nobly against a Chinese team that was their mirror
image will only enhance their burgeoning popularity.
</P>
<P>
   After Brandi Chastain made the penalty kick that assured the
Americans of a place in this nation's athletic pantheon, she and
her teammates hugged and slapped hands and waved to the crowd and
took a victory lap around the old stadium.
</P>
<P>
   It was a poignant scene, and the fans, notorious in these parts
for their hasty exits, remained in their seats for at least 20
minutes, savoring the triumph of a U.S. team that unlike so many of
its tiresomely boorish athletic contemporaries is a magical joy to
watch.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
