<SLUG> BC-SOC-CUP-SIDE2-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAMM MAKES QUIET CONTRIBUTION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM BARRERO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA _ America's most famous soccer player couldn't have
been more overjoyed that the latest chapter to her career ended
perfectly, even though she didn't do much of the writing.
</P>
<P>
   For three weeks, Mia Hamm, Team USA's ubiquitous star, reminded
anyone who would listen that this tournament was about her team and
her sport.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't about her icon status or commercials with Michael
Jordan or her ebullience, which places a smile on the face of
corporate America and sends millions of girls shrieking every time
they see her.
</P>
<P>
   True to her word, Hamm relished her team's World Cup victory
over China on Saturday _ a (begin ital)team(end ital) victory that
took 120 grueling minutes to achieve _ and she never once hinted it
mattered that her contributions won't be found in a box score.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just pure elation right now,'' said Hamm, who looked
fatigued. ``It's just so emotional.''
</P>
<P>
   Those emotions nearly overwhelmed Hamm when she was asked what
it meant to have her husband, Christian Corry, in attendance.
Corry, a Marine Corps pilot, was granted a temporary leave from his
post in Japan to attend the match.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's sacrificed so much. . . . We've both sacrificed a lot,''
Hamm said as tears welled in her eyes. ``It means so much to me to
have him here.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, when Hamm walked into the media tent, she
inconspicuously snaked her way through the crowd to an interview
chair, noticing that two of the game's heroes _ goalkeeper Briana
Scurry and defender Brandi Chastain _ had started their one-on-one
sessions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We love you Brandi, We love you Bri,'' Hamm yelled, sounding
every bit like the girls who shout her name with such voracity.
</P>
<P>
   After sitting down, Hamm joked with reporters that it was a good
thing a chair had been provided.
</P>
<P>
   ``It I had to stand,'' Hamm lamented, ``I'd probably collapse.''
</P>
<P>
   And with good reason.
</P>
<P>
   Hamm played every minute and scored a penalty kick, but she
couldn't believe it when assistant coach Lauren Gregg submitted her
name as one of the five penalty-kick takers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not very good at penalty kicks, so I asked Lauren if maybe
Mac (Shannon MacMillan) should take it,'' Hamm said. ``But she said
it was too late to change the order.''
</P>
<P>
   Gregg said her decision was simple.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just have the utmost confidence in Mia,'' Gregg said.
</P>
<P>
   During regulation, Hamm's runs down both sides of the field
generated a number of chances for the U.S. But for the fourth
consecutive game, she did not score _ leading some to wonder what
was wrong with America's soccer darling.
</P>
<P>
   But Gregg would have none of that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mia clearly was one of our most consistent players this whole
tournament,'' Gregg said. ``What people don't realize is when she
runs, the defense goes with her. . . . She's had an incredible
impact.''
</P>
<P>
   And Gregg said Hamm's impact works both ways, although most
probably don't notice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her defensive mentality is a cornerstone of our team
defense,'' said Gregg, referring to the numerous times Hamm helped
thwart China's attacks. ``It makes the job of the rest of the
team's defense so much easier. In my opinion, this was probably her
most consistent world event ever.''
</P>
<P>
   Consistency, teamwork and a championship. Hamm couldn't ask for
anything better.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
