<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WCUP-GAMER-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. WINS WOMEN'S WORLD CUP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM THOMAS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ The Rock was just a little stronger than The
Wall.
</P>
<P>
   In a match worthy of all the hoopla surrounding the finest
women's sporting event ever staged, U.S. goalkeeper Briana ``The
Rock'' Scurry made the decisive save that catapulted the Americans
to the 1999 Women's World Cup championship Saturday at the Rose
Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Scurry's diving stop on China's third penalty kick of the
shootout allowed the U.S. team to finally find a crack in the
Chinese goaltending. The Americans made all of their shots against
an otherwise brilliant goalkeeper, Gao Hong, who deservedly owns
the nickname ``The Great Wall of China.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. defender Brandi Chastain coolly placed the final shot past
Gao for a 5-4 shootout win after a scoreless 120 minutes. Chastain
then stripped off her jersey in celebration before a record crowd
of 90,185.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a team of courage,'' U.S. Coach Tony DiCicco said
before heading to the wild locker room. ``They fought and fought
through so many things to win this tournament, not the least of
which was an outstanding China team. I'm very, very proud.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. won its second of the three World Cups, avenging a loss
to Norway in the semifinals of the 1995 Cup and a defeat to China
in last spring's Algarve Cup.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first Women's World Cup to be decided by a shootout.
While many will argue that is not the best way to determine the
international champion, players on both sides were spent after 90
minutes of regulation and two 15-minute extra periods on a warm
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   That left the outcome on the shoulders of the two goalkeepers
and the five shooters from each team. Scurry, who had been
outstanding throughout the tournament, was the difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told her that all she could be in a shootout is a hero,
nothing else,'' DiCicco said. ``Bri was the hero.''
</P>
<P>
   Scurry said she had a feeling when China's Liu Ying stepped up
to take the third shot that she was going to make the save. The
27-year-old native of Dayton, Minn., dived to her left to knock
aside the attempt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just had a feeling I was going to get that one,'' Scurry
said. ``I don't know how or why.
</P>
<P>
   ``I read it well and she hit it hard, but I was able to get
there. I went totally on instinct. I knew that I just had to make
one save, because our kickers would do it for us.''
</P>
<P>
   The first two U.S. shooters were the team's ``Soccer Moms,''
Carla Overbeck and Joy Fawcett. Each buried kicks past Gao, as did,
in turn, Kristine Lilly, Mia Hamm and Chastain.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was momentary insanity,'' Chastain said of her post-kick
celebration. ``That's all it was.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a fitting end to a game in which both teams bared all.
The match had almost everything _ great defense, strong midfield
play, end-to-end action and drama. Everything, except goals.
Neither side was able to find a weakness or take control
offensively. China had 12 shots, three on goal, while the U.S. had
11, five on goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both teams had great performances,'' China Coach Ma Yuanan
said. ``The American team was more fortunate than us.''
</P>
<P>
   While the goalkeepers were nearly flawless, the U.S. was
fortunate to get its biggest save of the match from a forward _
Lilly.
</P>
<P>
   In the 100th minute, China took a corner kick that forced Scurry
slightly out of position. Fan Yunjie knocked a header to Scurry's
left, only to find Lilly standing on the line, nearly in the net.
She rejected the shot with a header to turn away China's best
opportunity to end the affair.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kristine Lilly is one of the best players in the world,''
DiCicco said. ``She always seems to find and invent ways to win
games, and this was just another way.''
</P>
<P>
   Chastain said Lilly ``did her job, nothing more and nothing
less.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was right where she was suppose to be, when she was
suppose to be. She made a huge contribution to the team right
there.''
</P>
<P>
   The save came just when China was starting to gain momentum, in
part because of the absence of star U.S. midfielder Michelle Akers.
During a Chinese corner kick just before the end of regulation,
Akers was knocked in the head by Scurry and left the match because
of what was described as heat exhaustion and a slight concussion.
Akers, who suffers from chronic fatigue syndrome, was not expected
to need hospitalization.
</P>
<P>
   DiCicco said Akers' willingness to sacrifice herself for the
victory epitomized the U.S. team's performance throughout the
three-week tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``What it came down to was these players not allowing themselves
to lose,'' DiCicco said. ``It was a storybook ending for a team
that has a place in history.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
