r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-DBACKS-ATHLETICS-     07-11 0612
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-DBACKS-ATHLETICS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG UNIT'S EFFORT FOR NAUGHT AS DIAMONDBACKS BATS SILENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD OBERT  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Again and again and again, it keeps happening. Randy
Johnson takes the mound for the Diamondbacks and gets no offensive
support.
</P>
<P>
   When will it end? When will the zeroes go away? When will the
left-hander get a win, let alone a run?
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks continued their futility at the plate with
Johnson pitching Saturday, and lost to the Oakland Athletics, 2-0,
before 36,042 fans at Bank One Ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's weird,'' catcher Damian Miller said. ``There's no
explanation for it, really. He goes out and busts his butt and we
run into a buzz saw every time.''
</P>
<P>
   This time, it was another rookie right-hander, Tim Hudson, who
had only six previous major league starts to his credit, before
giving up just three hits and striking out nine in 8 innings. It
was his longest big-league outing.
</P>
<P>
   Billy Taylor got the last two outs for his 22nd save that lifted
Oakland to .500 (43-43). The combined pitching effort matched the
best the A's have had all season.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks (47-41) fell 3{ games behind the San Francisco
Giants in the National League West.
</P>
<P>
   Zero, one, two and two. Those are the number of hits the
Diamondbacks have provided Johnson in his last four starts. St.
Louis rookie Jose Jimenez no-hit and two-hit the Diamondbacks in
two of those starts.
</P>
<P>
   The All-Star lost for the fifth straight time, while lowering
his league-leading ERA to 2.95 and collecting his 13th double-digit
strikeout game this season. He whiffed 11 A's, giving him a
league-best 211, before leaving after seven innings. He gave up
three hits, including a homer to Tim Raines to start the game _ the
same man who gave Johnson the nickname ``Big Unit'' when they were
teammates on the Montreal Expos.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you want me to say?'' Johnson said. ``I've been
pitching as good as I can. I know the guys are trying as hard as
they can. We're just going up against some pitchers who are
throwing some goose eggs up there.''
</P>
<P>
   This is getting rather redundant, though. In the last 34 innings
Johnson has pitched, the Diamondbacks have failed to score. In his
last four starts, Johnson has struck out 54, given up 19 hits and
allowed five earned runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It be hard pressed for anybody to have four games in a row to
pitch that well and come on the bad end of it four times,''
reliever Dan Plesac said. ``It's baffling.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson has never had a streak this bizarre and baffling before.
</P>
<P>
   Third baseman Matt Williams can't explain it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't speak for everybody,'' said Williams, who is 0 for 8
in this series against the A's. ``I was swinging at bad pitches and
you're not going to hit if you do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Hudson had the Diamondbacks grounding out and popping up with a
90 mile per hour forkball and an array of off-speed pitches.
</P>
<P>
   After left fielder Luis Gonzalez blooped a double in the first
inning, the Diamondbacks failed to get a base runner to second base
the rest of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Hudson, who has been outstanding (5-1, 2.09 ERA) since being
called up from the minors in early June, said he wasn't in awe of
the pitching matchup and the FOX regional television coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not pitching against Randy Johnson,'' Hudson said. ``I'm
pitching against their hitting.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson didn't start the game sharp. The first pitch Johnson
threw, Raines ripped an estimated 364 feet just into the left-field
seats for a 1-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't believe we got a run that early,'' Hudson said.
``Any time you get a lead in the first inn
</P>
</TEXT>
