<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-MANTEI-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ICEMAN COMETH, AND NONE TOO SOON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By AL TOBY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - When relief pitcher Matt Mantei walked into the
Diamondbacks' locker room for the first time, he got a lonely and
chilly reception.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was nobody in here,'' Mantei said in the air-conditioned
locker room after the Diamondbacks' 2-0 loss on Saturday afternoon.
``They were all outside playing the game. I got in a little late
today and we ``got'' a little miscommunication on my flight out
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Diamondback players and fans hope that's one of the only miscues
Mantei will have this season.
</P>
<P>
   In hopes of bolstering their fragile bullpen, the Diamondbacks
traded relief pitcher VladimirNunez, minor leaguer Brad Penny and a
player to be named no later than Oct. 15 for Mantei. The
Diamondbacks bullpen is clearly a weakness for the team. This
season, the bullpen has blown 14 of 29 save opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   The newly acquired Diamondback will earn $735,000 this year.
Mantei will be eligible for salary arbitration at the end of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   Diamondbacks managing general partner Jerry Colangelo said that
minor league prospects Nick Bierbrod and John Patterson aren't
candidates for the player to be named later.
</P>
<P>
   After arriving late at the park following flights from Miami and
Las Vegas, Mantei met his new teammates on the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody greeted me nicely in the dugout and I clicked pretty
well down in the bullpen,'' Mantei said.
</P>
<P>
   Mantei, a native of Tampa, said even though he's excited about
jumping into a division race, his thoughts still linger in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Mantei's trade came on Matt Mantei Pin Night at Pro Player
Stadium. Mantei said before he left the park, he grabbed about 50
pins as a going-away memento.
</P>
<P>
   ``I miss Florida,'' Mantei said. ``I've been there for five
years and it was a great organization and they took care of me and
were patient with me. I felt like I owed them something.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did me a favor getting me out of there. (General Manager
Dave) Dombrowski said I should be somewhere I'm going to pitch more
and get some more innings, so they sent me here.''
</P>
<P>
   This season, Mantei has converted 10 of 12 saves for the
Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   Mantei, 26, is a right-hander who throws in the mid to high 90s.
He was 1-2 with a 2.72 ERA and 50 strikeouts in 36 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Mantei's only flaw is a history of health problems early in his
career. The most serious was a thickness in his rotator-cuff, which
had to be scoped in August 1996. Mantei sat out the entire 1997
season so he could rehab his shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Pitching coach Mark Connor gave the trade a thumbs up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody know this kid has got great stuff,'' Connor said.
``He's an up-and-coming guy. We traded two young pitchers, one of
whom is in the big leagues now, for another young pitcher who has
had success in the big leagues on a regular basis. We feel good
about the trade.''
</P>
<P>
   Connor described Mantei as a classic closing pitcher with a good
curveball and even better fastball.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing about having a guy with the velocity he throws with
is you don't necessarily have to have pinpoint control,'' Connor
said. ``If you're going to make a mistake the hitter isn't going to
hit it because of the velocity on the pitch. They don't have time
to react.''
</P>
<P>
   The only request Mantei made of the Diamondbacks was to play
``Ice,'' ``Ice, Baby'' over the PA system when he's introduced in a
game.
</P>
<P>
   Mantei was given the nickname ``Iceman'' by former Marlins
pitcher and current New York Met Al Leiter because of his likeness
to the former rapper.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, barring the baseball scar on his upper lip, Mantei does
bear a resemblance to Vanilla Ice.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, he did own ``To the Extreme'' when he was in high school.
</P>
<P>
   No, he doesn't have any of the musician's albums today.
</P>
<P>
   With youthful eagerness, Mantei said he's itching to get on the
mound after a four-day rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to go out there and have fun like I've always had
and just enjoy myself and get the job done and not change a
thing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm anxious to get the first one out of the way, that's the
hardest thing to get out of the way.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
