r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-ROSE-GONZALEZ-AZR     07-11 0605
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ROSE-GONZALEZ-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GONZALEZ TEAMS UP WITH BOYHOOD HERO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By AL TOBY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - When outfielder Luis Gonzalez is offered pancakes for
breakfast by a waiter or waitress, it usually isn't a big deal.
</P>
<P>
   Getting offered pancakes by baseball legend Pete Rose is
something totally different.
</P>
<P>
   ``Luis, want some pancakes?'' Rose casually asked while standing
in a small breakfast line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Uh, no thanks,'' Gonzalez said with a childish smirk.
</P>
<P>
   After breakfast Gonzalez and his boyhood hero spent Saturday
morning at a sports card show at the North Phoenix Baptist Church.
The two signed autographs for fans and waxed about the state of the
sport they love.
</P>
<P>
   ``I watched him play throughout almost his whole career,''
Gonzalez said. ``He was my favorite player growing up in Tampa. The
'75 Big Red Machine was my all-time favorite team.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was Charlie Hustle, always diving for everything. That's
the guy I always looked up to.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez first met Rose more than 20 years ago in Tampa, where
the Reds held spring training. At the training camp Rose signed a
picture for the young Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a big thrill for me to meet him out there as a kid,''
Gonzalez said.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez wasn't the first in his family to formally meet Rose.
His younger brother and other Little League baseball players shot a
soup commercial with Rose in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got a couple of chuckles from the pictures,'' Gonzalez
said.
</P>
<P>
   Rose, baseball's all-time hits leader with 4,256, said he
doesn't have to give Gonzalez any hitting tips.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy's batting .360,'' Rose said. ``I couldn't hit that
high. He's got the right tools. He just works hard, is on time and
uses the whole field.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Too many guys go up there wanting to be home-run hitters and
always pull the ball. You got to use the whole field.''
</P>
<P>
   Rose said the change from the lowly Detroit Tigers to the
successful Diamondbacks has been a big factor in Gonzalez's
hitting.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing to do when you're a baseball player is have fun,''
Rose said. ``And it's fun when you're winning. That's 30-40 points
in your batting average, I think, as opposed to playing as an
individual. It was no fun for him playing in Detroit.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez is clearly having fun with the Diamondbacks. His .362
batting average is third-best in the National League.
</P>
<P>
   This year Gonzalez chased after Rose's National League record
44-game hitting streak. Gonzalez's streak ended at 30 games.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Gonzalez will play in his first All-Star game,
joining teammates Randy Johnson, Matt Williams and Jay Bell.
</P>
<P>
   Rose said he was happy to see Gonzalez selected as a reserve,
but wished that Texas Rangers outfielder Juan Gonzalez wouldn't
have opted out of the midsummer classic.
</P>
<P>
   The Ranger outfielder said he wouldn't play in the game unless
he was named a starter for the American League outfield. Thanks in
part to Cleveland fans' ballot box-stuffing approach, Indian
outfielders Kenny Lofton and Manny Ramirez will start. Seattle
Mariner Ken Griffey Jr. will join the two Indians for the American
League's starting outfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't agree with (Juan) Gonzalez,'' Rose said. ``He's a
great player and has had a couple of great MVP years, but he
shouldn't get offended because people out of Texas don't know who
the hell he is.''
</P>
<P>
   Rose, who played in a time where the players had a say in the
All-Star roster, said the current system is the best way to have an
All-Star Game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the fans' game,'' Rose said. ``It's a popularity game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
