<SLUG> BC-BKL-MERCURY-SPARKS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MERCURY MUST STOP SLIDE IN LA  
 PLAYOFF HOPES RIDE ON SPARKING A TURNAROUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ In the midst of last year's extended losing
streak, now a Mercury annual tradition, Michelle Griffiths vowed
damage control before the string equaled a franchise high of six.
</P>
<P>
   And Griffiths was one of five players in double figures when
Phoenix blew out Washington, 88-59, to stop the 1998 bleeding at
five and begin a climb to the WNBA Finals.
</P>
<P>
   The situation is increasingly dire today as five straight
defeats place the Mercury at 3-9, last in the Western Conference,
with only one valid path to meaningful recovery. Beat the Los
Angeles Sparks (9-5) here today and twice more in the next 10 days
to remain near the third and final West playoff berth.
</P>
<P>
   Narrow losses to LA (67-61) and West leader Houston (71-70) this
week prove Phoenix finally is playing well enough to beat a quality
opponent. But nothing shy of wins _ the franchise record being a
modest four in a row _ will have any effect in turning around a
season without back-to-back Ws.
</P>
<P>
   Griffiths, in the final trimester of her pregnancy, can have no
say in today's streak-busting try. But those who will include
6-foot-8 Maria Stepanova, who has quietly made an impact in three
consecutive games (combined 16 points, 13 rebounds, 5 blocks) and
is edging toward a primetime role.
</P>
<P>
   The idea with 7.3 seconds left against Houston Friday was for
Lisa Harrison to lob inbounds to Stepanova, coming off a Michele
Timms screen, hoping at minimum for a foul and a chance from the
free-throw line to upend the Comets. That play never developed, and
Phoenix's final shot was a missed baseline jumper by Jennifer
Gillom.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to have 11 people play hard for 40 minutes,''
Mercury Coach Cheryl Miller said. ``Whether that's bringing your
offensive game, your defensive game, whatever you can contribute
that night, you have to make sure you bring. Before you step on the
floor, you have to already predecide what you're going to bring to
this team and do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Against the Sparks on Wednesday, the Mercury struck gold with a
three-guard perimeter from the pool of Timms, Bridget Pettis, Edna
Campbell and Kristi Harrower. But that lineup saw little time vs.
Houston as Harrison started at small forward and played a
season-high 31 minutes to defend against Sheryl Swoopes.
</P>
<P>
   If 6-3 Gillom and 6-5 Marlies Askamp or Stepanova again are
effective today against 6-5 Lisa Leslie and 6-1 DeLisha Milton
(combined 15 points Wednesday), the Mercury could revert to small
ball to energize its transition game.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix shot 51.6 percent in the second half of the LA game
after a 25.8 percent first half, then was at 38.5 percent vs.
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks' franchise-high six-game win streak came to an end
Friday with a 77-72 loss to surging Sacramento (10-4), winner of
five of its last six.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to find a starting lineup that can jump-start us,''
LA Coach Orlando Woolridge said.
</P>
<P>
   That could mean Ukari Figgs, due back from a sprained ankle
after the All-Star Game on Wednesday, in guard tandem with
Yugoslavian Gordana Grubin rather than Penny Toler and Tamecka
Dixon.
</P>
<P>
   Today, though, the Mercury must account for 6-3 forward
La'Keshia Frett, who backed her 13-point outburst in Phoenix with
15 against Sacramento. Mismatches that put Frett or 5-11 Mwadi
Mabika against 5-7 Timms and 5-4 Harrower helped the Sparks on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Because Washington escaped double overtime with its fourth win
Saturday, only the 1998 East champion Cleveland Rockers have a
worse record than the Mercury. Rockers Coach Linda Hill-MacDonald,
at risk of losing her job after guiding the East in the All-Star
Game, has the excuse of 6-5 center Isabelle Fijalkowski not
returning to the league.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
