<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-11 00:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5856 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKO-WHA-REUNION-AZR &LR;      07-11 2121
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKO-WHA-REUNION-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GONE BUT NOT FORGOTTEN  
 IMPACT LINGERS LONG AFTER DEMISE OF UPSTART LEAGUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By CRAIG MORGAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   They were revolutionaries battling oppression _ pioneers in a
sport where little had changed in 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   Like ghosts of a bygone era, they will gather today in Windsor,
Ontario, to mark the 26 years since the World Hockey Association
completed its inaugural season.
</P>
<P>
   Gone are the banana-curved sticks, the candy-striped referee
shirts and the blue and red pucks.
</P>
<P>
   Gone are all but four of the 18 franchises that dotted the WHA
map.
</P>
<P>
   Gone into retirement are the owners, coaches and all but one
player. And gone are the hopes of establishing a true rival to the
National Hockey League's dominance.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, while the WHA never seriously challenged the NHL's hockey
supremacy _ expiring after seven seasons _ the upstart league left
a permanent mark on the sport and changed the course of
professional hockey irreversibly.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to competition for players, the WHA succeeded in driving
up salaries while pioneering rule changes and introducing hockey to
markets the NHL never dreamed of entering.
</P>
<P>
   It also extended the playing careers of a pair of hockey legends
while allowing up-and-comers such as Wayne Gretzky, Mark Messier,
Mike Gartner and Robbie Ftorek to take their first baby steps
toward superstardom.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't a fluke league,'' said hockey great Gordie Howe, who
played six seasons in the WHA with Houston and New England after a
Hall of Fame career with the Detroit Red Wings.
</P>
<P>
   ``They kept marketing it by saying, `It's not the NHL but it's
almost as good,' but I still feel the team we had in Houston could
have moved into the NHL and been in the top five.
</P>
<P>
   ``The WHA had some great players and some great teams. If we
just had a little more money behind us, we might have been able to
maintain it.'' &QL; 
Laughter, yawns &QL; 
The year was 1971. The Vietnam War was driving a philosophical
wedge through the heart of the nation. Ex-Beatle John Lennon had
just launched his solo career with the release of ``Imagine'' and a
young New York native named Julius Erving was getting ready to
reshape basketball and hairstyles in his first year in the ABA.
</P>
<P>
   The WHA's 12-team launch barely registered on the North American
consciousness. And when it did, it drew two prevailing reactions _
laughter and yawns.
</P>
<P>
   Not even the WHA's chief rival, the NHL, paid much heed. The
NHL's most storied franchise, the Montreal Canadiens, had just won
the Stanley Cup and the league had the world's premier players in
Bobby Hull, Howe and Bobby Orr.
</P>
<P>
   Given hockey's largely Canadian roots and the sport's regional
confinement in the U.S., launching a rival league in mostly
American markets seemed a curious venture. But equally vexing to
league founders Dennis Murphy and Gary Davidson was the utter
disdain with which their idea was greeted in Canada.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember I got on a plane and went up there to try and sell
the idea and I got the hell beaten out of me,'' said Murphy, who
also served a stint as general manager of the ABA's Miami
Floridians. ``The Canadians took the attitude `Why do we need you
to talk to us about hockey? What do you know about hockey?'
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Gary Davidson right then and there that I didn't think
our chances were very good.''
</P>
<P>
   But the NHL had one key chink in its armor _ the reserve clause,
which allowed teams to renew a player's contract upon termination
without the player's permission.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before the WHA, the NHL was like a monopoly and the players
were basically stuck with that arrangement,'' said Gartner, a
former Phoenix Coyote, whose professional career started in 1978
with the WHA's Cincinnati Stingers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no free agency like today. There wasn't much player
movement and owners basically paid us what they wanted. The WHA
finally gave us some leverage.''
</P>
<P>
   With the debut of the WHA there were 250 player spots to be
filled and the WHA needed star attractions if it hoped to survive
in a lukewarm hockey market. The league filled many of the spots
with marginal NHL players and career minor leaguers, while also
culling the untapped American college ranks.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the WHA drew rancorous laughter from its older
counterpart when it selected many of the NHL's top players at the
first draft in 1972. Since most NHL contracts were no longer than
two years, the WHA reasoned it would have an opportunity to talk to
players in the near future. But the NHL brass, headed by President
Clarence Campbell, questioned why anyone would want to join a
league with no history.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NHL was very arrogant toward us and I dare say we never
would have gotten started had it not been for the leadership they
had under Clarence Campbell,'' Murphy said. ``It was simple. They
never imagined they were vulnerable.''
</P>
<P>
   That all changed when Toronto Maple Leafs goaltender Bernie
Parent, a future Hall of Famer, signed a contract with the Miami
Screaming Eagles in February of 1972. Under intense pressure from
NHL owners not to give in to higher salary demands, Toronto made no
attempt to re-sign Parent.
</P>
<P>
   The ``coup de grace'' came four months later when Winnipeg Jets
owner Ben Hatskin wooed Hull away from the Chicago Blackhawks with
a $1 million signing bonus and a 10-year, $2.5 million contract,
making him the highest paid hockey player in the world.
</P>
<P>
   With one of its all-time greats in the fold, the NHL could no
longer ignore the WHA. Moreover, Hull's signing emboldened other
players to jump ship. Boston star goaltender Gerry Cheevers signed
with Calgary, Montreal defenseman J.C. Tremblay signed with Quebec
and Boston's Derek Sanderson signed with Philadelphia for $2.65
million.
</P>
<P>
   Mixed bag &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At the start of the inaugural 1972-73 season, the WHA had enough
marquee players to attract substantial interest.
</P>
<P>
   The first season was a mixed bag. Eleven of the 12 teams
remained in playoff contention for most of the season and, despite
a Blackhawks-imposed injunction that kept him out of the league for
15 games, Hull did not disappoint, scoring 51 goals and 103 points
in just 63 games.
</P>
<P>
   The season also saw the emergence of young stars like
Philadelphia's Andre Lacroix (league-best 124 points) and Danny
Lawson (league-high 61 goals).
</P>
<P>
   The New England Whalers won the AVCO Cup as league champion in
the first season, defeating the Jets, 4-1, in the best of seven
championship series.
</P>
<P>
   But throughout the year the league struggled financially. Two
teams averaged close to 7,000 fans per game but the league average
was just 5,298.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Raiders played to tiny crowds at Madison Square
Garden, while the Chicago Cougars changed owners like underwear and
spent a season at tiny Randhurst Shopping Center in an arena that
seated about 2,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember having a ticket drive to sell season tickets in
Cincinnati and Pete Rose came and bought four tickets,'' said Tampa
Bay Lightning Coach Jacques Demers, who coached three seasons in
the WHA with Indianapolis, Cincinnati and Quebec. ``We were hoping
he'd buy 4,000.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for the Stingers, attendance problems were part of
a growing trend. While Canadian franchises like Edmonton, Winnipeg
and Quebec saw increases in attendance, the American franchises
were constantly folding or changing cities due to lack of interest
and revenue to pay their high-priced players.
</P>
<P>
   After the league topped out at 14 teams in the 1974-75 season,
Chicago, Minnesota and Denver disbanded the following year with
Toronto, San Diego, Calgary and Phoenix soon to follow.
</P>
<P>
   In its final season, 1978-79, the WHA sported just six teams
with the Indianapolis Racers closing up shop early in the year.
</P>
<P>
   Thugs, pioneers &QL; 
Thuggery was a serious concern in the WHA with many of the marginal
players hanging on based on their ability to mix it up. The
Minnesota Fighting Saints lived up to their name with a memorable
brawl against Chicago and Calgary and Quebec squared off in a 1976
melee that required police officers to subdue it.
</P>
<P>
   But the league was also busy pioneering a free-wheeling, passing
and skating-based game that was a stark contrast to the NHL's
classic dump and chase. Nobody exhibited that style better than the
Coyotes' predecessors, the Winnipeg Jets.
</P>
<P>
   After a pair of disappointing seasons Winnipeg's ownership
realized it needed players to complement Hull's brilliance. Few
inroads had been made in the European market before the Jets dove
headlong into the continent and produced Swedish star forwards
Anders Hedberg, Ulf Nilsson and defenseman Lars-Erik Sjoberg.
</P>
<P>
   Paired with Hull on the Jets top line, the Swedes worked magic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did a few line rushes with him, and Ulf and I just looked
at each other,'' said Hedberg, who was first wooed to Winnipeg by
team physician Jerry Wilson. ``You could just feel it would work.
Somehow we already knew where each other was going to be. We said,
`This is too good to be true.' But we were scared to talk to Bobby
about it because he was such a big star.
</P>
<P>
   ``A couple days later Bobby called Jerry Wilson and said, `It
can't be true. Three guys can't work that well together.' ''.
</P>
<P>
   They did. That season Hull broke Phil Esposito's NHL goal record
of 76 with 77 goals in 78 games while adding 65 assists. Hedberg
had 53 goals and 47 assists and Nilsson had 26 goals and 94
assists. Winnipeg would go on to win two AVCO Cups with the group
and three in all.
</P>
<P>
   The WHA continued raiding Europe for players. Hartford signed
Swedish defensive siblings Christer and Thommie Abrahamsson and
Toronto inked Czech's Vaclav Nedomansky and Richard Farda.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like this whole new world we had never seen before and
we ended up putting a lot of great players on the map,'' Demers
said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the unique style of play and the increasing number of
marquee names, financial problems continued to plague the league
until talk of a merger with the NHL finally surfaced in 1977.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until 1979, with the retirement of Campbell and the
obvious draw of Gretzky, that the NHL finally approved the deal
thanks to the efforts of former Roadrunners President and General
Manager Bill McFarland.
</P>
<P>
   ``(New NHL President) John Ziegler and I were classmates and
good friends at the University of Michigan,'' McFarland said.
``(Union chief) Alan Eagleson fought the merger all along, but by
that time he was pretty much on his own.''
</P>
<P>
   With all the hurdles removed, four WHA teams joined the NHL in
time for the 1979-80 season: Winnipeg, Quebec, Hartford and
Gretzky's Edmonton Oilers, who were consistently the WHA's top draw
with an average of 11,255 fans their final season.
</P>
<P>
   The only two franchises to play out the 1978-79 season and not
be absorbed into the NHL were the Birmingham Bulls and the
Cincinnati Stingers.
</P>
<P>
   The merger brought Gretzky to national audiences and was marked
by the return of Howe and Hull, who played on the oldest line in
league history with Dave Keon for one season in Hartford.
</P>
<P>
   Through shrewd drafts and the presence of Gretzky and Messier,
Edmonton won five Stanley Cups in the 1980s and established itself
as one of the great hockey dynasties.
</P>
<P>
   The other WHA franchises weren't so lucky, however. Facing
increased costs, Quebec moved from the tiny Le Colisee to Colorado,
where it became the Avalanche and won the Stanley Cup in 1995-1996.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a widespread effort by fans and local businessmen,
Winnipeg moved to Phoenix one year later and Hartford became the
Carolina Hurricanes for the 1997-98 season.
</P>
<P>
   The WHA has all but vanished from the face of professional
hockey with just one former player still active - Vancouver's Mark
Messier. Twenty years removed from its last game, however, the
WHA's legacy remains.
</P>
<P>
   WHA rules like overtime periods to decide ties have since been
adopted by the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   The WHA's success in cultivating European talent led the NHL to
finally abandon its Canadian-centric ways, evident in this year's
amateur draft, where the top four players were European.
</P>
<P>
   But the WHA's most lasting contribution to the game was its
effect on player salaries and freedom of movement. By signing Hull
to a then unheard of sum, Winnipeg and the league gave players a
bargaining chip that has since been parlayed into
multimillion-dollar contracts by today's players.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stan Mikita said it best,'' said Howe, citing the Chicago
Blackhawks Hall of Famer. ``He said, `Gordie, every morning in
Chicago when I wake up I get down on my hands and knees, cross my
hands together, look up and say, Thank you, Bobby Hull. Thank you,
Bobby Hull.' '' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
