<HEADER>
A5857 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-WHA-PHOENIX-AZR &LR;      07-11 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-WHA-PHOENIX-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROADRUNNERS GAVE UP A YEAR TOO EARLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By CRAIG MORGAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's June in Phoenix. Valley fans stream into America West Arena
hoping their hockey team can pull out a Game 7 win and finally
advance to the Stanley Cup finals.
</P>
<P>
   The opponent is the dreaded Edmonton Oilers, a team that has
haunted the Roadrunners since the old World Hockey Association
days. But the word on the street is Coach Robbie Ftorek has the
lads ready to play.
</P>
<P>
   Confused? Not if you could see inside Bill McFarland's
imagination.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think people realize how close the Roadrunners came to
being an NHL club,'' said Phoenix's former president and general
manager. ``If (owner) Karl Eller had just stuck with it another
year they probably would have been part of the merger into the NHL.
If that had happened, we might not be talking about the Phoenix
Coyotes today.''
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix was originally part of a 1972 agreement between the NHL
and the Western Hockey League. With the NHL exploring expansion,
McFarland secured a contract with NHL President Clarence Campbell
that would have placed NHL franchises in each of the WHL's cities.
</P>
<P>
   But the NHL dragged its feet on a timeline and a few of the
cities joined the WHA instead, nullifying the deal that same year.
</P>
<P>
   After capturing the Patrick Cup as WHL champs in the league's
final two years, the Roadrunners also jumped to the WHA.
</P>
<P>
   The move proved tougher than anticipated. Phoenix lost an
estimated $2 million annually before Eller finally pulled the plug
in 1977. Huge player salaries and average crowds of just 7,296 were
the main culprits.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did well in our first two years on the ice, but the ticket
prices stayed the same and the WHL wasn't the WHA,'' McFarland
said. ``The average salary in the WHL was about $15,000 while the
average WHA player was making between $35,000 and $50,000 with a
bunch of $100,000 guys.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew we couldn't increase the ticket prices significantly
and keep our fan base so, we just didn't have a way to make it
happen. Karl did the only thing he could do.''
</P>
<P>
   The franchise still left a glut of memories in its three-year
tenure in the WHA. In their first season, 1974-75, the Roadrunners
became the first WHA franchise to make the playoffs. Sandy Hucul
earned Coach of the Year honors that same year and Robbie Ftorek
won the MVP award in 1976-77 and is still the only Phoenix hockey
player to have his number retired from a major professional league.
</P>
<P>
   Not bad for a guy who wanted nothing to do with the WHA when he
was in the Detroit Red Wings farm system.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in Cleveland for a game and I had some time to kill, so
I decided to check out a Cleveland Crusaders-Edmonton Oilers
game,'' Ftorek recalled. ``There was nobody there, the game wasn't
very good and here comes Cleveland with these ugly purple and black
and white uniforms and Edmonton has even uglier blue and orange
ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking at this saying `What am I watching? I'm never
playing here.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Money and opportunity changed Ftorek's mind. Despite a torrid
start to the 1973 season, Detroit sent him down to the minors in
Virginia Beach for the remainder of the year. That's when McFarland
came calling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill made it pretty simple for me,'' Ftorek said. ``He said,
`I only have one thing to say to you. You can either play for the
Red Wings and ride a bus or play for the Roadrunners and fly.' ''
</P>
<P>
   McFarland flew Ftorek and his wife out for a summer stay at the
Biltmore and the pair fell in love with the Valley. A few months
later, the feeling was reciprocated.
</P>
<P>
   In 53 games, Ftorek pumped in 31 goals and added 37 assists as
the fledgling Roadrunners went on a late-season tear to qualify for
the AVCO Cup playoffs with a 39-31-8 record.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had rabid fans and the largest booster club of any sport,''
recalled Al McLeod, who played for the team from 1974 to 1977.
``When we made the playoffs that first year it was a pretty amazing
atmosphere.''
</P>
<P>
   The feeling was fleeting. Quebec defeated the Roadrunners in
five games in the first round. But Ftorek was still on his way to
becoming a full-fledged superstar.
</P>
<P>
   In 1975-76, he had 41 goals and 72 assists to finish fourth in
the league in scoring. Again, Phoenix fell in the first round of
the playoffs, this time to the San Diego Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   With little scoring punch left after a season of defections,
Ftorek shouldered the load in Phoenix's final campaign, notching 46
goals and 71 assists while earning the MVP award by one vote over
Winnipeg's Anders Hedberg.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing I remember most about Robbie is what a great
competitor he was,'' said defenseman Jim Niekamp, the Roadrunners'
all-time WHA leader in games played. ``We were good friends because
we had common ground, both of us being American in a sport where
there weren't many Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   After two seasons of playoff hockey, Phoenix fell to 28-48-4 in
1976-77 and the team ceased operations. Ftorek moved on to
Cincinnati and the rest of the players dispersed throughout the
league.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, Edmonton, Hartford, Winnipeg and Quebec joined
the NHL as did Ftorek, who played out his career with the Nordiques
and the New York Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just glad the WHA was born and I had a chance to play in
it,'' said Ftorek, now the coach of the New Jersey Devils. ``I have
a lot of ties and good friendships in Phoenix and the fans were
always great to me. My heart will always be there.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
