<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKO-WHA-HOWE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOWE GOT CHANCE TO PLAY WITH SONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By CRAIG MORGAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   One year after signing NHL great Bobby Hull, the WHA recorded
another victory.
</P>
<P>
   The fledgling league lured legendary Gordie Howe out of
retirement and into a Houston Aeros jersey.
</P>
<P>
   The Hall of Famer had left the Detroit Red Wings after the 1971
season because of a nagging wrist injury, but he never felt
comfortable in retirement.
</P>
<P>
   With sons Marty and Mark languishing in the minor leagues,
unable to play in the NHL due to a minimum age requirement of 20
years, Gordie's wife, Colleen, pressed the WHA on its own age
policy. League brass had none at the time and, after quick
discussions, realized it had another means of attacking the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   With all of Canada's junior leagues now open for sale, the WHA
continually undermined the NHL by signing top young talent like
Wayne Gretzky, Mark Messier and Ken Linseman, before they came of
NHL age.
</P>
<P>
   Aeros Coach Bill Dineen did his part by drafting Marty and Mark
Howe, and at age 45, Gordie soon joined them in Houston with a
jersey that read ``GORIDE HOWE.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Not too many Texans knew who Gordie Howe was,'' Howe said with
a chuckle.
</P>
<P>
   That didn't last long.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started the first game of the season together and when I
stepped on the ice with my boys it was like fulfilling a lifelong
dream,'' said Howe, who was named league MVP in his first season
with 100 points. ``I remember the first shift somebody took a run
at me and he went away with six to eight stitches. The next shift
another guy took a run at me and he went away with six to eight
stitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came to the bench and Marty said, `Dad, what the heck are
you doing?' I told him, `I'm just trying to set an example, son.''
</P>
<P>
   Howe did that by playing six seasons in the WHA, scoring 174
goals and adding 334 assists. In 1980, after one more season in the
NHL, he finally retired at the age of 52. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-11-99 0043EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
