<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-DAVIS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOODBRIDGE OUT OF DAVIS CUP 
</HEADLINE>
 CUP-WOODBRIDGE-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ When the Australian Davis Cup team meets the
United States in this weekend's quarterfinal tie, Todd Woodbridge
will not be among them.
</P>
<P>
   Australian captain John Newcombe said Saturday that Woodbridge,
who along with doubles partner Mark Woodforde has won five
Wimbledon doubles titles, was ``not coming'' to the meet but did
not elaborate further.
</P>
<P>
   Australian public relations official Lysette Shaw said that
Woodbridge is injured, but she also did not elaborate further. She
said that a news release will be issued Sunday night (to allow for
Australian time) that will both detail the extent of Woodbridge's
injury and announce which player here will replace him in doubles.
</P>
<P>
   Woodbridge's absence means the Aussie roster consists of Patrick
Rafter, Mark Woodforde, Lleyton Hewitt, Sandon Stolle and Andrew
Illie. The latter is a 23-year-old alternate who went from being
ranked 473 to 59 last year.
</P>
<P>
   Rafter arrived Saturday afternoon and took part in the second of
the team's two practice sessions Saturday. Woodforde was scheduled
to arrive late Saturday &UR;  &LR; night.
</P>
<P>
   The US-Australia meet, the 100th in Davis Cup history, will be
held Friday through Sunday here at Longwood Cricket Club. It will
mark the 45th meeting between the teams, which have played in more
Davis Cups than any other nations.
</P>
<P>
   The United States team is set to arrive Sunday. The US holds a
14-8 record against Australia in matches played in this country.
The last time the Americans lost to Australia in a Davis Cup match
here was 1973, when a team led by Newcombe and Rod Laver triumphed,
5-0, in the finals in Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   Hence, the importance of Woodbridge, 28, and Woodforde, 33, who
have teamed up to form one of tennis's most visible and successful
doubles teams. Widely known as the Woodies, they have captured a
record five Wimbledon titles (1993-97).
</P>
<P>
   With 51 doubles titles (including nine Grand Slam events) in the
Open Era (since 1968), they are the third- winningest doubles team
of all time, second to Peter Fleming/John McEnroe and Bob
Hewitt/Fred McMillan, who have won 57 doubles titles each.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the tandem won five titles in 10 finals and reached
the finals at Wimbledon for the sixth consecutive year. In 1996,
they captured 12 titles in 13 finals and took the gold medal at the
Atlanta Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   The Woodies began playing as doubles partners in Davis Cup
competition in 1993. They have a 13-2 mark in Davis Cup doubles
play and have not lost a match since 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Of the five current Davis Cup players, Woodforde is the only one
who played on the 1993 Davis Cup team which lost to Germany in the
final.
</P>
<P>
   Woodbridge's absence marks the second setback in a week for
Australia, a once-dominant Davis Cup team which hopes to capture
its first title since 1986, when it defeated Sweden, 3-2, in the
final.
</P>
<P>
   Hewitt, the 18-year-old rising star who vaulted from being
ranked 722d in the world in 1997 to 113th in 1998, was named to the
team last week after Mark Philippoussis suffered a knee injury at
Wimbledon while leading in a match against eventual champ Pete
Sampras.
</P>
<P>
   With the recent changes, Australia will likely be much different
that the team that defeated Zimbabwe, 4-1, in the Davis Cup first
round in early April.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the setbacks, Newcombe is confident about the team he
has brought to Longwood. He added that a win by Hewitt at the Davis
Cup would spell a significant victory for the future of Australian
tennis.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great opportunity for him,'' said Newcombe, ``and I
think it puts a lot of pressure on the American players, because
they won't want to lose to an 18-year-old rookie in their own
hometown.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they lost to Philippoussis, it would be, 'Well, he's pretty
good,' but this is an untested player.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
