<SLUG> BC-SOC-BURN-WIZARDS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BURN FLURRY SCALDS WIZARDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BLANE BACHELOR 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Fans who arrived late and left early at last night's
Burn game against the Kansas City Wizards might as well have not
come at all.
</P>
<P>
   The Burn opened its scoring eight minutes into the game and
didn't find the net again until there were 10 minutes left to play.
In the final 10 minutes, four players scored to complete a 5-0 rout
against the Wizards at the Cotton Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   The Burn's margin of victory was the largest in team history.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed that,'' Burn defender Eric Dade said. ``I know \Rthe
Wizards\S probably have a different outlook, but we needed that for
our confidence. Goals do a lot for a team, and we got some other
people in on the scoring. You can say all you want about having a
good defense, but if you don't score goals you're not going to win
the game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Burn (10-9) took an early lead on an eighth-minute score
from forward Jason Kreis off a combined assist from Leonel Alvarez
and Jorge Rodriguez. As the Burn remained scoreless, the Wizards
stayed within striking distance for the next 72 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City (4-13) had its best chance of the first half on a
hard shot from Chris Brown to the far post. Burn goalkeeper Matt
Jordan, who was selected as an All-Star reserve last week, made a
diving save to preserve the Burn's 1-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   But the Wizards couldn't maintain that kind of effort throughout
the second half, mainly due to a red-card ejection of defender Uche
Okafor in the 53rd minute. Burn forward Oscar Pareja streaked
through an open midfield and pushed the ball past Okafor, who
brought Pareja down hard.
</P>
<P>
   The one-player deficit seemed to infuse the Wizards with an
immediate burst of energy, getting four solid scoring chances in
the minutes after the ejection, but that was their last dangerous
push of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to get off to a fast start, but we gave away a bad
goal, and our confidence went wobbling again,'' Wizards coach Bob
Gansler said. ``After the ejection, there were too many obstacles
to overcome, not the least was that we played hurried and
scurried.''
</P>
<P>
   The Burn, however, regrouped from there, making the most of its
one-player advantage with crisp passing and accurate crosses. The
late-game scoring onslaught started in the 80th minute, with a
well-orchestrated assist effort from Alvarez and Kreis to Chad
Deering for the goal.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie forward Paul Broome followed with his first MLS goal in
the 84th minute and combined with Kreis to assist Ted Eck five
minutes later. The Burn kept pushing until the very end, with Kreis
firing a free kick into the net with 10 seconds remaining.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
