<HEADLINE>
OLSON'S ROLE CHANGING BUT VIABLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD OBERT  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - With  &UR; Matt Mantei in as the Diamondbacks' new closer,
 &UR; Gregg Olson said he'd take on whatever role Manager  &UR; Buck Showalter
had for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not a whole lot I can do,'' said Olson, who has blown
six saves in 17 opportunities, a year after making good on 30 of 34
save opportunities. ``The team went out and solidified the bullpen.
It's been a sore spot to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Showalter said he still saw Olson as a viable part of the
bullpen. Olson likely will be used in a setup capacity.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the teams left standing at the end of the season are able
to pitch the seventh, eighth and ninth innings,'' Showalter said.
``I think Gregg cannot only help us pitch those innings but can
help us take some of the strain off of a guy like  &UR; (Darren)
Holmes.''
</P>
<P>
   Holmes, who has been on the disabled list for tightness in his
lower back, will pitch a two-inning simulated game today and a
one-inning simulated game Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   He is eligible to come off the DL after the All-Star break, but
Showalter said he'd have to wait and see how Holmes' back
responded.
</P>
<P>
   Showalter said what he did with 20-year-old right-hander
 &UR; Byung-Hyun
 &UR; Kim depended on Holmes' health. Showalter said he'd have to decide
whether to go with 11 or 12 pitchers after the break.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are two ways to look at it,'' Showalter said. ``You send
B.K. down there (to Triple-A Tucson) to start and get innings or we
can keep him here with 12 pitchers and not overextend him
physically by having him pitch back-to-back days.''
</P>
<P>
   Olson said he would take his move in the pen in stride and hope
for the best.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still the same pitcher I was last year,'' he said. ``You
go through these periods in your life when bounces don't bounce
your way and the proverbial blank happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he's taking the trade for a closer as a rejection,
Olson said, ``The whole year has been somewhat of a rejection. You
make the most out of what you've got.'' &QL; 
On the mound &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander  &UR; Todd Stottlemyre, rehabilitating a partially torn
rotator cuff and labrum, pitched off the mound for the second time
Saturday. Showalter said the workout had gone well.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the week, Stottlemyre said he had experienced no
stiffness in his shoulder the day after pitching from the mound. &QL; 
On the move &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pitcher  &UR; Bobby Chouinard, who has been called up to the
Diamondbacks from Tucson three times this season, said he was
always ready to move.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a MASH unit,'' he said. &QL; 
Welcome, Erik &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander  &UR; Erik Sabel had his contract purchased from
Triple-A Tucson on Friday, and outfielder  &UR; Dante Powell was sent
back south.
</P>
<P>
   Sabel, who has pitched in the past two games, is the first
Diamondbacks draftee to appear in a major league game. He was the
42nd round pick in 1996.  &UR; Nick Bierbrodt was called up a few weeks
ago, but he did not appear in a game. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
