<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-COLLINS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURVIVING COLUMBINE GIVES PLAYER PERSPECTIVE 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWPORT, R.I. _ Jake Cram was glad to be hanging out at the aged
tennis pen called the Casino Saturday afternoon. Young Jake Cram
was very glad to be anywhere Saturday. Location didn't matter.
</P>
<P>
   He could hear the chatter of gulls overhead, feel the sea breeze
riffling his sandy hair, touch the finely groomed grass court on
which he sat quietly, in a corner of the intimate timber stadium.
He was alive.
</P>
<P>
   That had seemed an unlikely prospect for Jake Cram of Littleton,
Colo., not quite three months ago _ a day when even reaching his
19th birthday sounded risky, a day he was indelibly scarred by a
massacre. But spared.
</P>
<P>
   The sounds that day inside Columbine High School were awful,
terrifying, murderous, threatening _ guns and bombs outside the
door where Jake and schoolmates, 60 of them, were sardined into a
tiny room ``praying, crying, but trying hard not to make a sound
that might be heard by Dylan and Eric.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday was supposed to be John McEnroe's day at the Casino,
where he was tapped for the International Tennis Hall of Fame. But
it was 18-year-old Jake Cram's day, too. McEnroe, the tennis
player, has heard thunderous applause throughout the world, and
received more during the induction ceremony. Cram, also a tennis
player, heard little applause from the few people watching
Columbine High matches. But he has heard the thunderous explosions
touched off by killers, a din that ``I may never get out of my
head. But things are better now.''
</P>
<P>
   Jake Cram, a trim 6-footer on his way to Notre Dame on a partial
tennis scholarship, was honored also, at noon on a side court,
receiving one of the annual Bill Talbert Junior Sportsmanship
citations. A pretty fair kid player, he finished third among
Colorado schoolboys last year and this, and is good enough to be
accepted in the US Junior Championships next month at Kalamazoo,
Mich.
</P>
<P>
   ``The `Zoo, I'm really looking forward to it.'' He is talking
before he and fellow Talbert winners (Rebecca Reynolds of El Paso,
David Martin of Tulsa, and Rick Phillipp of Fort Wayne, Ind.)
settled into an out-of-the-way niche behind the court to watch
McEnroe and an Australia luminary, Ken McGregor, accepted into the
Hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a while after the shooting I didn't look forward to
anything. I was completely out of it for three weeks, just going
through the motions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lost weight. I couldn't sleep, but when I could the
nightmares were terrible. I still have them, but not as many. A
hypnotist has helped me with my sleeping. Now I'm doing OK. This is
great, seeing McEnroe. I watched him on TV when I was a kid.'' Just
like everybody watched the kids at Columbine.
</P>
<P>
   ``April 21st?'' Jake reflects and his sea-blue eyes pinch with
pain. ``I drove to school, takes me about five minutes. Not a
special or different day. I was in the choir room when it happened.
No, I can't remember what we'd been singing, but we were getting
ready for a concert . . . that never happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``A kid came in the door shouting, `They're shooting!' We
thought it was a joke. But I saw the barrel of a shotgun. Somebody
slammed the door, and a teacher, Theresa Miller, told us to get
down, get into the office inside the room.
</P>
<P>
   ``Really a small office, maybe 10-by-15 feet. We were really
packed in,'' Jake scrunches his shoulders close together. ``Sixty
of us, mostly girls, for 3 1/2 hours.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was scary,'' Jake says. ``Dark, hard to breathe. We were
able to knock some holes in the ceiling to help a couple of kids
with asthma, help them breathe. We held them up to the holes, but
three girls fainted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three-and-a-half hours and we didn't know if we'd live or die.
The shooting went on. We were scared they'd bust in on us.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't know who was doing the shooting, but afterwards when
I found out it was Eric (Harris) and Dylan (Klebold), I couldn't
believe it. I couldn't have imagined it. When we were little kids I
spent a lot of time with Dylan. I still can't believe it.
</P>
<P>
   ``My best friend, Matt Cornwall, was in there with me. We tried
to comfort each other. It's funny. He's going to go to UC
(University of Colorado) Denver. He's gonna feel more comfortable
staying close to home with his family. I'm close to my family, but
I just want to get out of Littleton for a while.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the kids had a cell phone and we were talking to the
police. They told us the SWAT team would be coming in to get us.
But they didn't. We kept saying over and over, `Why don't they
come?' Three-and-a-half hours. I was angry that they waited so long
to try. I'm still angry. They could have saved Mr. (Dave) Sanders,
who died. We knew he was dying, and prayed they'd come.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finally the SWAT team came, and we ran out behind them . . .
through the bodies . . . the kids I knew. The bodies in the hall .
. . I'll never get those out of my mind. That was the worst.''
</P>
<P>
   Jake is glad to report that Pat Ireland is doing well. ``You
know, the kid who was shot in the head and fell out of the window.
He was paralyzed, but that passed. He's doing a lot better. My
friend, Seth Houy, was in the library. One of them pointed a gun in
his face, saying, `You want to die?' The gun jammed and Seth ran
out of there. Got away.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was lucky. All of us who got out are lucky. But I lost
friends. The funerals were tough. Then, TV coming to our
graduation. Weird. Yeah, I think I'm OK.'' He looks it, turned out
in sport jacket and tie. ``I had to buy clothes for this weekend. I
never,'' he is amused, ``never wore a tie before.'' He was not
sure, April 21, that he ever would.
</P>
<P>
   John and Kathy Cram, who accompanied their son to Newport, were
in the dark for a long time that day, too. Kathy says, ``Tennis
friends of Jake's from all over the country were watching TV and
phoning us, wanting to know if he was OK. Was he in the school?
Were we all right? They were very comforting in a hard time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Afterwards his tennis friends were very supportive. They got
him out playing again. He keeps hearing from kids he met at
tournaments.''
</P>
<P>
   Jake has been consulting a psychologist, Dr Renee Norcross, whom
he'd known before, and says, ``She's helped me. Before the shooting
she had helped athletes deal with pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   He grins. ``Pressure? This thing has given me a total change of
perspective. I was a good competitor, maybe not like McEnroe. But I
didn't like to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Jake Cram, obviously a good kid, will be playing next for
Notre Dame, glad to be here, there, anywhere, saying, ``I'll try
hard. But . . . if I lose . . . well . . . so?''
</P>
<P>
   He is smiling. ``A tennis match isn't life or death.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-11-99 0052EDT &QL; 
