<HEADLINE>
RODEO BULL SETS BOUNTY RECORD IN TEXAS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRETT HOFFMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MESQUITE, Texas _ With explosive jumps and wrecking-ball drops,
Mesquite Championship Rodeo bull Dodge Durango dumped his 41st
consecutive rider last night, denying Troy Jones of Killeen a
record $29,000 bounty.
</P>
<P>
   Jones stayed aboard the 1,900-pound high jumper for 2.4 seconds
at Mesquite Arena. The average stay on the bull has been 2.3
seconds since Dodge Durango debuted at the world's most renowned
weekly rodeo in April 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``\RDodge Durango is\S about to make a believer out of me,''
said Neal Gay, who has watched an abundance of high-profile bulls
perform at Mesquite since opening the Friday and Saturday night
rodeo in 1958. ``I've never bragged on him a lot because it takes
awhile to determine whether a bull is great. But we've proven that
by taking him all over.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the Mesquite Rodeo, Durango's appearances during
the past 15 months range from the Southwestern Exposition and
Livestock Show Rodeo in Fort Worth to the Professional Bull Riders
World Championships in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   ``He bucks strong overtime,'' Gay said. ``Everybody who gets on
him says that he is strong.''
</P>
<P>
   The bounty for staying on Durango rises $500 each time that the
bull bucks off a victim. When Durango makes his scheduled
appearance at Mesquite next weekend, the bounty is expected to be
$29,500.
</P>
<P>
   That is a record for the bounty bull program, sponsored by a
national automobile company at Professional Rodeo Cowboys
Association shows. The previous record for highest bounty was
$28,500. Cory Check of Eastman, Wis., earned the sum for staying on
Dodge Laramie II at Mesquite.
</P>
<P>
   The bounty program began in 1992 and the Mesquite Championship
Rodeo bull Dodge Dakota was its first big star; the bull went
undefeated for most of the season until Joe Wimberly of Cool made a
qualified ride and pocketed $17,000.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-11-99 0053EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990711.0022 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-11 00:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5871 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-REDSOX-BRAVES-BOS     07-11 0848
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX, WASDIN THROW ONE AWAY 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-BRAVES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The bunt never has been a weapon of choice for the Red
Sox.
</P>
<P>
   But as a means of self-destruction, seldom has it been more
effective than it was Saturday afternoon, when failure to execute
bunt plays in the 11th inning _ both on the offensive and defensive
sides _ cost the Red Sox dearly in a 2-1 loss to the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox had a chance to take the lead in the 11th when
Darren Lewis drew a leadoff walk. Red Sox manager Jimy Williams
flashed the bunt sign to third-base coach Wendell Kim, assuming
that Kim in turn would deliver the message to Damon Buford. But Kim
said he never saw the sign from Williams, and Buford swung away,
grounding into a double play.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in the bottom of the inning, after a leadoff walk to
Andruw Jones, Sox reliever John Wasdin fielded Brian Hunter's
two-strike bunt in front of the plate, wheeled and drilled Hunter
in the helmet with his throw, the ball caroming past first baseman
Mike Stanley down the right-field line as Jones circled home with
the winning run.
</P>
<P>
   An afternoon of exquisite pitching and minimum offense _ an
exchange of solo home runs by Mike Stanley (No. 13) and Andruw
Jones (No. 16) through the first 10 innings _ ended with Wasdin
lamenting the wasted effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a shame the game had to be lost in a fashion like that,''
said Wasdin, who now has been pinned with three straight losses
after winning seven decisions in a row, even though he'd dispatched
the middle of the Braves' order in the 10th on a strikeout and
double play. ``To be on the losing end three times in the last two
weeks is kind of frustrating.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an easy play. I can't explain it. It's a play you work on
day in and day out. I charged it hard, came up with it, but
couldn't make a good throw to the first baseman.''
</P>
<P>
   But as hard as it was for Wasdin to accept his breakdown, at
least a play was made, however hideous. Imagine how Williams felt
that Buford never received his instructions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I got screened when I gave the sign,'' Williams said.
``If anybody messed up that play, it was me. I must have been
screened off from Wendell. It's my fault that I wasn't in position
to be seen. In my mind, we were going to bunt.''
</P>
<P>
   In Kim's mind, Williams was blaming the wrong guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I messed it up, that's all I can say,'' Kim said. ``He gave
it. I didn't see it. I should have known. I'll take the blame, I
want to take the blame.''
</P>
<P>
   How do such things happen? Kim offered one hint when he said
that Williams ``kind of ducked down'' as he gave the sign, because
he didn't want Bobby Cox, the Braves manager whom Williams long
served as third base coach, to steal the sign. ``Coxie knows him
well,'' Kim said. ``And Jimy didn't know what cameras might be on
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Buford, standing at home plate, said it occurred to him that a
bunt might be in the offing. ``Think about it,'' he said. ``You got
(Rudy) Seanez on the hill, Stanley and (Troy) O'Leary coming up,
that gives you two legitimate chances to drive him home if he's on
second.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just one of those things you look back on in the course
of a game.''
</P>
<P>
   But Buford wasn't about to act independently. ``I just looked
for the sign, that's it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked down there, didn't see a sign, so I swung and tried
to hit it over the wall. It didn't work.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox' offense, which has produced just one run in its last 15
innings, was hardly firing on all cylinders against Billerica's Tom
Glavine, the lefthander who gave up Stanley's first-pitch home run
to open the second inning, but allowed just one more base runner to
advance as far as second base in his nine innings of work.
</P>
<P>
   It got no easier against the Braves' bullpen. Lefty John Rocker
struck out the side in the 10th, and Seanez dispatched Stanley on
another ground ball after Buford's double play in the 11th.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the Sox' offense, Stanley, who has homered four
times on this trip, grimaced and replied: ``Lack thereof would be a
better word for it. We haven't been able to muster a whole lot
against these guys.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves could do little against Sox starter Mark Portugal
(six innings, one run, six hits) and four Sox relievers, including
new papa Rich Garces, who got the last out of the eighth and left
two runners on base in the ninth, shortly after his wife, Lisabeth,
delivered their third child.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tommy didn't give us a lot to hit,'' Portugal said. ``You know
coming in you're not going to get much against these guys. He just
did it a little longer than I did. He came out on the top end
today. You can't worry about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox, with Nomar Garciaparra missing his eighth straight game
with a strained left groin, can still come home with a .500 record
on this 10-game trip. They're 4-5, with an appointment against Greg
Maddux, the four-time Cy Young Award winner, still to come.
</P>
<P>
   It's not the ideal sendoff to a vacation, however short.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-11-99 0054EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990711.0023 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-11 00:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5872 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     07-11 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAME GOAL-LESS BUT RIVETING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA _ President Clinton rose to leave the Rose Bowl in the
76th minute of a scoreless Women's World Cup final between the U.S.
and China on Saturday. You know how it is: When in Southern
California, do as the Southern Californians do. At that moment, it
didn't look good for the future of top-flight women's soccer in
this country. After all, if a standoff between world super powers
couldn't hold the attention of the First Fan for a 90 minutes, what
hope was there for hooking the masses?
</P>
<P>
   Just when the Secret Service had secured the exit, however,
President Clinton sat back down in his suite. The hope here is that
his action reflected the mood of his constituents. Because anybody
who saw the match through to its conclusion was rewarded with
glorious theater.
</P>
<P>
   It took two hours and 10 penalty kicks and when U.S. defender
Brandi Chastain delivered her final soliloquy, with her left foot,
the principal actors were all too pooped to take many curtain
calls.
</P>
<P>
   Two scoreless halves, followed by two scoreless 15-minute
overtime periods, isn't the way the U.S. players would have
scripted this final act. To be sure, the last thing they were
looking to do was re-create the drama of Harvey Haddix's 12-inning
perfect game of 40 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   They knew it was goals the record crowd of 90,185 had come to
see. No one had to tell them the average sports fan craves offense
only slightly less than his next beer or plate of nachos.
</P>
<P>
   And yet it's hard to imagine anybody panning Team USA's victory
via penalty kicks. It was riveting in the way no-hitters are, with
defensive plays saving the day.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Kristine Lilly covered her teammates' tushes as well as
any pitcher could cover home plate with a game riding on his tag.
In the 10th minute of the first overtime, Chinese defender Fan
Yunjie headed a ball at the U.S. goal and caught keeper Briana
Scurry in a vulnerable position.
</P>
<P>
   It looked like nothing was going to get between the ball and
China's trophy dance until Lilly materialized at the goal line and
headed the shot out of harm's way.
</P>
<P>
   To that point, the overtime period had been played mostly in
Team USA's end, but Lilly's save seemed to pump new oxygen into the
U.S. players' deflated lungs. They controlled the tempo the rest of
the way, then made each of their penalty kicks under the most
suffocating of circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   As confident as the Americans were in the penalty kicks, China's
goose egg was all but burned into the grass when their third
shooter, Liu Ying, sent the ball in the very direction Scurry was
leaning. Scurry batted down the ball. The next U.S. shooter, Lilly,
applied the screws by coolly converting her kick to put the
Americans ahead, 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. prevailed 5-4, and if that struck you as anticlimactic,
well, the victorious players could feel your bathos.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who knows what would have happened if we had kept playing?''
U.S. co-captain Carla Overbeck said. ``Winning and losing in
penalty kicks is not a fun thing. I don't think that's a good way
to end it. But we'll take it.''
</P>
<P>
   But of course.
</P>
<P>
   If soccer had the same set-up as the golf championship of this
country, the players would have returned today for at least 90 more
minutes of combat. If FIFA had taken its cue from the NHL, the
players would have played on and on and on until one of the goalies
cracked.
</P>
<P>
   Neither of those alternatives sounded particularly appealing to
reserve midfielder Tisha Venturini, who said, ``I don't think
anybody was up to playing any more. You don't understand how
exhausted the players were.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't just the 88-degree heat that sapped the players'
energy. For the past three weeks they have been tugged every which
way by an adoring public. The U.S. team has been so accommodating -
to reporters, autograph seekers and late-night talk show hosts
alike - it was only fitting that they would give the largest crowd
ever to view a women's sporting event more soccer than was
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder America has gone gaga over the confident, colloquial
crusaders for women's soccer. Happily, it has been anything but a
one-sided love affair.
</P>
<P>
   Even Mia Hamm, the reluctant object of so many people's
affection, let her guard down long enough to show her gratefulness.
She thanked a Korean journalist for sticking around after the North
Koreans were eliminated to report on the remaining matches.
</P>
<P>
   ``We appreciate that you continued to cover the tournament,''
Hamm said. ``It says a lot about how attitudes are changing.''
</P>
<P>
   The proof of President Clinton's change in heart is in the
negatives snapped in the U.S. locker room after the players'
champagne bath.
</P>
<P>
   ``I turned around and there he was,'' Venturini said, wide-eyed.
``He came in and gave a nice speech. He was hugging people. We took
some pictures.''
</P>
<P>
   Those are the photographs the players will hold dear. The
picture the rest of us will carry from the day is of 90,000
spectators staying around long enough to salute 20 very deserving
women. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
