<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-GOMEZ-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUTFIELDER'S TANTRUM OVER VOTING ILL-ADVISED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's often been the belief of Latin American ballplayers that
they must play and live to a different standard than their
U.S.-born counterparts. For much of the 1960s and '70s there was
probably some truth to those sentiments.
</P>
<P>
   But times have changed, and the Latin-born player has become an
accepted part of the landscape in the majors. Yet some continue to
draw back to the once-valid argument for answers when they feel
slighted by the American public.
</P>
<P>
   Case in point, Texas outfielder  &UR; Juan Gonzalez, who will not be
a part of the American League All-Star team after he declined
Manager
 &UR; Joe Torre's invitation to be a reserve. Gonzalez cannot understand
why he finished fifth among AL outfielders.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a shame,'' Torre said of Gonzalez. ``I think it is an
honor, and if not honored they should be obligated.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez, who is truly not a bad guy but did receive bad advice,
cited Cleveland's stuffing of the ballot box as one reason, yet
refused to look at  &UR; Ivan Rodriguez, a Rangers teammate who easily
outdistanced everyone at his position. All Gonzalez, a two-time
MVP, has to do is look in the mirror for his answers.
</P>
<P>
   This is a player who often scowls at the official scorer if a
call doesn't go his way. He also jogs on grounders and pouted
earlier this season when a ball hit the top of the fence, bounced
back into the playing field and was not ruled a home run, but was
instead called a double.
</P>
<P>
   If the balloting were truly slanted in Cleveland's favor, then
how did Seattle's Ken Griffey Jr. lead all players? Maybe if
Gonzalez had a little bit of charisma he wouldn't be viewed as a
sullen and petulant star.
</P>
<P>
   The voters, all fans, look into a player's heart, as well as his
talent, when making their choices for the All-Star Game. Gonzalez,
who has an entourage that often pulls him in different directions
and fills his head with misinformation, could have the baseball
world in the palm of his hand if he only tried.
</P>
<P>
   One look at Dominican-born  &UR; Sammy Sosa, the top vote-getter in
the National League, should be all Gonzalez needs to see for proof
of how much can come your way if you just let it flow. &QL; 
Trivial question &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Who are the two members of the Diamondbacks pitching staff to
have participated in a no-hit victory at the major league level? &QL; 
Serious finger-pointing &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If there's one thing that gets the ire of major league players,
it's when their manager outs them to the world. It's one thing for
a manager to be critical, but quite another for him to jam a sword
into his own players.
</P>
<P>
   Yet that's exactly what Baltimore Manager  &UR; Ray Miller has done
to his relievers. Granted, the Orioles bullpen has been among the
worst in the majors, but to single them out as the biggest reason
for this dysfunctional club's miseries is quite another matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be embarrassed to stand in front of the ball club if I
were a relief pitcher right now,'' Miller said this month. ``I'd be
embarrassed to walk through this clubhouse. . . . It's a crying
shame that you have a ball club busting their butts and doing
everything in the world, and you can't get one guy to shut the
door. I'm getting tired of watching guys pitch like they're scared
to death. We need someone to step up out there or we'll get a whole
new bunch of them.''
</P>
<P>
   It's no secret that Orioles relievers are fuming mad with
Miller. Veteran reliever  &UR; Arthur Rhodes was the most vocal of the
relievers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bullpen gets blamed for everything,'' Rhodes said. ``So
from now on, everything that happens, just blame it on the
bullpen.'' &QL; 
Jose can finally see &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay designated hitter  &UR; Jose Canseco, more on the ball than
he may ever lead on, had an accurate way to describe his career
after learning he had been selected to the All-Star Game after a
seven-year gap.
</P>
<P>
   ``When was the last time I made the All-Star team, 1942?''
Canseco said. ``I can't remember back that far.''
</P>
<P>
   His last appearance came in 1992. The seven years between
appearances is second only to the eight years  &UR; Paul Molitor and
 &UR; Steve
 &UR; Sax had between their All-Star appearances since the voting
returned to the fans in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've come full circle,'' Canseco said. ``As a baseball player,
no one has experienced as much as I've experienced. I was talked
about as being the best player in the world, hands down, by far, at
one point, being this freak that nobody understood. I stood 6-4,
250 pounds and was running 4.3, 4.4 40s. The first guy to do 40-40.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I was, more or less, an outcast in baseball, being
completely forgotten. The worst player. A total joke. Washed up.'' &QL; 
Oh, I wish I were an . . . &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's not unusual for starting players who land on the disabled
list to go batty trying to find ways to spend their time while
injured. Pittsburgh shortstop  &UR; Pat Meares, on the DL since May 12
after surgery to his left hand, is no exception, though he has
discovered some rather creative things to do.
</P>
<P>
   Meares served as the television analyst for a Pirates three-game
series in Detroit June 79. During Pittsburgh's last road trip, he
took his shirt off and took in some rays while tanning himself on
the upper deck at Veterans Stadium, while his teammates played
Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   A few days later, though, Meares topped it all by dressing as a
bratwurst and racing around the bases against an Italian Sausage
and a hot dog during the sausage race at Milwaukee's County
Stadium. He won, by the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just trying to stay sane and off the FBI's most wanted
list,'' Meares said. ``Who knows what I might do next, though. I'll
keep it a secret.''
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh Manager  &UR; Gene Lamont has found no problems with
Meares' escapades.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just trying to have some fun, and that's fine,'' Lamont
said. ``He had everyone going in Milwaukee with the sausage thing.
I hadn't seen that many guys in our dugout all season.'' &QL; 
Former D-Backs update &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Tony Batista, who was given first and second cracks at the
starting shortstop job in Arizona, seems to have finally caught
fire. Entering the weekend series, Batista had seven home runs and
21 RBIs in just 22 games with Toronto. Entering the weekend,
Batista was batting .286 for the Blue Jays.
</P>
<P>
   Reliever  &UR; John Frascatore, who along with Batista was sent to
Toronto in exchange for left-handed reliever  &UR; Dan Plesac (who has
done a wonderful job for the Diamondbacks), had a series to
remember against Baltimore. Frascatore was the winning pitcher in a
three-game series against the Orioles, tying a major league record
for consecutive victories by a reliever.
</P>
<P>
   Also, reliever  &UR; Amaury Telemaco, who was claimed off waivers by
Philadelphia earlier, has had a 1.54 ERA in 11 innings since
joining the Phillies. &QL; 
Trivial answer &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The obvious one is  &UR; Randy Johnson, who had a no-hitter against
the Detroit Tigers on June 2, 1990. It has been Johnson's only
no-hitter of his career.
</P>
<P>
   The other is a bit trickier. Reliever  &UR; Gregg Olson was one of
four Baltimore Orioles to combine on a 2-0 no-hitter in Oakland on
July 13, 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Olson pitched the final inning for the victory. Orioles pitcher
 &UR; Bob
 &UR; Milacki started the game and was removed after six innings because
he was making a spot start.  &UR; Mike Flanagan,  &UR; Mark Williamson and
Olson each pitched one inning to close out the game against  &UR; Eric
Show of the A's. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE HIT LIST &QL; 
 &UR; Oh yeah, this is one way to get him back: Mets Manager  &UR; Bobby
 &UR; Valentine, spun the knife another quarter-turn into  &UR; Bobby Bonilla
last week when he said Bonilla's been great, other than being
caught smoking a cigarette in a no-smoking section. It was an
embarrassing revelation, especially since it's doubtful Bonilla's
wife knows he smokes from time to time.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; He's declared his independence in a big way: Texas rookie  &UR; Jeff
Zimmerman, who may be the best setup pitcher in the game, was named
to the American League All-Star team, two years after he was
pitching in the independent Northern League.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Flashback: Phil Roof.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; And, oh, how the East Coast folks love to ride us
 &UR; about our 115-degree days: The temperature on the artificial turf
at Philadelphia's Veterans Stadium registered 161 degrees during
last Sunday's game between the Cubs and Phillies. ``It was
unexplainable, really. Just scorching, relentless heat,'' Phillies
center fielder
 &UR; Doug Glanville said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; New era?: For the first time since 1991, the Atlanta Braves
will not have a starting pitcher at the All-Star Game. &QL; 
EXTRA BASES &QL; 
With Cleveland's  &UR; Travis Fryman out for at least two months,
 &UR; Jim &UR; Thome has brushed the dust off his third baseman's glove and
is returning to his original position. After 2{ years at first
base, Thome volunteered for the move.
</P>
<P>
   Major league officials are quietly negotiating with St. Louis
and the New York Mets to open their 2000 season with two regular
season games in Tokyo. But main attraction  &UR; Mark McGwire doesn't
seem enthralled with the idea: ``I'm absolutely against it. . . .
The game belongs here.''
</P>
<P>
   The Detroit Tigers, one of the most storied clubs in all of
major league baseball, appear headed toward having the worst record
in the 1990s. Detroit was 668-811 through Friday. Minnesota is next
at 688-787.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out the Dodgers were fined $200,000 and banned from
signing any foreign players for six months after it was discovered
they illegally signed Cuban defectors  &UR; Juan Carlos Diaz and
 &UR; Josue Perez, each declared a free agent this month.
</P>
<P>
   Knuckleballer  &UR; Tom Candiotti, back with Cleveland, has replaced
struggling right-hander  &UR; Dwight Gooden in the Indians' rotation.
Gooden is now the mop-up man in Cleveland's bullpen. Of Gooden's
392 career appearances, 389 have been as a starter.
</P>
<P>
   The Orioles' bullpen blew its major league-leading 20th save
Wednesday night. The all-time record for one season was set last
season when St. Louis blew 31 saves. With a half season left to be
played, Baltimore appears to be priming itself for a run at the
record. &QL; 
THE RUMOR MILL &QL; 
Cincinnati has had serious conversations with the Yankees, who
don't seem put off by the idea of sending  &UR; Andy Pettitte to the
Reds. The problem is Cincinnati's unwillingness to part with left
fielder &UR; Greg Vaughn, whose departure would surely enrage shortstop
and captain
 &UR; Barry Larkin.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay closer  &UR; Roberto Hernandez, who has 24 saves, is
definitely available. But the Devil Rays had no interest in helping
expansion brother Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Reliever  &UR; Mel Rojas, who has had a terrible time since leaving
the Expos for the big bucks of free agency three years ago, has
apparently decided to hang it up for the season. Rojas, who was
sent to Montreal's Triple-A club July 2, has not reported and is
back at his Florida home.
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore catcher  &UR; Lenny Webster and Philadelphia catcher  &UR; Bobby
Estalella are both on the market. Pittsburgh, which suffered the
gruesome loss of  &UR; Jason Kendall last week, is interested in
acquiring one of them.
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh right fielder  &UR; Jose Guillen, whom the Diamondbacks
desperately tried to pry away from the Pirates during spring
training, is now on the open market and can be had for the right
price. Guillen was recently sent to Triple-A for the second time
this season.
</P>
<P>
   Orioles ownership, which, unfortunately, truly runs the show in
Baltimore, is mulling over the possibility of making several moves
over the next three weeks. On the agenda are trading
 &UR; Juan Guzman,  &UR; Scott Erickson, Webster and swapping Manager  &UR; Ray
Miller with  &UR; Eddie Murray.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado left fielder  &UR; Dante Bichette, who can veto any trade
now that he has played 10 years in the majors and the last five
with the Rockies, looks as if he is open to the idea of a deal. &QL; 
THE RANKINGS &QL; 
 &UR; TOP OF THE ORDER &QL; 
 &QL; 
1. ClevelandWith the title practically sewn up, what will the
second half bring?  &QL; 
2. NY YankeesThe confidence and swagger are back; it's time to wait
until October.  &QL; 
3. AtlantaThe Braves offense is severely missing injured
catcher &UR; Javier Lopez.  &QL; 
4. San FranciscoLooks as if they'll have to make a go at it without
 &UR; Barry Bonds again.  &QL; 
5. CincinnatiWhen  &UR; Ron Villone's going this good, anything can
happen.  &QL; 
6. HoustonIs there a better closer in the game right now than &UR; Billy
Wagner?  &QL; 
7. NY MetsWhy question anything that goes on with this club
anymore?  &QL; 
8. BostonSerious contenders do not lose games to Tampa Bay, not
with  &UR; Pedro Martinez.  &QL; 
9. PhiladelphiaIt's true. That is no mirage in the NL East
standings. &UR; BOTTOM OF THE ORDER &QL; 
 &QL; 
30. FloridaIf only they could face  &UR; Tom Glavine (5-10 vs. Florida)
all the time.  &QL; 
29. MinnesotaIntroducing the Twins All-Star . . .  &UR; Ron Coomer.
Honest.  &QL; 
28. BaltimorePicking up  &UR; Cal Ripken's 2000 option is the least of
this club's worries.  &QL; 
27. Montreal &UR; Brad Fullmer, sent down, reported but has refused to
play.  &QL; 
26. DetroitLots of talk about quitting going on. That's not going
to be good.  &QL; 
25. Tampa BayThe spunk is finally back now that the first-half
catastrophes are over.  &QL; 
24. Los AngelesClub was 13-26 through Friday since firing coaches
in May.  &QL; 
23. AnaheimHuge disappointment. Then again, they're not out of it
yet.  &QL; 
22. Kansas CityTeetering on the brink of mediocrity once again. ON
THE RISE &QL; 
 &UR; Toronto Blue Jays: A 5-1 homestand and a dramatic ninth-inning
victory over Baltimore Wednesday night have the Blue Jays believing
they can be destiny's darling in 1999. With Boston still not a
certainty to contend in the second half, why not Toronto? They have
solid starting pitching and an offense capable of scoring runs in
bunches. The Blue Jays aren't all the way there, but they're not a
bad club. &QL; 
GOING SOUTH &QL; 
 &UR; Chicago Cubs: When the Cubs last met the cross-town White Sox, they
were riding high, nine games over .500 and just one game behind
first place in the NL Central. A 6-20 span later, and the Cubs are
lucky not to be in last place. The pitching staff's ERA is near the
bottom in the league and prospects for improving don't seem on the
horizon. Over a span of 23 games, opponents had scored 205 runs.
That's an average of nearly nine runs per game. The Cubs haven't
won two in a row since June 8. &QL; 
OVERHEARD &QL; 
Chicago Cubs first baseman  &UR; Mark Grace after recently playing at
Coors Field: ``They grew the grass longer and made it little bit
more fair, because this grass used to be faster than AstroTurf. But
playing here is like hitting with no gravity. Even I've got power
here.'' &QL; 
OUT OF LEFT FIELD &QL; 
On a club loaded with rookies, it's no surprise the Minnesota Twins
have several players worth mentioning. Promising starter  &UR; Joe &UR; Mays,
who was moved from the bullpen to the rotation in June, has a
sparkling 0.82 ERA and has allowed 19 hits in 22 innings. More
amazing, two of his starts have come against the Cleveland Indians,
the best hitting club in the majors. &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Pedro Gomez can be
reached at (602) 444-2364 or at pedro.gomez(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
