<SLUG> BC-SOC-WCUP-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
3RD-PLACE GAME ENDS IN SHOOTOUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM THOMAS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Some members of the Norway and Brazil
contingents grumbled about having to stay in California for a week
to play in the third-place game of the Women's World Cup, and FIFA
indicated it may consider eliminating the match.
</P>
<P>
   But both teams came to play Saturday and put on a spirited
display of soccer at the Rose Bowl. They just had stay around a
little bit longer than expected.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Despite numerous opportunities by each side, the match was
scoreless after regulation, resulting in a shootout. After Norway
star Ann Kristin Aarones missed high on her team's sixth shot,
Brazil's Formiga quickly stepped up and hit a low shot to the left
inside of the net for a 5-4 decision.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams put pressure on the defenses in the late stages of
regulation, combining for 25 shots. &QL; 
Goooooooals? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Many people point to the ability of women's teams to score more
often than men's teams as a reason for the popularity of this World
Cup.
</P>
<P>
   With 123 goals through 30 matches heading into the final day of
the tournament, fans saw an average of 4.10 goals per match.
</P>
<P>
   With four of the highest-scoring teams in Saturday's
championship and third-place matches, it was thought that goal
total would rise.
</P>
<P>
   So what happens? Both matches were scoreless, forcing shootouts.
</P>
<P>
   That left China's Sun Wen and Brazil's Sissi as the tournament
leaders in goals with seven apiece.
</P>
<P>
   Ten players scored for the United States, led by Tiffeny
Milbrett with three goals. Norway had eight players score, with
Aarones netting four.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the four teams that played Saturday scored seven goals
in a match during the group play phase. The U.S. defeated Nigeria,
7-1; Brazil beat Mexico, 7-1; Norway downed Canada, 7-1; and China
overwhelmed Ghana, 7-0. &QL; 
All-tournament team &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Five members of the champion U.S. side were selected to the
World Cup All-Star team.
</P>
<P>
   Goalkeeper Briana Scurry, defenders Brandi Chastian and Carla
Overbeck, midfielder Michelle Akers and striker Mia Hamm were
American selections to the 16-player squad.
</P>
<P>
   China led all nations with seven players. Goalkeeper Gao Hong,
defenders Wang Liping and Wen Lirong, midfielders Liu Ailing and
Zhao Lihong, and strikers Jin Yan and Sun were selected.
</P>
<P>
   Germany's Doris Fitschen, a defender, and Bettina Wiegmann, a
midfielder, also made the team along with midfielder Sissi and
striker Aarones. &QL; 
A thorn? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Security was tight at the Rose Bowl on Saturday because of
President Clinton's appearance at the matches.
</P>
<P>
   All members of the press had their computer bag and briefcases
subjected to a police dog's trained nose.
</P>
<P>
   The president visited the locker rooms of the teams after the
championship match, first China's then the American's. That made
for a long wait before players appeared for interviews, and
prompted this comment from a FIFA official:
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm with FIFA and we're visitors in this country, so we have
to respect the security procedures of the White House. It's a thorn
in the side, I know. There is another term for it, but we'll just
go with that today.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
