r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-NEWYORK-SUBWAY-SE     07-11 1269
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-NEWYORK-SUBWAY-SERIE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERLEAGUE BRINGS BIG GAMES TO BIG APPLE  
 NYC EXCITED ABOUT POSSIBLE SUBWAY SERIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Big Apple. The city that never sleeps. America's
gutter. New York City, the lone American city that can hold its own
with any destination on the planet, can be different things to so
many.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever it truly represents, if New York is viewed objectively
it remains the undisputed capital of the professional sports world,
specifically baseball.
</P>
<P>
   It has generally been an accepted notion that Major League
Baseball's golden era began just after World War II and came to a
halt with the end of the 1950s. For proof, look no further than
Yogi Berra, the king of baseball one-liners, who confirmed the
belief.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that time, it was the golden era,'' Berra said, putting
things in the type of perspective that only he seems capable of
doing. ``But baseball is still good.''
</P>
<P>
   It should come as no surprise that from 1946 to 1959, a club
from New York appeared in the World Series 18 times. Seven of those
years, the World Series never left New York City, reinforcing the
term ``Subway Series'' as a part of baseball's landscape.
</P>
<P>
   With the Yankees, far and away the most storied and decorated
club in big league history, and cross-town New York Mets each in a
position to qualify for the playoffs (each would if the season
ended today), the burning desire of every New York fan is no
secret.
</P>
<P>
   ``New York likes excitement,'' said former Brooklyn Dodgers
pitcher Joe Black. ``A New York World Series would have definite
entertainment value. I don't think it would have the same frenzy of
the old Dodgers-Yankees World Series. Now it's just words across
the chest of each club. Before it was in the fans' hearts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be for the championship of New York and baseball. But
the drive inside the players' hearts, I don't think, would be the
same. They don't adopt the same loyalty that existed back then.''
</P>
<P>
   It's possible the allegiances each New York borough had with its
club _ Brooklyn with the Dodgers, the Bronx with the Yankees and
Manhattan with the Giants _ may no longer exist, but it doesn't
take much for New York to reach fever pitch when it comes to the
possibility of the first Subway Series in 43 years.
</P>
<P>
   New Yorkers have spent the last few days doing nothing but
talking about the Yankees-Mets interleague series this weekend,
praying it's a prelude to an October meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have an idea of what it would be like,'' said Mets assistant
general manager Omar Minaya, who grew up a few minutes from Shea
Stadium in Flushing. ``I assure you, whatever idea I have, it would
be 10 times more.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stock market would have to close because no one would get
any work done. A New York World Series would be felt worldwide,
because the financial markets would come to a stop. I hope Wall
Street has some sort of emergency plans.''
</P>
<P>
   If Saturday's raucous crowd was an indication of what an October
meeting between these two clubs might bring, then Minaya's
prediction may very well be true.
</P>
<P>
   In the 37 years the Mets and Yankees have shared New York, the
two clubs have never made the playoffs in the same season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we're that far away from it happening,'' Yankees
center fielder Bernie Williams said. ``With a few breaks, it could
happen. This might be the year. If it does, there will be riots in
the streets. It would definitely be wild.''
</P>
<P>
   The Subway Series was born in 1921, when the Yankees and
then-New York Giants shared the famed Polo Grounds and each won
their respective league to set up New York's dream matchup.
</P>
<P>
   The Polo Grounds was the Giants' home park, and they agreed to
allow the Yankees to play their home games there for a fee. The
bitterness in their rivalry was born that season when the Giants
were offended their tenants consistently drew larger home crowds
during the regular season than they did.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants served notice that 1922 would be the Yankees' final
one at the Polo Grounds. The Yankees, with a young up-and-coming
right fielder by the name of Babe Ruth in their midst, began
construction on Yankee Stadium, also known as the House that Ruth
Built.
</P>
<P>
   As much as many throughout the rest of the country may cringe
when they think of New York and everything it represents, Major
League Baseball has always ridden a little higher when a New York
club was on top.
</P>
<P>
   ``I agree that New Yorkers can be awful and snobby, and I'm one
of them,'' said longtime ``New York Daily News'' baseball writer
Red Foley, now retired. ``If you play on a New York team in any
sport, you're instantly perceived as being better than any player
anywhere else.
</P>
<P>
   ``The perception is always how the backup Yankees catcher or
middle infielder could start anywhere else. And let's face it,
perception is the whole thing in sports.''
</P>
<P>
   In New York's case, perception is backed up by the cascade of
media here. New York remains the media capital of the world. So
it's only natural that a glut of attention comes from being a
champion in New York.
</P>
<P>
   For proof, look to stately Yankees Manager Joe Torre, who is
featured on a national television campaign for a financial
investment company.
</P>
<P>
   Even with all the attention di rected toward these three games
between the Yankees and Mets, the players continue to try and
insist Yankees-Mets interleague games are nothing special.
</P>
<P>
   But megastar Jerry Seinfeld, Wimbledon champion Lindsay
Davenport, Mayor and Senate hopeful Rudy Giuliani, and the
extremely satisfied Donald Trump don't collectively show up for any
ordinary regular season game, as they did Friday night. The nearly
deafening beat that pulsated throughout Shea Stadium over the
weekend was very real.
</P>
<P>
   For a city that normally is running several miles per hour
faster than anywhere else, the jump over the weekend had it going
at nearly breakneck speed, no matter how much players from both
sides tried to downplay it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just another game?'' Yankees bench coach Don Zimmer asked. ``I
don't buy that (expletive). These people are whoopin' and
hollerin'. This is the party of their life. This is wild.
Everything about it is different.''
</P>
<P>
   Three Yankees players missed the second of three team buses that
ran Yankees players and staff from the Bronx to Queens, where Shea
Stadium is located.
</P>
<P>
   Not wanting their boys to sit around for another 90 minutes
waiting for the next bus, a New York City police officer
volunteered to take the three Yankees on the 12-mile drive that can
take up to 45 minutes with heavy traffic.
</P>
<P>
   The three team buses that brought Yankees personnel also had
police escorts, sirens and all, for their drive through three of
New York's five boroughs.
</P>
<P>
   All this talk of a possible all-New York World Series has
brought back sweet memories of the time when New York City seemed
to own the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we would play the Yankees in the Series, I would ride the
subway from my home in Brooklyn to Ebbets Field,'' Black said.
``You couldn't get on without hearing everyone talking about
baseball. They didn't really know me and would ask who I was for.
I'd tell them I like players on both teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'd ask where I was sitting, and I'd say I had a friend who
sometimes let me in the ballpark. They wanted to come along, but
I'd say he wouldn't let me in unless I was alone. The Brooklyn fans
felt like it was truly their team, like we were all family. In a
way, we were family because we were in it together.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
