<HEADER>
A5877 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-WCUP-BICKLEY-AZR &LR;      07-11 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WCUP-BICKLEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEY SCORE, HEAR THEM ROAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, CALIF. - Lost in the moment, she defined the moment.
</P>
<P>
   With the ball safely in the net and a groundbreaking victory in
hand, Brandi Chastain ripped off her shirt in jubilation, stunning
the crowd and an international television audience with the sight
of . . .
</P>
<P>
   A black sports bra.
</P>
<P>
   I am woman. Hear me score.
</P>
<P>
   ``Momentary insanity. Nothing more, nothing less,'' Chastain
explained. ``I just kind of lost my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   A nation knows the feeling.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, the U.S. Women's soccer team put the exclamation
point on a daring vision. After two overtimes and 120 minutes of
pressure-packed drama, after a gut-wrenching round of penalty
kicks, they outlasted fatigue, heat and a powerful China team to
win the World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   And as they paraded around the Rose Bowl, with gold medals
bouncing around their necks and silver confetti swirling around
their heads, they were very much aware of their place in history. A
team with a cause, a team with their own declaration of
independence.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of America is part of this victory and (part) of this
team,'' U.S. Coach Tony DiCicco said. ``They so much epitomize what
America is all about.''
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to cheer the American flag, to find the patriot
within, but this well runs much deeper. From the beginning, this
was about liberation, shattering perceptions, creating role models
for young women everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will give young girls the courage to try sports and all
types of activities,'' said President Clinton, who witnessed the
match in person, in a television interview.
</P>
<P>
   It has been very easy to stereotype this event, from the Brady
Bunch following to the perception that soccer is the ultimate
symbol of middle-class suburbia. But for the past three weeks,
everything clicked. The attendance figures for the tournament have
been overwhelming. And not only was Saturday's crowd the largest
gathering to ever witness a woman's sporting event, it also beat
the men's World Cup final by 10,000 fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``That knocks the boots off everybody,'' forward Tiffeny
Milbrett said. ``Because no one expected that.''
</P>
<P>
   Stripped to its essence, that is the beauty of this team. They
exceeded a whirlwind of hype, surpassed all expectations, broke
through every barrier. And it should be lost on no one that the
biggest hero on Saturday was the goalie, a woman named Briana
Scurry, a 27-year-old from Minnesota who calls herself ``the fly in
the milk.''
</P>
<P>
   Scurry is also an African-American, proving this team was not
only about gender.
</P>
<P>
   ``Diversity is important for the future of the game,'' Scurry
said. ``Soccer is pretty much a suburban, elitist sport. It always
has been.''
</P>
<P>
   The stated mission of the 1999 World Cup was ``staging a
breakthrough event for women's sports and inspiring the next
generation of female athletes.'' With 2,000 people attending
practice sessions during the week, it's obvious they succeeded.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, fans were cloaked in red, white and blue. Some wore
the American flag like capes. Others had their faces painted at a
free booth outside the stadium. Clinton called the event ``in some
ways, the biggest sporting event in the past decade.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the momentum is expected to reach a fever pitch, and
U.S. soccer officials say enrollment in youth leagues will reach
record numbers in the coming months.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see hundreds of thousands of girls register in the fall
that otherwise wouldn't have registered, if not for this event,''
said Marla Messing, president and CEO of the Women's World Cup.
``They want to be like Mia Hamm and Julie Foudy and play in a
Women's World Cup.''
</P>
<P>
   Prompted by a team of heroes, a team full of inspiration and
role models. And now, they are off for a victory tour, soon to be
seen on Letterman and cereal boxes and T-shirts across the nation.
</P>
<P>
   It will be a while before anyone can judge the full sociological
impact of this team and this event, whether mainstream America is
now ready to accept female sports. But it's a safe bet that a
country of young women and young girls turned off the television on
Saturday feeling pretty good about this team.
</P>
<P>
   And themselves. &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at (602) 444-8253 or at
dan.bickley(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
