<DOCNO> NYT19990711.0029 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-11 01:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5878 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-NHLNOTEBOOK-BOS &LR;      07-11 1818
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SINDEN, FISHER SEND JOHNSON OUT WITH KIND WORDS 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ They have been friends for 45 years. They have seen
each other through marriage and children, exchanged stories of
their parallel careers, and teased each other relentlessly. Both
are also members of the Hockey Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   When it was announced that Bruins vice president Tom Johnson had
decided to retire from the organization after 36 years and 52 in
the NHL, Montreal Gazette writer Red Fisher couldn't resist the
urge to weigh in on the end of an era.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was never, ever really appreciated in Montreal, even though
he played on all those great teams,'' said Fisher, referring to
Johnson's run with the Canadiens, during which he won six Stanley
Cups. ``The reason for it was he, and others with him, played in
the very long shadow of Doug Harvey. The only defenseman I ever
considered better than Doug Harvey was No. 4 Bobby Orr.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who faces hip replacement surgery in late summer or
early fall, endured a great deal of pain as a player. Fisher said
no matter how much Johnson was suffering, he'd be out there
battling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of all the great players I covered in Montreal in the 1950s, I
don't think there was anybody who played with more pain when he had
to,'' said Fisher. ``He'd take shots in his knees. They were ripped
up, and he'd come out and play. Injuries didn't matter to this guy.
He'd never make any kind of a big deal about it. As a result, he
became a great favorite of (then Canadiens general manager) Frank
Selke Sr. (Selke) didn't play too many favorites, but certainly,
Tom Johnson was one of his favorites. In those days, you didn't
have any players association to say you shouldn't play or you can't
play. This guy came out and played like no other player did. I
admired him a great deal for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson came to the Bruins via the waiver draft in 1963, and
Fisher said it was a very difficult decision for Selke to leave
Johnson exposed.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the kind gestures made by Johnson that few found out
about, Fisher said there was one that stood out. During a game
against the Maple Leafs in Toronto, Johnson's face was sliced open
by a skate blade. The team returned to Montreal after the game, but
Johnson remained in the hospital, and Fisher stayed, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to the hospital to see Tommy because he was a friend,''
said Fisher. ``I had to talk my way into his room, almost force my
way into his room. They wouldn't let anyone but family into the
room because his face had blown up to twice its normal size. Both
eyes were covered in bandages. I spent the afternoon with him. I
flew home the next day, and that same day, a dozen roses were sent
to my wife by Tom, saying `Thanks for your husband's visit to me in
the hospital.' I challenge you to find any other player who would
do something like that. He was that kind of a guy, and always has
been. He was generous to a fault. In Montreal, if there was a party
to be held during an off day, it was almost always held at Tommy
Johnson's. As a player, he never got the credit he deserved. He
deserved his spot in the Hall of Fame. And I don't think anybody
can have a better friend.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruins president/GM Harry Sinden, another close friend of
Johnson's, said he'll miss seeing him every day in the office.
Johnson has moved to the Cape but will keep in touch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I value his assessment of the players and the team,'' said
Sinden. ``I know he's having his hip replaced. I hope everything
works there and he can get back on the golf course. That's the one
thing outside of hockey that he has a strong interest in. It would
be a shame if he couldn't play golf. He's very confident everything
is going to be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Sinden said one of his favorite Johnson stories goes back a
number of years. A Montreal Gazette writer, not Fisher, was
criticizing Sinden on a daily basis, and Johnson was reveling in
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were in Montreal for the playoffs,'' said Sinden. ``(This
writer) would give it to me all the time. Tom was laughing. One
day, he mentioned Tom in the same way he was giving it to me. It
was the morning of a game; Tom was in there getting it from him.
Now, all of a sudden, it means something. Before, when it was just
me getting ripped, he'd laugh and say, `Look what he said.' We go
to the game that night and we lose, and right next to our dressing
room _ you couldn't move in that little room, it was so crowded.
Well, he sought out the writer and pounced as hard as he could on
his foot. The guy went to his knees, he hit him so hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Chances are there was a wicked grin of satisfaction on Johnson's
face at the time. No matter what the situation, Johnson always
found humor in it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's had some tough times physically,'' Sinden said. ``He's
always got a sense of humor and a needle as long as anybody's. He's
really going to be missed around here.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   We told you all the wonderful optimism regarding Bruins goalie
Byron Dafoe's contract negotiations was going to fade. So it has.
Dafoe said since the team made him an offer and his camp responded,
talks have ceased. That's not necessarily a problem, but with Dafoe
having until Thursday to decide on filing for arbitration, he would
have liked to have had more dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our phone is there. We're waiting for a return call,'' said
the team's clear-cut MVP. ``If not, we have a decision to make come
July 15. We have not made that decision yet. We're weighing both
sides of the coin. I have an inclination one way, but until I have
to make a decision, I won't make one. There are pluses and minuses
to both sides. We have to decide which has the bigger upside.''
</P>
<P>
   Realistically, Dafoe could not file for arbitration, then
threaten to withhold his services come training camp if no deal is
reached. However, with Dafoe's outstanding statistics, he has a
case for a hefty arbitration award.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to have a conference call with the (players
association) early (this) week,'' said Dafoe, a restricted free
agent. ``Hopefully, we hear from Harry and (assistant GM Mike
O'Connell) by then, but if not, then we have to follow through with
what we're going to do. It really comes down to what (agent Ron
Salcer) and I feel is the right way to go. The PA is good for us in
terms of giving us insight into what other players have done and
what they're going to do and what comparable signings have been.
The PA is notorious for their gung ho, hold out, hold out, let's
get the big bucks kind of thing, and that's fine because that's
their job, but the bottom line is: We do what we feel is right.
That's kind of where we're stuck at right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Sinden said the club expects to meet with Jay Fee, the agent for
backup goalie Rob Tallas, soon on a new deal for the Group 2 free
agent. Sinden also said the team has had preliminary discussions
with representatives for free agents Hal Gill and P.J. Axelsson.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As if professional hockey wasn't dangerous enough, Anaheim star
Teemu Selanne is pushing the envelope with his love of car racing.
The 29-year-old was practicing for a rally event in his native
Finland when he struck another car, injuring the driver, Parliament
member and president of the Finnish Ice Hockey Federation Kalervo
Kummola.
</P>
<P>
   Police said Selanne, who admitted he was at fault, will likely
be charged with reckless driving. The real question is: What is
Selanne doing? The standard player's contract doesn't prohibit car
racing, but it does leave the door open for the Mighty Ducks to
void Selanne's lucrative pact if he suffers a serious injury behind
the wheel.
</P>
<P>
   ``The player and club recognize and agree the player's
participation in other sports may impair or destroy his ability and
skill as a hockey player,'' reads the standard contract.
``Accordingly, the player agrees he will not during the period of
this contract or during any period when he is obligated under his
contract to enter into a further contract with the club engage or
participate in football, baseball, softball, hockey, lacrosse,
boxing, wrestling or other athletic sports without the written
consent of the club, which consent will not be unreasonably
withheld.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Sinden, the consent to which it refers allows
players to skate during the summer in order to keep in shape.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to say what I'd do,'' said Sinden. ``Our players
have participated in a race up in New Hampshire. It was a stock car
race for charity. But we judged it to be very safe and very
unlikely something would happen. Then you get into the business of
whether that's an athletic contest or not. That clause really only
refers to an athletic contest. If they got hurt doing that, and you
refused to honor the contract, they'd probably sue you to say they
could do that. It's a gray area. We get requests to play hockey,
but I can't remember anybody wanting to play any other sport. For
each individual case, you'd have to judge it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It was an expensive week for the New York Rangers, and truth be
told, they're not much better. They doled out more than $50 million
signing unrestricted free agents Theo Fleury, Stephane Quintal, and
Valeri Kamensky. Quintal and Kamensky alone cost $28.4 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was certainly not a surprise, not from that team,'' Sinden
said.
</P>
<P>
   Sinden, who was criticized by Rangers GM Neil Smith last fall
for overspending on bonuses for Joe Thornton and Sergei Samsonov
(you can look it up), said he was already in trouble with one
general manager _ Chicago's Bob Murray _ for picking defenseman
Nick Boynton with the 21st selection in last month's draft, and he
didn't want to take the bait on Smith.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob Murray's sick of me,'' Sinden said. ``I don't want to make
Neil Smith sick of me.''
</P>
<P>
   After Murray ripped Sinden on draft day, Sinden called, seeking
a reason for Murray's diatribe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I reached him, but I never got an explanation,'' said Sinden.
``He apologized, but I didn't get an explanation. I would've much
preferred the explanation.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In about a week, it's expected Pat Quinn will officially take
over as general manager of the Maple Leafs, adding that role to his
duties as coach. At the draft in Boston, there was a hullabaloo
between team president Ken Dryden and Quinn over the dismissal of
former associate GM Mike Smith. Dryden said Quinn was involved in
the process. Quinn said he wasn't. But everything appears to have
been smoothed over. ``I got apprised of some of the things,'' Quinn
said, referring to the behind-the-scenes maneuverings. ``Now we
have to go forward. I had no intention of doing anything but
coaching, but now circumstances are different.'' . . . There are 55
days until training camp. Seems like the season just ended, doesn't
it? Maybe because it did.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
