</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-FRANCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRANCE DRIVING FORCE IN NASCAR SURGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ The hallways of NASCAR's headquarters are
exquisitely appointed with photographs and artifacts that pay
tribute to its past and present. But there is a framed
black-and-white photo of a strapping Bill France Jr. in his early
20s _ a toothy smile creasing his face as he sits perched atop a
piece of road construction equipment _ that seems to depict just
how far the 66-year-old NASCAR president has come in his undisputed
stewardship of the world's largest auto racing sanctioning body.
</P>
<P>
   From road construction worker to auto racing czar.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he was merely striking a pose or actually knew how to
operate the piece of machinery, France reclined in a plush leather
chair in his gymnasium-sized office and confirmed that, yes, he
indeed knew his way around a ``vibratory compactor.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh yeah, I drove it all day for many a day,'' he said,
recalling how he assisted in the building of the flagship facility
of his family's racing empire, the 2.5-mile superspeedway at
Daytona. ``It's similar to those big rollers that you see now
working on the roads. But this machine vibrated all the grains of
sand, locked it together, and packed it down. I worked out there on
it for about 13, 14 months.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, he can drive just about any piece of machinery that
there is,'' said 36-year-old Brian France, NASCAR's senior vice
president of marketing and communications and the younger of Bill
and Betty Jane France's two children, both of whom hold high-level
positions in the family's businesses. Sister Lesa France Kennedy
serves as an executive vice president and board member of
International Speedway Corp., a publicly-owned corporation that
recently expanded its holdings with the $700 million acquisiton of
Penske Motorsports, giving ISC control of 10 tracks (with four more
on the drawing board) and 14 NASCAR Winston Cup dates.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is very mechanical-minded, and it probably served him well
in the competition area,'' Brian added. ``He's a well-rounded guy.
If he came along today, he's so good at so many things _ he's good
at communications, he's good at marketing, he's a good technician,
and has a feel for all those aspects of the sport _ that he'd
probably be frustrated just doing one part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet it is hard to imagine that, during his time working on
the construction of Daytona International Speedway, France never
stopped to take in the huge project and envision the fame and
fortune the object of his labors would one day bring his family and
the burgeoning sport of stock car racing.
</P>
<P>
   As far as he was concerned, there was only one visionary in the
family.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was my father,'' France said, referring to Bill Sr.,
NASCAR's founder, who died in 1992, some two decades after he
handed over the reins to Bill Jr. ``I'd like to say that I could
really see all that, but my father was the one who was the main guy
at the time.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Now, as NASCAR finds itself speeding toward the high-banked turn
of the century, Bill France Jr. is being looked upon as the man
whose vision will continue to drive the wildly successful and
widely publicized NASCAR Winston Cup Series, the sanctioning body's
premier division, and position it among the mainstream American
professional sports leagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I think he really wants us to be recognized as a top
sports league in this country,'' his son said. ``That's what he
wants, and he knows that the numbers now are undeniable.''
</P>
<P>
   At the 1998 Winston Cup awards banquet in New York, where Jeff
Gordon was feted as the champion of NASCAR's 50th anniversary
season, France took the podium and said it was his desire to see
NASCAR not only join ranks with, but also rival the NFL, NBA, NHL,
and Major League Baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're there, to a large degree, right now,'' France
said. ``They used to talk about the Big Five being baseball,
football, basketball, hockey, and maybe tennis. But the Big Five
now are those first three, NASCAR _ and not just auto racing but
NASCAR _ and golf. So if you look at what the people are watching,
the NFL is still leading the charts. But we're doing just as well
as the others.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then you take the live gate. If you look at the attendance,
we're just about 19 of the top 20 (sporting) events. We outdraw a
lot of the sporting events in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   To illustrate the point, the 70th baseball All-Star Game will be
held Tuesday at Fenway Park, but its combined gate for the two days
of pregame festivities and the game itself will likely fail to
outdraw Sunday's Jiffy Lube 300 NASCAR Winston Cup race at New
Hampshire International Speedway in Loudon, where 100,000
spectators are expected.
</P>
<P>
   And while its TV ratings have yet to approach the numbers
achieved by baseball and football, Winston Cup racing has enjoyed a
steady increase in viewership over the last three years, prompting
NASCAR officials in February to consolidate their television rights
in the hopes of landing a lucrative TV package that some are
speculating will fetch anywhere from $300-$500 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know what the market will bear,'' said Kevin
Triplett, NASCAR's director of operations. ``But we think we're
taking a good product to market.''
</P>
<P>
   And that is due in large part to France's management of the
series. He has elevated the one-time regional sport, whose sponsors
were largely automotive-related and whose fans largely hailed from
the Southeast, to a national sport that has grown to reach markets
from coast to coast and has attracted major consumer product
sponsorships.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But what does the future hold for NASCAR? What is France's
vision?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we need to keep doing what we're doing now and try not
to let something start snowballing,'' he said. ``One of my bigger
fears, and it's always been a concern, is if the costs of having a
car out there gets prohibitive for race fans to buy tickets and it
doesn't get prohibitive for networks to sell advertising.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has to be some kind of a balance if you're going to have
a good economic system. And if that influences what the product is
going to be, then we've got to keep our racing healthy. When I say
healthy, I'm not just talking about 40 cars at a racetrack, but
good competitive racing that's exciting and that you'll want to
watch.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it costs too much to go racing, or if any of those numbers
get out of sync with the revenue that's involved with a company . .
. then you're not going to be around long, and doors are going to
get shut.''
</P>
<P>
   But France has taken measures to ensure NASCAR remains a
profitable venture well into the next millennium. In February, he
announced he was stepping aside and handing over day-to-day
operations to Mike Helton, who now oversees all of NASCAR's
divisions as chief operating officer. Initially, the public
perception was that France was getting ready to retire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, it had come off that way in some regard, but it was
simply a commitment from Bill and his family . . . to develop
another level of management,'' Helton said. ``And while the
day-to-day operations were something that he gave up, he didn't
give up everything. He's as busy today as he's ever been. He just
divided up some of the things he routinely did from an
organizational chart.''
</P>
<P>
   By lightening his load, France was able to focus his attention
on the merger between ISC and Penske Motorsports, one that will
make the new conglomerate the largest provider of motorsports
events in the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill is a very serious individual,'' said Roger Penske, a
Winston Cup and CART car owner who will serve on the ISC board as
vice chairman. ``He stands by his word. I think he has never taken
his eye off the garage, and he's stayed very close to the athletes,
the car owners, and the track owners. And he's developed a
tremendous loyalty, and that's what kept his sport together.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even with all of his tremendous success, he's not let any of
that get him away from the core business, which is dealing at the
track level with the officials, the competitors, and car owners. I
think you've seen that with what he's done at his tracks; we're
trying to make that the ultimate fan experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Said NHIS owner Bob Bahre, ``In all honesty, (France is) the
type of a guy _ and I'm not just saying this because I've got two
(Winston Cup) dates _ who's a pleasure to do business with. There
aren't too many people today you can say that about. He has the
upper hand because he controls all the dates, but you'd never think
so when you talk to him. He's just kind of a regular guy, and I
consider him a pretty good friend.''
</P>
<P>
   At a race last year in Atlanta, France was spotted as he walked
past a long line of fans. He was taken aback when one woman asked
him for an autograph. Why, he asked, would anyone want his
autograph?
</P>
<P>
   ``Because you're the reason we're all here,'' the woman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, if I don't wake up tomorrow,'' he drawled, ``they'll
still run this race without me.''
</P>
<P>
   He knows there will be a day when the show will indeed go on
without him. By then, however, he hopes it will be strong enough to
withstand his absence. How will he ever reconcile his retirement
with his immense passion for the sport he helped to build? How will
his love of deep sea fishing, airplanes, and all things mechanical
replace his deep-rooted love of racing?
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll work out,'' France said. ``I'll need to get out of the
way one day, so the younger ones can take over and a whole lot of
people can have some moves.''
</P>
<P>
   But even then, Bill France Jr. will always remain a prominent
figure in NASCAR's big picture.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-11-99 0109EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
