u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-AUTORACINGNOTEBOO     07-11 1286
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-AUTO </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRAVEN LOOKING FOR GOOD RUN AT HOME 
</HEADLINE>
 RACING NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUDON, N.H. _ Ricky Craven stood in his garage at New Hampshire
International Speedway Friday afternoon and smiled wearily as he
tried to describe the support he got from New England fans at
qualifying for Sunday's Jiffy Lube 300 NASCAR Winston Cup race.
</P>
<P>
   Although the wild fan reaction was drowned out by the throaty
roar of his No. 50 Midwest Transit Chevrolet Monte Carlo, Craven, a
33-year-old native of Newburgh, Maine, said the home crowd did not
go unnoticed or unappreciated after he landed a solid 12th starting
spot with a run of 129.732 miles per hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think this sport is much different from any other
professional sport,'' said Craven, who has been exposed to both the
exhilarating and humbling sides of the NASCAR circuit. ``The good
days are hard to come by when you're in the position I'm in, which
is a rebuilding mode. I'm trying to reestablish myself.''
</P>
<P>
   That was why Friday's fan reaction was just the pick-me-up
Craven needed, especially after his Winston Cup career took a
tumultuous turn following a stirring pole victory in last year's
Jiffy Lube 300.
</P>
<P>
   ``This place is just so good to me,'' Craven said. ``I don't
know what it is, but coming here is always a boost. The fans, I
guess . . . I just wish I could take them with me every week
because it's so motivating to have that kind of support.''
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Craven came to NHIS and got a huge boost when he won
the pole for the Jiffy Lube 300, wresting it away from former
Hendrick Motorsports teammate Jeff Gordon. It came in Craven's
first race back in the No. 50 Budweiser Chevrolet after he spent 3
1/2 months recovering from the effects of post-concussion syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very, very difficult time in my career because I
didn't know if I was ever going to race again,'' he said. ``I
didn't know if I was going to be allowed to race again. I didn't
even know if I could or if I'd even be given the chance, you know?
</P>
<P>
   ``In those 90 days, I think I experienced every emotion
possible, but coming back and winning the pole was like, `Ahhh.'
Was it a championship? No, but for that day we were best and nobody
can take it away from you. But if you can do that once, then why
can't you do that every week? You can't, you just have to
understand what your weaknesses are and you've got to expand on
your strengths.''
</P>
<P>
   Three races later, Craven resigned from his ride with Hendrick
Motorsports, a well-heeled and successful three-car team he called
``the Chicago Bulls of racing.'' He arrived for the 1999 Daytona
500 as driver for SB III Motorsports, but parted ways with that
outfit following a 31st-place effort in the MBNA Platinum 400 at
Dover, Del.
</P>
<P>
   After he sat out the next three races, Craven signed on with
owners Hal Hicks and Mike Witters to drive _ on a race-to-race
basis _ their Midwest Transit-sponsored Chevy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a tough couple of years, really,'' said Craven, who
started 30th and finished 43d in his debut in the Midwest Transit
car last Saturday night at Daytona in the Pepsi 400. ``Last year
really wasn't much fun and this year we were so far behind the
8-ball most of the year, we seemed to be fighting an uphill battle
and it's a hard way to race. But I'm really excited about being
with these guys because there's a lot of potential. There's no . .
. we all have the same agenda: we want to perform well, we want to
run well, and we want to get better every week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a couple of years from now when we're back in our top
form _ in two weeks or two months or two years or whenever I get
back to where I feel I'm in contention _ I'll have toughened up
because I think I'll have experienced the highest of highs and the
lowest of lows.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Points leader Dale Jarrett thought it was a good omen that the
last six Winston Cup champions led the points race at the midway
point of the season. However, Jarrett, who extended his lead over
Bobby Labonte to 177 points (2,674 to 2,497) with a victory in the
Pepsi 400, was quick to point out one thing. ``I guess the downside
of that is, the last time somebody lost it, he was in a Robert
Yates car, and nobody's pointing that out,'' Jarrett said,
referring to how in 1992 Davey Allison led in points halfway
through the season but eventually lost to Alan Kulwicki. ``We want
to make sure we continue the string they've had for six years in a
row now. But it's good because I think over the last three years,
the second half of the season has been better for our race team and
that's good for us to look at in that sense. But we also realize
that we've had a tremendous first half of the season and we have a
lot of confidence, too, and we certainly want to be sitting here
next year talking about how it happened seven years in a row.''
Halfway through the 34-race season, Jarrett is not expecting to sit
on his lead by driving conservatively. ``I have no idea when that
point may come, but it's not now, that's for sure,'' he said. ``Our
lead could be gone here (Sunday) by having a bad day and Bobby
Labonte finishing up front like he has all year. We've got to
continue to try and win races and we've got to hope that we're good
enough and that we don't have any problems and that we can continue
to build on our lead.'' . . . Though he qualified third for
Sunday's race in his No. 18 Interstate Batteries Pontiac, Labonte
remained perplexed by the tricky mile oval at NHIS. ``We've been
coming up here since 1990 and you'd think we'd get something
figured out by now,'' he said. ``I know where all the best
restaurants are . . . but it's always fun to come here, because
it's always challenging.'' Labonte's favorite eatery? The Grist
Mill.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While Dale Earnhardt Jr. will be driving Sunday with a chipped
right shoulder blade, the toughest man in Sunday's race will be
none other than Mark Martin. The driver of the No. 6 Valvoline Ford
Taurus suffered fractures in his left wrist, left ribs, and tibia
plateau of his left knee when he crashed July 2 during a happy-hour
practice session for the Pepsi 400. Martin showed up the next day
with a cast on his wrist and gutted out a 17th-place finish after
he was forced to start his backup car from the rear of the field.
Wednesday, Martin underwent surgery on his knee and had a screw
placed in it to provide more stability to his kneecap, so he could
compete at NHIS. Although Matt Kenseth was brought in as a
precautionary measure, Martin endured excruciating pain to qualify
Saturday in the second round. ``Well, I'd rather be doing this than
laying on a bed,'' Martin said. ``We're doing OK. We're not as fast
as we need to be and I'm not as much of a hero as I'd like to be,
so we're doing the best we can do.'' As far as his game plan? ``I'm
going all the way. That's it. We're gonna race as hard as we can
race.'' . . . With the baseball All-Star Game being held Tuesday at
Fenway, several drivers weighed in with their predictions. Jeremy
Mayfield, a Reds and Braves fan, and Ward Burton, a Cardinals fan,
picked the National League, while John Andretti chose the American
League ``unless they invert the field after the fifth inning,'' he
said, referring to NASCAR's all-star race, the Winston, where the
field is inverted midway through the race. ``I don't get the chance
to follow baseball much, but if it's anything like our all-star
game, it ought to be exciting,'' said Mayfield. ``Of course, in
their all-star game, if they make a mistake they call it an error.
In our all-star game, if you make a mistake they call it a big
wreck.''
</P>
</TEXT>
