<HEADLINE>
GREAT DEBATE TURNS INTO NO-BRAINER 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM McCABE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Tiger Woods is ranked No. 1 in the world. David Duval
is ranked No. 2. The last time we were here, there was a huge
outcry about supposed injustice. Not much noise this time.
</P>
<P>
   Nor should there be. Woods has won three times in his last four
starts (one in Germany). He has broken 70 in 10 of his last 16
rounds on the PGA Tour. In 15 starts this year, including his
appearance in Germany, he has four wins and six other top 10s.
</P>
<P>
   Week in and week out, Woods is the best. It shouldn't even be
debated. His performance at the Western Open last week was a
spectacular display of power and finesse, a clinic on 300-yard,
fairway-splitting drives and flop shots out of nasty rough to pins
cut tight. (Which is to say nothing about his splendid commercials.
Would you say the man has some hand-eye coordination? Or can we not
say anything while the litigation is in process?)
</P>
<P>
   Quite often we overlook how consistent Woods is. Since turning
pro in 1996, he has played in 77 PGA Tour events and missed just
one cut (two if you count the AT&AMP;T debacle last year when Woods and
many others did not return five months later to play a third
round). Just as impressive is the fact that nearly every time he
sticks the peg in the ground, Woods is in contention.
</P>
<P>
   Duval shot a 59, won four times in his first eight starts this
season, and generally deserved his short-lived reign as No. 1. But
as good as he is, he's a notch below Woods.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, unless they go head to head this week at the
British Open, that silly Aug. 2 made-for-TV event will get even
more hype. Too bad, because without tournament pressure on the
line, the event doesn't have any taste. Then again, tasteless TV is
what we love.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It is a safe assumption that Jesper Parnevik, who plays most of
his golf in the US, is an automatic as one of captain Mark James's
two picks for the European Ryder Cup team. But it is not out of the
realm of possibility that Parnevik could qualify automatically.
It's a long shot, of course, but a victory at the British Open (he
has two seconds and a fourth in the event since 1994), on top of
his strong performance at the Loch Lomond (joint fifth) could vault
him in the standings. If he moves closer to the top 10, look for
him to play more events in Europe to gain points in an effort to
make things easier for James. Of course, there are other matters on
the eccentric Swede's mind these days. Only Parnevik could explain,
after missing a short putt in the second round Thursday, that there
was what he considered a good reason for his miscue. ``I've had
this bet with my caddie and I was trying to figure it out,''
Parnevik told reporters. ``If you put a rope around the earth and
then put another one about it on 3-foot stakes, what is the
difference in length? I told him it is less than 20 yards and he
thinks it's 10,000 or something.'' And you stand over short putts
thinking about which way they will break? . . . While you can count
on Parnevik being at The Country Club, it appears as though two
experienced Ryder Cuppers need not book seats on the Concorde. Ian
Woosnam has said he is sick of the Ryder Cup; his play of late
indicates he is sick of golf. Woosnam has missed the cut the last
two weeks, and with just two top-10 finishes this year, he is 36th
in the standings. Costantino Rocca missed the cut at Loch Lomond
and his best finish in 17 starts is a 10th at the Italian Open. He
has been top 20 just one other time and in 60 rounds this year he
has broken 70 just 15 times . . . As for James, he repeated again
last week he will not be a player-captain, something the Ryder Cup
matches have not had since Arnold Palmer in 1963. But while he
indicated earlier in the season that he would lean toward not
playing, he has been in such fine form lately (he is seventh in the
standings) that there are now thoughts of relinquishing his
captain's duties. At a recent meeting with some media members, Ben
Crenshaw quipped: ``The American captain has no such worries.''
Indeed, it has been a rough year for Crenshaw, who withdrew from
the British Open the other day. He has missed the cut in all 11 of
his starts, with just one sub-70 round in 23 efforts. Crenshaw is
so passionate about golf history, you know it must be killing him
not to be at a venue such as Carnoustie, but he showed a ton of
class when he explained in his withdrawal letter: ``I want to give
my space to somebody who could make better use of it.'' . . . The
withdrawals of Americans from the British Open also included Tom
Kite, John Daly, Fred Couples, and Steve Jones. Kite is simply
waiting to turn 50, which he'll do Dec. 9. Daly was no surprise. He
desperately needs to get away from the game and here's hoping he
gets rest, works out a few problems, and returns in good form
because a good John Daly is something the game needs. Couples's WD
is bothersome. He cited the fact that he wasn't playing well. So
what? He's a world-class player and should have more regard for a
game that has made him so wealthy.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jack Nicklaus's withdrawal from the US Senior Open, on the heels
of bowing out of the Senior Players Championship, is no cause for
alarm, according to Dr. Benjamin Bierbaum. ``His hip is fine. He
was playing to get in shape. He was tired of hanging out, hitting
balls, and exercising, but, no surprise, he pushed it to the
limit.'' Bierbaum performed left hip replacement surgery on
Nicklaus Jan. 27 at New England Baptist Hospital and had said then
that ``I didn't think he'd be ready for the endurance of
competitive golf'' for six months. But Nicklaus came back in four
months to play in a Senior PGA Tour event, then his own Memorial
Tournament. He also played at the US Open at Pinehurst but with
Bierbaum watching from the gallery on Friday, Nicklaus missed the
cut and acknowledged the hip was sore. ``The doctor was right,''
said Nicklaus on his way out of Pinehurst. Bierbaum prescribed rest
for the 59-year-old Nicklaus, though the Golden Bear left open the
possibility of playing a pro-am with Michael Jordan Thursday, then
taking part in the ensuing Ameritech Senior Open at Kemper Lakes
outside of Chicago . . . A few days after his clubs were stolen
from his garage, Greg Norman got them back, just in time for the
British Open. A man who had worked on the roof of Norman's home in
Hobe Sound, Fla., turned himself in after being suspected of
stealing two sets of custom-made Cobra clubs. He faces criminal
charges and the guess here is that he can forget about a job
referral . . . The phenom is playing quite well, thank you.
Shooting low numbers, going about the job as efficiently as
observers had predicted. Sergio Garcia? Well, sure. But how about
Grace Park? The Korean-born teenager has played in four Futures
Tour events and won two. She already ranks ninth on the money list
(top three earn LPGA Tour cards for 2000) and the eight players
ahead of her have played an average of nearly 12 events. Last
year's US Women's Amateur champion has refused _ at the insistence
of her father, who runs the show _ sponsor's exemptions into LPGA
Tour events in favor of the low-key, hard life of the Futures Tour.
Park takes her act to Avon, Conn., for this week's stop . . . Juli
Inkster's outstanding 1999 season is continuing with the Michelob
Light Classic this weekend, then she'll play the JAL Big Apple in
New York next week. After a week off, she'll enter the du Maurier,
then decide on the area.WEB.com Challenge at Pleasant Valley the
week after. Inkster's success this year, she said, can be
attributed to her decision to go with a left-hand-low putting grip
_ but mainly on short putts. ``I don't really have a set footage,''
she said. ``I just do more by feel.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
