<HEADLINE>
RUMOR MILL WARMS AS TRADE DEADLINE NEARS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Baseball marches inexorably toward the July 31 trade deadline.
The rumors mount.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees are quietly shopping pitcher Andy Pettitte, who is
9-13 with a 5.56 earned-run average in his past 27 starts going
back to last year. Pettitte is making $5.9 million this season and
is arbitration-eligible. The Yankees would prefer to use that money
toward securing shortstop Derek Jeter and reliever Mariano Rivera
to long-term contracts. The Yankees also think that Pettitte's
reliance on a cut fastball is robbing him of his velocity, just as
it did with Jim Abbott.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians need a third baseman now that Travis Fryman could be
gone for the season. They have asked about Wade Boggs, but the
Devil Rays want him to get his 3,000th hit for them. They have
talked with San Diego about Carlos Baerga, with the Cubs about Gary
Gaetti and with Pittsburgh about Ed Sprague.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians even have talked about moving Jim Thome back to
third, but he's uncomfortable about it, having grown into a first
baseman at 245 pounds. Top prospect Russell Branyan is striking out
too much at Triple A.
</P>
<P>
   Include second baseman Delino DeShields on the list of players
the Orioles would like to dump, if they can get owner Peter
Angelos' permission. They would rather go with rookie Jerry
Hairston Jr., who has played well when DeShields has been hurt.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockies have made everybody but Larry Walker available. That
includes pitcher Darryl Kile and outfielder Dante Bichette. Kile's
big curve has been a bad fit at Coors Field, where the ball doesn't
break sharply because of the altitude. The Rockies are looking for
sinkerball pitchers. The Yankees and Braves could use Bichette.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox also need an outfielder with power. Bichette might
be a possibility, but the Red Sox would prefer Montreal's Rondell
White or Detroit's Bobby Higginson.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets have asked about Montreal pitcher Dustin Hermanson.
</P>
<P>
   Oakland pitcher Kenny Rogers continues to expect a trade,
knowing he won't re-sign with the Athletics next year. Said Rogers,
``I think certain things would be smart for the team to do, but I
don't run things. I like pitching here, but they can't move the
park somewhere closer \Rto his home in Tampa\S. And my family will
be with me next year, no matter what.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pirates are looking for a veteran catcher to replace Jason
Kendall, and some of the names mentioned are Joe Oliver, Lenny
Webster, Jorge Fabregas and Darrin Fletcher.
</P>
<P>
   The Marlins made a curious decision in trading Matt Mantei, who
has a chance to be an All-Star closer. He was also working cheap.
Why trade him to Arizona for Vladimir Nunez, who couldn't do the
same job for the Diamondbacks, and pitching prospect Brad Penny?
Why go for high-risk potential when the Marlins already had the
real thing?
</P>
<P>
   SPOTLIGHT ON RANDY JOHNSON
</P>
<P>
   Mike Fiala Randy Johnson tied a National League record with 43
strikeouts in three games, but the Diamondbacks' offense has let
him down.
Johnson's strikeout tear gets Arizona no wins
Randy Johnson tied a National League record when he struck out 43
batters over three consecutive games. But he lost all three games
as the Diamondbacks were shut out every time.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's amazing,'' catcher Damian Miller said. ``I've never
seen anything like that. The things that have happened to this team
this year, the things I've seen, are unbelievable. You can't
explain it. It's weird.''
</P>
<P>
   It gets weirder. Yesterday, Johnson pitched against Oakland, and
the Diamondbacks were shut out again, 2-0. In four consecutive
starts, Johnson has no victories and no runs scored for him. He
struck out 11 in seven innings yesterday, boosting his four-game
total to 54.
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals pitcher Jose Jimenez started the stretch with a
no-hitter. He also won the rematch with Johnson, 1-0, with a
two-hitter. Cincinnati's Ron Villone and Scott Williamson beat
Johnson with a combined two-hitter in between the two games against
the Cardinals. Tim Hudson and Billy Taylor combined on the shutout
for Oakland yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   That's no runs on six hits over 34 innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing I can do about it,'' said Johnson, who still
moved into the NL lead with a 3.03 earned-run average after the
first three losses. ``I just go out there and do the best I can.
There's no satisfaction in strikeouts.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No one feels as bad as us hitters,'' infielder Andy Fox said.
``We're just as disappointed as \RJohnson\S is. It's just one of
those messed-up things about baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Dwight Gooden set the National League record for three games
when he whiffed 43 in three games in September 1984 (11, 16 and
16). Nolan Ryan holds the major-league mark of 47, in August 1974
(19, nine and 19).
</P>
<P>
   QUICK HITS
</P>
<P>
   Angels reliever Troy Percival, selected to the All-Star Game,
defended Juan Gonzalez's refusal to play. Said Percival, ``I don't
blame him. Guys who put up the numbers should be one of the top
three guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Tigers manager Larry Parrish, forced to fire pitching coach Rick
Adair, is feeling heat in Detroit. But Parrish, remembering whom
the Tigers almost hired, said, ``The fans are going to look at our
record and say I'm messing up. But if a team doesn't play well _ as
Davey Johnson is experiencing with the Dodgers _ you don't win.''
</P>
<P>
   Mariano Rivera's excuse for missing the All-Star Game?
Apparently he's unhappy with the contractor who is building his
dream home in Panama and wants to deal with the situation
personally.
</P>
<P>
   Oakland is starting to think Jimmy Haynes, 2-0 with a 2.54
earned-run average in his past four starts, is starting to turn
into the No. 1 starter the Athletics have long expected him to be.
With Tim Hudson pitching well and Mark Mulder, last year's No. 1
pick, getting closer, this franchise could turn into a powerhouse
if the new owners can muster enough money to keep their young
talent together.
</P>
<P>
   Braves right-hander John Smoltz is on the disabled list with
more elbow problems. He has had two operations on the elbow since
1994 and said he's considering retiring after his contract expires
in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Trachsel of the Cubs is 0-8 with a 9.41 ERA in his past
nine starts. The team record for a losing streak is 13, set by
Robert McCall in 1948.
</P>
<P>
   Astros interim manager Matt Galante said the Cincinnati Reds are
for real: ``When you see Pokey Reese play the way he's playing,
that's for real. You see \RScott\S Williamson and \RDanny\S Graves
pitch, that's for real. And you've got your mainstays, like
\RBarry\S Larkin _ who's better?''
</P>
<P>
   San Diego pitcher Andy Ashby, who used to pitch for Colorado,
had allowed 15.81 runs per game at Coors Field before his shutout
there Sunday. Said Ashby, ``I have no bad feeling toward the
Rockies. But I thank God every day that they traded me.''
</P>
<P>
   The Marlins gave 16-year-old Venezuelan shortstop Miguel Cabrera
a $1.8 million signing bonus. They say he would have been a high
first-round pick if he had been eligible for the draft, and he
could ease the pain if the Marlins can't sign Spring High pitcher
Josh Beckett, the second overall pick of the draft.
</P>
<P>
   Go figure. The Phillies set a team record with 41 runs scored
(14-1, 21-8 and 6-2) in a three-game sweep of the Cubs last
weekend. Immediately after that, they were blanked by the Brewers'
duo of Jim Abbott and Rafael Roque, who both have ERAs over 5.80.
</P>
<P>
   \Nsubheds:Inside the numbers \Nsubheds:Bullpen toughness Jeff
Zimmerman of the Rangers entered the weekend with the lowest
batting average allowed among relief pitchers in all of baseball.
The list: Pitcher, team H-AB Avg. American League Jeff Zimmerman
18-164 .110 Troy Percival, Angels 14-109 .128 Mariano Rivera,
Yankees 22-121 .182 Billy Koch, Blue Jays 22-116 .190 Jason
Grimsley, Yankees 34-166 .205 C.J. Nitkowski, Tigers 23-111 .207
Mike Venafro, Rangers 27-129 .209 Doug Brocail, Tigers 35-164 .213
Keith Foulke, White Sox 42-194 .216 John Wasdin, Red Sox 34-156
.218 National League Armando Benitez, Mets 17-147 .116 Billy
Wagner, Astros 16-135 .119 Pedro Borbon, Dodgers 16-110 .145 Dennis
Cook, Mets 20-130 .154 Scott Williamson, Reds 32-193 .166 Jason
Christiansen, Pirates 17-101 .168 John Johnstone, Giants 24-136
.176 Dennys Reyes, Reds 21-119 .176 Alan Embree, Giants 21-115 .183
Matt Mantei, Diamondbacks 24-129 .186 acquired from the Marlins on
Friday
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
