<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBO-COACHES-PAY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOW PAY, WORKLOAD TAKE TOLL ON TEXAS HIGH SCHOOL COACHES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STACY FEDUCIA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Trimble Tech High School head football coach
Gerry Magin could not answer the telephone last week.
</P>
<P>
   He was out on the practice field, laying squares of sod.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the best place to catch him from June to August when
he's not teaching summer school is out on the tractor mowing that
field, in the fieldhouse painting the Bulldogs' locker room or in
the weight room, ensuring it's open to the public this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an unbelievable amount of work to deal with in this
district _ paperwork, taking care of the field, the fieldhouse. We
don't want to come across like we're whining, but it would be nice
to be paid for those extra days,'' said Magin, entering his second
season as the Bulldogs' athletic coordinator, head football coach
and head wrestling coach.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of extra-duty-days' pay and the burden of noncoaching
duties on top of a full course load have combined to make football
coaching in Fort Worth a revolving-door profession. The district
has hired new head coaches for all 12 of its varsity football
programs in the past three years.
</P>
<P>
   Although some of those coaches have been reassigned for reasons
ranging from rules violations to low participation rates and others
have resigned for health or personal reasons, all have expressed
disgruntlement. Finding high-quality coaches or replacing departed
assistants becomes increasingly difficult when most other large
districts offer extra-duty days as compensation.
</P>
<P>
   Fort Worth athletic director Paul Galvan is attempting to
address the situation. He has submitted a proposal to the school
board to add 10 extra days to the standard 187-day teaching
contract for campus athletic coordinators or head football coaches
and five extra days for all other team sports coaches and their
assistants. Fort Worth school-board trustees are considering the
proposals in the 1999-2000 budget. A public hearing on the budget
is scheduled for Aug. 10, and the trustees will vote on it Aug. 24.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our basketball coaches work during Thanksgiving and Christmas
holidays. Baseball, softball and track \Rcoaches\S work during
spring break. All these programs have additional days,'' Galvan
said. ``We've gotten a lot of support from the superintendent and
the board for improving facilities for the kids. Let's look at
doing something for the people that work the long hours with these
kids.''
</P>
<P>
   School superintendent Dr. Thomas Tocco said he sympathizes with
the coaches and hopes that a board-commissioned study of statewide
salaries and wages will provide objective evidence of
discrepancies. That study, which will analyze the pay structure of
everyone from maintenance workers to assistant principals, should
be completed within eight months, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be the first to admit that if there were sufficient money,
it'd be helpful to have them at a stipend level that is
commensurate with the number of hours and the number of days it
takes to fulfill that responsibility,'' Tocco said. ``As a general
statement, if we are not doing something this year, it's unlikely
that we will be doing it next year because of the tightness of the
budget.''
</P>
<P>
   Football coaches in Fort Worth are paid a $7,241 stipend for the
after-school duties they perform during the duration of their
187-day standard teaching contract. However, they report a minimum
of 10 days early to begin two-a-days in August, and, like Magin,
all are required to work throughout the summer to keep their fields
weeded, mowed and open to the public.
</P>
<P>
   If they worked in Austin, the football coaches wouldn't be
required to mow the fields this summer.
</P>
<P>
   If they coached in Dallas, they might not be teaching a full
course load next fall.
</P>
<P>
   If they coached in any other large district in the state, they'd
be paid for all the extra days they work. \Nsubheds:Reasons for
discontent In discussions with Fort Worth head football coaches,
three key issues emerge that they say makes coaching in the city
difficult and offers from other districts more attractive:
</P>
<P>
   The lack of extra-duty-days' pay. Fort Worth is the only large
school district in the state that does not compensate coaches for
the extra days they work in addition to their stipend.
</P>
<P>
   The extra workload required. Fort Worth coaches are required to
maintain their fields and fieldhouses during the summer months when
they are not covered by their 187-day teaching contract.
</P>
<P>
   The full course load. Fort Worth head football coaches are
typically competing against rural and suburban schools that do not
require their coaches to teach full course loads in addition to
their athletic periods.
</P>
<P>
   As a head football coach in Fort Worth, Magin earns a flat
stipend of $7,241 in addition to his teaching salary. His
assistants receive a stipend of $2,576, which is defined as pay for
after-school responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
   A teacher with 20 years of experience, Magin earns $197 per day
over the course of his 187-day teaching contract. With 10
extra-duty days, he would see an increase of close to $2,000 in his
coaching pay. Apart from his teaching schedule, Magin calculates
that for football he works an additional 860 hours per year _
including as many as 40 extra days in the summer _ at a rate of
roughly $8.40 per hour.
</P>
<P>
   He calculates that his assistants work about 550 additional
hours and average around $4.70 per hour.
</P>
<P>
   The McDonald's on Berry Street in Fort Worth is hiring part-time
workers starting at $6.50.
</P>
<P>
   The opportunity for additional income was one reason head
football coaches Billy Hall and Don Morland left Southwest and
Eastern Hills, respectively, in May to become assistants at
programs outside the Fort Worth district.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a pay raise and a smaller course load, but those are
little bitty things,'' Hall said, explaining his move from Class 4A
Southwest to Class 3A Alvarado. ``It's a great opportunity for me
to get back to the kids. In football when you have to do all the
maintenance and the paperwork, you cut down on coach-kid time and
that's what you really love doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Morland left a playoff team with nine returning starters to
become assistant head coach at Azle. In leaving, he cited working
at brand new facilities and not having to complete reams of
administrative paperwork that come with being the head football
coach/athletic coordinator in Fort Worth. \Nsubheds:Statewide
solutions The San Antonio Northside school district is the state's
sixth-largest district, serving approximately 63,000 students with
seven Class 5A high schools, compared with Fort Worth's 78,000
students with 13 high schools and 12 varsity programs.
</P>
<P>
   The Northside board recently passed an athletic department
proposal that restructures the coaching contract away from flat
stipends and toward ``the most equitable system,'' Northside
athletic director Dub Farris said.
</P>
<P>
   The department created a model schedule based on the
UIL-determined seasons for each sport and calculated the number of
extra days needed for each sport, ranging from four to 31. Four
two-hour practice days constitute one extra day, therefore a
football coach would be compensated 10 extra days at minimum for
the 10 weeks of the regular football season. One game day is
considered one extra day, so a volleyball coach would be
compensated for the team playing in a Saturday tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``If their teaching contract says they work 187 days but they
begin practicing before school starts because of UIL rules, they
should be paid for it,'' Farris said. ``I think it's selfish of the
district to think they're going to get people to go out and do
those jobs and not pay them.''
</P>
<P>
   Arlington and Birdville are among area school districts
considering proposals to fund additional days for coaches.
</P>
<P>
   Using a survey of like-sized school systems that was sponsored
by the Texas Association of School Boards, Arlington athletic
director James Hyden found 10 days to be a minimum, while some
districts guarantee pay for as many as 25 extra days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those that are paying 10 are also paying a bigger stipend,''
Hyden said. ``I think it helps you get a more quality coach, and
you don't get the young, real good coach who stays for only three
or four years and then moves for that 10 extra days.''
</P>
<P>
   The Austin school district pays its head football coaches a
$7,248 stipend _ almost identical to Fort Worth _ but Austin
coaches also receive 25 extra days of pay and, starting this
season, they will not have to mow their fields.
</P>
<P>
   Unhappy with the maintenance department's handling of the fields
in the late 1980s, Fort Worth coaches requested campus-based
equipment to mow the fields themselves, making them responsible for
all practice fields at their high schools and feeder middle
schools. If the fields become weed-infested and overgrown during
the summer _ or even during the school year _ coaches receive a
written notice from the district.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to school so I wouldn't have to do any landscaping,''
Ruben Calderon, the Diamond Hill-Jarvis head football and head
basketball coach, said with a laugh. ``It's hard to tell a coach to
be here in the summer to mow a field. What if I have a coach with
another job who is bringing in additional income in the summer?
What do you say to him?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not asking for a raise. We're just asking to be paid for
the work we're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Based on the 1998-99 compensation schedule, a grounds worker for
the Fort Worth school district can earn a minimum of $7.89 per hour
and a maximum of $13.04. A head football coach's hourly rate falls
on the lower end of that range, but an assistant coach could
consider grounds work as a promotion.
</P>
<P>
   Like other district coaches, Magin's stipend-based $8.40 an hour
is meted out over an additional 40-hour, after-school work week
that encompasses conducting daily two-hour practices; attending
middle school, freshman and junior varsity football games; scouting
films of upcoming opponents; cleaning the toilets after games; and,
of course, mowing the Bulldogs' one field. \Nsubheds:Reduced
teaching load The extra workload is a given in an urban school
district, but it comes on top of the requirement that coaches teach
four 50-minute classes per day in a traditional schedule or three
90-minute classes per day in a block schedule. That doesn't include
duties coaches might assume as the campus athletic coordinator who
is responsible for UIL eligibility forms, daily practice reports
and other documentation for every boys and girls athletic activity
on campus _ all for $1,500 with no extra days.
</P>
<P>
   In Fort Worth, neither campus academic coordinators nor
vocational coordinators are required to teach classes.
</P>
<P>
   To put its coaches on even footing with opponents, the Dallas
school district has proposed removing the campus athletic
coordinator _ typically the head football or boys basketball coach
_ from the classroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``You study what other districts are doing and their campus
athletic directors are not having to teach classes,'' Dallas
assistant superintendent Troy Mathieu said. ``You don't just want
your kids to participate. You want them to have every opportunity
to reach their potential. We think taking the campus athletic
directors out of the few classes they do have will help bring
better control to the department and make a more efficiently run
campus.''
</P>
<P>
   Wyatt head football coach Anthony Criss believes a reduced
course load would make Fort Worth schools more competitive. The
first Fort Worth school to win a playoff game since 1996, Wyatt was
defeated in the second round last fall by eventual 1998 Class 4A
Division I champion Grapevine.
</P>
<P>
   Wyatt and first-round opponent Dallas South Oak Cliff were the
only two of Grapevine's five playoff opponents whose coaches taught
full course loads.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are expected to compete with those people who are given
more time,'' Criss said. ``Seventy thousand dollars is not going to
make me a better coach, but having eight hours of preparation time
a day vs. three hours of preparation time a day ``will'' make me a
better coach.''
</P>
<P>
   Tocco, meanwhile, said coaches will remain teachers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every coach must be a teacher,'' he said. ``That is an issue
that will not get resolved any time soon in this system.''
</P>
<P>
   In his second year at Dunbar, head coach Bob Jones was courted
by nationally ranked Clovis West High School in Clovis, Calif. He
turned down the lucrative offer because he wouldn't be able to
bring along his team of assistants, but the offers keep coming for
young, talented coaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't spend the extra time, we're behind everybody we
play and we can't be successful,'' Jones said. ``It doesn't become
a big thing until you're not getting paid to be here a month before
school starts.''
</P>
<P>
   Until that time, he and his peers will be out on their tractors,
mowing the fields.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
