<HEADLINE>
ANGELS WIN FOURTH STRAIGHT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ As outfielders Jim Edmonds and Tim Salmon get closer to
returning to the lineup, the Angels are playing more like the team
many expected them to be when the season began.
</P>
<P>
   They won their fourth in a row Saturday, beating the Colorado
Rockies 9-3 before 48,069 at Coors Field. It was their fourth
consecutive win, their sixth in eight games and their 11th in 17.
</P>
<P>
   In the process, they moved to within 6{ games of first-place
Texas in the AL West, the closest they've been since June 27. They
have a chance to reduce their deficit even more today and head into
the All-Star break on a roll.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels had 13 hits Saturday, giving them 28 in the two games
at Coors Field. Garret Anderson had three hits (including a home
run) for the third game in a row. In the past 13 games, he has six
three-hit games.
</P>
<P>
   Darin Erstad also had three hits and Matt Walbeck had two,
including a two-run triple in the fourth inning that gave the
Angels the lead for good.
</P>
<P>
   Troy Glaus had two hits, including his 15th homer of the season.
He has three homers in the past two games and four in the month of
July.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' Angels manager Terry Collins said when asked
to explain the offensive turnaround. ``We have been swinging better
and we're at Coors Field. You've got to put the ball in play here
and if you do it you're going to get hits.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels were hitting before coming to Colorado, though. In
eight games in July, they are hitting .329 (95 for 289) and
averaging 7.3 runs per game.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels also got another solid outing by starting pitcher
Omar Olivares (8-6), who gave up three runs and six hits in eight
innings coming off a complete game in his last start. Rockies
starter Pedro Astacio (8-8) got the loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to keep competing here,'' said Olivares, who
allowed three runs in the third but worked out of jams in the first
and seventh. ``I got ground balls when I needed them and double
plays when I needed them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough for everybody to pitch here. But I was able to hit
the corners and spot the ball where I wanted. Usually when you have
control you're successful.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I always knew he could pitch, but he's pitched as good as I've
ever seen him _ and I've seen him pitch for a long time,'' Collins
said. ``I've seen his sinker better, but his pitch selection and
location are better now.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson got the Angels started with a home run (No.13) leading
off the second inning. He has his average up to .293, the highest
it's been in more than a month (.296 on June 7).
</P>
<P>
   But he says his confidence isn't any higher than it always is.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't hit on confidence,'' he said. ``I hit on being a
hitter. Going up and having a plan and letting the chips fall where
they may. Otherwise, you have (ups and downs). I try to stay on an
even keel.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels' season hasn't been anything but steady, but they are
happy with their current direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to get back (to .500) to start,'' Collins said.
``Until then, we've just got to keep playing. We can't worry about
anything but what we're doing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
