<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDMONDS' REHAB SPEEDS UP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Jim Edmonds continues to surprise everybody with his
rapid recovery from shoulder surgery, and after initially expected
to be out until mid-August, he could be back before the end of the
month.
</P>
<P>
   Next week, Edmonds will take batting practice off live pitching
along with Tim Salmon (sprained left wrist) provided their are no
setbacks.
</P>
<P>
   A rehab assignment would follow and probably last about a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel better than I ever expected to be (at this point),''
Edmonds said. ``(Friday) I was swinging (off a tee) as hard as I
could. I think I surprised them.''
</P>
<P>
   Edmonds credits his rapid recovery to the aggressive rehab work
he did with Dr. David Bradley at Newport Physical Therapy in
Newport Beach. And it helps that the shoulder involved is his
right, non-throwing shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing I'm concerned about is my swing... and running
into walls,'' Edmonds said.
</P>
<P>
   In other injury updates:
</P>
<P>
   Pitcher Jack McDowell, recovering from elbow surgery Feb. 2,
made his second rehab appearance Saturday for Triple-A Edmonton
against Oklahoma. He gave up a three-run homer among six hits in
six innings.
</P>
<P>
   Pitcher Ken Hill (inflamed right elbow) threw for 20 minutes
Saturday and felt ``diminished pain'' according to manager Terry
Collins. He's eligible to come off he disabled list July 16, but he
isn't expected to return to the rotation by then. He's scheduled to
throw again next Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Glaus supporter: Troy Glaus hit only .130 in May and .227 in
June, but never was in danger of being sent to the minors _ unlike
Todd Greene _ because of his defense.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, he's hitting .236 with 15 homers and 40 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   ``You tell me who we have in this locker room who can hit like
he's hit and who can play third and catch the ball like he has,''
Collins said. ``You find me someone who can do that, and I'll send
(Glaus) to the minors.''
</P>
<P>
   Glaus is beginning to hit again, much like he did in April when
he was at .341 with five homers and 16 RBI. In his first eight
games in July, Glaus is hitting .300 with four homers and 10 RBI.
He hit two homers Friday night against the Rockies and another
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've hit some balls hard that have been caught and hit some
soft that were hits,'' Glaus said. ``I'm contributing to the team
winning, which is all I can ask for.''
</P>
<P>
   Even during the tough times, Glaus said he never doubted his
ability to snap out of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was always a light at the end of the tunnel,'' he said.
``You put in time, effort and work, you'll have change. That was
all I could do. Even with a 0-for-4, if I'm prepared I know I did
all I could do that day.''
</P>
</TEXT>
