<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELTRE'S HIT IN NINTH LIFTS DODGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The showdown between Kevin Brown and Ken Griffey,
Jr. was a dud Saturday night, and the Dodgers could not have been
happier.
</P>
<P>
   Two strikeouts, one pop out, and no drama. Just the way the
Dodgers wanted it as they sought their first three-game winning
streak in three months.
</P>
<P>
   They got it, but not until the bottom of the ninth, when Adrian
Beltre's RBI single gave the Dodgers a 2-1 victory over the Seattle
Mariners in front of 50,813 at Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Beltre, who made a brilliant defensive play on a bunt attempt in
the eighth inning, blooped a base hit off Jose Paniagua (6-8) over
the head of shortstop Alex Rodriguez that scored Devon White.
</P>
<P>
   It made a winner of closer Jeff Shaw (2-2), who took over for
Brown to start the ninth inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers thought Brown, who allowed just two hits, might get
his first victory in three starts after he was lifted for pinch
hitter Dave Hansen to open the eighth against Mariners reliever
Jose Paniaqua.
</P>
<P>
   Hensen singled and moved to second on a sacrifice. He was lifted
for pinch runner Trenidad Hubbard, and the Dodgers had runners at
first and second after Eric Young walked.
</P>
<P>
   With Mark Grudzielanek at the plate, Hubbard took off for third.
He had the base stolen, but his momentum carried him off the bag
after a pop-up slide and third baseman Charles Gipson applied the
tag.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers manager Davey Johnson argued, but replays supported
third base umpire Gerry Davis. Grudzielanek, the home run hero of
Friday's victory, grounded to short to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners had a chance to win it in the ninth against Shaw,
who allowed a leadoff single to Brian Hunter. David Bell popped
out, bringing Griffey to the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw struck him out, the sixth time in two games Griffey went
down on strikes. Shaw walked the next batter, Rodriguez, but got
out of the inning when David Segui lined to right.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, whose poor showing in his two previous starts probably
cost him a spot on the National League All-Star team, walked one
and struck out seven. He gave up a home run to David Segui with one
out in the second inning, then walked the next batter Butch Huskey.
But he retired 20 of the next 21 batters and allowed the Dodgers to
stay close.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, who cut his ERA from 3.67 to 3.53, didn't get much
support. The Dodgers had a runner on base in each of the first four
innings against Mariners starter John Halama, who entered the game
4-2 overall and 4-0 as a starter.
</P>
<P>
   But Halama, acquired last July in the big Randy Johnson trade,
was almost as stingy as Brown. The Dodgers didn't score until the
fourth when Eric Karros doubled and later scored on a sacrifice fly
by slumping Raul Mondesi, who had just two RBI in his last seven
games.
</P>
<P>
   Halama allowed just one base runner in his final three innings,
when Karros reached on a fielding error by Gipson with two outs in
the sixth. But Karros was picked off to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Karros returned to the lineup after being given Friday off by
Johnson. All the Dodgers' top players have been rested in an effort
to shake things up, but the move surprised Karros after hitting two
homers Thursday in Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is a much different philosophy from the managers in the
past,'' said Karros, who is batting .367 in his last 16 games.
``But put it this way, it's easy to understand when things aren't
going well.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown's biggest concern was getting himself back on track. He
was coming off two of his poorer starts with the Dodgers, allowing
15 runs in 12 2/3 innings to the Giants and Padres.
</P>
<P>
   Most pitchers throw on the side once between starts. But since
Monday's 8-4 loss at Coors Field, Brown has thrown twice in an
attempt to smooth his mechanics. His last session went 45 minutes,
about three times longer than usual.
</P>
<P>
   Brown even had catcher Todd Hundley stand in the left-handed
batter's box and critique his pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kevin is a perfectionist,'' said pitching coach Claude Osteen,
who had the same role at Texas in 1993-94 when Brown pitched for
the Rangers. ``The velocity is going to be there, but when you're
off just a little the hitters will make you pay. He is taking the
team's struggles very personally. He knows only one way to make it
stop.''
</P>
</TEXT>
