<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OSTEEN: DREIFORT MAKING PROGRESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Darren Dreifort, making his 17th and final start
of the first half today against Seattle, is showing signs of
improvement, says pitching coach Claude Osteen.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to tell from his 6-8 record and 5.79 ERA. But in his
last four starts, Dreifort has an ERA of 3.90 (11 earned runs,
251/3 innings pitches) even though he is 1-3. Dreifort also has
shown better control, walking two batters in his last two starts
and seven in his last four. In his third start of the year,
Dreifort walked nine.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't just look at the numbers, you'll see he is
becoming more of a pitcher,'' Osteen said. ``He's been working on a
changeup and is getting better with it. He used to use his slider
as his offspeed pitch. It was a good pitch for him and it's hard to
go away from. But now he has another option.''
</P>
<P>
   Dreifort allowed five runs and nine hits in last Tuesday's 5-2
loss at Colorado. He left after giving up three singles that
resulted in two runs in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   Dreifort has left many people wondering when he will stop being
known as a ``kid pitcher.'' He was drafted in 1993 and is a year
older than more established starters Chan Ho Park and Ismael
Valdes.
</P>
<P>
   But there was elbow surgery and a long debate on whether he
should start or relieve. He had great movement on his fastball, but
it never seemed to work to his advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's OK for a closer or setup man,'' Osteen said. ``But for
a starter, hitters will make you throw strikes. Darren is learning
that now.''
</P>
<P>
   !arrow!Roar of the crowd:!off! A night after hitting a three-run
homer, recording a career-high four RBI and making a run-saving
diving catch, shortstop Mark Grudzielanek was still on a roll.
</P>
<P>
   In his first at-bat, Grudzielanek singled to give him eight hits
in 15 at-bats since coming off the disabled list. And for the first
time since joining the Dodgers last July 31, Grudzielanek received
a lift from the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard the cheers and I really appreciate it,'' said
Grudzielanek, who batted second Saturday after leading off on
Friday. ``With this season there hasn't been a lot to cheer, but
it's nice to know they recognize the effort.''
</P>
<P>
   Grudzielanek, who once hit 54 doubles in a season for Montreal,
never has had an offensive presence with the Dodgers. He admits
that has been frustrating, but thinks his time on the DL (broken
right hand) has helped his game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It enabled me to take a step back and re-evaluate,'' he said.
``It made me realize that maybe I have to relax more. I haven't hit
here like I hit there and that has been difficult. I've always been
aggressive at the plate, but that hurt me. I wanted to do well and
started swinging at bad pitches. The time off has allowed me to
take a step back.''
</P>
<P>
   Quick hits: Antonio Osuna (elbow) reported no discomfort after
throwing 12/3 innings Friday in a rehab outing at Single-A San
Bernardino. The club will have Osuna throw today and Tuesday for
San Bernardino and hopes to activate him for Thursday's series
opener against the Angels. . . . Today's Seattle starter, Jeff
Fassero, might be coming off eight shutout innings against the
Angels, but he is the sixth pitcher in major-league history to
allow as many as 27 home runs before the All-Star break. Twice in
his career, Bert Blyleven gave up 30 homers before the break (1986
and 1987). Phil Niekro gave up 29 (1970), as did Ferguson Jenkins
(1973). Catfish Hunter was touched for 27 homers (1973). Back in
1957, Washington Senators left-hander Pedro Ramos gave up 27.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
