<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-VERMONT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFENDING VERMONT'S VIRTUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Vermont'' on the label sells the product _ even if the product
is made in Japan. So it goes with ``Vermont Curry,'' which, loaded
with apples and honey though it may be, comes from a factory way
east of Montpelier.
</P>
<P>
   Crafty marketers have also pushed ``Vermont Maple Orchards''
syrup from a factory in Canada, packets of Vermont flower seeds out
of Louisiana, and a cologne called ``Vermontage'' that's made in
New Jersey. (They couldn't call it ``Essence of Bayonne''?)
</P>
<P>
   Vermont is right to get cranky about this, although state
officials may have a tough time proving consumer fraud in the
courts. Still, their effort to strengthen state regulations
regarding misleading labeling sends a much needed message to the
world of commerce: Don't sell what isn't yours.
</P>
<P>
   Ignoring that message could cost a company a $10,000 fine in
Vermont and a load of bad publicity.
</P>
<P>
   Advertising has always stretched the truth, selling the image of
a glamorous life in a lipstick tube or athletic prowess in a soft
drink can. But such nonsense passes as fantasy, with the poetic
license of the huckster allowing for ad copy that promises, say,
``that fresh Vermont feeling,'' or an experience ``just like a trip
to the Green Mountains.''
</P>
<P>
   Deliberately trying to trick the public is something else, and
indicating that a product is ``Vermont made'' when it isn't crosses
what should be a clear ethical line.
</P>
<P>
   The consumer has a responsibility here too: to read the fine
print, usually on the back, way down at the bottom, where the
manufacturer's address can be found.
</P>
<P>
   This bogus selling of Vermont is, of course, a backhanded
compliment to the state that is embedded in the national
consciousness as the home of all things wholesome. What the
usurpers don't realize _ or maybe they don't care _ is that they
destroy a little piece of the public's trust in Vermont's virtue
every time they misrepresent it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-11-99 0209EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
