A5897 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDITORIAL-HILLARY-BOS     07-11 0380
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-HILLARY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KIBITZING ON JERUSALEM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   All politicians pander at one time or another, so Hillary
Clinton's assurance to the president of the Union of Orthodox
Jewish Congregations of America that Jerusalem is the ``eternal and
indivisible capital of Israel'' and that the US Embassy should move
as soon as possible from Tel Aviv to Jerusalem may simply be the
telltale sign that she has finally decided to turn pro as a
politician.
</P>
<P>
   In her compulsion to say precisely what a sector of the New York
electorate wants to hear, Clinton is no worse than other pols who
have pronounced the same pandering phrases. What sets her version
apart is the piquancy of a first lady contradicting her husband and
his administration's prudent policy _ that the political status of
Jerusalem is to be decided in final-status negotiations between
Israel and the Palestinians and should not be prejudged by any
symbolic American gesture.
</P>
<P>
   In the Middle East there is no doubt that whatever formula the
two parties agree upon, Jerusalem will be Israel's capital. The
challenge facing the negotiators will be to devise an arrangement
that allows both Israel and the Palestinians to claim a capital in
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   This is doable, and if Israel's new prime minister, Ehud Barak,
can accomplish what he has set out to accomplish, it will be done.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to Barak's task of negotiating an accord on
Jerusalem that satisfies both peoples, Hillary Clinton's opinion is
just so much kibitzing. She was trying to compensate for having
said last year that it is ``in the long-term interests of the
Middle East for Palestine to be a state.'' To political
consultants, this was a flagrant no-no. Never mind that as obdurate
a hawk as Ariel Sharon has said that a Palestinian state is
inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   But all sides make fools of themselves on this issue. James
Zogby of the Arab American Institute said: ``Those in the Jewish
community pressuring politicians to take such positions are
damaging the search for peace and damaging American interests and
American leadership.'' This is hyperbolic nonsense.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, most of these parochial posturings have no effect in
the Middle East.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-11-99 0214EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
