<HEADER>
A5902 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DODGERS-WRITETHRU     07-11 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS WIN ON BELTRE'S HIT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A hero was emerging in the late innings Saturday
night and it wasn't Kevin Brown or Ken Griffey, Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Brown was gone and Griffey shut down by the time Adrian Beltre
stepped to the plate with two outs in the ninth inning and the
winning run at second.
</P>
<P>
   His single gave the Dodgers a 2-1 victory over the Seattle
Mariners that marked the club's first three-game winning streak in
more than two months.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important to me that the team looks to me in situations
like that,'' Beltre said. ``We can't expect (Gary) Sheffield or
Raul Mondesi to do it for us every night. If we are going to pull
out of this thing, everybody has to contribute.''
</P>
<P>
   For the Dodgers, Beltre's single was the play of the night,
giving Jeff Shaw (2-2) the victory after Brown limited the Mariners
to two hits in eight innings. But it was Beltre's amazing
off-balance throw from third on an eighth-inning bunt by Charles
Gipson that stirred the Dodger Stadium crowd of 50,813 and truly
showed the depth of his talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is just playing with so much confidence right now,'' second
baseman Eric Young said of Beltre, who is batting .302 in his last
11 games. ``You can just see it in the way he carries himself right
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown didn't seem to mind the no decision just as long as the
team got the victory. He twice struck out Griffey, who fanned six
times in the first two games of the series.
</P>
<P>
   Brown didn't think he pitched much better than his last outing,
when he allowed six runs in 62/3 innings against Colorado. This
time, he only gave up a home run to David Segui in the second and a
one-out double to Tom Lampkin in the fifth. Brown retired 20 of the
final 21 batters he faced.
</P>
<P>
   ``A game like this is proof what can happen when you make good
pitches and get a few breaks,'' said Brown, who walked one and
struck out seven. ``It also shows what we are capable of in the
second half. There is no need to look back on what already has
happened.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers (38-47) still are 11 games behind San Francisco in
the National League West. But a victory today in the final game
before the All-Star break and a Colorado loss to the Angels could
pull the Dodgers even with the Rockies and out of fifth place for
the first time in two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners had a chance to win it in the ninth against Shaw,
who allowed a leadoff single to Brian Hunter. David Bell popped
out, bringing Griffey to the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw struck him out but walked the next batter, Alex Rodriguez.
He retired Segui on a liner to Mondesi in right that ended the
inning.
</P>
<P>
   Mondesi, who has hit just one homer in his last 132 at-bats,
also played a critical role in the ninth. Although he is not
hitting, Mondesi's walk off Jose Paniagua (6-8) moved Devon White
to second and set up Beltre's winning single.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought that was a key at-bat in the inning,'' Shaw said.
``Mondy hasn't been hitting for power, but he showed great patience
there. It paid off and put the winning run in a position to
score.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown, whose poor showing in his two previous starts probably
cost him a spot on the National League All-Star team, cut his ERA
from 3.67 to 3.53, but didn't get much support. The Dodgers had a
runner on in each of the first four innings against Mariners
starter John Halama, who entered the game 4-2 overall and 4-0 as a
starter.
</P>
<P>
   But Halama, acquired last July in the big Randy Johnson trade,
was almost as stingy as Brown. The Dodgers scored their only other
run in the fourth when Eric Karros doubled and scored on a
sacrifice fly by Mondesi, who had just two RBI in his last seven
games.
</P>
<P>
   Most pitchers throw on the side once between starts. But since
Monday's 8-4 loss at Coors Field, Brown has thrown twice in an
attempt to smooth his mechanics. His last session went 45 minutes,
about three times longer than usual.
</P>
<P>
   Brown even had catcher Todd Hundley stand in the left-handed
batter's box and critique his pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kevin is a perfectionist,'' said pitching coach Claude Osteen,
who had the same role at Texas in 1993-94 when Brown pitched for
the Rangers. ``The velocity is going to be there, but when you're
off just a little the hitters will make you pay. He is taking the
team's struggles very personally. He knows only one way to make it
stop.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
