<DOCNO> NYT19990711.0046 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-11 09:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5903 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WATCHDOGS-0712-COX     07-11 0870
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WATCHDOGS-0712-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    WATCHDOGS IN GOVERNMENT ARE HEARD BUT OFTEN IGNORED
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Inside almost every agency of the federal
government, outposts from an army of roughly 15,000 workers have a
mission to search and expose ways that taxpayers' money is
squandered.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators, auditors, inspectors general and congressional
overseers, at a cost of about $2 billion from the $1.7 trillion
budget, churn out their warnings of federal waste, abuse and fraud.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not clear who is listening and responding, especially
at a time when deficits are turning into surpluses.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, some reforms follow, but often only after hundreds
of millions of dollars have already found their way down various
rat holes.
</P>
<P>
   Among long-festering problems that have resurfaced in recent
weeks:
</P>
<P>
   The Energy Department and one of its contractors, Westinghouse,
spent a decade and nearly a half-billion dollars before deciding
last year that a chemical process for removing radioactive waste
from its Savannah River site near Aiken, S.C., was unworkable.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than safely separating the most concentrated waste, now
kept in underground storage tanks, the process produced explosive,
toxic benzene.
</P>
<P>
   Westinghouse is now working on an alternative method that would
cost up to $3.5 billion and which would not be in operation until
at least 2007. What's more, if that system doesn't work, the cost
could soar to $75 billion. That would equal all of federal aid to
elementary and secondary schools for five years.
</P>
<P>
   If this seems shocking to some, it is not to Victor S. Rezendes,
who directs studies of the Energy Department for the General
Accounting Office (GAO), a 3,300-person agency which is the
investigative arm of Congress and the largest single watchdog
agency in the government.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a surprise,'' Rezendes said last week of the
Savannah waste program, as he cited the history of the project.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent post-mortem of the Savannah River situation, the
General Accounting Office reviewed the history, which included
numerous warnings from an inspecting team from the agency starting
in the early 1990s, followed by a GAO report raising questions, as
well as critical reports from the Energy Department's inspector
general.
</P>
<P>
   In its response, the department has acknowledged ``weaknesses''
in its management and agreed to changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some reforms have been made,'' said Rezendes. ``But they are
not always effectively implemented.''
</P>
<P>
   _ At the Department of Housing and Urban Development (HUD),
officials have turned the throttle up on loans to rehabilitate
housing, despite repeated warnings that growing defaults could
threaten its $3.6 billion loan insurance fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``HUD is not adequately overseeing key aspects'' of the program,
said the GAO in a report last month that's the latest of a string
of critical federal reviews over four years. The accounting office
said that the regional ``Homeownership Centers'' in Atlanta,
Denver, Philadelphia and Santa Ana, Calif., were not properly
overseeing the loans and that some inspectors hired to oversee the
repairs have approved shoddy or incomplete work.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a similar report from the Housing Department's inspector
general two years ago, few changes have been made in the program,
which increased by eightfold in four years. HUD has disputed much
of the criticism. In its response to the GAO, the department called
the rehab program ``inherently riskier'' than other loan programs.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Pentagon has been under fire since 1970 for losing track
of vast amounts of property that it ships around the world. A GAO
report issued this month found the Defense Department had no
records for $2.7 billion worth of excess equipment shipped for
disposal last year.
</P>
<P>
   The poor record-keeping is especially wasteful, the accounting
office has reported, because useful items are sometimes destroyed
as surplus. An audit two years ago, for example, found that the
Army could have saved $200,000 by using Cobra helicopter parts that
were scheduled to be destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the apparent lack of progress, GAO spokesman Cleve
Corlett argued that such recommendations do pay off eventually.
</P>
<P>
   ``About three-fourths of our recommendations are implemented
within four years,'' Corlett said. His agency has claimed
responsibility for $19.7 billion in financial improvements last
year, which the GAO calculates as either saving money or putting
funds to better use.
</P>
<P>
   Those improvements represent $49 for every $1 that the General
Accounting Office spent over the past five years, Corlett said.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Rezendes acknowledged that progress can be glacial. He
noted that from 1980 through 1996, the Department of Energy had 80
major projects costing over $100 million, but it completed only 15,
most of them behind schedule and over budget. Thirty-one of the
projects were cancelled after expenditures of more than $10
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he was discouraged that agencies do not reform their
ways, he said wryly, ``That's how we make our living.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
