<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-11 13:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5949 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-IOWA12-COX     07-11 1159
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-IOWA12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush turns to Iowa for first votes
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ He's wooed the money and wowed the pollsters.
Now, front-runner George W. Bush goes to work to win votes from the
first people to cast ballots in the GOP presidential derby.
</P>
<P>
   Bush will campaign this week in eight cities in Iowa, where next
month's Republican straw poll could make or break some candidates,
even though the poll is more symbolic than substantive.
</P>
<P>
   For Bush, the Aug. 14 balloting offers a first test of his
middle-of-the-Republican-road effort to win the nomination of a
party heavy on social conservatives, including Iowa Christian
Coalition members who are mobilizing to play a big role.
</P>
<P>
   Though he does not mention names, Craig Bergman, the group's
executive director, makes it clear that Bush is not the Christian
Coalition's kind of candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Abortion, he said, remains ``a key factor among our
constituency.'' A ``supermajority'' of Iowa Christian Coalition
members, according to Bergman, wants a presidential candidate who
pledges to pick an anti-abortion running mate and appoint judges
who share that view. Bush has declined to make such a pledge. He
opposes abortion but says he would not work for a constitutional
amendment banning it because there is no public consensus on the
issue.
</P>
<P>
   While Bush is working Iowa on Thursday and Friday, Bergman's
organization will be working to connect its 15,000 members with the
presidential candidates they support. A survey will produce lists
that the group will share with the candidates, along with a
suggestion that the candidate transport those supporters to Ames
and pay the $25 cost of casting a straw vote.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush camp, predicting he will run first in the straw poll
despite a late start, does not believes it has anything to fear
from the Christian Coalition effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are getting a lot of support from Christian Coalition
members,'' said Bush spokesman David Beckwith. ``And in Iowa the
Christian Coalition is a force. We're in contact with them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Christian Coalition has flexed its political muscle at past
Iowa straw polls. In 1987, Pat Robertson won the poll and later
finished second in the 1988 Iowa GOP presidential caucuses.
</P>
<P>
   Several GOP candidates _ including Dan Quayle, Gary Bauer, Pat
Buchanan, Alan Keyes and Steve Forbes _ want to be this year's
candidate for social conservatives. Bergman said Christian
Coalition members would like to see that field narrowed.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are too many people in the race, and some of the lesser
qualified individuals should do the honorable thing after the straw
poll and join another campaign or go home,'' said Bergman, citing a
sentiment he said he frequently hears.
</P>
<P>
   Candidates expected to drop out after straw poll
</P>
<P>
   Odds also are good that the straw poll will shrink the field.
Candidates who already have had trouble raising money will find
that task even more difficult after an also-ran showing in Ames.
</P>
<P>
   That's why the straw poll is the show it is. The poll is
actually a fund-raiser for the Iowa Republican Party. Candidates
set up booths at the Ames coliseum to hawk their message and
memorabilia to anyone who pays $25 (or finds a candidate to pay the
$25 for them) to cast a ballot. There are few rules, and the
campaigns spend considerable effort lining up ``voters'' _ luring
them with free transportation, free entertainment and free food.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush team is negotiating with several country music stars.
Lamar Alexander's party will feature Crystal Gayle. ``It's as close
as you get to a political carnival,'' says Iowa political scientist
Arthur Miller.
</P>
<P>
   Beckwith said the event has become, thanks to Iowa GOP
self-promotion and media attention, a ``key test of determination
and organization.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And we're starting late. We have enormous popular support in
the state and our supporters are eager to compete and we're
determined to back them,'' he said. ``This isn't a caucus. A caucus
is bad enough. You sit there for four hours in the fire station.
This is give-up-an-entire-Saturday in the middle of summer.''
</P>
<P>
   And for some GOP candidates, it could become a
give-up-your-White-House dreams Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Not a single delegate will be at stake in Ames, but Miller
believes the event will narrow the field, perhaps to as few as one.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he wins big in that straw poll, that may be the end of the
contest right there,'' he said of Bush. ``Everything may be over.''
</P>
<P>
   And even if it isn't, it could be for some contenders. Among
those in harm's way is Alexander, who has campaign chairs in all 99
Iowa counties and former four-term Iowa Gov. Terry Branstad on his
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot is at stake for a lot of us,'' Alexander said last week
in Des Moines. ``I plan on making a stellar showing.''
</P>
<P>
   But he also wants the straw poll stakes to be high for Bush, who
has said he is in it to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything outside of a landslide for Bush is a big loss,'' said
Alexander spokesman Brian Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone wants to play
</P>
<P>
   The straw poll does not necessarily offer a sure forecast of
what will happen at Iowa's first-in-the-nation February caucuses.
Four years ago, Bob Dole and Phil Gramm each got 24 percent of the
straw-poll votes, putting them atop a 10-man field. By February,
Dole ran first and Gramm was a campaign-killing fifth with 9
percent. Gramm's strong straw poll showing was buoyed by his
successful effort to get non-Iowans to Ames, a ballot-stuffing game
played by several candidates.
</P>
<P>
   This year, new rules: Straw voters will have to prove they are
Iowans.
</P>
<P>
   Not all candidates are sure they want to play. Arizona Sen. John
McCain has declined to participate. Elizabeth Dole is unsure at
what level she will play.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to keep our powder dry before making any public
comment about resources we will devote to this straw poll,'' said
Dole spokesman Ari Fleischer. ``To be a meaningful election it
ought to be a fair fight not tilted by massive infusions from
checkbooks.''
</P>
<P>
   Forbes and Bush, the candidates with the most money, won't say
how much they will spend on the straw poll. Last week, both
campaigns bid for the best rally site outside the coliseum where
the straw vote will take place. Bush won at a previously unheard-of
$43,500. ``The whole idea of raising this money is so that we can
be competitive with anybody,'' said Beckwith, whose candidate has
more than $36 million in the bank. Forbes has raised more than $3
million, but has millions of his own money to spend _ and has shown
a willingness to do so in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Said Forbes operative Bob Haus, ``You could spend millions on
this thing if you aren't careful.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody is going to throw a big party to say thanks to
people who come down to spend a sweaty day in Ames in August,''
Haus said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
