<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EZZARD-COLUMN12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Is Georgia asleep in the forest?
 &HT;    By Martha Ezzard
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Congress acts in sneaky ways sometimes _ even
anti-democratic ways.
</P>
<P>
   An amendment, never aired or debated publicly, slithered through
the back door of a Senate Appropriations bill recently. It read
like legal gobbledy-gook, but its impact is pretty simple: It
affects whether our grandchildren will ever catch a native brook
trout or see a rare wildflower in the Chattahoochee National
Forest.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody in Georgia's congressional delegation needs to raise a
fuss about it. Here's what happened:
</P>
<P>
   In Sierra v. Martin, the U.S. Court of Appeals in Atlanta halted
seven logging projects in the Chattahoochee forest. The U.S. Forest
Service didn't follow its own rule, the court said, which requires
site-specific inventories of certain wildlife populations before
timber sales are approved. It's designed to assure that the rarest
wildlife don't become endangered. District officials also ignored
their 15-year-old management plan, which calls for a survey of
sensitive species. The Forest Service admitted that threatened
wildlife live in the proposed logging areas, and the agency didn't
appeal the court's ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Now some lawmakers want to void that court decision and make the
inventories optional for all national forests. A spokesman for
Forest Service Chief Mike Dombeck says the Clinton administration
strongly opposes the amendment.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed Dunaway Gap timber sale in northwest Georgia is an
example of why the site inventory makes sense. The Forest Service
said logging there would cause 30 tons of sediment to flow into the
East Armuchee Creek, the habitat for threatened mussels. Still,
there was no checking on the mussels. Officials said mussels (SET
ITAL)could(END ITAL) exist in other parts of the forest, so it
wasn't necessary. That's a little like telling your children rare
songbirds are probably (SET ITAL)somewhere(END ITAL) _ so don't
worry that you can't hear any.
</P>
<P>
   The suit was brought by several local and national environmental
groups, among which only the Sierra Club opposes timber sales on
forest lands. ``We don't want to shut logging down,'' said Bob
Kibler, a retired neurosurgeon who is president of the 1,000-member
Georgia Forest Watch. But the citizen groups are frustrated by
Washington's back-door tactic.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Alexander, chairman of the Rabun County Coalition, contacted
Georgia's U.S. senators, Paul Coverdell and Max Cleland, to ask
them to remove the amendment when the bill comes to the Senate
floor. Alexander hasn't heard back from either of them.
</P>
<P>
   Coverdell recently voted against a bill to stop taxpayer
subsidies for logging roads, so if he comes to the rescue of the
Chattahoochee forest, it would be a pleasant surprise. Coverdell
received $47,000 last year from timber-related industries, and
Cleland received $6,000. But Coverdell has supported the GOP push
for using real scientific data as the basis for environmental
decisions, which is what the surveys provide.
</P>
<P>
   Chattahoochee forest supervisor George Martin said he is not
allowed to lobby Congress, but he says he's trying to rewrite the
district plan to eliminate the site-specific inventories.
</P>
<P>
   He says other tools, such as ``habitat analysis,'' will do just
as well. Budget cuts won't allow his staff to do total inventories,
he claimed _ although the court's opinion doesn't say anything
about counting all the critters in the forest.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia has only one representative on the House Appropriations
Committee, where a similar amendment is being prepared. Republican
Rep. Jack Kingston received more timber industry PAC money last
year than anyone else in the current Georgia House delegation _ but
that doesn't mean he won't support giving Georgians a say on policy
that affects our forest so directly.
</P>
<P>
   Here's hoping he will.
</P>
<P>
   For more information on campaign contributions and the
environment, check the Environmental Working Group web site:
www.ewg.org
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
