<HEADER>
A5959 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SIDNEY-SLAYINGS12-COX     07-11 1577
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIDNEY-SLAYINGS12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A shooting changes a quiet town
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Downtown Sidney, Ohio, still boasts an
old-fashioned car hop at the beloved local restaurant, The Spot.
The decor is '50s-style, but folks have been coming to the ``Cook's
Spot,'' as it was originally known, since 1913.
</P>
<P>
   Car hop Holly Hall's brother owns The Spot, as her father did
before him. ``I was born and raised in Sidney,'' Hall said, ``and
when I was a kid we all slept with the front screen door open.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night, she shut and locked all her windows and doors
and turned on the air conditioning, even though it wasn't a hot
night. She sat transfixed as, all evening long, the TV scrolled the
advisory about Mike Hensley, telling residents to stay inside,
until the words ``heavily armed and very dangerous'' seemed branded
into her brain.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed like it ought to be a weather report,'' Hall said,
``and not a warning about a murderer on the loose.''
</P>
<P>
   Downtown Sidney still boasts stunning 19th-century architecture
and a true walking society, where friends need no better pretext
than a stroll to get together. Brad Wille, 21, and Josh King, 18,
had walked only a few blocks Thursday afternoon when they heard
``somebody screaming as loud as day,'' Wille recounted.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first, I thought it was a kid or something,'' he said. Then
came what sounded like a woman crying, `` Oh my God, my leg! My leg
!''
</P>
<P>
   ``We better check it out, Josh,'' Wille told his friend. They
cut through the yard to find a woman struggling to raise herself
from the vegetable garden where she had fallen. ``I've been shot in
the leg,'' the woman screamed, ``and there are two other girls in
the house and he killed them!''
</P>
<P>
   Wille and his friend didn't pause to consider whether they might
be in danger. They didn't feel fear so much as disbelief, a sense
of unreality. ``I had to look down at her leg to make sure it was
real,'' Wille said. The gaping hole in her pants leg, and the blood
streaking her arm and legs, made him realize, ``That's not fake.''
</P>
<P>
   A rush of adrenaline jolted them out of their trance. They
pounded on the back door of the next-door neighbor, who called 911.
After assuring the victim help was on the way, the men flagged down
a neighbor who turned out to be an off-duty police officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to give credit to the Sidney police and rescue,'' Wille
said. ``They were on it. They were there in under a minute.''
</P>
<P>
   Police give credit to the two young Samaritans, whose quick
thinking may have saved the life of Veronica Eagy, 22, who crawled
out of a basement window after the killer left her for dead. Eagy
was in fair condition late Saturday at Miami Valley Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did what was best,'' said Sidney Capt. Dean Kimpel.
``That tells you that, even though bad things happen, there are
still good people around.''
</P>
<P>
   Still shaken by the ordeal, Wille repeats the story; if he says
it often enough, perhaps, it will finally seem real.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night's horror seems impossibly incongruous with the
sense of well-being, of order, that permeates the town, named an
All-American City in 1964. The heart of the city is Court Square,
presided over by the magnificent 1881 limestone courthouse.
</P>
<P>
   Court Square is a classic Midwestern town square, a designated
National Historic Landmark. It is is flanked by the impressively
Gothic 1876 Monumental building, the first in Ohio to honor the
Civil War dead, and the eye-popping 1886 Louis Sullivan edifice,
the People's Federal Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Other than the modern cars and the shiny mower grazing the
courthouse's manicured lawn, you can almost imagine yourself in the
early part of the century. This is the America of church steeples
on every corner, of bountiful front porches and Fourth of July
parades that go on for hours. Traditions live on here that have
vanished elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   But there is one longtime hallmark of the town's character that
seems to be slowly vanishing:
</P>
<P>
   Trust.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a church-going person could up and do that, then you can't
trust anyone any more,'' said movie theater manager Wally Gibbs.
</P>
<P>
   Downtown Sidney still boasts an old-fashioned movie theater,
complete with deco-style marquee, little changed since its grand
opening in the '20s. In what passes for controversy in this town,
the balcony was converted into a two-screen theater in the '70s.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night, Gibbs did something far more radical in this
neighborly, open-door town: He closed and locked the theater doors,
so no one could get in after the show started.
</P>
<P>
   The doors were barred against a man who had been a fairly
regular customer, a man Gibbs knew by sight but not, until Thursday
night, by name. Mike Hensley, he said, ``seemed like a normal
person,'' like any other customer.
</P>
<P>
   Through all that interminable night, Gibbs fielded calls from
frantic parents of his young employees, begging their children to
come straight home after work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who would ever believe it would happen in an all-American
city?'' marveled Edna Stiefel.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are thinking this town isn't as safe as we thought,''
said Brad Wille. ``For a long time people thought this is a town
where you didn't have to worry about violence, but apparently, it's
not.''
</P>
<P>
   Townspeople talked of little else Friday. Rumors spread like
brush fires. The Sidney Daily News and Dayton Daily News sold out
everywhere; in the public library, patrons craned their necks to
read newspapers over each others' shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   Parents held their children tightly. Jamie Huecker, 22, lives a
few blocks from the house where the three teen-aged girls were
murdered. ``I'm freaking,'' said the mother of two toddlers. ``A
lot of people are going to be a lot more cautious as to who they
let their kids go visit, or what neighbors they will let them play
with.''
</P>
<P>
   She used to pick up the newspaper and tell herself, ``I'm glad I
don't live in Dayton.'' Now, she said, ``You're not safe anywhere.
Those girls were too young to die.''
</P>
<P>
   Angel Burns said she would also be more cautious with her
children. When she heard the news, however, she was anything but
surprised that Hensley, her classmate in the Sidney High School
class of '88, was the suspect.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it would be anybody in Sidney,'' she added, ``it doesn't
surprise me it was him.''
</P>
<P>
   Tosha Barrett, 16, one of the slain girls, was trusting,
outgoing, said her aunt, Brenda Stiver. ``She didn't think anybody
would hurt anybody,'' Stiver said.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Stiver wonders if anyone is safe anywhere. ``This is just a
small town,'' she said. ``If you can't control the violence in such
a small town, there is no control any more.''
</P>
<P>
   For months, Tosha and her sister Fawnda had lived with Stiver
and her husband Doyle, and 6-year-old daughter Cortnee who always
called her cousins her ``sisters.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Stiver has been crying so much that her face looks bruised.
``I just pray to God they catch him . . . ,'' she said. ``He's
still out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly everyone in this city of 19,000 knew one of the victims
or someone affected by the tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sidney is so small, this hits everybody,'' said Larry Boykin,
20. ``Amy Mikesell (another slain teen) was my little sister's best
friend in school.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Rosie Breen spoke wistfully of a recent conversation
with her neighbor Brett Wildermuth, the fourth victim in the
shooting rampage.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nobody in this world that's any nicer than those
people,'' Breen said of the Wildermuths.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two days ago, (Brett) was out here teaching his little
5-year-old how to ride her bicycle. He said, `Rosie, do you think
I'll ever teach her?' I said, `Sure you will.'''
</P>
<P>
   She paused and stared out at the spot in front of her home where
Wildermuth had been with his little girl. ``Well, he won't now,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Tom Miller doesn't want the people of Sidney to lose their
trust in each other or their community after the tragedy, which
follows an unusually high number of violent crimes over two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a small, quiet, nice town, we really are,'' Miller said.
``It's a community to be proud of. I'm fearful some of these
unrelated incidents have given us a name that we don't deserve.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite such qualms, city officials plan to cooperate with
producers of the television program ``America's Most Wanted,'' who
have expressed interest in the case. ``I hate the notoriety,''
Miller acknowledged, ``but it's more important that this guy gets
caught.''
</P>
<P>
   A veneer of normalcy returned to Sidney over the weekend.
Thursday's terror subsided with reports that Hensley had fled to
another state.
</P>
<P>
   Customers thronged to The Spot for the famous sky-high pies. The
movie theater unbolted its doors for screenings of ``Wild, Wild
West,'' ``American Pie'' and ``Tarzan.'' Gibbs turned his attention
back to small-time miscreants, teen-agers attempting to sneak into
R-rated movies.
</P>
<P>
   But people like Brad Wille, whose life intersected, briefly but
irrevocably, with the killer next door, wonder if they will ever be
the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never had any experience like that, and I hope I never do
again,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He wondered, too, if his town will ever be the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eventually, this will all blow over, and people will get on
with their lives,'' he said. ``But nobody is ever going to forget
it.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
