<HEADER>
A5966 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-BLOODY-SUNSET16     07-11 0470
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-BLOODY-SUNSET16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    True crime tale revived
 &HT;    By Michael Shashoua
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ Nancy Powell's reticence belies the nature
of her true-crime story, experienced nearly firsthand.
</P>
<P>
   Powell, once a St. Augustine reporter for the Florida
Times-Union, covered the brutal 1974 murder of Athalia Lindsley, a
prominent personality in the town. Now she's told that story at
length and in detail in ``Bloody Sunset in St. Augustine: A True
Story,'' co-authored with Jim Mast (251 pages, Federal Point
Publishing, $10).
</P>
<P>
   ``The response has been overwhelming,'' said Powell, who uses
the pseudonym Shannon Smith in the book, actually a manuscript
written not long after the murder and ensuing trial. She never
intended to tell the story with her own name on it.
</P>
<P>
   Athalia Lindsley had a career as a model in New York, dating
Joseph Kennedy Jr. (John F. Kennedy's older brother who died in
WWII) at one point. Even when she moved to Florida, settling down
somewhat in her marriage to a St. Augustinian named Jim Lindsley,
she never did quite settle down. Athalia antagonized many people in
the town, especially the city manager, Alan Stanford, whom she
vehemently criticized at public meetings over a host of issues.
</P>
<P>
   Both Stanford and Jim Lindsley became suspects in Athalia's
murder, but while Jim was cleared, Stanford was tried for the
crime, although he wasn't convicted. It's the lingering lack of an
answer to whodunnit that's at the crux of Powell's book. But she
herself shies away from venturing a guess.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel I know who did it, but if you read carefully, you can
draw your own conclusion,'' Powell said. ``There are people who say
Lindsley did it, even though he had two or three good alibis. There
are some will stand up and swear he did it.''
</P>
<P>
   The book has garnered interest from unexpected quarters. Even
some of the principals in the case have taken part in public
appearances for the book, first printed in December 1998. Judge
E.L. Eastmoor, who presided at Stanford's trial, signed copies of
the book when Powell appeared at the Barnes &AMP; Noble store in St.
Augustine this spring. Walter Arnold, Stanford's defense attorney,
has also signed copies of the book for readers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody sort of took it on,'' Powell said.
</P>
<P>
   Most surprising to Powell, however, has been the interest of
younger readers in the story.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've gotten just as many young (people) as older ones, who
might have actually heard about it. A lot of the people are dead,
some of the main characters, like Jim Lindsley. Everybody except
Alan Stanford.''
</P>
<P>
   (Michael Shashoua is books editor of the Daytona Beach (Fla.)
News-Journal.) ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-07-09-99 1536E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
