 AM-ADD-NYT-BUDGET  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Add N.Y. Times News Service budget for papers of Monday, July
12:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMNISTS (Moving in ``k'' category.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SAFIRE-COLUMN _ Details to come. By William Safire.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT (Moving in ``e'' category.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   KANSASCITY-MUSEUM _ The Nelson-Atkins Museum of Art in Kansas
City, Mo., has selected Steven Holl, the New York architect, winner
of the competition to design the museum's first expansion since its
opening in 1933. By Julie V. Iovine.
</P>
<P>
   SUMMER-BOOK-SURPRISE _ Hannibal Lecter and Harry Potter are
shaping up as the summer's must reads. Harry who? Hannibal the
cannibal is the title character of Thomas Harris' grisly new novel
who has appeared in two previous novels and two movies. But riding
broomstick high, right behind the ghoulish Dr. Lecter, is Harry
Potter, an orphan wizard with unruly hair and a lightning scar on
his forehead. This unusually adept pupil at Hogwarts School for
Witchcraft and Wizardry is the hero of two wildly successful
British children's novels by J.R. Rowling. By Eden Ross Lipson.
</P>
<P>
   OZ-TV-VIOLENCE _ Crucifixion. Cannibalism. Slow death by eating
glass. Sexual mutilation. Is there nothing Tom Fontana won't do on
his HBO prison series, ``Oz''? ``The problem with TV violence, it's
a lie,'' said Fontana, who writes most of the show's episodes and
is one of its executive producers, along with Barry Levinson and
Jim Finnerty. ``People get shot and don't bleed. They get hit and
walk away. If you have to do it, you have to do it as horrifically
as it really is.'' And Fontana is really trying as hard as he can.
By Dinitia Smith.
</P>
<P>
   TANGLEWOOD-OZAWA (Lenox, Mass.) _ The descriptive subtitle that
Beethoven provided for the first movement of his ``Pastorale''
Symphony reads, in English translation, ``Awakening of happy
feelings upon reaching the countryside.'' Perhaps by opening the
1999 summer season of the Boston Symphony Orchestra at Tanglewood
with the ``Pastorale'' the conductor Seiji Ozawa was hoping to
engender just such happy feelings among his players and the
orchestra's administration. They have all been through a lot
lately. By Anthony Tommasini.
</P>
<P>
   PROSECUTION-BOOK-REVIEW _ Christopher Lehmann-Haupt reviews
``The Prosecution: A Legal Thriller,'' by D.W. Buffa.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;   &UR; (Moving in ``f'' category unless otherwise noted) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BIGFILMS-SMALLBUCKS (Undated) _ It's already shaping up as a
summer of movie blockbusters, with ``Star Wars,'' ``The Spy Who
Shagged Me'' and ``The Wild, Wild West'' already out and other
widely anticipated films like ``Eyes Wide Shut'' and ``The
Haunting'' still to come. And with so many ``megaplex'' cinemas
available, replete with big screens and so-called stadium seating,
filmgoers are having a better theater-going experience than ever.
So why are all of the main movie-theater companies all losing money
and their stocks all sagging? By Geraldine Fabrikant.
</P>
<P>
   READING-HABITS (Undated) _ Eight-year study on America's reading
habits show young people are reading less and older people are
reading more. By Doreen Carvajal.
</P>
<P>
   HDTV-STANDARDS (Washington) _ Sinclair Broadcasting, which
controls more television stations than any other industry player,
has embarked on a crusade to have the FCC revisit the technical
standard for digital television _ even as stations around the
country have begun installing equipment and consumers have begun
buying TV sets based on that standard. By Joel Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   TV-PROGRAM-MUSIC (Undated) _ Recent developments concerning the
linking of network television programming to music sales. By Bill
Carter.
</P>
<P>
   ECOMMERCE-WOMEN (Undated) _ The E-Commerce Report Column: as
women start to use the Internet more for shopping, the prospects
sharply improve for online retailers. By Bob Tedeschi.
</P>
<P>
   SEGA-DREAMCAST (Undated) _ Sega has an unusual roll-out strategy
for its next-generation game console, the Dreamcast, a machine on
which the company's existence may be riding. By Sharon R. King.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-BRIEFS (Undated) _ Short items concerning news about
computers, including:
</P>
<P>
   _ An e-commerce company with roots in the Greek shipping
industry will be announced this week.
</P>
<P>
   _ For those who feel the need for more than a mere financial
advisor, there's MyCFO.com, the latest start-up from Jim Clark.
</P>
<P>
   _ Wrestling video games have become big sellers.
</P>
<P>
   SESAMESTREET-BERLITZ (Undated) _ Sesame Street and Berlitz join
up to form language classes for children abroad. By Lawrie Mifflin.
</P>
<P>
   VODKA-AD-COLUMN (New York) _ The Advertising Column: There's an
old saying that nothing rhymes with ``orange.'' So there may not be
a rhyme for a multimillion-dollar campaign to pitch a new
orange-flavored variety of Absolut vodka _ but there certainly is a
reason. By Stuart Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   LAW-MERGER (Undated) _ Partners at Rogers &AMP; Wells in New York
and the London firm Clifford, Chance approve the merger that would
create the world's largest law firm and are in the process of
merging with a large German firm. By Melody Petersen.
</P>
<P>
   ECON-CALENDAR (Undated) _ Key government figures this week.
</P>
<P>
   BOND-CALENDAR (Undated) _ The week's planned offerings.
</P>
<P>
   EQUITIES (Undated) _ Equity issues coming to market this week.
</P>
<P>
   DIVIDEND-MEETINGS (Undated) _ Major meetings this week.
</P>
<P>
   BIZGLANCE (Undated) _ Major financial stories at a glance.
</P>
<P>
   PATENTS (Undated) _ The weekly patents column. By Sabra
Chartrand.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MEDIA-BUSINESS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Coding varies.)
</P>
<P>
   MINORITY-JOURNALISTS (Seattle) _ Four minority-journalist
organizations, representing 6,000 reporters and editors, convene
here. By Felicity Barringer.
</P>
<P>
   MEDIA-TALK (Undated) _ Short news items about the media
business, including:
</P>
<P>
   _ The harsh realities behind MSNBC's canceling of
``Hockenberry.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Children have gone from being a very low priority on the
coverage lists of major national newspapers and television news
networks to being a modest priority, according to a two-part study
released last week.
</P>
<P>
   _ Jousting between Steve Brill and Norm Pearlstine.
</P>
