<BODY>
 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
(th) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR MONDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Monday, July 12:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-BARAK-ARAFAT (Jerusalem) _ Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat meet Sunday, vowing to
renew efforts for peace. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   CONGO-ASSESS (Lusaka, Zambia) _ While its authors pitched it as
a triumph , Saturday night's signing of a cease-fire deal to end
the war in Congo had something of a rising air of fiasco about it.
By Donald G. McNeil Jr.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-PAKISTAN (New Delhi, India) _ India and Pakistan agree on
a withdrawal of Islamic militants from mountain redoubts on the
Indian side of Kashmir. By Celia Dugger and Barry Bearak.
</P>
<P>
   IRAN-PROTEST (Cairo, Egypt) _ In a new sign of militancy, at
least 15,000 Iranian students took to the streets of Tehran on
Sunday in what has become a protest against a divided government
whose security forces remain in conservative hands. By Douglas
Jehl.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-PROTEST (Orahovac, Yugoslavia) _ Several thousand ethnic
Albanians marched through this little town Sunday in the fourth day
of peaceful protests against plans to station Russian troops among
the NATO peacekeepers here. By John Kifner.
</P>
<P>
   YUGOSLAVIA-U.S. (Washington) _ How the Clinton administration is
trying to undermine the Milosevic regime in Belgrade, and why it is
so difficult to promote opposition from outside. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   HOLBROOKE (Washington) _ Sen. Charles Grassley, R-Iowa, who is
blocking a final Senate vote on Richard Holbrooke's nomination to
be chief American diplomat at the United Nations, charged Sunday
that Secretary of State Madeleine Albright was directly responsible
for the delay because of her treatment of a State Department
employee described as a whistleblower. By Philip Shenon.
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA-REBELS _ Just two weeks before new peace talks are to
begin, Colombia's largest rebel group launches a stunning offensive
aimed at cities across the country. By Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   ALASKA-GATHERERS (Kwethluk, Alaska) _ To a remarkable degree,
thousands of native people still live off the land here in the
Alaskan tundra, taking 90 percent or more of what they eat every
year from the great back country, the rivers and the Bering Sea.
But 40 years after Alaska became a state, 20 years after land-claim
disputes in the oil rush led Congress to give the people known as
``subsistence gatherers'' priority rights to fish and game, and 10
years after the state's highest court declared that protection
unconstitutional because such natural bounty was for the ``common
use'' of all Alaskans, the debate has reached a bitter crisis
point. By Sam Howe Verhovek.
</P>
<P>
   GM-LIABILITY (Los Angeles) _ The huge jury verdict against G.M.
is likely be reduced significantly, but documents emerging from
that case and others elsewhere in recent years do not bode well for
GM. There are dozens of suits around the country, and lawyers
lining up to get hold of documents that could significantly hurt
the company's standing in those cases. By Andrew Pollack.
</P>
<P>
   PRISON-MENTAL-ILLNESS _ The first comprehensive study of the
mentally ill in prison shows that some 16 percent of inmates have
mental problems. The study provides enough other detail to
highlight what is one of the most significant problems in both
mental health and crime _ the role of jails as the new mental
institutions. By Fox Butterfield.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-HATE-ARRESTS (San Francisco) _ Two brothers arrested in
California charged with murdering a gay couple may now be linked to
synagogue burnings in California. And authorities are checking to
see if they are linked to other hate groups, particularly the one
in the Midwest whose membership included the Illinois man who went
on a racially-motivated killing spree last week. By Evelyn Nieves.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (Moving in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-CASH-GLUT (Washington) _ Beyond the presidential
candidates, the coming election season is awash in cash, with
congressional candidates taking advantage of a strong economy to
raise huge amounts. By Adam Clymer.
</P>
<P>
   HMO-LOBBY (Washington) _ With the Senate set to begin a weeklong
debate on HMOs on Monday, we examine the industry's lobbying
campaign, aimed mainly at slowing down the drive for a ``patients'
bill of rights.'' By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   JUDGE-WALD-PROFILE (Washington) _ Judge Patricia Wald retires
from the U.S. Court of Appeals for the D.C. Circuit for a seat on
the international war crimes tribunals; long one of the most
influential federal judges, especially in matters of federal
regulation, and role model for a generation of women lawyers. By
Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   DWI-STUDY (Washington) _ The federal highway safety agency has
overstated the effectiveness of state laws that lower the threshold
for alcohol in the bloodstream to be considered legally drunk, a
government review has found.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOVING LATER:  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AM-ADD-NYT-BUDGET _ A rundown of culture and financial stories;
has already moved.
</P>
<P>
   AM-PAGE1-NYT-CONSIDER _ A list of stories being considered by
