<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-11 16:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6027 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OZ-TV-VIOLENCE-ART-2T     07-11 1140
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OZ-TV-VIOLENCE-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRISON SERIES SEEKS TO SHATTER EXPECTATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV:  Photo  is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By DINITIA SMITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Crucifixion. Cannibalism. Slow death by eating glass.
Sexual mutilation. Is there nothing Tom Fontana won't depict on his
HBO prison series, ``Oz''?
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem with TV violence, it's a lie,'' said Fontana, who
writes most of the show's episodes and is one of its executive
producers, along with Barry Levinson and Jim Finnerty. ``People get
shot and don't bleed. They get hit and walk away. If you have to do
it, you have to do it as horrifically as it really is.'' And
Fontana is really trying as hard as he can.
</P>
<P>
   At its worst ``Oz,'' which begins its third season on Wednesday
looks as if it had been conjured up by adolescent boys trying to
gross each other out. At its best, though, ``Oz'' has elements of
Greek drama (including eyes being gouged out). There is also a
chorus, in the person of a crippled convict, Augustus, played by
Harold Perrineau, who narrates episodes from a glass cage. He even
quotes de Tocqueville.
</P>
<P>
   So far ``Oz,'' one of HBO's highest-rated dramatic shows, has
received mostly favorable reaction. The critic Stanley Crouch,
writing in The New York Times Magazine, praised it for its
``consistently brilliant acting _ some of the best in the history
of television.'' The show, Crouch wrote, ``is a landmark for the
medium.''
</P>
<P>
   Others, however, have condemned it for its violence.
``Ultimately,'' a critic for USA Today wrote, ``the show is as
dehumanizing as the prison system it attacks.'' Fontana and
Levinson are in effect glorifying the violence they depict, another
critic wrote, in The Village Voice: ``Levinson and Fontana
estheticize the material at the same time they're hyping its raw
realism.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oz'' takes place in the Oswald Maximum Security Penitentiary,
in an experimental unit the inmates have derisively nicknamed
Emerald City. But this is no dreamland. It has the latest style in
prison design, glass instead of bars, and video cameras for maximum
surveillance. The unit is perpetually bathed in an antiseptic
light.
</P>
<P>
   Here an idealistic prison administrator, Tim McManus, played by
Terry Kinney of the Steppenwolf Theater in Chicago, believes he can
genuinely rehabilitate people. But time after time he is defeated.
An affair with a tough prison guard, played by Edie Falco of HBO's
hit mini-series ``The Sopranos,'' has also failed. Now McManus has
become ``the prison he was trying to reform,'' Kinney said.
</P>
<P>
   Among Oz's good guys are the well-meaning warden (Ernie Hudson)
and the prison psychologist, Sister Peter Marie (Rita Moreno). B.D.
Wong plays a priest who sometimes seems astonished by the evil he
encounters. In one episode he gives communion to an inmate who ate
his own mother (and froze his father to save him for Thanksgiving).
</P>
<P>
   The prisoners of Oz display an almost limitless capacity for
betrayal and for inflicting pain. Still, Fontana strives to find a
core of humanity in each.
</P>
<P>
   The series is filmed in the old headquarters of the National
Biscuit Co. on West 16th Street in Manhattan where Fontana and the
actors were interviewed in January as they were filming the new
season's shows. Fontana was also interviewed later by telephone.
</P>
<P>
   Among his creations is the cunning Ryan O'Reily, played by Dean
Winters. ``He's my Iago,'' Fontana said. ``He has to survive by
making everyone think he's on their side.'' O'Reily, the epitome of
derailed intelligence, gets his way by setting one inmate against
the other.
</P>
<P>
   Adewale Akinnuoye-Agbaje plays Adebisi, a wild-eyed African who
rapes another prisoner. Adebisi is ``just pure, driven instinct,''
said Akinnuoye-Agbaje, a former model who was born in England of
Nigerian parents and has a law degree from Kings College in London.
</P>
<P>
   But the most evil among the evil is Vern Schillinger, the leader
of the Aryan Brotherhood, played by J.K. Simmons. Schillinger is
``one of the few characters I ever played that I refer to in the
third person,'' Simmons said, adding that last season he became
depressed by the role.
</P>
<P>
   He is happier now because Schillinger has been removed from ``Em
City'' and put into the general prison population, ``so I didn't
have to show up and be an extra all the time,'' Simmons said. The
excuse for the change, he said, will be that ``I couldn't live and
play well with others.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year Schillinger took as a sex slave Beecher, a
middle-class lawyer (Lee Tergesen), imprisoned for killing a child
while driving drunk. Schillinger burns a swastika on Beecher's
buttocks and, along with two others, breaks Beecher's arms and
legs. But Beecher seems to be regaining his strength. Last season,
by biting his attacker, he fought off an inmate who was forcing him
to perform a sex act.
</P>
<P>
   And somewhere in a gray area between good and evil is the
prisoner Kareem Said, played by Eamonn Walker, who is the Muslim
spiritual leader of the prison.
</P>
<P>
   Behind these characters is Fontana, a graduate of a Jesuit high
school in Buffalo whose sister is a nun. Fontana had himself filmed
being tattooed with the word Oz for the series' title. ``No one
else would do it,'' he said. ``I bled for the team.''
</P>
<P>
   While he was a student at Buffalo State College, he worked at
the Studio Arena Theater as a stage manager and publicist. ``An
incredible range of New York professionals, the best writers,
actors, directors would come up to do things,'' Fontana said. In
1975 he moved to New York City to write plays. ``My plays were OK;
they weren't great,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While working at the Williamstown Theater Festival as a
``general factotum'' for Nikos Psacharopoulos, then artistic
director, Fontana met Blythe Danner and her husband, Bruce Paltrow,
who was the creator of ``St. Elsewhere.'' Ms. Danner had seen
Fontana's play ``Specter Bridegroom,'' based on the Washington
Irving story, and urged her husband to see it, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he wanted to play tennis, see his kids,'' Fontana said.
So, as a sop, Paltrow asked Fontana to write an episode of ``St.
Elsewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My entire career is based on the fact he was too lazy to come
and see the play,'' Fontana said.
</P>
<P>
   He was a success at ``St. Elsewhere,'' a documentary-style
hospital series, and shared two Emmys for writing. Fontana won
another Emmy, for the police drama ``Homicide,'' which he also
developed with Levinson.
</P>
<P>
   When Levinson and Fontana set out to create ``Oz,'' they decided
to make it different from other prison shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a whole heritage of them,'' Fontana said. ``I'm trying
to take the audience's expectations and shatter them.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``Oz'' also looks different because he and his cinematographer
at the time, Jean de Segonzac, decided to shoot the series in
16-millimeter film instead of the usual 35. ``It's less pretty,''
Fontana said, and it gives the scenes a grainy look. The equipment
is also lighter. ``You pick up time, and you pick up mobility,''
Fontana said. ``It gives the shows a kind of energy.''
</P>
<P>
   To speed up shooting, and to create the harsh prison light, the
set is permanently lighted from the ceiling, which means that less
equipment has to be moved.
</P>
<P>
   And while broadcast network shows are divided into acts, each
ending in an artificial climax to allow for commercials, ``Oz''
runs one hour straight on HBO, a premium cable channel. ``With `Oz'
you can never break away,'' Fontana said. ``It's unsettling in a
good way.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Fontana said the series would have been possible only on a cable
channel like HBO, which can tackle controversial subjects without
the limits set by network standards. ``They're the only ones who
would let me do it the right way,'' he said. ``All the others would
make me tone it down.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that Chris Albrecht, the president of HBO Original
Programming, told him, ``I don't care if none of the characters are
likable.'''' Fontana added, ``That gave me the freedom to not have
to make it palatable.''
</P>
<P>
   He defends the prisoners' evil doings. ``It's like Shakespeare
or Greek tragedy: All the characters are bold in their action,'' he
said. ``It's all rooted in my Latin and Greek from the Jesuits. I
loved Edith Hamilton, Sophocles, Euripides, Aeschylus and
Shakespeare. They were my boys.''
</P>
<P>
   He is drawn to larger-than-life protagonists, Fontana said. And
they are punished for their sins accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Biting someone's penis off is a punishment worthy of the
crime,'' Fontana said, referring to the series' most grotesque
incidents. But he added that there was also a touch of Chekhov in
the show, a ``great sense of longing and loss.''
</P>
<P>
   Insisting that ``Oz'' presents a true picture of American prison
life, Fontana cited a 1998 Amnesty International report critical of
the criminal justice system in the United States. He said the
Amnesty report had even given him ideas for the show.
</P>
<P>
   ``Throw rats in the cell?'' Fontana said. ``I'm going to do
that.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea of a rat in the pod _ oh man!'' he said, wiping his
brow with a sweep of his hand.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-11-99 1658EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990711.0063 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-11 16:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6029 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SEGA-DREAMCAST-ART-80     07-11 1167
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEGA-DREAMCAST-ART-800&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEGA IS GIVING NEW PRODUCT SPECIAL PUSH 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By SHARON R. KING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two months before the product is scheduled to go on sale at
retailers throughout the country, Sega Enterprises plans to start
making its next-generation videogame console available for rent
this week through about 1,000 Hollywood Video stores, along with a
new version of ``Sonic the Hedgehog,'' a popular Sega game,
designed for the updated machine.
</P>
<P>
   For Sega, much rests on the success of the new game console,
called the Dreamcast, and on the unusual pump-priming marketing
experiment. The Tokyo-based company has been losing money and is in
the midst of an overhaul that includes eliminating 1,000 jobs _
about a quarter of its work force.
</P>
<P>
   Long ago the leader in the videogame industry, Sega now ranks a
distant third in the $10 billion worldwide videogame market, behind
Sony and Nintendo. Some analysts say that a failure with Dreamcast
will force Sega to leave the game console business and jeopardize
its ability to remain independent.
</P>
<P>
   Making the new machines available for rent before they go on
sale is a reversal of the typical market introduction for videogame
machines, in which rental units usually are not made available
until six months or more after a new console goes on sale in
stores. The move is part of a planned $100 million promotional
campaign for Dreamcast and is intended to whet potential buyers'
appetite for the machines.
</P>
<P>
   In Japan, where the Dreamcast has been available for almost a
year, the system has had such weak sales that last month a Japanese
rating agency lowered Sega's credit rating to one notch above junk
status. The rating change pushed Sega's stock to a new low in
Tokyo. The company's American depository receipts, each
representing a quarter of an ordinary share, were as low as
$3.15625 on June 28 and closed on Friday at $3.875 _ down from a
52-week high of $6.25 last December.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sega probably has six months and at most nine months to gain a
significant following for Dreamcast, or it's game over,'' said John
Latta, president of Fourth Wave, a market research firm that tracks
the video and arcade game industries. ``Their objective must be to
sell as many units and as many games as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Sega hopes the promotion _ which begins at 12:01 a.m. on
Thursday with midnight parties at Hollywood Video stores in New
York, Chicago, Los Angeles, San Francisco and Portland, Ore. _ will
spur consumer demand for the game system, said Bernie Stolar,
president of Sega of America. Most stores will have about 10
Dreamcasts available for rent at $19.99 each, although some stores
will offer as many as 100 of the machines.
</P>
<P>
   In about 600 stores, kiosks also will be available where the
game can be played. In August, a Dreamcast version of Sega's
football title, ``NFL 2000,'' and a new wrestling title, ``Ready 2
Rumble,'' from Midway Home Entertainment may be available, Sega
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Dreamcast console is to be offered for purchase starting on
Sept. 9 at $199, with about 16 games scheduled for release by then.
</P>
<P>
   The Dreamcast system will feature a 56-kilobit-a-second modem,
allowing users to play games on the Internet. The Dreamcast console
is a 128-bit machine, meaning its chip processes 128 bits of
information at a time _ compared with 64 bits for the slower Sega
Saturn player currently on the market, and the 64-bit Sony
Playstation and Nintendo 64.
</P>
<P>
   A hand-held visual memory unit can be bought separately for the
Dreamcast. The small, rectangular device, which resembles a
Tamogotchi virtual-pet toy, will allow players to swap games and
characters as well as play some videogames. The company said that
consumers had placed reservations to purchase more than 100,000
Dreamcasts. It hopes to double that number by September and to sell
1 million consoles by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Sega also hopes that it has learned from mistakes made with
several previous consoles, whose dismal showings hurt the company's
popularity among consumers and retailers.
</P>
<P>
   Just 5 million of Dreamcast's predecessor, the Saturn, have been
sold worldwide since its introduction in November 1995. By
contrast, more than 24 million Nintendo 64 units have been sold
since 1997, while more than 54 million Sony Playstations have been
sold since 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've taken an aggressive stance,'' Stolar said.``We really
need to win back the confidence of consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   To promote the system, Sega is spending about $100 million on
the introduction, about twice what Sony spent when it released the
Playstation, said Stolar, a former Sony executive vice president
who worked on the Playstation introduction.
</P>
<P>
   The company is spending another $100 million on product
development. In addition, it is taking the unusual step of helping
outside developers cover the cost of creating games, Stolar said.
</P>
<P>
   And for the September rollout, the game system will be available
simultaneously at about 15,000 retailers.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``They're being very retailer friendly,'' said Gary Neville,
owner of Dragon's Den, a Yonkers, N.Y., videogame store, and
Forbidden Planet, a similar store in New York City. ``They're
promising the world right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Sony and Nintendo, however, are not sitting idly by as Sega
works to regain market share.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies have announced plans for new consoles. Sony's
Playstation II could reach the United States in the fall of 2000.
Sony's new system, also a 128-bit console, is widely expected to be
the most powerful gaming system available, featuring movielike
graphics. Nintendo's next system, which will move the company from
the cartridge to the DVD format, may be available worldwide late
next year.
</P>
<P>
   And both Sony and Nintendo plan to lower the prices on the
current game systems to about $99, compared with about $129
currently.
</P>
<P>
   Sega may indeed have the advantage of being first with a 128-bit
system, but whether it will be able to maintain its momentum in the
face of its competitors' more powerful systems is uncertain. A
number of analysts outside of Sega are skeptical.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many believe the Sony Playstation II will be the dominant
system,'' said James Lin, a research analyst at Wedbush Morgan
Securities in Los Angeles. Despite Dreamcast's superior graphics _
an important feature for game enthusiasts _ the current Playstation
is still the leading system in Japan, he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a make-or-break system for Sega,'' Neville, the
retailer, said. ``If they don't launch this system correctly, they
can really hang it up. They'll be in the video hall of fame next to
the Atari Jaguar.'' He was referring to a 64-bit system with a
compact disk player that was released in the early 1990s and
quickly disappeared.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
