<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Monday, July 12, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Another comfortably cool morning is expected from New England
southwestward to the central Plains. A few record lows are likely
in the upper lakes and the interior Northeast. An expansive area of
high pressure stretching from Cape Cod to southern Missouri will
supply the northern half of the nation, east of the Rockies, with
generally dry and very pleasant midsummer weather.
</P>
<P>
   The boundary with a tropical air mass over the South will be
marked by clouds, showers and clusters of thunderstorms. A
developing disturbance in the western Carolinas will spark several
large thunderstorms near the coast. Flooding rains and damaging
winds are possible. More showers and storms will be found along the
front from the interior Gulf states to south Texas.
</P>
<P>
   A disturbance in the jet stream moving through the Ohio Valley
will draw clouds northward from the front into the Appalachians and
Middle Atlantic states. Showers will grow over the central
Appalachians and some will move into Virginia. The moistening of
the cool, dry air mass over southern Virginia and North Carolina
will cause temperatures to average fifteen degrees or more below
seasonal levels.
</P>
<P>
   Warmer air pushing east from the northern Rockies may produce a
thundershower in northern Minnesota. Hot weather, with record
highs, in the Northwest will be accompanied by sunny skies and
gusty winds near the Cascades. The Southwest will stay unsettled
with clouds and thundershowers migrating north toward the Central
Valley.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: Flood Legacy
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of Thursday's flood in Las Vegas, Friday was an
unusually cool day. The normal high temperature for July 9 is 104
degrees and the lowest maximum, prior to Friday, was 94 degrees in
1966. However, the mercury failed to reach 90 this past Friday due
in large part to the flood the day before. The normally arid air
near the surface was still saturated from evaporating the recent
rain. The sun's energy worked at drying the land instead of heating
the air. At the same time, the moist lower atmosphere produced
abundant clouds by midday, curtailing the warming process.
</P>
</TEXT>
