<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-11 17:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6037 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TANGLEWOOD-OZAWA-ART-     07-11 0966
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TANGLEWOOD-OZAWA-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSTON SYMPHONY: OZAWA AND COMPANY IN PERFECT SETTING FOR
`PASTORALE' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By ANTHONY TOMMASINI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LENOX, Mass. _ The descriptive subtitle that Beethoven provided
for the first movement of his ``Pastorale'' Symphony reads, in
English translation, ``Awakening of happy feelings upon reaching
the countryside.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps by opening the 1999 summer season of the Boston Symphony
Orchestra at Tanglewood with the ``Pastorale'' the conductor Seiji
Ozawa was hoping to engender just such happy feelings among his
players and the orchestra's administration. They have all been
through a lot lately.
</P>
<P>
   Ozawa, who is celebrating his 25th year as the orchestra's music
director, recently announced that he would be leaving in 2002 to
become the music director of the Vienna State Opera. The
announcement was unexpected. Clearly Ozawa has a solid core of
support in the Boston organization. But the level of discontent
that has become public knowledge, at least among many of the
players, is striking.
</P>
<P>
   Ozawa will be in place for three more seasons in Boston and four
summers at Tanglewood, including this one, and surely he will want
to accomplish much with his remaining time. Yet the schedule,
though planned well before his announcement, suggests that the
separation process may already have begun.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 22 major Boston Symphony Orchestra programs this summer,
Ozawa will conduct only five. (He will also lead one high-profile
concert in the main Music Shed with the combined players of the
Tanglewood Music Center Orchestra and the Gustav Mahler Youth
Orchestra.) For much of August he has commitments elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the threat of rain, Friday's opening night concert drew
some 9,200 people (including picnickers on the lawn) to the
orchestra's bucolic Berkshire Mountain summer home. Like many
concerts under Ozawa, this one was mixed. Making a program of
Beethoven's Sixth (``Pastorale'') and Seventh symphonies is at once
timid (the music is tried and true) and risky (a conductor and
orchestra are inevitably setting themselves up for comparison with
the glorious performance histories of these works). And though
there was nothing particularly wrong with the performances, there
was nothing particularly special either.
</P>
<P>
   In the ``Pastorale'' Ozawa seemed to be trying for a genial,
undulant quality. Often it just seemed placid. He devoted a great
deal of attention to expressively shaping the long melodic arcs in
the first violins. But the result was melodically top-heavy. In
general, there was little sense of the extraordinary daring in this
piece; for example, the way Beethoven in the first movement will
repeat a short motif for a shockingly long stretch of time. It
should provoke you to wonder, ``What's going on here?,'' not lull
you into dreamy thoughts of birdies and babbling brooks.
</P>
<P>
   There were some lovely individual moments from the players, and
at times the orchestra sound was luminous. But given the collected
talent onstage the performance had a disappointing sense of just
not clicking.
</P>
<P>
   For some, Ozawa's way with the Seventh Symphony might have been
too driven. I thought it essentially effective and at times
exciting. The vivace first movement was a bit heavy footed, but the
allegretto had a taut, restrained beauty. And the finale built with
rushing energy to its pummeling, exuberant conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of dramatic timing, nature and Beethoven were not in
sync. The anticipated rain did arrive, a short, heavy downpour, but
during the first movement of the Seventh Symphony, not the storm
section of the ``Pastorale,'' which would have been most effective.
</P>
<P>
   The weather was balmy on Saturday night for the concert
conducted by Andre Previn. The program's all-Mozart first half was
unimaginative and somewhat skimpy: the Overture to ``Le Nozze di
Figaro'' followed by the Violin Concerto No. 3 with the always
popular Itzhak Perlman as soloist, who played with his trademark
sleek technique and creamy tone.
</P>
<P>
   The second half offered the first performance of a suite that
Previn has fashioned from his opera, ``A Streetcar Named Desire,''
which received its premiere last fall at the San Francisco Opera.
As a concert work, the suite is impractically long (nearly 50
minutes) and imbalanced: there are extended orchestral interludes
and whole long arias for Blanche, yet just two brief scenes
involving Mitch. Susannah Glanville, a British soprano with a
sizable lyric voice who took over the role of Blanche from Renee
Fleming in San Francisco, sang compellingly, and the young American
tenor Anthony Dean Griffey, who created the role of Mitch, was
impressive and affecting, though underutilized.
</P>
<P>
   The suite did nothing to alter my opinion that Previn's opera,
though ably done, does not stand up to this iconic, timeless play.
</P>
<P>
   For all its restraint and for all Previn's sensitivity to the
story, the music could be a film score by one of the highly skilled
European composers who took refuge in Hollywood during World War
II, though Previn's evocations of jazz are more authentic.
</P>
<P>
   The orchestra played with lush sound and confidence, if with
little sense of involvement.
</P>
<P>
   The Tanglewood season runs through Aug. 30. Once again the most
intriguing event of the summer looks to be the Festival of
Contemporary Music, featuring the young musicians of the Tanglewood
Music Center during the last week of this month. For listeners with
a sense of adventure and all the participants, this exciting
new-music festival always engenders happy feelings in the
countryside.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-11-99 1709EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990711.0069 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-11 17:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6038 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KANSASCITY-MUSEUM-315     07-11 0629
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KANSASCITY-MUSEUM-315&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KANSAS CITY MUSEUM PICKS ARCHITECT FOR ADDITION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mo.)  (js) 
 By JULIE V. IOVINE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Nelson-Atkins Museum of Art in Kansas City, Mo., has
selected Steven Holl, the New York architect, to design its first
expansion since its opening in 1933.
</P>
<P>
   The new addition, which is largely submerged and features seven
glass extrusions scattered in the grassy turf of a 17-acre
sculpture park, will enlarge the museum by 55 percent, to 374,000
square feet. Marc F. Wilson, the museum's director, described the
scheme as ``great quartz crystals spilling neatly on the side
lawn.''
</P>
<P>
   Holl was selected from six finalists, including Tadao Ando of
Osaka, Japan; Christian de Portzamparc of Paris; Annette Gigo and
Mike Guyer of Zurich; Carlos Jiminez of Houston, and Rodolfo
Machado and Jorge Silvetti of Boston. The designs presented by all
six architects will be on display at the museum from Aug. 7 through
Oct. 17.
</P>
<P>
   The museum's trustees have raised $135 million as part of a
capital campaign undertaken in 1997 and have dedicated $80 million
to creating the new addition to the Beaux-Arts style museum.
Construction is expected to begin in early 2001 and be completed by
the summer of 2004.
</P>
<P>
   The Nelson-Atkins Museum is one of the most distinguished
general art museums in the United States, with an especially strong
Chinese art collection of landscape paintings from the Sung
Dynasty. Its holdings include 13 monumental bronzes by Henry Moore
and a series of Olympian-sized shuttlecocks commissioned from Claes
Oldenberg and Coosje van Bruggen.
</P>
<P>
   The museum was designed in 1927 by Thomas Wight, a Canadian-born
architect who had apprenticed with McKim, Mead and White. While
extensive renovation of the building is not part of Holl's mandate,
enticing the people of Kansas City to treat the museum as a more
welcoming place is. ``For too many people, for too long a time,
this museum was a big stone front,'' said Donald J. Hall, the
senior trustee.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Holl's design was selected unanimously by a nine-member
committee that included Hall, chairman of Hallmark Cards; J. Carter
Brown, director emeritus of the National Gallery of Art, and Ada
Louise Huxtable, architecture critic of The Wall Street Journal.
</P>
<P>
   Holl, 52, is pre-eminent among a generation of architects
(including Tod Williams and Billie Tsien, Henry Smith Miller and
Laurie Hawkinson and Eric Owen Moss) who appear always to be
emerging from the long shadow of architects like Frank Gehry, Peter
Eisenman, Richard Meier and even the nonagenarian Philip Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Holl took a bold chance in his proposal. The program had called
for the architects to make their addition on the imposing north
facade. The other entrants did use the classical front as a
backdrop to their sculptural activities. But Holl left the original
building untouched and set his approximately 140,000-square-foot
addition to the eastern side, submerging it beneath disparate glass
lanterns that he called ``a meandering garden of lights.''
</P>
<P>
   Visitors will arrive at a large stone plaza with a reflecting
pool and enter the glowing lantern of a new three-story lobby or an
underground parking garage lighted by glass lenses in the bottom of
the pool. Within the lobby pavilion, a ramp will lead down to ``an
umbilical cord zone,'' the architect said, where one will proceed
to the old building or to the new galleries, whose shaped ceilings
respond to the rolling topography outside. At several points it
will be possible to pass between interior and exterior sculpture
gardens.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's different without being confrontational,'' Wilson said of
the design.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
