<SLUG> BC-SESAMESTREET-BERLITZ-400&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BERLITZ WILL USE `SESAME STREET' TO TEACH ENGLISH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: China, Japan, Taiwan)  (js) 
 By LAWRIE MIFFLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Berlitz International is joining hands with the producers of
``Sesame Street'' to use the internationally known television
program in a multimedia project to teach English as a second
language to children around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Led by an exuberant purple Muppet named Tingo, created for the
project by the Jim Henson Co., ``Sesame English'' will be a
15-minute program produced by the Children's Television Workshop
and licensed exclusively by Berlitz for use in its 400 teaching
centers in 50 countries, and for sale in book, audio, video and
CD-ROM form.
</P>
<P>
   For the nonprofit Children's Television Workshop, which retains
the right to sell the program to television networks, the project
brings to fruition a long-held vision of using ``Sesame Street'' to
help youngsters around the world learn English, along with the
various social skills Bert, Ernie, Big Bird and friends have always
taught.
</P>
<P>
   For Berlitz, ``Sesame English'' is a step in its fledgling
effort to expand its language instruction business from adults to
children and teen-agers. Indeed, the company's executive vice
president and chief operating officer, Mako Obara, unabashedly
forecast a potential $4 billion global market for this new venture,
including all sales and Internet distribution (that would be almost
10 times Berlitz's 1998 total sales revenue of $436 million).
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember, we have exclusive rights to sell this or license to
a third party, worldwide,'' Obara said at a news conference
announcing the venture last Thursday. ``And we think Internet use
will be very important. We may develop straight-to-home sales from
our Web site.''
</P>
<P>
   Summing up the two partners' specialties, Obara added: ``For the
TV program, they develop, we advise. For the live instruction
programs and instructional materials, we develop, they advise.''
</P>
<P>
   The Children's Television Workshop has invested about $15
million to create and produce 52 episodes of the new program, which
will be finished by the end of the year (they include some footage
from the ``Sesame Street'' program library, along with new
segments).
</P>
<P>
   The partners said they would start the project in China, Taiwan
and Japan, partly because of the demand for English instruction in
those nations.
</P>
<P>
   While the show probably will not be on television networks until
next spring, Obara said language-instruction programs could start
in Berlitz centers as early as September.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The products will be marketed to schools and after-school
learning centers, as well as to Berlitz customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are keenly aware that English is the uncontested first
choice among Berlitz customers around the world,'' said Hirosama
Yokoi, president and chief executive of Berlitz International, a
unit of Benesse Corp. ``CTW discovered the same phenomenon in its
worldwide broadcasts.''
</P>
<P>
   Although ``Sesame Street'' in other nations is produced in
partnership with local broadcasters and done in the local language,
the producers are often asked for English-language videos of the
program. David Britt, president and chief executive of the
Children's Television Workshop, said recent immigrants to the
United States _ including adults and older siblings of Sesame
watchers _ often use the program to learn English and something
about American customs.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, Workshop executives had been looking for partners in
various countries to develop ``Sesame Street'' as an
English-instruction tool. Then someone thought of Berlitz, said
Robert Minsky, executive vice president for corporate planning and
marketing at Berlitz.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said, `Why are you running from country to country when
Berlitz is teaching in 50 countries and has 120 years' experience?'
'' Minsky recounted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
