<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-READING-HABITS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN SEARCH OF READERS, PUBLISHERS LOOK TO THE ELDERLY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Nonsubscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(hlw) 
 By DOREEN CARVAJAL    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Long Island Fiction Book Club is a suburban Port Washington,
N.Y., reading group that has endured longer than some marriages and
pored over the pages of more than 100 novels from Flaubert's
``Madame Bovary'' to Amy Tan's ``Joy Luck Club.''
</P>
<P>
   But even the founder and some of its members willingly confess
to an embarrassing little secret of their past _ aliteracy. ``In my
40s and 50s, I never read a book, except for art books,'' said
Lawrence Kamisher. Now, at 72, he says he devours about two titles
a week and indulges in three reading groups plus regular
discussions at the local gym whirlpool.
</P>
<P>
   A fellow fiction club member, Norman Glasserow, also confesses
some mortification. ``I'm ashamed to say it, but months went by
before I read a book,'' Glasserow said. ``I would go to gatherings
and people would start discussing the latest contemporary fiction.
I stood with my mouth agape. I would edge my way over to a
corner.'' At 76, he says, he has made a conscious effort to read
more frequently.
</P>
<P>
   In a decade when booksellers are battling fiercely for customers
and titles are as accessible as a click of a computer keyboard,
fewer people are reading, according to an ambitious new study. But
the older the age group, the more people are reading _ with people
over 50 reading an average of an hour a day, nearly double the time
of people in their 20s and below.
</P>
<P>
   Those trends are reflected in the report, by the NPD Group Inc.,
a market research concern in Park Ridge, Ill., which for the last
eight years has been methodically collecting information in a study
of the daily activities of 24,000 men and women _ 3,000 different
people each year _ who were chosen to reflect the national
population, spanning the ages of 18 to 90.
</P>
<P>
   The NPD's research through the 1990s detects a continuing
falloff in younger readers who said they spend at least 30 minutes
of the day reading anything. The percentage is relatively stable
for people 55 and older, with an increasing percentage for people
over 65.
</P>
<P>
   At the start of the study in 1992, almost 51 percent of the
people in the study said they were reading that amount of time. But
by 1999, the percentage had dropped to 45 percent. The steepest
reduction came among young men between the ages of 18 and 34: _
about 22 percent who reported reading that amount, down from 36
percent in 1992. The survey, which has a margin of error of plus or
minus 3 percent, did not ask participants to break down their form
of reading _ such as books, magazines, newspapers or computer
screens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reading happens to be the one area that has the greatest
potential for change in the next 10 years,'' said Harry Balzer, a
vice-president for the NPD Group. He predicted that as the baby
boomer generation ages it could be a help the book market because
of its numbers and older people's penchant for reading.
</P>
<P>
   But in the mean time, the challenge for book publishers is to
devise strategies to nurture future generations of readers and to
court older buyers in a market for popular titles that was
confronted in the last two years with a 3 percent decline in the
number of books purchased.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
