<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-11 17:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6042 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-READING-HABITS-ART-2N     07-11 0973
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-READING-HABITS-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: books purchased. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Simon &AMP; Schuster, a unit of Viacom Inc., for instance, has just
published a new book, ``Serpent'' by the thriller writer Clive
Cussler that is a super-sized paperback hybrid designed to appeal
to aging readers with fading vision with larger type and a cheaper
price than a hardcover or quality trade paperback.
</P>
<P>
   Publishers like Scholastic and Avon Books are meeting informally
with teen-age students and establishing focus groups and advisory
boards to literally get a read on their tastes. Their appetite for
more realistic books has prompted Scholastic to commission a
six-part book series based on the diaries and journals of eight
anonymous high school teens-agers called, ``Diary of Junior Year.''
In May, Avon, a unit of the Hearst Corp., created a new literary
imprint for older teen-agers called Avon Tempest with a debut book
about heroin addiction featuring a teen-age character called
``Smack.''
</P>
<P>
   The critical question for the book industry is whether reading
will always naturally evolve with age.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, some of the earliest reading surveys in the United
States, dating back to the 1920s, showed a reverse pattern with
reading declining with age. Various Gallup Poll surveys continued
to detect such a pattern in 1949 and 1966, but by 1984 when
pollsters asked the question ``are you reading a book presently''
the percentage of younger readers trailed behind middle-aged and
older readers.
</P>
<P>
   No one is quite sure why the pattern of reading has shifted
among age groups, but one theory is that in earlier years younger
people tended to read in higher percentages because they were
better educated than the older readers. And now, with the American
population becoming more educated, new explanations have developed
to explain where the attention of younger readers may be wandering.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier last year, Jean Feiwel, the publisher of Scholastic
Books, gathered about 10 teen-age students in New York to learn
more about the daily routine of their lives. In March, the company
followed up those informal discussions with focus group studies of
ninth-grade high school students in Stamford, Conn., and Encino,
Calif., to develop a better strategy for marketing books to younger
readers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that struck me enormously is that their days are
just jammed, from 6 a.m. to 12, just relentlessly scheduled by
themselves. Homework. Before school sports. Church. Music. Going to
the movies. Hanging out with their friends,'' said Ms. Feiwel, who
noted that reading has become almost an activity that has to be
scheduled rather than a spontaneous ritual.
</P>
<P>
   Even though there are fewer people reading, the amount of time
people actually spend reading has decreased only slightly in the
last eight years, according to the NPD study _ down to 44 minutes a
day from 46. The steepest drop in reading time was detected among
men between 18 and 34 who are reading about 13 minutes less a day
since 1992, down from 29 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   At the University of Maryland, John P. Robinson, a sociologist,
has been conducting the ``The Use of Time Project'' since 1965,
questioning people about their daily activities every 10 years
through 1995. His study also detected about a 10-minute drop from
34 minutes in daily reading over that period, but his information
showed that most of that decline came from newspaper reading while
people had slightly increased their reading in a combined category
that included books and magazines.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see that there has actually been a gain in free-time
activity to about 42 to 44 hours a week,'' said Geoffrey C. Godbey,
a co-author with Robinson of a book called ``Time for Life'' and a
professor of leisure studies at Pennsylvania State University.
``And for the first time we see that gain going to forms of
recreation like exercise.''
</P>
<P>
   Through much of the 1990s, people have consistently told
pollsters for Roper and Gallup that they value reading, desire
books for Christmas presents and consider reading one of the most
important elements in the education of their children.
</P>
<P>
   But in Gallup's last poll on actual reading habits, in 1990,
those good intentions did not necessarily result in more reading.
Gallup, which has been querying people about their reading habits
since 1949, detected a downward trend _ the proportion of Americans
who had not completed a book in the last year had doubled to 16
percent in 1990 from 8 percent in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   Does it matter if fewer people are reading? Carl F. Kaestle, the
author of a history of reading, ``Literacy in the United States''
and a Brown University professor of education, said that he tends
to take the nonalarmist view.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never believed that the sky is falling down,'' Kaestle
said. ``But on the other hand, as an educator, I'm devoted to
analytical thinking and it makes me nervous if people are reading
less, because reading in print is traditionally the way we help
people to sharpen their thoughts. Are people substituting
electronic communication?''
</P>
<P>
   The information in the NPD study is gathered through check-off
time sheets divided in half-hour increments through a day. The firm
picked the 20 daily activities that people were most likely to be
involved in based on their market research. It did not include a
separate category for computer use or online activity, which
participants could have checked off in a variety of categories like
home entertainment or simply ``other.''
</P>
<P>
   But even those categories did not show dramatic gains. The
activity that did gain the most in time spent was rather mundane _
sleeping. In all age groups, people are sleeping more _ between
five to 35 minutes more a day.
</P>
<P>
   ``What this study says,'' Balzer of the NPD Group, ``is that
people are literally pursuing their dreams.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
