<HEADER>
A6046 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIGFILMS-SMALLBUCKS-A     07-11 1166
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIGFILMS-SMALLBUCKS-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLENTY OF SEATS AVAILABLE, EVEN AT SUMMER BLOCKBUSTERS 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Photo and graphic are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By GERALDINE FABRIKANT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For movie theater owners this summer, it is the best
of times and the worst of times.
</P>
<P>
   The summer is shaping up as the best ever at the box office, on
the strength of hits like ``Stars Wars,'' ``Austin Powers'' and
``The Wild, Wild West,'' and with widely anticipated movies like
Stanley Kubrick's ``Eyes Wide Shut'' still ahead. And filmgoers are
flocking to sparkling new megaplexes _ theater complexes that
typically have more than a dozen big screens, digital sound systems
and so-called stadium seating, with armchairs arrayed in tiers to
offer each member of the audience an unobstructed view.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the new megaplexes,'' Gloria Dickerson, a children's
book distributor, said enthusiastically as she left a screening
last Thursday of the Spike Lee film, ``Summer of Sam,'' at the new
Loews megaplex on Manhattan's East Side. ``The seats are
comfortable. I think they're wonderful.''
</P>
<P>
   In short, for filmmakers and their audiences, going to the
movies has seldom been better. So how come the companies that run
the theaters are having such a lousy summer?
</P>
<P>
   The four leading publicly held exhibitor companies _ AMC
Entertainment, Carmike Theaters, GC Cos. and Loews Cineplex
Entertainment _ all lost money in their most recently completed
fiscal years, and their stocks are sagging. While the extent of the
problem varies among these companies, all are finding themselves on
the wrong side of two economic forces: a glut of screens that
cannot keep up with record demand for movie tickets, and a costly
unplanned obsolescence for hundreds of cinemas.
</P>
<P>
   Though audiences are flocking to the spacious new megaplexes,
people are staying away in droves from many of the so-called
multiplexes of shoe-box size theaters that have been a mainstay of
shopping malls and a staple of the movie industry for decades.
</P>
<P>
   Because the big exhibitors with the financial clout to erect the
new megaplexes are also the largest owners of the fading
multiplexes, companies like AMC and Loews tend to be bearing the
brunt of the forces they themselves have unleashed. And while
analysts predict that the strongest exhibitors will survive the
theater industry's transition from shoe boxes to showcases, few
expect the recovery to be swift or smooth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will take another two years before the investments pay
off,'' predicted Christopher Dixon, a media analyst at Paine
Webber, who has been bearish on the exhibitor stocks for the past
two years.
</P>
<P>
   Scrambling to respond to the public's overwhelming preference
for megaplexes, the big theatre chains are attempting to convert
multiplexes to megaplexes whenever and wherever they can. Many of
the old multiplexes, however, simply cannot be revamped _
especially within shopping malls where there may be little
flexibility to expand floor plans and raise ceilings for
stadium-style layouts, which require at least twice the height of a
conventional theater. In such cases exhibitors may seek to sell the
theaters, keep marginally productive theaters open while waiting
for their leases to expire or simply close the theatres and take
write-offs while building new megaplexes elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   But none of this is happening fast enough to reduce the current
glut of movie screens _ 34,160 throughout the United States. That's
approximately one for every 8,000 people in the nation, notes
Sumner M. Redstone, who is chairman of the entertainment company
Viacom Inc. The number of movie tickets sold annually has risen 40
percent since 1988, to a current rate of 1.4 billion each year.
Unfortunately for exhibitors, the number of screens has increased
even more so _ by 47 percent during that same period.
</P>
<P>
   Redstone, who also personally owns the private exhibition
company National Amusements, with some 1,300 screens, says that the
United States has become ``overscreened.'' That is why, even as
National Amusements has joined the megaplex mania in this country,
it is also busily building theaters in less glutted markets like
Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   For similar reasons, virtually every American movie exhibition
company is investing overseas. GC Companies, for example, already
has theaters in Mexico and has formed an alliance with Hoyts Cinema
Group for new megaplexes in Argentina, Brazil and Chile.
</P>
<P>
   But with the United States remaining the core market for
exhibitors, theater companies have little choice but to pour money
into the type of theaters that American audiences are now
demanding.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stadium seating is a breakthrough in the industry,'' Redstone
said. ``Where we have built them, we are doubling and tripling our
business. For example, in Cincinnati, where we have a 20-screen
stadium seating complex, we are doing three to four times as much
business as we did a year ago, before we converted the multiplex.''
</P>
<P>
   The megaplexing of America is generally agreed to have begun in
1994 when AMC Entertainment, the nation's largest publicly owned
theater chain _ or ``circuit,'' in industry parlance _ opened a
megaplex in Dallas, called the Grand. Built after extensive
interviews with moviegoers, the Grand was immediately successful
and yielded a basic formula that has been widely copied since: 14
or more screens, stadium seating, arm rests that hold drinks and
can be tilted up to convert individual seats into a cozy love-seat
tandem, a digital sound system and a ceiling-to-floor, wall-to-wall
screen.
</P>
<P>
   Such luxurious viewing does not come cheap, though. For Loews,
which is building megaplexes with as many as 24 screens and more
than 3,000 seats, the construction cost is $1 million a screen _
which does not include the cost of buying or leasing the land. That
compares with an old multiplex with eight to 12 screens, perhaps
2,500 seats and a construction cost of about $600,000 a screen.
Loews says that 432 of its screens _ or about a quarter of the
company's U.S. total _ are now in megaplexes and that within the
next few years the majority of its screens will be in these new
supercinemas.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of Loews, Laurence Ruisi, says that this fast-track
construction schedule accounts for his company's poor results for
fiscal 1999, which ended in February. Loews reported a net loss of
$5.9 million on sales of $851 million. Though cash flow _ earnings
before interest, taxes, depreciation and amortization _ was
positive at $144.2 million, Loews reported its loss on revenue of
$851 million. And Ruisi predicted that it might be two more years
before the company returned to profitability.
</P>
<P>
   But at that point, he promises, Loews' business will be better
than ever. ``The megaplexes are much more profitable for us,''
Ruisi said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Redstone, too, describes the new-theater boom as a business for
long-term players with deep pockets.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reward is terrific, but the capital costs are enormous,''
he said. ``In Revere, Mass., we have the largest-grossing National
theater in New England. We are tearing it down, and we are spending
about $20 million to build a new 20-screen stadium-seat theater.''
</P>
<P>
   A theater chain that does not protect its turf with a megaplex
risks losing business, Redstone said, citing research by National
Amusements indicating that audiences will bypass a multiplex closer
to home to see a film at a megaplex that is farther away.
</P>
<P>
   But it is not always the case that for each new theater complex
built another is torn down.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody is building new screens, and the old screens are not
coming off line as quickly as expected,'' said Marina Jacobson, who
follows the movie exhibition business for the investment firm of
Bear, Stearns.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Take the case of the new Loews megaplex on Second Avenue at East
32nd Street in Manhattan. The company already owned a three-screen
multiplex two blocks away on East 34th Street when it broke ground
for the megaplex. Last year, Loews sold the 34th Street multiplex
to Clearview Cinemas. That came in response to a ruling from the
Justice Department's antitrust division that Loews' acquisition of
a separate big theater chain, Cineplex Odeon, had given the company
too many theaters in Manhattan. As a result of the transfer of the
34th Street property to Clearview, Loews' new megaplex is competing
with a multiplex virtually around the corner.
</P>
<P>
   So far, though, it appears that the Loews megaplex that is
drawing the crowds _ and the new releases. While the Loews lineup
last week had a full complement of hits and recently released
block-buster hopefuls (including ``South Park,'' ``Wild, Wild
West,'' ``Big Daddy,'' ``Tarzan,'' ``Austin Powers,'' ``Summer of
Sam'' and ``The General's Daughter'') the nearby Clearview
multiplex had only three movies, whose popularity crested weeks
ago: ``Notting Hill,'' ``Walk on the Moon,'' and ``The Red
Violin.''
</P>
<P>
   The industry's ``overscreening'' gives an advantage to
distributors, the middlemen who take Hollywood's films and
apportion them among the exhibitors. Distributors and exhibitors
divide the box-office gross, with the theater owners getting
perhaps only 10 percent of the take when a film first opens but
keeping an increasingly larger percentage of receipts the longer
the film runs.
</P>
<P>
   Using time-honored formulas that vary slightly depending on who
has the most leverage, the exhibitors and distributors generally
aim for a 50-50 split over the film's entire run. Right now,
though, the leverage is clearly with the distributors, which not
only have greater leeway than in the past to pick and choose among
local theaters but can also dictate tougher terms. Thus 20th
Century Fox, a News Corp. subsidiary, has been able to demand a
formula that may allow it to keep a 52 percent share of the take
from exhibitors with whom it has favored copies of its block-buster
``Star Wars.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Alan Gould, an movie industry analyst for the
investment firm of Gerard Klauer Mattison, was bullish on the
theater-chain companies. Now, though, he has lowered his earnings
estimates for the entire group.
</P>
<P>
   ``We simply didn't realize how fast the cash flow from the
multiplexes would decay,'' Gould said. ``It has been a forced
cannibalization. Now, if someone plops down a megaplex, it gets the
best movies and the best attendance.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   For AMC, Loews and the other megaplex builders, the big issue
now is getting rid of their aging multiplexes as quickly as
feasible. In many cases, long-term leases at shopping malls and
other locations means swallowing big write-offs when the older
cinemas take early retirement.
</P>
<P>
   And the alternative of selling the complexes no longer seems as
easy as it was as recently as a year ago, when several financial
players were still gobbling up theaters. Two leveraged buyout
firms, Kohlberg Kravis Roberts and Hicks, Muse, Tate &AMP; Furst, for
example, jointly acquired several chains, now called Regal Cinemas.
But they are no longer aggressively buying up properties, and
analysts see little hope that other big buyout firms will enter the
theater market.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they thought that if they could lead a consolidation
in the industry, they would have more clout in negotiating terms of
the film studios for movies; but that didn't happen,'' said one
movie studio analyst, who spoke on the condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   But this industry melodrama may yet have a happy ending _ at
least for the companies with the financing to build megaplexes. To
control their own costs, Hollywood studios are trying _ or so they
claim _ to cut back on the number of films they produce each year.
Fewer movies would give each new release a better chance of getting
more screen time, with the longer runs that favor the exhibitors.
</P>
<P>
   If that trend bears out, and as the least profitable multiplexes
are gradually phased out, some analysts expect a return to good
times for the theater chains. Michael Wolff, who heads the media
consulting business at Booz Allen &AMP; Hamilton, predicts that running
movie theaters will be an attractive business once the rebuilding
is finished.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are not comparable to other high-growth industries, but
they are a reliable, steady cash-flow business,'' Wolff said. ``I
think the megaplexes will become major entertainment centers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
