<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-11 17:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6048 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PROSECUTION-BOOK-REVI     07-11 0895
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROSECUTION-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE PROSECUTION': SHREWD AND ON THE SIDE OF JUSTICE, OR SO HE
THOUGHT
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Publication notes are at end of review.)  
(nk) 
 By CHRISTOPHER LEHMANN-HAUPT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   How can people tell lies in public and continue to live with
themselves? This question _ not irrelevant to recent public
discourse in the United States _ troubles Joseph Antonelli, the
narrator of D.W. Buffa's absorbing new legal thriller, ``The
Prosecution.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have not always told the truth in my life, but I never lied
in a court of law, and I spent years defending murderers and
rapists and thieves,'' muses Antonelli, ruefully recalling why he
gave up being a criminal defense lawyer at the end of Buffa's
explosive first novel, ``The Defense.''
</P>
<P>
   He continues: ``I did not need to lie; the law itself allowed me
to make certain that people who should have been punished were set
free. I had wanted to be a lawyer who never lost a case because
every client was innocent; instead I became a lawyer whose only
concern was preventing anyone from ever proving that my client was
guilty.''
</P>
<P>
   But now, at the start of Buffa's new novel, Antonelli is being
urged by his old friend Judge Horace Woolner, a former district
attorney of their hometown of Portland, Ore., to come out of his
secluded retirement. Woolner has a case for Antonelli. It seems
that one Travis Quentin, ``a guy'' who ``was arrested for a double
homicide down in Los Angeles'' offered to tell about another murder
if his sentence would be reduced to life instead of the death
penalty.
</P>
<P>
   The story that Quentin then told concerned the unsolved rape and
murder in a hotel room two years earlier of Nancy Goodwin, the
pregnant wife of Marshall Goodwin, the present chief deputy
district attorney of Portland. According to Quentin's testimony, he
had been hired by Goodwin to commit the murder as part of a plea
bargain deal on a drug case in Portland. The crime was committed
while Goodwin was prosecuting a murder, which gave him a perfect
alibi. Woolner wants Antonelli to look into Quentin's story, and
then, if he believes it, to accept an appointment as special
prosecutor and go after Goodwin.
</P>
<P>
   Antonelli bites. He loves Woolner and Woolner's wife, Alma;
admires him for overcoming the adversity of being black and having
had both his legs blown off in battle and shares his concern that a
public figure could be living a lie. He interviews Quentin in
prison and learns among other things the identity of the woman who
allegedly handed Quentin the envelope containing Goodwin's
instructions: Kristin Maxfield, another prosecutor, whom Goodwin
married a year after his wife's death. Antonelli confronts Goodwin
over lunch, forces his indictment and goes to trial.
</P>
<P>
   There follows an electrically charged courtroom drama complete
with an opposing attorney you love to hate, a feisty black judge
who treats everyone in her court like kindergarten cutups and a
surprising outcome. But the results leave Antonelli dissatisfied
and wondering about fairness and whether the complete truth has
come out. Unspoken but very much on the reader's mind is the
question of why Woolner pushed Antonelli so hard to take on the
case in the first place. And how is the Woolners' fancy social life
connected to the story, especially Alma's role as a board member of
Portland's ballet company?
</P>
<P>
   Then, as occurred in Buffa's previous novel, a second murder
case surprisingly explodes, which not only shocks Antonelli, but
also changes his take on the first case. His world goes spinning
out of control.
</P>
<P>
   Several flaws mar ``The Prosecution.'' The trickiness of the
plot's many twists and reversals borders on contrivance. The
picture of Antonelli in retirement reading Aristotle is hard to
believe and somehow lends a sententiousness to his many
pronouncements. (``Like time itself, the law stops for no one.'')
And the big surprise of the outcome falls far short of the genuine
shock of the final twist in ``The Defense.''
</P>
<P>
   All the same, the authentic courtroom scenes leave one with the
sense that Buffa, who for 10 years worked in Oregon as a defense
attorney, has more to say about the law than the usual lawyer
turned novelist. (``What you really have going on out there,''
remarks Woolner with typical acuteness about one charismatic
lawyer's power to intimidate, ``are a bunch of weak-willed lawyers
and feebleminded judges too scared of what they don't know to have
any idea of what to do with someone who pretends he does.'')
</P>
<P>
   More important, the novel's exploration of the theme of lying
lends it a resonance that continues to play on the reader's mind.
At first, Antonelli deplores what he sees as a widespread loss of
moral equilibrium. ``There's something Nietzsche wrote,'' he
complains: `` `The morning paper has replaced the morning prayer.'
People used to believe in God, in a moral code that never changed;
now no one believes in anything except that everything is always
changing and nothing is always either right or wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   But as the novel's deeper truths unfold, Antonelli comes to
recognize that in fact the truth is often ambiguous and that even
the best of us must sometimes live a lie.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   THE PROSECUTION
</P>
<P>
   By D.W. Buffa
</P>
<P>
   274 pages. A John Macrae Book/Henry Holt &AMP; Co. $25.
</P>
</TEXT>
