<HEADLINE>
TOO FEW VIEWERS FOR `HOCKENBERRY'  
 NEWS MEDIA'S EYE TURNS MORE TO CHILDREN  
 TIME EDITOR CHALLENGES CONTENT OF BRILL'S 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Bylines follow individual items.)  
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the pinball-fast world of cable news, where stories,
correspondents and schedules are constantly changing, it takes
something special to stand out. A host with a strong identity who
attracts a regular following _ liie CNN's Larry King _ has
tremendous value, especially in prime time, where the
highest-priced advertising is mined.
</P>
<P>
   That fact of life seems to be the real reason behind MSNBC's
decision last week to cancel John Hockenberry's 10 p.m. talk show,
``Hockenberry.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that Hockenberry _ an experienced, Emmy-award-winning
journalist with obvious intelligence _ did not have a distinctive
personality. But after six months on the air he had too few
viewers, and NBC has someone ready to replace him whose audience is
twice the size of Hockenberry's.
</P>
<P>
   That person is Chris Matthews, the host of ``Hardball with Chris
Matthews,'' a high-decibel interview show at 8 p.m. weeknights on
CNBC, the business-news channel that is MSNBC's sibling in the NBC
News family. It regularly attracts 400,000 to 500,000 viewers.
</P>
<P>
   Matthews' show is vulnerable because the Nasdaq stock market has
decided to add an evening trading session, and when it does _ the
time frame is still undecided _ CNBC will continue its market
coverage into the evening.
</P>
<P>
   So NBC News executives had the idea to move Matthews' show to
MSNBC, which could use a ratings boost. In prime time, MSNBC has
seen the smaller Fox News Channel nipping at its heels, and even in
recent weeks surpassing MSNBC in the prime-time Nielsen ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Hockenberry, who is also a correspondent for ``Dateline NBC''
(where his reports reach 15 million or more people, compared with
the 200,000 or so he reached on MSNBC) was told that his MSNBC show
would be canceled because the network wanted to ``move in another
direction,'' Hockenberry said on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was disappointed and very surprised,'' Hockenberry said.
Referring to the Kosovo crisis, which pumped up all the cable news
networks' Nielsen ratings from late March through mid-May, he said,
``All our numbers fell away after the war ended; it wasn't just
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Hockenberry's show often beat its Fox News Channel
counterpart, ``The Crier Report,'' in that 10 p.m. time slot.
</P>
<P>
   MSNBC spokesmen, speaking not for attribution, mentioned the
Matthews scenario, and said NBC News executives saw the move as a
``win-win'' situation: ``Dateline'' would have Hockenberry back
full time and MSNBC would get the benefit of Matthews' audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's true that I'm very happy to be back at `Dateline,' which
is a great place to work,'' Hockenberry said. ``But look, they
didn't come to me and say, `John, ``Dateline'' really needs you _
can you give up your show?' I have to be honest about that.''
</P>
<P>
   _ LAWRIE MIFFLIN
</P>
<P>
   News Media's Eye Turns More to Children
</P>
<P>
   Children have gone from being a very low priority on the
coverage lists of major national newspapers and television news
networks to being a modest priority, according to a two-part study
released last week. And when children appear in news reports, it is
less often as victims or perpetrators of crimes than was the case
five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Dale Kunkel, an associate professor of communication at the
University of California at Santa Barbara, who conducted the
analysis for Children Now, an Oakland-based research and advocacy
group, saw two ``stereotype-busters'' in the latest results.
</P>
<P>
   ``It counters the stereotype that the only way kids get in the
news is in stories about crime and violence,'' Kunkel said. Such
articles and programs accounted for 23 percent of the total about
children, compared with 40 percent five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It also contradicts the stereotype that you're more likely to
see a person of color in a crime and violence story,'' he said.
``In coverage of minority children as compared to children as a
whole, there were fewer stories about crime and violence in the
ethnic-minority part of the sample, and that was not true in the
past.''
</P>
<P>
   The study examined news coverage in five newspapers _ The New
York Times, The Los Angeles Times, The Chicago Tribune, The Atlanta
Constitution and The Houston Chronicle _ in November 1998, and the
coverage on the evening news broadcasts of ABC, CBS and NBC in the
same month. The earlier study was done in November 1993, and
reported in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The 1998 analysis found a 37 percent increase in the number of
newspaper articles about children (an average of 6.3 per edition)
and no change in the amount of television time devoted to children
by the ABC, CBS or NBC evening news broadcasts (there were fewer
programs, but more time spent on each).
</P>
<P>
   ``The growth in the number of child-related stories is accounted
for by stories on health and safety issues,'' Kunkel said, ``and by
cultural stories like teens as trend-setters, or how kids use the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   His study was done before the Littleton, Colo., school
shootings. But he said that ``one can't necessarily assume the
patterns the study identified will be altered significantly'' by
the shootings.
</P>
<P>
   _ LAWRIE MIFFLIN
</P>
<P>
   Time Editor Challenges the Content of Brill's
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday afternoon, several dozen reporters, television
producers, newspaper editors and columnists found themselves
staring at a blistering letter, sent to them by Norman Pearlstine,
editor in chief of Time Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The 25-page packet, dated July 8, was a point-by-point rebuttal
of an article in the July/August 1999 issue of Brill's Content,
``Time on Big Sugar,'' which dismantled an article by Donald L.
Barlett and James B. Steele about corporate welfare.
</P>
<P>
   The Time article was critical of the Fanjul family, which owns
Flo-Sun Inc., one of the United States' largest sugar growers, and
was part of a series in Time magazine by Barlett and Steele that
won a National Magazine Award and a George Polk Award for the
magazine earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Pearlstine's language concerning the magazine and its founder,
Steven Brill, was tart. The article criticizing the Time article,
he wrote, ``seriously undermined your own legitimacy as a media
critic'' _ but he made special note of Brill's ``lengthy
professional relationship with Joseph R. Klock Jr., the general
counsel for Flo-Sun and the Fanjul family's other sugar
interests.''
</P>
<P>
   Pearlstine pointed out that Klock incorporated and represented
several of Brill's Florida companies, including ``Am-Law Florida
Enterprises Inc., Am-Law Miami Review Inc. and Am-Law Lee Car Sales
Inc. In addition, Klock has served as a panelist on seminars
sponsored by The American Lawyer when you owned that publication.''
</P>
<P>
   Brill said he was undisturbed by the allegations, and said that
Klock last represented him 14 years ago. He referred to the packet
as ``this letter and a 22-page ridiculous attachment.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing there,'' he said. ``The stuff about the
lawyer is just hilarious. Someone who represented me 14 years ago
and I am somehow in his pocket? I have bigger conflicts with Time
Warner.'' He said Walter Isaacson, Time's managing editor, is a
good friend and so is Pearlstine.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Brill has posted a five-page response to
Pearlstine's 22-page rebuttal on the Web page of Brill's Content
(Brillscontent.com).
</P>
<P>
   _ ALEX KUCZYNSKI
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
