<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: U.K., Germany, N.Y., Wash.)  (js) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROGERS &AMP; WELLS APPROVES MERGER WITH LONDON FIRM
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers at Rogers &AMP; Wells in New York and Clifford Chance in
London approved a merger of their firms, the first combination
between major British and American law firms. The firms' partners
also agreed to push forward with plans to merge with Germany's
third-largest law firm _ a move that would create the largest law
firm in the world in terms of both lawyers and revenue, pushing
aside two American giants.
</P>
<P>
   CONVENTION FOCUSES ON DIVERSITY
</P>
<P>
   At a convention in Seattle, more than 5,000 minority journalists
_ and hundreds more people who train them, hire them and advertise
with their news organizations _ spent days debating what news
organizations must do to present a more complete picture of their
communities. The main goal of the convention was to underscore the
importance of increasing the number of minority journalists in
newsrooms, but a survey showed that more than half of minority
journalists plan to leave the business in the next five years.
Some, like Mary Lou Fulton, who worked at The Los Angeles Times,
left for the online world, while others think their career
prospects are limited.
</P>
<P>
   `SESAME STREET' AS ENGLISH LESSON
</P>
<P>
   Berlitz International is joining with the producers of ``Sesame
Street'' to use the internationally known television program in a
multimedia project to teach English as a second language to
children around the world.
</P>
<P>
   MORE WOMEN ARE SHOPPING ONLINE
</P>
<P>
   Women are joining the Internet more quickly than ever, nearly
erasing the gender gap among the medium's 92 million users. Perhaps
more significant for the Internet economy, though, is the fact that
the percentage of online shoppers who are women has jumped in the
last 12 months, to 38 percent from 29 percent. And industry
executives expect that presence to rise quickly over the next year.
</P>
<P>
   COMMERCEKEY DELIVERY
</P>
<P>
   Commercekey, an Internet start-up that helps businesses set up
shop on the Web, has its own fleet of cargo vessels standing by to
deliver merchandise around the world.
</P>
<P>
   SEGA GIVES GAME CONSOLE A PUSH
</P>
<P>
   Two months before its new game console is scheduled to go on
sale nationwide, Sega Enterprises plans to start making it
available for rent this week through about 1,000 Hollywood Video
stores, along with a new version of the game ``Sonic the
Hedgehog.'' For Sega, much rests on the success of the new console,
called the Dreamcast, and on the unusual pump-priming marketing
experiment.
</P>
<P>
   `HARDBALL' MOVING TO MSNBC
</P>
<P>
   MSNBC is canceling John Hockenberry's 10 p.m. talk show to make
way for ``Hardball with Chris Matthews,'' which is now on CNBC, the
business-news sibling of MSNBC. Matthews' show, which regularly
attracts 400,000 to 500,000 viewers, is expected to bolster
prime-time ratings at MSNBC, which is feeling pressure from the Fox
News Channel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
