<HEADER>
A6054 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JUDGE-WALD-PROFILE-AR     07-11 1077
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JUDGE-WALD-PROFILE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAR-CRIMES JUDGE IS USED TO BREAKING NEW GROUND 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By LINDA GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Leaving a life-tenured federal judgeship for a
two-year term on the international war crimes tribunal in The
Hague, Patricia Wald is setting out, at age 70, on her next great
adventure.
</P>
<P>
   It may seem a long leap from her paneled chambers at the end of
a quiet corridor in the federal courthouse here, where
administrative procedure and the intricacies of sentencing
guidelines are the staples of an often arcane appellate docket, to
life as one of 14 judges from 14 countries charged with devising a
collective legal response to large-scale brutality in the former
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   But Judge Wald, who will retire this fall after 20 years on the
District of Columbia U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, has taken leaps
before. The first woman ever to serve on the appeals court, she
still remembers her job search in New York in the spring of 1951,
as she was about to graduate near the top of her class from Yale
Law School.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really a shame,'' a partner of one fancy firm told the
young Patricia McGowan after inspecting her credentials. ``If only
you could have been here last week.'' Seeing the law student's
puzzled expression, the partner continued, with no further
explanation necessary: ``We hired a woman last week.''
</P>
<P>
   Judge Wald was at the leading edge of a generation of women that
included Justices Sandra Day O'Connor and Ruth Bader Ginsburg,
roughly her contemporaries, who entered the legal profession in the
decade after World War II and found themselves in uncharted
territory, unwelcoming if not downright hostile.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had very little expectation of what would become of us,''
Joan Bernstein, Judge Wald's law school roommate and now director
for consumer protection at the Federal Trade Commission, said the
other day.
</P>
<P>
   In Judge Wald's chambers, along with pictures of her eight
grandchildren, hangs a photo of the 1950-51 Yale Law Journal staff:
the two roommates, prim female visions of the early 1950s,
surrounded by two dozen classmates in suits and ties.
</P>
<P>
   Each woman found her own way through the wilderness. In Judge
Wald's case, it was a mixture of the traditional and the
untraditional. She was an only child raised by a single mother in
an extended family of factory workers in the old mill town of
Torrington, Conn. No one in her family had ever been to college,
but her relatives recognized her gifts and supported her ambitions.
</P>
<P>
   She married a classmate, Robert Wald, who will join her in The
Hague and commute to his law firm's London office. Theirs was an
unconventional match for its time: he is Jewish, she Irish
Catholic.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a way, the absence of tradition was the absence of
restraint,'' Judge Wald said during a conversation last week in her
chambers.
</P>
<P>
   The only lawyer she had met as a child was a classmate's father,
a local judge. While she heard there was a female lawyer not far
away in Bridgeport, she had never met one. But she had an idea of
what lawyers did. Several of her relatives were involved in labor
union activities in the Torrington brass mills, where she worked
during the summers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew how important the lawyer was to the union,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   After law school, she got a highly prized clerkship for Judge
Jerome Frank of the 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, one of the
most prominent federal judges of his time. Calling her the best law
clerk he had ever had, Frank, who sat in New Haven, Conn., helped
her get a job in Washington with the law firm now known as Arnold &AMP;
Porter.
</P>
<P>
   Then came babies _ five in seven years (no twins), who as adults
are scattered from Washington to Boston and as far west as Denver.
For 11 years, she was essentially a full-time mother, with
occasional consulting positions on task forces and commissions on
such topics as a bail reform.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always assumed the time would come that I would go back to
work,'' she says now. ``I just wasn't sure how or when.''
</P>
<P>
   Her timing, the late 1960s, coincided with the birth of
public-interest law, and she handled a series of cutting-edge cases
on the rights of women, children, and poor people for the local
legal-services organization and the Center on Law and Social
Policy, a pioneering public interest law firm here.
</P>
<P>
   It was a public career of increasing visibility that led her to
a position as an assistant attorney general in the administration
of President Jimmy Carter and from there to the appeals court. She
served as the court's chief judge from 1986 to 1991 and has written
820 published opinions.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Wald was an obvious choice for a job in the Clinton
administration, and she was briefly in the news for twice taking
herself out of consideration to be attorney general. From her years
in the Justice Department, ``I knew the job,'' she says now, ``and
I knew how large the political component was _ it was just not the
right job for me.''
</P>
<P>
   But the job on the International Criminal Tribunal for the
Former Yugoslavia, for which she was recommended by the State
Department, is another story. Throughout her career, she has held
fast to the liberal view of the Constitution as an engine of social
progress, an idea that often seems anachronistic in today's
conservative judicial climate in the United States but that is a
fresh ideal to many in Eastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Since the early 1990s, Judge Wald has made almost a second
career out of helping the new Eastern European democracies build
their legal systems. She has made 15 trips to the region _
including one last year to Belgrade, Yugoslavia _ many under the
auspices of the American Bar Association's Central and East
European Law Initiative.
</P>
<P>
   She has monitored elections, advised on setting up court systems
and reviewed new constitutions. Helping the tribunal construct a
new system of international justice is a logical next step.
</P>
<P>
   ``To get beyond the high abstractions of the rule of law has
been immensely interesting,'' she said, reflecting on the
challenges and rewards of her recent involvement. ``Sitting around
a table with homemade vodka and writing a constitution bring a kind
of intimacy to the constitutional process that we've long since
left behind us here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-11-99 1749EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990711.0083 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-11 17:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6055 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUMMER-BOOK-SURPRISE-     07-11 0951
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUMMER-BOOK-SURPRISE-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FANTASY TALE OF AN ORPHANED WIZARD IS A SURPRISE BEST SELLER 
</HEADLINE>
 (nk) 
 By EDEN ROSS LIPSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hannibal Lecter and Harry Potter are shaping up as the summer's
must reads. Harry who?
</P>
<P>
   Hannibal the cannibal is the title character of Thomas Harris'
grisly new novel who has appeared in two previous novels and two
movies. So his place atop the best-seller lists is predictable.
</P>
<P>
   But riding broomstick high, right behind the ghoulish Dr.
Lecter, is Harry Potter, an orphan wizard with unruly hair and a
lightning scar on his forehead. This unusually adept pupil at
Hogwarts School for Witchcraft and Wizardry is the hero of two
wildly successful British children's novels by J.R. Rowling.
</P>
<P>
   Last week there were 826,000 copies in print of the first novel,
``Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone,'' and some 915,000 of the
second, ``Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets,'' which was
published on June 2. At bedtime, at the beach, by the pool, in the
back of the car, whole families are reading about the boarding
school where the food is delicious and the equipment list includes
a wand and cauldron.
</P>
<P>
   The Potter books are an international phenomenon; in two years
the first has been published in 115 countries in 25 languages. The
headline in the British newspaper The Guardian on Thursday
proclaimed, ``Hannibal eaten for breakfast by 13-year-old.'' The
article said that 24 hours before publication of the third book,
``Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban,'' with a first printing
of 240,000, it had surpassed ``Hannibal'' on the Amazon.com.uk
charts.
</P>
<P>
   The book went on sale 15 minutes after school ended that
afternoon to stampedes of children going from schoolyards to
stores. Scholastic Press, the American publisher, plans a national
release of that book here on Sept. 7, the day after Labor Day.
British wholesalers have been reminded of the territorial rights of
British publishers and told not to sell ``Azkaban'' abroad. But as
was the case this spring when the second book was available only in
Britain, and e-commerce bypassed copyright, many American readers
and bookstores have already ordered copies directly or on the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   All winter and spring teachers and librarians marveled at the
speed with which children, particularly ``reluctant readers,''
embraced ``Sorcerer's Stone.'' But the biggest surprise, based on
anecdotal evidence, may be the books' combined power to bring boys
back to reading. Calls to sleep-away camps for children aged 8 to
15 around the United States early this month suggest that roughly a
third of the children had already read them.
</P>
<P>
   Bill McMahon, director of Camp Moosilauke, in Orford, N.H., said
ordinarily boys tend to ``leave reading a little behind'' at camp,
though they read every night. This summer, he said, ``we are seeing
them in the hammock at free time and down at the beach with the
books.'' He noted that European campers there had packed their own
editions.
</P>
<P>
   The boys' enthusiasm for Harry Potter is spilling over into
other books, many booksellers and librarians say. They cite, for
example, ``Holes'' by Louis Sachar (Frances Foster Books/Farrar
Straus &AMP; Giroux). This adventure story about Stanley Yelnats
(admittedly certified in adult eyes because it is the winner of the
1998 National Book Award and the 1999 Newbery Medal, the highest
award for a children's book) is selling at nearly twice the
expected rate, more than 190,000 copies in five months. At Barnes &AMP;
Noble, said Steven Geck, the children's buyer, other hardcover
fiction for middle-grade readers, especially boys, is selling
strongly as well.
</P>
<P>
   American girls, for the most part, have always been readers,
have loved series and have been receptive to suggestions for the
next book. Boys have always found alternatives to reading: think
Tom Sawyer. But adult concern for reinforcing boys' reading skills
has intensified in recent years as alternative temptations have
burgeoned to include Pokemon, Play Station, computer games or the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Hardy Boys'' and the baseball novels of John R. Tunis
notwithstanding, the last title genuinely popular with boys, as
opposed to one foisted on them by adults, was probably ``Hatchet,''
Gary Paulsen's realistic 1987 novel about a boy stranded for 54
days in the Canadian wilderness. The book and its sequels remain
popular paperback titles.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the '90s boys read the paperback ``Goosebumps''
series avidly, but, as Clifford Wohl, a former children's
bookseller, put it: ``You couldn't get them off that dime. You
couldn't say, `Here's another scary book you might like.' No. They
only wanted `Goosebumps.' It was like a fence, and the boys were
trapped within the series.''
</P>
<P>
   But word of mouth, not to mention placement in the front of
bookstores because of the best-seller status, has made the Potter
books a crossover phenomenon. They are now attracting adult readers
here pretty much as they did in Britain, where the second book
topped the best-seller lists last year.
</P>
<P>
   Sally Lodge of Wellesley, Mass., said: ``I've been a mother for
almost 18 years, and never in my parenting career have all three of
my children read and even fought over the same book. But then my
husband started the first book at the same time the 11-year-old was
reading it, and he wanted it reserved for him. So he hid it under
his pillow. But she found it.''
</P>
<P>
   Juliette Smith, a counselor at Camp Kamaji, a girls camp in Cass
Lake, Minn., is reading the first book to 8-year-olds, a chapter a
night. ``They are silent throughout,'' she said, ``and then say,
`Can we read some more?'''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Boarding school books have been a British export since ``Tom
Brown's Schooldays'' and fantasy worlds since J.R.R. Tolkien's
``Lord of the Rings.'' Contemporary writers successfully working
with witchcraft and parallel universes include Diana Wynne Jones
and Terry Pratchett, who said recently in The Sunday Times of
London that the British were major exporters of imaginary worlds.
</P>
<P>
   The great summer read in the United States 25 years ago, in fact
the best-selling adult novel for six months, was ``Watership
Down,'' by Richard Adams, a dense fantasy about a rabbit
civilization. A children's title in England, the novel was
considered so sophisticated here that it was published as an adult
book. Today it's a paperback popular on middle-school reading
lists.
</P>
<P>
   Although they are widely admired, and read, by adults, there has
been no confusion about the Potter books. Susan Hirschman, the
editor of Greenwillow Books, who bought ``Watership Down,'' says
that Ms. Rowling's achievement in the Potter books is: ``She never
breaks out of her voice. There's no Roald Dahl bark in the prose,
no adult asides.''
</P>
<P>
   The fantasy is firmly in the British tradition: The wizards live
by rules, hovering above England in a setting quite near reality
but not part of it and so clearly described that young readers can
map it. Hogwarts has required classes in charms and potions, name
tags on black robes and on pointed hats; the mail is delivered by
owls, and Harry stars in the spectacular airborne school sport
called Quidditch, riding his Nimbus 2000 broomstick. And of course
there are good and evil.
</P>
<P>
   The plot springs from the fact that Harry's parents were
murdered by the dark prince Voldemort, generally referred to as
``You Know Who.'' He and his legion disappeared during the years
Harry was in the care of his dreadful human relatives, the
Dursleys. Voldemort's followers are reappearing in pursuit of
Harry, and he lurks somewhere ahead in future books along with the
fevers of adolescence.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Rowling said she imagined the character while riding on a
train. She planned seven books, one for each year of boarding
school, carrying Harry from just before his 11th birthday when he
is summoned to Hogwarts, to graduation. Several years later, while
she was an unemployed single mother on the dole, she sat in cafes
in Edinburgh writing the first novel in longhand while her infant
daughter napped beside her.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur A. Levine of Scholastic, an editor with a keen eye for
fantasy, bought the American rights to the first novel after
reading advance galleys of the British edition. It was a spirited
auction, and the price, $105,000, was the highest then paid for a
foreign children's novel.
</P>
<P>
   In consultation with the author Levine changed the title from
``Philosopher's Stone'' to ``Sorcerer's Stone'' and made small
editing changes that smoothed out differences in British and
American speech. He also added rich paper, a cover illustration and
decorative chapter illustrations.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Scholastic _ best known to adults for the paperback series ``The
Animorphs,'' ``Goosebumps,'' ``Baby Sitters Club'' and ``Fear
Street'' _ used the marketing strategies and techniques given to
promising adult fiction titles. Barbara Marcus, the executive vice
president of the book division, said the strategy included sending
nearly 2,000 advance copies to so-called ``big-mouth'' or
influential adults and children. Scholastic placed Harry Potter in
all its advertisements and in the fall and holiday catalogs,
invested in easel displays and posters and brought Ms. Rowling to
the United States. Independent booksellers in particular eagerly
``hand sold'' the book, recommending it to holiday shoppers.
</P>
<P>
   The first printing was 35,000, with a hefty marketing budget of
$100,000. Still, Diane Roback, children's editor of Publishers
Weekly, which gave ``Sorcerer's Stone'' a starred review and an
interview, says: ``Marketing can only go so far because it's
directed at adults. It's the incredible word of mouth among kids
that has blown this into a phenomenon.''
</P>
<P>
   Scholastic planned to bring out ``Chamber of Secrets'' in
September, a year after the first Harry Potter title, but large
numbers of books imported from England forced them to move up the
date and then to schedule ``Azkaban.'' Appearing in American stores
a week ahead of ``Hannibal,'' ``Chamber of Secrets'' spent a week
as No. 1 on the best-seller list in The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   Beth Peffer at the Bank Street College Book Store in Manhattan
thinks the almost immediate availability of the sequel helped
develop reader loyalty. Often there have been long intervals
between installments of many of the best loved American children's
books.
</P>
<P>
   Using the example of Jean Craighead George's ``Julie of the
Wolves,'' she pointed out: ``The original kids outgrew it before
the sequel came. We sold that to another generation entirely. But
here the sequel is being sold to the initial excitement.''
</P>
<P>
   A new ``Ramona'' book by Beverly Cleary will be published this
fall; the first was published in 1952, the last 15 years ago.
Compare that to three Harry Potter books in a year, something that
never occurs in adult publishing.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Rowling, who will do an American book tour in October, is
off somewhere finishing the fourth book. In the future the novels
will be published simultaneously in all English-speaking countries.
</P>
<P>
   So where, cynical parents sated by ``Phantom Menace''
merchandise this summer must be wondering, is the movie? Where are
the toys? How can this be just a book? Warner Brothers has the film
and merchandise rights to the first book, but there will be a lull
before American children see their personal image of Harry replaced
by a face on a movie screen or have a chance to buy a certified
Nimbus 2000 broomstick.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
