<SLUG> BC-PATENTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATENTS: CUTTING THE TIME TO RECHARGE COMPUTER BATTERIES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas)  (lb) 
 By SABRA CHARTRAND   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lightweight, long-lasting batteries may be the Holy Grail of the
portable-computer industry. Anyone who used a first-generation
laptop in the early days of personal computing will remember toting
a 3-pound battery that lasted only a few hours. Since then,
batteries for laptop and hand-held computers, notebooks and
personal digital assistants have slimmed down considerably and
gained longevity. But even the best lithium ion batteries are
drained eventually.
</P>
<P>
   In pursuit of a solution to the enforced down time of battery
recharging, a designer for Compaq Computer Corp. in Houston looked
for a way to make the computer recharge its own batteries. He
settled on the keyboard.
</P>
<P>
   Adrian Crisan invented a keyboard embedded with magnets and
coils that spark an electric current each time a typist strikes a
key. The electricity is fed to a power generator, which in turn
charges a laptop battery. The more a person types, the more
electricity is fed to the battery charger.
</P>
<P>
   In his patent, Crisan said his invention ``can be used to
lengthen the operating period of the portable computer,'' or
alternatively, lighten the primary battery.
</P>
<P>
   The invention relies on magnets mounted on the stem of each key
of a keyboard, under the key cap. There might be one magnet per
key, but to increase the energy generated, Crisan recommends
several magnets per key.
</P>
<P>
   A number of coils are attached at one end to a printed circuit
board and at the other to each magnet. Depressing a key forces the
magnets to move over the coils. The movement generates an
electrical current. The current from all the keys is collected and
directed into a charge pump. The pump multiplies the voltage
received until it is higher than the voltage of the computer's
battery. This increased voltage is then fed into a battery charger
and transferred to a small secondary battery.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the small battery is discharged rather than the main
battery, the capacity of the main battery is conserved to allow the
portable personal computer to operate in an extended manner,''
Crisan wrote. His patent, 5,911,529, belongs to Compaq.
</P>
<P>
   Patents may be viewed on the Web at www.uspto.gov or may be
ordered through the mail, by patent number, for $3 from the Patent
and Trademark Office, Washington DC 20231.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-11-99 1800EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
