A6060 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-PROGRAM-MUSIC-2TAK     07-11 0849
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PROGRAM-MUSIC-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CBS SEEKING DUAL PAYOFF ON ROCK SERIES
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By BILL CARTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Looking to enter what is becoming a growing secondary profit
center for television networks _ sales of music CDs tied to
programming _ CBS begins shooting this week on the most ambitious
music-oriented miniseries to date, ``Shake, Rattle, and Roll,'' a
four-hour film filled with original or little-known songs, some
composed by such famous names as Bob Dylan and Carole King, and
remakes of 1950s hits performed by a long roster of contemporary
singing stars.
</P>
<P>
   The show is a fictional account of a band's rise in the early
days of rock'n'roll. With talent ranging from blues artist B.B.
King to rhythm-and-blues singers K-Ci and JoJo, and Terence Trent
D'Arby, and rock performers like Blink 182 all signed to perform in
the show and on the soundtrack, CBS is looking for the ultimate
crossover appeal for the production, hitting both fans nostalgic
for the music of that era and young music fans who may be hearing
it for the first time,
</P>
<P>
   The network has deals in place with Seagram's MCA Records as
music partner and Phoenix Pictures as production partner and all
the parties are looking to cash in on a massive marketing plan
designed to sell the CD soundtrack album of the show, which CBS
will broadcast on Nov. 7.
</P>
<P>
   As Jeremy Hammond, the vice president and director of marketing
for MCA Records put it, ``If this show captures people's
imaginations the way we hope it will, with CBS pushing it on
television and MCA's marketing muscle behind it, we could sell
millions of CDs.''
</P>
<P>
   CBS also hopes to reach ratings that approach blockbuster status
and perhaps even bring in millions of younger viewers the networks
has had trouble reaching on a regular basis.
</P>
<P>
   The miniseries as music marketing tool became one of the favored
new genres of television networks last season when NBC scored in
both ratings and record sales with two music-oriented miniseries,
``The Temptations'' and ``The 60's.'' Both show were ratings hits
and both sold hundreds of thousands of CDs when NBC, a subsidiary
of General Electric, aggressively sold them through on-air pitches
and toll-free telephone numbers. ``The 60's'' became one of the
hottest albums in the country right after it was broadcast, selling
more than 400,000 copies.
</P>
<P>
   CBS noticed the potential as soon as it saw the ratings for
``The Temptations'' last November. It put ``Shake, Rattle and
Roll'' into development virtually the day that film was on the air,
and onto a fast track for production the day the ratings came in
for ``The 60's'' last February.
</P>
<P>
   The idea for the project started with one of the network's own
executives, Michael Wright, a vice president in the movie and
miniseries department. Wright, who said he had been a ``rock'n'roll
junkie my whole life'' was trying to think of a project that could
involve music and somehow appeal both to CBS's core audience of
mostly older viewers and the younger viewers the network would like
to reach.
</P>
<P>
   He came up with the notion of a love story of a young couple set
against the beginning days of rock'n'roll. They form a band known
as The Harleys and encounter both success and disappointment in
trying to forge a music career in those sometimes tempestuous days
of rapidly changing music.
</P>
<P>
   The key to getting the project off the ground, Wright said, was
securing the services of Spencer Proffer, a music industry veteran,
with producing and composing credits going back two decades and
connections to artists and executives throughout the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Proffer had been expanding his own interests into films,
including work for Showtime on ``Gods and Monsters,'' and he was
immediately enthusiastic about the project. ``I committed because I
know this was going to be done right, by people with a real passion
for the music,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That passion was expressed by the commitment not to include any
songs that did not fit organically into the story. Thus when the
young hero, a country singer, begins discovering what was known at
the time as ``race music'' in roadhouses in Missouri, he encounters
both the early work of Little Richard (played by Billy Porter, who
starred in ``Smokey Joe's Cafe''' on Broadway) and a fictional
blues singer, played by B.B. King. The latter sings a song, ``Fur
Slippers,'' an original and never-before-heard composition by Bob
Dylan, described by Hammond of MCA as ``a smokin' blues number.''
</P>
<P>
   Proffer made the contact with Dylan, and acquired the rights to
the song. He said Dylan, along with B.B. King, felt the project was
a sincere attempt to capture the moment in time when blues evolved
into what became rock'n'roll.
</P>
<P>
   Proffer credited Mike Robe, the film's writer and director, with
fleshing out the story in a way that would accommodate the notion
of numerous song performances while also telling a story that
emphasized both the romance and, more subtly, the way music of that
era helped break down racial barriers in the country.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The film will include the old recordings of a few songs played
as background like Chuck Berry on ``Maybelline,'' and The Platters
singing ``Only You,'' but for the most part Proffer lined up
contemporary artists to stand in for 1950s rock pioneers. So Dickie
Barrett, the lead singer of current ska group The Mighty Mighty
Bosstones, plays Bill Haley singing the film's title song. Chante
Moore, the rhythm and blues diva who has a current single hit with
``Chante's Got a Man,'' will sing the lead in a female group
modeled on The Shirelles. She sings a new song written by Carole
King, who really did write for the Shirelles.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the three members of Blink 182 will play Jan and Dean
singing ``Dead Man's Curve.'' D'Arby will play rock legend Jackie
Wilson singing one of his hits ``To Be Loved.'' The show will also
include one of the staples of the era, the street corner doo-wop
group, in this case formed by a collection of top current rhythm
and blues singers headed by K-Ci and JoJo, who had a triple
platinum album, ``Love Always,'' last year and a new album, ``It's
Real,'' which has already sold more than a million copies. They
will sing a street corner version of the Little Anthony and the
Imperials hit ``Tears on My Pillow.''
</P>
<P>
   Proffer also reached out to perhaps the most successful
composers of that era, Jerry Lieber and Mike Stoller, asking if
they had, what he called ``any old chestnuts'' that had been lost
to time. They offered up dozens of possibilities from which he
chose two songs few have heard of since they were obscurely
recorded in 1953 and 1954, ``One Bad Stud'' and ``Touch of
Heaven.''
</P>
<P>
   For other songs he needed, Proffer went to other friends in the
music business including Graham Nash, who worked on two songs, and
one the most prolific composers from the golden age of soul, Lamont
Dozier, who collaborated with Proffer on the show's de facto theme
song, an anthem called ``Side By Side,'' which is sung by The
Harleys in the show and then by the entire cast (and much of the
crew including Wright of CBS, who also sings background on several
other vocals) as the closing number.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   After lining up the artists and acquiring rights to the music,
Proffer began arranging and producing it. He finished a first mix
of the songs several months ago. Hammond said a final mix would be
ready at the end of the summer and would be rolled out in stores
beginning in early October. MCA will work the usual retail outlets
to place the record, he said, and then CBS will begin a huge
marketing push, both on the television network and on its numerous
radio stations when the miniseries begins. That will include not
only a toll-free number commercial after each night of the show but
also a Web site that will be set up to help sales.
</P>
<P>
   Proffer said for him and many of the other music artists
involved in the project, the profit motive was secondary to a
chance to do a project that tapped so deeply into their musical
roots. But he conceded, ``We think we will do some serious commerce
with this project.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-11-99 1805EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990711.0089 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-11 18:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6062 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRISON-MENTAL-ILLNESS     07-11 1252
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRISON-MENTAL-ILLNESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPERTS SAY STUDY CONFIRMS PRISON'S NEW ROLE AS MENTAL HOSPITAL 
</HEADLINE>
 
 (ATTN: Ill., Md.) (nk) 
 By FOX BUTTERFIELD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The first comprehensive study of the rapidly growing number of
emotionally disturbed people in the nation's jails and prisons has
found that there are 283,800 inmates with severe mental illness,
about 16 percent of the total jail population. The report confirms
the belief of many state, local and federal experts that jails and
prisons have become the nation's new mental hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   The study, released by the Justice Department on Sunday, paints
a grim statistical portrait, detailing how emotionally disturbed
inmates tend to follow a revolving door from homelessness to
incarceration and then back to the streets with little treatment,
many of them arrested for crimes that grow out of their illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   According to the report, mentally ill inmates in state prisons
were more than twice as likely to have been homeless before their
arrest than other inmates, twice as likely to have been physically
and sexually abused in childhood and far more likely to have been
on drugs or alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   In another reflection of their chaotic lives, the study found
that emotionally disturbed inmates had many more previous
incarcerations than other prisoners. More than three quarters of
them had been sentenced to jail or prison before, and half had
served three or more prior sentences.
</P>
<P>
   Many of them were arrested for bizarre public behavior or petty
crimes like loitering or public intoxication. But the report, by
the Justice Department's Bureau of Justice Statistics, also found
that mentally ill inmates in state prisons were more likely than
other prisoners to have been convicted of a violent crime.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, once incarcerated, emotionally disturbed inmates in
state prisons spend an average of 15 months longer behind bars than
other prisoners, often because their delusions, hallucinations or
paranoia make them more likely to get in fights or receive
disciplinary reports.
</P>
<P>
   ``This study provides data to show that the incarceration of the
mentally ill is a disastrous, horrible social issue,'' said Kay
Redfield Jamison, a professor of psychiatry at the Johns Hopkins
School of Medicine. ``There is something fundamentally broken in
the system that covers both hospitals and jails,'' said Jamison,
the author of ``Night Falls Fast: Understanding Suicide,'' to be
published later this year by Knopf.
</P>
<P>
   With the wholesale closings of public mental hospitals in the
1960s, and the prison boom of the past two decades, jails and
prisons are often the only institutions open 24 hours a day and
required to take the emotionally disturbed.
</P>
<P>
   The hospitals were closed at a time when new antipsychotic drugs
made medicating patients in the community seem a humane alternative
to long-term hospitalization. From a high of 559,000 in 1955, the
number of patients in state hospitals dropped to 69,000 in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   But drugs work only when taken, and many states failed to build
a promised network of clinics to monitor patients. To compound the
problem, for-profit hospitals began turning away the psychotic.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the number of jail and prison beds has
quadrupled in the last 25 years, with 1.8 million Americans now
behind bars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jails have become the poor person's mental hospitals,'' said
Linda A. Teplin, a professor of psychiatry and director of the
psycho-legal studies program at Northwestern University.
</P>
<P>
   All previous estimates of the number of emotionally disturbed
inmates have been based on research by Teplin in the Cook County
Jail in Chicago. She found that 9.5 percent of male inmates there
had experienced a severe mental disorder like schizophrenia, manic
depression or major depression, four times the rate in the general
population.
</P>
<P>
   Teplin said that while she welcomed the Justice Department
count, it was open to question because the study relied on reports
by the inmates themselves, who were asked whether they had a mental
condition or had ever received treatment for a mental problem.
People with emotional disorders often are not aware of them, or do
not want to report them, she said, so the Justice Department
estimate of more than a quarter million inmates with mental illness
may actually be too low, Teplin said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Teplin said, the study was not conducted by mental
health professionals using diagnostic tests, so it was impossible
to tell what mental disorders the inmates suffered from, and
whether they were severe illnesses, like schizophrenia, or
generally less severe problems, like anxiety disorders.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most striking findings in the study, and the one most
likely to be disputed, is that mentally ill inmates were more
likely to have been incarcerated for a violent offense than other
prisoners, with 53 percent of emotionally disturbed inmates in
state prisons sentenced for a violent crime, compared with 46
percent of other prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, the report found that 13.2 percent of mentally ill
inmates in prisons had been convicted of murder, compared with 11.4
percent of other prisoners, and 12.4 percent of mentally ill
inmates had been convicted of sexual assault, compared with 7.9
percent of other prisoners. Emotionally disturbed inmates in state
prisons had also been convicted of more property crimes, but were
only half as likely to have been sentenced for drug crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates for the mentally ill have worked hard to show that
emotionally disturbed people are no more violent than others, to
try to lessen the stigma surrounding mental illness. But recent
research, while confirming that mentally ill people may not be more
violent than others, suggests that they can become violent in a
number of conditions, including when they are off their
medications, are actively psychotic or are taking drugs or alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   In another important finding, also subject to differing
interpretations, the study found that reported rates of mental
illness varied by race and gender, with white and female inmates
reporting higher rates than black and male inmates. The highest
rates of mental illness were among white female state prisoners,
with an estimated 29 percent of them reporting emotional disorders,
compared with 20 percent of black female prisoners. Overall, 22.6
percent of white state prisoners were identified as mentally ill,
compared with 13.5 percent of black prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Dorothy Otnow-Lewis, a psychiatrist, said the differences
were a result of white psychiatrists ``being very bad at
recognizing mental illness in minority individuals.'' Psychiatrists
are more likely to dismiss aggressive behavior in men, particularly
black men, as a result of their being bad, rather than being mad,
said Otnow-Lewis, who is a senior criminal justice fellow at the
Center on Crime, Communities and Culture of the Soros Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Faenza, president of the National Mental Health
Association, said the finding that mentally ill inmates tend to
have more previous incarcerations than other prisoners ``shows that
the criminal justice system is just a revolving door for a person
with mental illness, from the street to jail and back without
treatment.''
</P>
<P>
   Jamison noted that jails and prisons are not conducive to
treatment, even when it is available. ``Inmates get deprived of
sleep,'' she said, ``and isolation can exacerbate their
hallucinations or delusions.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
