u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VODKA-AD-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      07-11 0818
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VODKA-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABSOLUT PITCHES ORANGE-FLAVORED VODKA 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's an old saying that nothing rhymes with ``orange.'' So
there may not be a rhyme for a multimillion-dollar campaign to
pitch a new orange-flavored variety of Absolut vodka _ but there
certainly is a reason.
</P>
<P>
   Seagram Americas is bringing out Absolut Mandrin, the brand's
fourth flavor after Peppar (pepper, introduced in 1986), Citron
(citrus, 1988) and Kurant (currant, 1992) for a clear reason: The
flavored segment of the vodka market is growing faster than the
vodka category as a whole. And with a major Absolut competitor,
Stolichnaya, offering an orange flavor _ ``Stoli O'' to the in
crowd _ it is not surprising that Absolut would roll into the
orange arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes sense for Absolut to not let Stolichnaya have it to
themselves,'' said Bob Keane, editorial director at Adams Business
Media in New York, which tracks the performance of the liquor
industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``And it makes sense because orange is a good flavor,'' he
added, as evinced by the longtime popularity of drinks that mix
vodka with orange juice as well as brisk sales for citrus-flavored
vodkas like Absolut Citron.
</P>
<P>
   The Mandrin variety is to be introduced on Thursday and is
scheduled to be available nationwide by Sept. 1. It's the first new
flavor of Absolut being brought out by Seagram Americas since its
parent, Seagram Co., acquired the brand's worldwide distribution
rights in 1994 from the Swedish distiller, Vin and Sprit AB.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a market leader, we have to be proactive,'' said James E.
Schleifer, North American marketing director for Absolut at Seagram
Americas in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel there's a great opportunity here,'' he added, because
``in-depth surveys showed this flavor provided an optimal
complement'' to the current Absolut line.
</P>
<P>
   Flavors account for 15 percent of the volume of Absolut; Seagram
distributed 3.6 million cases of the brand last year, according to
Adams, up 5.5 percent from 3.4 million in 1997. And the
citrus-flavored Absolut Citron accounted for 75 percent of the
total flavor volume; distribution of Absolut Citron in 1998
increased 15 percent from 1997, to 460,000 cases from 400,000.
</P>
<P>
   Absolut has continued performing well under Seagram, remaining
the nation's No. 1 imported vodka brand and No. 2 over all behind
only Smirnoff. But as Seagram intensifies its focus on
premium-priced brands like Absolut, the company is increasingly
pursuing a strategy known as creating news: teaching old brands new
tricks to further stimulate sales among shoppers who crave novelty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Though in a certain sense we are following the Absolut
template, we started with a fresh sheet of paper for Absolut
Mandrin,'' said Richard Lewis, worldwide director for the Absolut
account at TBWA/Chiat/Day in New York, part of the TBWA Worldwide
unit of Omnicom Group.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Absolut Mandrin will be the first Absolut with a
punt _ the indentation at the bottom of the bottle _ to be colored
to match the flavor. ``When we showed it to consumers, their jaws
dropped so much you could fit an orange in,'' Lewis said. ``When
they see it on the shelves, it will be provoking.''
</P>
<P>
   The campaign for Absolut Mandrin is starting with two print ads
that are running on consecutive right-hand pages of magazines like
GQ, New York, Rolling Stone, Spin and Vanity Fair. The first ad
carries the headline ``Absolut sighting'' under a photograph of an
orange posed to resemble a UFO.
</P>
<P>
   The second ad carries the headline ``Absolut arrival'' under a
photograph of the Absolut Mandrin bottle, the punt gleaming as if
lit by, in Lewis' words, ``an orange sunrise.''
</P>
<P>
   Subsequent ads will include ``Absolut balance,'' Lewis said,
with an orange wedge perched atop the bottle, and an ad in which
``an orange will be inserted in place of the word `orange.'''
Marketing plans include store displays, postcards, T-shirts, shot
glasses and orange-shaped recipe brochures.
</P>
<P>
   There will also be promotions, Schleifer said, that will include
flying or tethering a 60-foot-high hot air balloon ``at Absolut
Mandrin `arrival parties' in August and September in the Hamptons,
Chicago, Los Angeles and Miami.''
</P>
<P>
   Are vodka drinkers being absolutely overwhelmed by variety,
considering that there will be four flavors of Absolut plus two
variations of the base brand (in 80 and 100 proof) along with the
multiple flavors of Stolichnaya, not to mention other upscale
brands like Finlandia, Ketel One and Skyy?
</P>
<P>
   ``This could end up like wine coolers, a flavor-of-the-month
business,'' said Keane at Adams. ``A retailer or a bar isn't going
to have room for all of these.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But flavored vodkas appeal to younger adults,'' he added,
``and are good for the modern martinis. In the first year, Absolut
Mandrin should easily do 50,000 cases.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
