<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-11 18:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6065 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ASIA-RECOVERY-ART-110     07-11 1188
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASIA-RECOVERY-ART-1100(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: GLOBAL CRISIS APPEARS OVER, BUT ASIA'S ECONOMIC ILLS
LINGER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Thailand, Malaysia, Indonesia, South Korea, Philippines,
Brazil, Russia)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By DAVID E. SANGER and MARK LANDLER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just two years after it began, the financial crisis that started
in Asia and spread pain around the world appears to be over _
leaving many to wonder if the symptoms have abated before the
disease could be treated.
</P>
<P>
   All the conventional measures of health look good. Stock markets
that tumbled soon after the crisis started in Thailand in July 1997
have bounced back, ranking among the world's best performers in the
first half of 1999. Currencies that plummeted, leaving ruin in
their wake, have crawled back. Foreign investors who fled Asia like
movie-goers from a burning theater are returning, poking around for
hidden bargains amid the embers.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton's plausible assessment nine months ago that
the world faced ``the worst financial crisis in half a century''
now seems like a distant echo from another financial era.
</P>
<P>
   But the recovery may have come too fast. In interviews with
business executives, policymakers and investors in Asia and
America, there is a common thread: The remarkable speed of the
rebound has drained the political urgency out of many reforms that
seemed so vital during the darkest days of the crisis _and may
still be essential to Asia's future. Most Asian countries have not
genuinely confronted the twin weaknesses of their economies:
insolvent banks and deeply indebted corporations. Bad loans and bad
habits still plague financial institutions from Korea to Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hear a lot about reforms since the Asian crisis,'' James
Harmon, chairman of the Export-Import Bank of the United States,
said in an interview. ``The truth is that many of the reforms are
not proceeding. Old habits die hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Harmon speaks from bitter experience. Not long ago he quietly
sought help from Indonesia's president, B.J. Habibie, in convincing
one of the country's biggest conglomerates, the Bakrie Group, to
begin paying back $80 million owed to the Ex-Im Bank, an
independent U.S. government agency that promotes exports by
subsidizing loans and providing credit guarantees to developing
countries that buy American-made goods. Harmon's message was
unspoken, but clear: The United States stood behind the bailout
that kept Indonesia from a wholesale financial meltdown, and its
taxpayers should not be stiffed.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Harmon has proven singularly unpersuasive, perhaps
because the man who owes him, Aburizal Bakrie, has also emerged as
one of Habibie's staunchest supporters. Bakrie did not respond to
several requests for an interview.
</P>
<P>
   In the place where the crisis began, Thailand, the man
responsible for overhauling the battered financial system, Amaret
Sila-on, rarely misses an opportunity to warn that less has changed
than meets the eye.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, he says, Thailand has finally created a bankruptcy court,
after two years of foot-dragging by politicians who also head some
of the country's biggest insolvent companies. But cronyism lives,
he warns, as does the system that heedlessly lent money to the
politically powerful.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the rule of law still remains weaker than the rule of
men,'' Amaret argues, ``banks will return to their old ways despite
the restructuring efforts.''
</P>
<P>
   The guiding ethic around Asia these days seems to be this: Wait
it out, because in a rebounding market, we will not have to change
much. Foreign money is returning, in some cases fueled by Western
companies seeking bargains, in other cases by mutual fund managers
riding the momentum of a perceived recovery. Some funds may also
belong to wealthy ethnic Chinese and others in Southeast Asia who
sent cash abroad during the crisis and now are gradually bringing
it back home.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of CEOs are clinging to their jobs,'' said Razak
Baginda, the executive director of the Malaysian Strategic Research
Center, a research firm in Kuala Lumpur. ``In a way, they've been
saved by the stock market.''
</P>
<P>
   While some of Asia's most troubled companies had to liquidate or
sell out to Western investors, many firms that appear insolvent
have remained frozen in place. The result is that the corruption
and collusion that contributed to the crisis, and the complacency
that allowed banks to lend with abandon as governments looked the
other way, have not disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no question that with improving markets, political
pressure to change things is reduced,'' Stanley Fischer, the No. 2
official at the International Monetary Fund, said recently. Fischer
argues, however, that the risks of a ``systemic crisis'' have been
reduced, partly because of changes at his own institution.
</P>
<P>
   James D. Wolfensohn, the president of the World Bank, which
often openly disagrees with the IMF's prescriptions, calls the end
of the crisis ``a very mixed story,'' and worries that institutions
like his own ``no longer have the leverage to get the system
fixed'' now that the countries are not in need of immediate cash.
</P>
<P>
   One reason the reforms have been so plodding is that no one ever
really decided what caused the crisis. Americans were quick to
point to traditions of cronyism and corruption. But those practices
have characterized business in Asian countries for decades, and
didn't slow what was known as the East Asian miracle.
</P>
<P>
   Asians, bolstered by some big-name Western economists, blamed
the IMF for worsening the crisis by forcing big spending cuts to
trim deficits. The IMF reversed its strategy after some months. In
the end, U.S. and IMF officials note, the countries that most
closely followed its advice _ Thailand, South Korea and Brazil _
appear to have rebounded the fastest. The two nations that were so
mired in political chaos that they never executed the IMF's plans _
Russia and Indonesia _ are still in deep trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Pressure from Washington has been uneven. For much of last year,
the Asian crisis dominated White House strategy sessions, with many
senior officials fearing it could puncture Wall Street's party. But
the sense of crisis abated last September after Russia's economic
collapse was contained more quickly than anyone expected. And
gradually the impetus for wide-ranging reforms slackened, and grand
plans for remaking the world financial system became modest
adjustments, including new IMF mechanisms to respond earlier to
``economic contagion'' hitting otherwise well-run countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end, Rubin's caution about messing with the market
system won out,'' one senior administration official said recently,
referring to former Treasury secretary Robert Rubin, whose
resignation took effect 10 days ago, two years to the day after
Thailand's crisis began. ``That may have been the right instinct.
We'll know in about 10 years.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Some problems that triggered the crisis seem to have been at
least temporarily addressed. Virtually all the crisis-hit countries
frittered away state foreign currency reserves trying to keep their
currencies strong _ and tried to hide that news from investors. Now
that the IMF has pressed countries to publish more information,
data once considered state secrets can now be found on the fund's
Internet site (www.imf.org).
</P>
<P>
   The Thai baht and the Korean won float freely, and the countries
have rebuilt their war-chests of foreign currency, mostly by
exporting to the United States and stacking up the dollars they get
in return.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Asian countries have largely halted their practice of
borrowing from abroad on short terms to finance big, long-term
projects. That proved disastrous when projects ground to a halt and
currencies fell, forcing companies and banks to repay huge debts
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Other bad habits are proving harder to break. No Asian country
has yet put an effective bankruptcy law on its books, meaning it is
still impossible to wipe out insolvent businesses, settle with
creditors and rebuild viable companies. Thailand has come closest _
opening its first bankruptcy court last month and staffing it with
60 judges.
</P>
<P>
   Still, skeptics say it will take months for those judges to
master complex bankruptcy laws. And they will find it hard to fight
proprietors of debt-ridden companies, some of whom sit in the Thai
Senate and have bitterly opposed the passage of stronger laws.
</P>
<P>
   In Indonesia, where the laws are even more toothless, the
government has resorted to shaming its corporate sector. The
Indonesian Bank Restructuring Authority recently named the 100
worst debtors in local newspapers. But even conglomerates on the
list, like the Bakrie Group, are dragging their feet on resolving
their debt problems.
</P>
<P>
   Bakrie has offered to give its banks equity in return for
canceling its $1 billion in debt. The U.S. Ex-Im Bank and other
creditors object that the plan would leave the Bakrie family, which
dug the conglomerate into a hole in the first place, with
considerable influence. And they believe Bakrie has wildly
overstated the value of that equity. Still, some local bankers say
Bakrie's creditors may have little choice but to comply.
</P>
<P>
   ``When companies tell their creditors to go through regular
legal channels, that basically means, `Go fly a kite,''' said a
senior official at a U.S. bank in Jakarta, who spoke on condition
of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Rizal Ramli, an Indonesian economist, said the government lacked
the courage to go after well-connected tycoons. ``During the
Suharto era,'' he said, ``there were only five conglomerates that
were untouchable because of their ties to Suharto. Now, there seem
to be many more.''
</P>
<P>
   As long as Asia's banks cannot pursue debtors, they cannot clean
up their balance sheets. Nearly half of all loans carried on the
books of Thai banks are classified as nonperforming _ meaning they
will probably never be repaid. As a result, Thailand's banks have
not made fresh loans, hampering economic recovery, even with a
resurgent currency and stock market. The same is true in Indonesia,
Malaysia, and South Korea _ and of course in Japan, whose banking
problems continue to affect the rest of Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Hopes that the crisis would bring accountability to Asian
business are fading fast, too. In Malaysia, the infrastructure
giant, Renong, ran up $2.4 billion in debts, despite winning
lucrative franchises to run toll roads and bridges. Renong's
creditors blamed the youthful chairman, Halim Saad.
</P>
<P>
   Renong is now being rescued by a $2.2 billion bond offering by
one of its subsidiaries, which operates Malaysia's key north-south
toll highway. Although the bonds are not guaranteed by the
government _ which would make it a direct bailout _ analysts say it
will result in higher tolls or force the government to extend the
company's franchise. Halim, a protege of Finance Minister Daim
Zainuddin and a favorite of Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad, has
meanwhile kept his job.
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere, perhaps, is the danger of Asia's backsliding more
apparent than in the case of Philippine Airlines. The flagship
carrier of the Philippines has been staggering under $2.2 billion
in debt _ the victim of costly fleet expansion at the time of the
regional crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Philippine Airlines, commonly known as PAL, is controlled by
Lucio C. Tan, one of the country's leading tycoons and a loyal
supporter of the Philippine president, Joseph P. Estrada, who used
a PAL plane for free during last year's presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The government has so far refused to bail out the airline, but
Estrada has made it a personal mission to keep Philippine Airlines
flying. He has backed a rehabilitation plan that would leave Tan, a
tobacco-and-beer mogul, in control. Ex-Im Bank, which financed the
purchase of Boeing planes by the airline, opposes the plan _ and
seized a PAL Boeing 747 earlier this year when it flew into the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   A court forced it to return the plane, but now it has threatened
to seize four Boeing 747s, saying that it fears PAL is not
maintaining them well enough to preserve their value as collateral
on the loan. Tan has not responded to repeated interview requests.
</P>
<P>
   Philippine Airlines proposes to recover by persuading the
government to reduce the number of rival carriers able to fly into
the Philippines. That would run counter to the whole movement to
open up Asia's markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``This would be a disaster, not just for the tourist industry
but for the country in general,'' said Emmanuel Gonzalez, the
president of the Hotel, Resort and Restaurant Association of Cebu,
a resort island in the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
   As the Asian crisis recedes, Gonzalez is finally seeing his
business improve. But the Philippine Airlines case reminds him of
how little has changed in the clubby world of Asian commerce.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people here say, `Wouldn't it be awful if we lost our
flag carrier?''' he said, ``I wonder if they're really saying,
`Wouldn't it be awful if we didn't get our free tickets anymore?'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
