<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAW-MERGER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICAN AND BRITISH LAW FIRMS SET TO MERGE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., N.J.)  (rk) 
 By MELODY PETERSEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lawyers at Rogers &AMP; Wells in New York and Clifford Chance in
London announced Sunday that they had approved a merger of their
firms, the first combination between major British and American law
firms.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the firms' partners said they had agreed to
push forward with plans to merge with Germany's third-largest law
firm _ a move that would create the largest law firm in the world
in terms of both lawyers and revenue, pushing aside two American
giants.
</P>
<P>
   Partners at the three firms said Sunday that they were reacting
to the needs of their multinational corporate clients, who often
must hire myriad law firms.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to do the best deals for our clients,'' said Keith
Clark, senior partner at Clifford Chance, who will become chairman
of the combined firm. ``They don't want time delays and
inefficiencies from appointing a half-dozen law firms around the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   The top partners at the German firm _ Puender, Volhard, Weber &AMP;
Axster _ have already agreed to merge with Clifford Chance.
Partners at all three law firms plan to vote on the German merger
in September. The merger with Rogers &AMP; Wells and Puender, Volhard
would be effective on Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   The combined firm would have 2,700 lawyers and 30 offices
worldwide. The three firms will earn more than $1 billion in fees
this year, the partners said.
</P>
<P>
   Skadden, Arps, Slate, Meagher &AMP; Flom in New York is now the
world's leader when it comes to fees, earning $890 million last
year, according to American Lawyer magazine. In terms of lawyers,
Chicago's Baker &AMP; McKenzie ranks first, with 2,330.
</P>
<P>
   At least one competitor was not shaken by the news. Robert C.
Sheehan, executive partner at Skadden, Arps, said that his firm
would not be looking soon for a partner to try to keep its place at
the top.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've never done a merger with anyone, and we don't
contemplate doing one in the foreseeable future,'' Sheehan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You tend to be known by the work you do,'' he said, and not
just by the size of the firm.
</P>
<P>
   But Clifford Chance partners were clearly excited Sunday about
their plunge into New York's financial and legal markets. Clifford
Chance will have more than 300 lawyers in New York, far more than
any other British firm.
</P>
<P>
   Clark vowed Sunday that Clifford Chance would become one of the
10-largest New York firms within three years. ``We already have a
number of lawyers calling and asking to join us,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Partners at Rogers &AMP; Wells voted unanimously to join the British
giant, Clark said. The vote means that Rogers &AMP; Wells, a New York
institution that traces its roots back 128 years, will cease to
exist on Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   The combined firm will be known as Clifford Chance Rogers &AMP;
Wells in the United States and as Clifford Chance elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   The New York firm's partners include William P. Rogers, 86, who
was secretary of state in the Nixon administration and attorney
general under President Eisenhower.
</P>
<P>
   But while the formal terms of their merger are now set, the two
firms must work on adapting to each other's culture, language and
work methods.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be an enormous job,'' said Joel F. Henning, senior
vice president at Hildebrandt International, a consulting firm
based in Somerset, N.J., that advises law firms that are merging.
``They must agree on everything from the way they spell the word
`realize' to the best way to compensate people.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark said that partners had agreed to a compensation system
that was more British than American. Most British firms pay their
partners based on seniority and the number of years they have
worked for the firm, a system known as ``lock step.'' But most
American law firms have opted instead for a system that they refer
to as ``eat what you kill,'' where partners are paid based more on
the amount of new business they generate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
