<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-11 18:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6070 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIOSCOPE-COLUMN-SFCHR     07-11 0908
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIOSCOPE-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMALL INVESTORS ENJOY TESTING THE MURKY WATERS OF BIOTECH STOCKS
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By TOM ABATE 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
The nature of biotech stock investing today may well be summed up
by the lyric to an old love song: ``Fools rush in where wise men
never go.''
<P>
   At a time when the institutional investors _ a.k.a. wise men _
have fallen out of love with small to mid-sized biotech, individual
investors _ alas, we don't know whether foolishly or not _ have
rushed in to embrace the sector.
</P>
<P>
   Small investors have become so important to the industry's
fortunes that a recent edition of BioCentury, the weekly trade
newsletter based in San Carlos, Calif., focused on what the trade
calls retail investors.
</P>
<P>
   The universe of small investors includes some who have
gravitated to biotech for goofy reasons, like the sheer fun of
accumulating large positions in stocks that sell for $2 or $3.
These bottom-fishers may indeed get lucky, but they tend to be the
folks who e-mail me from time to time, complaining about stocks
that have nosedived.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are solid reasons for retail investors to study
small to midsized biotech stocks, according to Richard van den
Broek, an analyst with Hambrecht &AMP; Quist. The most important is
demographics: Aging baby boomers are expanding the market for
drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, this demographic trend means some drug discovery
firms will strike it rich. But that begs the key question: which
companies and when?
</P>
<P>
   If you're thinking of betting on biotech, here are a few tips to
help you avoid rushing in too foolishly.
</P>
<P>
   First, before you test your luck with individual shares, try
investing in a mutual fund that specializes in the broad heading of
life sciences.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately the universe of such funds with proven track
records isn't large, said Steve Janachowski, a financial planner in
Tiburon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the funds haven't been around long enough,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   One of the best options, according to Janachowski, is Invesco
Health Sciences Fund. In the seven years this mutual has been
around, its annual return has ranged from a 14 percent loss in
1992, to a 43 percent gain in 1998. Year-to-date, the fund is down
4 percent but it still rates a four out five possible stars
according to Morningstar, which evaluates fund performance.
</P>
<P>
   If you have access to the Web, you can use Morningstar to get a
free peek at more health or biotech funds. Go to
www.morningstar.net and click on fund selector. That takes you to a
page that asks you to select a fund category (choose U.S. stocks)
and a second criterion, like one-year return.
</P>
<P>
   You'll have to hunt through the list that appears for funds with
health, life sciences or biotech in the name. Copy down the names _
and the ticker symbols _ and return to the Morningstar.net home
page. Type the ticker symbol into the ``Quicktake'' function to
learn more about the fund.
</P>
<P>
   If you have a hankering to invest in individual shares, you'll
need to do a lot more research. Even expert investors get burned on
biotech stocks because negative developments can pop out of
nowhere. A failed clinical trial can send shares tumbling, and
there's no way to know in advance.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are new tools available to help individual
investors get up to speed on small biotech offerings. Small Caps
Online (www.smallcapsonline.com) is a New York firm that offers
free research reports on biotech firms with market capitalizations
under $250 million.
</P>
<P>
   These are exactly the firms that have been overlooked by
institutional investors, and the large investment banks who do most
Wall Street research. Small Caps is trying to establish itself as a
full-service investment bank to help tiny biotech firms, according
to spokeswoman Jennifer LaVin.
</P>
<P>
   Small Caps plans to support itself by earning fees from helping
biotech firms do mergers and other deals. While it remains to be
seen how that business will fare, the firm is issuing Wall
Street-type research reports, free, to small investors.
</P>
<P>
   One last caveat.
</P>
<P>
   Biotech or medical device companies need Food &AMP; Drug
Administration approval before they can sell products. The FDA puts
these products through a three-step process of clinical trials
before it gives thumbs up or down.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street analysts start tracking companies after they've
successfully completed their third round of trials. But they don't
rush out and buy on that news, because the firm still has two more
hurdles: It needs a positive FDA advisory panel vote and then full
FDA approval.
</P>
<P>
   In general, Wall Street has waited until after final FDA
approval to buy into a biotech stock. Sure, the institutions miss a
little upside appreciation, but they also avoid most of the
downside risk of placing bets too early.
</P>
<P>
   The experience of Scios Inc. provides a good parable on the
virtue of patience. Shares in the Mountain View firm started
climbing steadily, from below $4 last November to a high of $12.50
earlier this year. Driving the gain was positive news about a
congestive heart failure drug. Scios stock rose when the drug,
Natrecor, show positive results in Phase III trials. It rose again
when an FDA advisory panel _ the second-to-last step in the process
_ gave it a good recommendation.
</P>
<P>
   But in late April, the full FDA told Scios the drug needed more
tests. Scios shared abruptly plunged below $4 again, and have
bumped along there ever since.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
