<HEADER>
A6075 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRO     07-11 0796
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; THE BEST AND THE WORST OF SECRETARIES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Washingtonian magazine credits recently resigned Treasury
Secretary  &UR; Robert Rubin &LR;  for stabilizing global financial markets,
saving the Mexican economy and preventing Asian economic problems
from becoming catastrophes for the United States, and calls him the
fifth best Cabinet secretary in the century.
</P>
<P>
   Numbers one through four, in descending order:  &UR; George C. &LR; 
 &UR; Marshall &LR; ,  &UR; Harry Truman &LR; 's secretary of state, author of the
Marshall Plan;  &UR; Carter Glass &LR; , Treasury secretary under  &UR; Woodrow &LR; 
 &UR; Wilson &LR; , who implemented the Federal Reserve System;  &UR; Henry &LR; 
 &UR; Kissinger &LR; , secretary of state under  &UR; Richard Nixon &LR; , for opening
relations with China;  &UR; Henry Morgenthau Jr. &LR; , Treasury secretary
to &UR; FDR &LR; , who was ``among the first to warn the president of Nazi
genocide.''
</P>
<P>
   Washingtonian's five worst:  &UR; John Mitchell &LR; , Nixon's attorney
general, mastermind of Watergate;  &UR; Albert Fall &LR; , Interior secretary
to  &UR; Warren Harding &LR; , convicted in the Teapot Dome scandal;  &UR; Andrew
Mellon &LR; , Treasury secretary in the  &UR; Calvin &LR; 
 &UR; Coolidge  &LR; and Harding administrations, blind to the coming crash of
1929;  &UR; Earl Butz &LR; , Nixon's Agriculture secretary, a joker and
``national embarrassment'';  &UR; James Watt &LR; ,  &UR; Ronald Reagan &LR; 's
Interior secretary, who insulted blacks, Jews and ``cripples'' and
is said to have mishandled public lands.
</P>
<P>
   P.S. Washington Monthly says that the following job titles have
been added during the Clinton administration's ``Reinventing
Government'' initiative: deputy associate deputy secretary;
associate deputy assistant secretary; assistant deputy assistant
secretary.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; RELIEF ON THE WAY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Collection boxes for Kosovo relief placed in the offices of
Conde Nast magazines caused some confusion, says the New York
Observer.
</P>
<P>
   Two Allure staffers were said to have had ``a bit of a tiff over
whether or not it was appropriate or not to donate makeup.'' At
Vogue, editor  &UR; Anna Wintour &LR;  is said to have caught a staff member
going through the box. ``She thought the box was full of free
stuff,'' says the Observer. At Vanity Fair, the collections
included ``a slightly torn and slightly pilled pashmina shawl,
Stila lip gloss and an outdated movie studio release guide.''
</P>
<P>
   At Glamour, the box served a dual purpose. An office memo
advised staff members that unless they cleaned their winter
sweaters out of the closets, they would be donated to the Kosovars.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SIGNING UP GOD &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The Daily Telegraph of London reports that Church of England
officials were outraged to have been solicited to make a major
donation to become the ``preferred religious partner'' of the
official souvenir brochure of the Millennium Dome.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper reported that the church was told if it didn't
agree, other groups, including Scientologists, would be asked to
participate. The company hired to line up sponsors for the brochure
has since had its contract terminated, said the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; David Faber &LR; , a member of Parliament's committee on the dome,
has accused the New Millennium Experience Company, which is
responsible for the dome, of ``constantly seeking to downgrade
Christianity.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Paul McCartney &LR;  banned members of the Tour de France team
he's sponsoring from eating meat, says the Times of London.
</P>
<P>
   - A staffer from the home office of a major San Francisco bank
called San Francisco recently to suggest that the company print its
literature in ``American, Mexican and Asian.'' And
 &UR; David Kelso &LR;  of Oakland, a man who cares about the environment, is
unhappy that the same bank has started using envelopes with plastic
rather than recyclable glassine windows.
</P>
<P>
   - Vacation postcards:  &UR; Carole Terwilliger Meyers &LR; , returning
from England, saw &UR; Sean Connery &LR;  collecting his own bags at JFK.
 &UR; Maria Manetti Farrow &LR; 's pals are proud that she attended  &UR; Puff &LR; 
 &UR; Daddy &LR; 's exclusive party in the Hamptons last week. And  &UR; Denny &LR; 
 &UR; Kavanagh &LR;  of Mill Valley was most amused to note that speed bumps
in England are marked ``Humps for 50 Yards.''
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Maren Baturin &LR; , a staff member in the Chancellor's Office at
UC Berkeley, wonders if there's blatant sex discrimination in a
university job listing for a computer resource specialist at the
Haas School of Business. The qualifications include ``menstruated
experience in relational database management systems.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``The ability of one human being to make quick, personal
electronic contact with another human being is inversely
proportional to the quantity and sophistication of electronic
equipment used by the two of them.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  -  &LR; Leonard's Law of Electronic Communications, as submitted by
philosopher/editor  &UR; George Leonard &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-11-99 1829EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
