<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-11 18:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6081 &Cx1f; tta-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-MARTINEZ-PROFILE-     07-11 1130
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-MARTINEZ-PROFILE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL'S PEDRO MARTINEZ HAS OUTSIDE SHOT AT RARE FEAT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Mich., Calif., N.Y., Canada)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pedro Martinez can't lift a Volkswagen. There is nothing
cartoonish about his body, no Popeye forearms, no Superman chest;
Martinez possesses the physical presence of a toll taker. His
favorite dietary supplement could be grapefruit. But even though
Pedro Martinez is slight enough to be a tattoo on the biceps of
Mark McGwire, he is the Mark McGwire of pitchers in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, the star right-hander for the Boston Red Sox, has 15
victories this season and has an outside chance to become the first
pitcher in more than three decades to win 30 games, an
accomplishment that many within baseball believe would be more
incredible than McGwire's feat of 70 home runs last year, because
of the extraordinary efficiency that would be required of Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be something else if that can happen,'' said Roger
Clemens, the New York Yankees' pitcher who has won a record five Cy
Young Awards, given each year to the league's best pitcher, and
never accumulated more than 24 victories in any season. ``Just from
being in a five-man rotation, your margin for error would be so
minimal. It'll be interesting, something fun to watch in the second
half.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, 27, admired for his competitiveness and talent by
those who don't know him and for his humility and graciousness by
those who do, will start for the American League in Tuesday night's
All-Star game in Boston. Then later this week, he will begin the
second half of the season slightly off a 30-victory pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox have played 88 games of their 162-game schedule, and
Martinez could get 16 or 17 more starts in the second half,
depending on how integral his outings will be to the Boston playoff
hopes in the last month of the season and how he is employed by his
manager, Jimy Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Over the entire season, Martinez might get 34 to 36 starts. The
major league leader last year, Baltimore's Scott Erickson, had 36.
Denny McLain, the last pitcher to reach 30 victories _ he went 31-6
for the Detroit Tigers in 1968 _ started 41 games that season.
</P>
<P>
   In this era, when a starting pitcher is thought to have done
well if he pitches six innings and hands a lead to his relievers,
it is rare for a pitcher to be charged with a victory or a loss in
even 90 percent of his starts. Martinez has started 18 games and
had a decision in each, winning 15 and losing 3.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are all the factors Martinez cannot control. His team
must compile enough runs for him to win _ the Arizona Diamondbacks
have gone scoreless in Randy Johnson's last four starts _ and his
defense must support him. So long as opposing pitchers throw
strikes to McGwire, he has a chance to hit home runs; he can
control his own destiny. Martinez must be exceptional, and very,
very lucky, which is why the Yankee pitcher David Cone believes
winning 30 games would be such a significant single-season feat.
</P>
<P>
   ``He may get 35 starts to win 30, and that is the slimmest
margin for error, when you compare it to hitting .400 or 70 home
runs,'' said Cone. ``You have to not only be on top of your game,
but you have to have run support and have things go so well for
you. You have to be nearly perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez doesn't think of himself as a nearly perfect pitcher;
he doesn't even believe he is the best pitcher in his family.
Martinez grew up poor in the Dominican Republic, on a nameless dirt
road in Manoguayabo, and his boyhood hero was his brother Ramon,
who was tall and thin and four years older.
</P>
<P>
   Four Martinez brothers slept in the same room _ Pedro and Jesus
in one bed, Ramon and Nelson in the other _ and they played catch
for hours and for days. Pedro marveled at Ramon, at how hard he
could throw a baseball, and when Ramon signed a contract with the
Dodgers, it only confirmed his stature in the eyes of Pedro.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found him so impressive,'' Pedro Martinez said recently,
sitting in the Red Sox clubhouse in Fenway Park, ``because he was a
regular professional player.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramon broke into the major leagues in 1988, the same year the
Dodgers signed the then-120-pound Pedro. Pedro Martinez threw about
82 to 83 mph _ pedestrian, compared to his brother's fastball of 95
to 96 mph _ and he was convinced he would never throw as hard as
Ramon. But over a span of about seven months, Pedro grew and the
velocity of his fastball increased by about 10 miles an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Ramon already had shown him the value of changing speeds, and
Pedro Martinez had developed a changeup grip, with the baseball
tucked deeply into his hands. But in 1991, a minor league coach
named Guy Conti showed Pedro Martinez another type of changeup grip
_ the circle change, with the thumb and forefinger touching as if
to pull down a window shade and the ball propelled loosely by the
other three fingers _ and this distinguished the right-hander.
Martinez established himself in the majors in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   But Fred Claire, the Dodgers' general manager, needed a second
baseman, and after the '93 season he traded Martinez to the
Montreal Expos for Delino DeShields _ in retrospect, one of the
worst trades in baseball history.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez went 11-5 for the Expos in 1994, and his sometimes
reckless attempts to pitch inside sparked several brawls. Martinez
was still comparatively small, 5 feet 11 inches and 170 pounds, but
he was unintimidated and kept throwing inside. Reggie Sanders of
the Cincinnati Reds was so incensed about being hit that he charged
the mound, despite the fact that Martinez had had a perfect game in
progress and would not deliberately have ruined it by hitting
Sanders and thus giving him first base.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez had succeeded to that point mostly because of his
fastball and changeup. Attempts by the Dodger manager, Tommy
Lasorda, to show him a curveball grip hadn't resulted in the good
breaking ball Martinez wanted. He promised Joe Kerrigan, the Expos'
pitching coach, that when he returned for the 1995 season, he would
have a viable breaking ball. ``Boy, when he came back the next
spring, he did have a good curveball,'' recalled Kerrigan, who has
since moved on to be pitching coach for the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   The curveball grip that Martinez uses today came from Ramon, who
had been shown it by Eliadoro Arias, an instructor at the Dodgers'
baseball academy in the Dominican Republic. Pedro could throw this
breaking ball hard, ``more aggressively,'' he said, ``a lot
quicker. It clicked in right away.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   His repertory now included three well-above-average pitches, or
two more than most major league pitchers', and within three years,
he dominated the National League, going 17-8 with a 1.90 earned run
average and striking out 305 in 241 1/3 innings in 1997. Because of
their payroll constraints, however, the Expos traded him to the Red
Sox after the season.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez is 34-10 in one a half seasons with the Red Sox and he
has assumed Clemens' place of preeminence in Boston, serving as a
maestro of emotion for the Fenway Park fans, who stand and roar
with each inning-ending strikeout.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can feel the energy he brings on each pitch,'' said
Kerrigan. ``Somebody could walk in off the street and not know
anything about baseball, and they would know this guy is good at
what he does, just because of the passion he shows for each pitch,
the intensity.''
</P>
<P>
   He pitched against the Yankees in Boston on May 18, and measured
against his norm, he was vulnerable that night, allowing 10 hits
and four walks; at least one Yankee reached scoring position in six
of his seven innings. But whenever disaster seemed imminent,
Martinez seemed to ascend to a higher level of determination and
concentration, his fastball gaining 2 or 3 mph. Of his 11
strikeouts that night, nine came with runners in scoring position.
Five of the seven innings he pitched ended with strikeouts.
Martinez has faced 47 batters with runners in scoring position and
two out this year, and struck out 23, allowing just six hits
(.128).
</P>
<P>
   Scott Brosius, the Yankees' third baseman, struck out to end the
second inning. ``He fired something like six pitches to me, all
fastballs and changeups, got the count to 3 balls and 2 strikes _
and then he drops a curveball over for a strike,'' Brosius said.
``You're just not looking for that.''
</P>
<P>
   When a pitcher throws as hard as Martinez, Brosius said, the
hitter must respect the fastball first and foremost. To hit a
fastball of 95 to 96 mph, you must prepare to swing quickly,
cocking your hands for the explosive movement of the bat; there is
only an instant to discern whether Martinez has thrown a fastball,
curveball or changeup. The hitter's weight begins to shift from
back to front, his bat is moving forward, the swing reaching the
point of no return _ and all too often, that is when they realize
that Martinez has thrown a changeup low and out of the strike zone,
or that he has spun a curveball.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the most part, he keeps the hitters guessing,'' said
Bernie Williams, the Yankee center fielder. ``You can't really sit
on any of his pitches, because he has such great control of them
that he can throw any of them at any point in the count.''
</P>
<P>
   And if the hitter correctly guesses fastball, he still has the
challenge of making solid contact. Martinez's fastball moves in,
away, sinks, darts, and his physical size and seemingly effortless
delivery add to the deception. ``He just sort of slings the ball,
like a rubber band,'' said Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``His arm and motion is just so free and easy,'' said Brosius.
``He has that real easy cheese, that easy fastball. He's not an
intimidating guy as far as size. He's not like Randy Johnson, or
like Kerry Wood, who's got all those body parts coming at you.
Pedro is nice and loose and _ wap! _ he's on you. You know he
throws hard, but he's sneaky.''
</P>
<P>
   Brosius batted in the seventh inning of the May 18 game against
Martinez, two out and two runners on base. The count reached two
strikes, and fresh in Brosius' mind was that curveball Martinez had
thrown, but he anticipated a fastball; that's what a batter must
do.
</P>
<P>
   With his 136th pitch, Martinez threw a fastball, 96 mph, belt
high. Brosius swung and missed, and as Martinez walked off the
mound, the Fenway fans exploded in cheers, Brosius staring at him
incredulously.
</P>
<P>
   In street clothes _ he prefers jeans _ Martinez has no
distinguishing characteristics. Thin torso and moustache, long and
unassuming face. The game's best pitcher is not loud, does not come
off as brash. He is polite. Watching him greet fans reaching to him
from the stands, you get the sense he treats everybody as he would
a grandparent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best thing about him is his humility,'' said Kerrigan.
``He never pounds his chest about what he's done, what he's
accomplished. You walk in this clubhouse, and you wouldn't know
from the interaction that he's done what he's done in the game. He
never brags, never boasts, never talks about himself, never talks
about goals, never talks about strikeouts. This guy doesn't have
one ounce of braggadocio in his body.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramon won 123 games in 11 seasons for the Dodgers before his
shoulder gave out and required surgery. He hasn't pitched in about
a year now, and since signing as a free agent with the Red Sox, he
is rehabilitating his arm. The Red Sox believe he will pitch again
this year, but there is no certainty of that.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Ramon is the best pitcher in the Martinez family, Pedro
said; he says he never has believed he is better than Ramon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never did, and never will,'' said Pedro. ``Everything I know,
I learned from him, and to me, Ramon will always be some kind of an
older teacher, someone I really respect and admire.''
</P>
<P>
   Their lockers are adjacent in the Boston clubhouse. When Pedro
pitches, he will return to the bench and sit next to Ramon, and
Ramon will counsel his little brother, telling him what he thinks
he did wrong, reviewing his mechanics, suggesting adjustments.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is Pedro's sounding board,'' said Kerrigan. ``He is his
pitching coach. They're best friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramon had a throwing session on the Fenway Park mound a couple
of weeks ago, and as the older brother tossed fastballs and
changeups to Kerrigan, Pedro crouched on the back of the mound,
watching his big brother, as he did when he was a teen-ager. If
Pedro Martinez somehow finds a way to win 30 games, he will be the
first pitcher to do so in more than 30 years, but still, he
maintains, the second-best pitcher in his family. That will never
change. Never.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
