<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-lopez </SLUG>
 column-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Editors note: Some might find language objectionable 
 
Grivich diaries speak to young athletes, parents
<TEXT>
<P>
   By JOHN P. LOPEZ
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   The diaries _ dozens of them _ were spread across Helen
Grivich's bed like a quilt, covering every inch of it with a
tapestry of colors.
</P>
<P>
   The books were piled high. It was as if the skies opened and
down came the letters from heaven that over the past two years have
drenched Grivich with an all-too-late understanding.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the diaries were bound with images of daisies, some with
roses, others with flowers of every sort. There were purples and
pinks and yellows. Many of the books were covered with images and
pictures of kittens.
</P>
<P>
   The bindings on some were tattered. Others looked as if they
were kept together only with string and cardboard.
</P>
<P>
   But these were the letters from heaven Grivich wishes every
parent of every young aspiring athlete could read.
</P>
<P>
   These were the letters from heaven that were penned during
Hilary Grivich's all-too-short life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I knew then what I know now,'' Helen Grivich said.
</P>
<P>
   More, she wishes every parent can learn from them.
</P>
<P>
   Two years have passed since Hilary Grivich, a one-time
Olympic-level gymnast and aspiring Olympic diver, died just days
before her 20th birthday.
</P>
<P>
   A horrifying automobile accident on Houston's north side took
Grivich when everything in her often-troubled, often-confused life
finally seemed on course. Two years have passed since the promise
died, leaving so many friends and fans heartbroken.
</P>
<P>
   After her daughter's death, Helen Grivich went through her
daughter's room and began thumbing through the pages of the
numerous diaries Hilary kept for nearly 12 years.
</P>
<P>
   The heartfelt words, revealing emotions and biting commentary
expressed by Hilary continue to ring through Helen Grivich's mind.
There were literally thousands of entries Hilary wrote from roughly
her eighth birthday until just two days before her death in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   She intimately discussed everything. From the excitement of
joining Bela Karolyi's gym to the rigorous demands placed on her by
coaches. From the highs of winning a gymnastics World Championship
medal to the lows of being scored unfairly in the 1992 Olympic
Trials. From the heartbreak of losing her grandparents to the torn
emotions of being caught in her parents' divorce and the many ups
and downs of being a teen-age girl in a grown-up world.
</P>
<P>
   And as painful as some of those passages are for Helen Grivich
to make public, she has done it because she can't help but think:
Maybe some other parents can learn from it all.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe some other teen-age athlete feels those same emotions, and
their parents simply do not know. Or care. Maybe some other parents
can learn from the passion with which Hilary wrote and the mistakes
Helen and Peter Grivich made.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so revealing about teen-agers and how their feelings get
hurt and how we speak to them as parents,'' Helen Grivich said.
``It hurts me to know what she was feeling when we thought
everything was great. It's revealing to know how we treat them and
what they feel. It's important for parents to know.''
</P>
<P>
   Hilary began writing the diaries at her mother's urging, because
as a rising young gymnast at age 8, Hilary often would be away from
home. Helen Grivich wanted her daughter to have something in which
she could confide when her parents were not around.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though she spoke to us a lot, the diary was her safe
place,'' Helen Grivich said. ``She took it everywhere. You learn
awful things about yourself when you read them. You learn all these
little things about how she hurt inside, about what you did without
even realizing it. I want (the public) to have them, because it's
like, do other parents know this?''
</P>
<P>
   Early in her gymnastics career, most of the passages in Hilary's
diaries were filled with typical hopes and dreams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got to work out with the elites today!'' she wrote as an
8-year-old in 1986. ``I'm so excited. Someday, I'm going to the
Olympics. I just know it.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet even then, Grivich at times revealed the pressures she was
feeling from her parents and coaches and the pain under which she
had to perform.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, I don't know what to think anymore,'' she wrote in
1986. ``Everyone seems to take things out on me. One minute they're
really nice and the next they're as nasty as can be and I hate,
hate, hate them. I never know what's coming next. Don't they know
that sometimes I just hurt a lot?''
</P>
<P>
   The diaries cover every part of Grivich's life, but perhaps most
revealing are the teen-age years when Grivich joined Karolyi's
elite team and worked toward the 1991 World Championships and the
1992 Olympic Games with the likes of Kim Zmeskal, Betty Okino and
Kerri Strug.
</P>
<P>
   In early 1991, as injuries mounted and the pressure to make the
1991 World Championship team mounted, Hilary wrote: ``I'm hurting
all over and no one seems to care. My back is killing me. I have
diarrhea all the time and I don't know why. Sometimes, I get sick
to my stomach and I feel like I puke up everything I've had in my
stomach since 1978. I don't know why I put up with all of this.
Bela is treating me like crap.. Am I that bad? I missed a landing
today and my back really hurt. Bela got (mad) and kicked me out of
practice and told me to come back with a better attitude. My life
would be a hell of a lot better if I'd never met the son of a
bitch. But I'll show him who the real idiot is. I'm going to be the
best no matter what it takes. I'll show him just how stupid he is
for ever calling me a failure.''
</P>
<P>
   Grivich, of course, made the 1991 team and was the leadoff
athlete in what proved to be an unprecedented silver-medal
performance by the Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hilary Grivich NEVER gives up,'' she wrote in 1991. ``We did
it! What an awesome feeling to have that medal around your neck.
Next stop, Barcelona!''
</P>
<P>
   On the inside cover of a 1992 diary, Grivich wrote: ``This is my
Barcelona diary!''
</P>
<P>
   But later, she scratched through those words and wrote, ``Due to
rather unfair and unfortunate circumstances at (Olympic) Trials,
this Barcelona Diary is being written from my bed in Huntsville.''
</P>
<P>
   At those 1992 trials, Grivich fell victim to a horrible
political battle by USA Gymnastics. Most observers considered
Grivich among the best gymnasts at the trials, but she consistently
was scored low _ in part, many said, because of resentment many
judges and coaches had against Karolyi's heavy hand in the sport.
</P>
<P>
   Grivich watched the 1992 Olympics from home; Zmeskal, Okino and
Strug made it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried,'' Grivich wrote the day after the 1992 trials. ``I
did everything good, but the judges chewed me up and spit me out.
Why? Obviously, somebody didn't want me on the team. Jesus, why do
I fit into this mess? After they announced the team, I was sitting
on a mat and I hadn't cried yet. But when I heard the announcer and
saw the team march out, I put my head in my hands and sobbed. I've
never hurt so bad. I have to start a new life.''
</P>
<P>
   She was 14 years old. Still, after the controversial trials,
Grivich's parents continued to urge her to train and work toward an
outside chance at making the team as an alternate, or perhaps
continue with hopes of 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want out,'' Grivich wrote. ``I'm so sick of all of it. I
don't want it anymore, but everyone is telling me that I really do.
No, I don't! They can all go to hell. Why should I continue to kill
myself, with a broken shoulder and my back hurting so much? I'm
tired of the whole stupid thing. Of all people, Bela has been the
best. I've never felt so close to him. He said I will always be
Pluto _ the ultimate competitor, the strongest and most aggressive
person. He told me that without me, they'll be lucky to get a
bronze medal. I've made my decision. I'm retiring. Screw it.''
</P>
<P>
   Without Grivich, the USA team won the bronze medal; Zmeskal fell
short of individual all-around expectations after falling off the
balance beam during the compulsory competition. Through it all,
Hilary wrote about how her mother continued to pressure her to
compete.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother is being a real bitch,'' Grivich wrote. ``I weigh 90
pounds, that's five pounds more than my competition weight. She's
freaking out. She's bitching at me to run and exercise all day and
she's watching everything I eat. I truly cannot handle her like
this. This entire thing is giving me a complex. Every time
something like this happens, I drag up all those unpleasant
memories and re-piece together my shattered dream, all of which I'm
trying to safely tuck away in a padded cell in my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, while on an exhibition tour with the 1992 Olympic team,
Grivich continued to fight the tough feelings. This time, she often
shared her frustrations with Zmeskal, who also considered retiring
and felt the emotional pain of falling in Barcelona.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kim wants so much to prove to people that the Kim in Spain was
not the real her,'' Grivich wrote. ``She's afraid of failing, but
she's more afraid of having to live with these bad feelings for the
rest of her life. We talked until 4:30 in the morning yesterday.
She cried and I cried and I've never felt closer to anyone in my
life. Not even my family. If anyone understands what she's feeling,
it's me. I will never know what could have been. The only
difference for me was that I did my utmost, but was cruelly cheated
out of my lifelong dream.''
</P>
<P>
   A year later, Grivich decided to become a competitive diver. She
quickly rose through the ranks and earned a scholarship to the
University of Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The competitive fires raged. She confided to her diary that
after competing for the Cougars and graduating in 1999, she would
spend this year training for the 2000 Sydney Games.
</P>
<P>
   But as much as time passed and the sport changed, there still
were pressures that only Grivich's diary knew. Grivich's parents
divorced, complicating things even more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love you, diary,'' she wrote in 1995. ``In times of need, I
will always have you to turn to. At least I know that you will
listen without judging me. Somehow, you seem sympathetic.''
</P>
<P>
   In another passage, she wrote only: ``I want my daddy back.''
</P>
<P>
   Days later, she added: ``My mom is on me all the time and my dad
can't or won't deal with me. I'm ready to drop my scholarship and
start a new life. Again! Looking back on my life thus far, well,
it's sucked. Few and far between have been my fleeting moments of
joy and true happiness _ the 1991 worlds, the summer after I quit
gymnastics and the time I spent with my Nana and Gramps. I vaguely
remember a childhood. My life has fallen to pieces, as has my
family.''
</P>
<P>
   The passages in Grivich's diaries indicate that by 1996 she had
regained her composure, found numerous friends in diving and
established relationships with young men. Her performances in
diving reflected her confidence, as she placed in various meets
across the country.
</P>
<P>
   But then in the early summer of 1997, after spending the night
at a friend's house, Grivich got in her car and drove into town,
where she was supposed to meet her mother for breakfast. Somehow,
her car apparently swerved into a concrete barrier and flipped
several times. She was dead at the scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``She always handled things well outside,'' Helen Grivich said.
``She always was laughing or acted like it was no big deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Hilary's death, Helen Grivich often has reflected on the
words her daughter wrote. It has been sweet and yet painful for her
to watch her daughter's good friend, diver Laura Wilkinson, climb
the competitive ladder and become a favorite to make the 2000
Olympic team.
</P>
<P>
   Wilkinson still regularly writes Helen Grivich, often sending
postcards from diving meets. Zmeskal sent Grivich flowers on
Mother's Day this year. Others often correspond.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those diaries are my most cherished possession,'' Grivich
said. ``I wish every parent could understand what I understand
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Helen Grivich bought a new diary for Hilary's birthday in 1997,
but she never had a chance to give it to her. On the cover is a
colorful drawing of a kitten with its forelegs spread wide-open as
if it is about to give its owner a hug. The kitten is wearing a
Hawaiian shirt
</P>
<P>
   After Hilary's death, Helen Grivich wrote this passage in the
diary she planned to give to her daughter. It was a response to all
those letters from heaven:
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope Hilary had a wonderful time on her last night alive.
The doorbell rang at 8 a.m. There were six policemen there. I knew
it was bad, bad, bad. (One officer) told me Hilary was killed
instantly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, how I love you and I miss you, Hilary. At night, I close
my eyes and I see your car flip, flip, flip. I see you inside,
upside down, crying, and I can't comfort you. I wish I could put my
head on your chest and feel your breath. Oh, Hilary, I worry about
you, but it's going to be all right. It's going to be all right.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
