</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DWI-STUDY-370&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOWER BLOOD-ALCOHOL LIMIT DOES NOT REDUCE ACCIDENTS, STUDY FINDS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., N.Y., N.J., Conn., Mass.)  (js) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The federal highway safety agency has overstated
the effectiveness of state laws that lower the percentage of
alcohol in the bloodstream needed to classify an individual as
legally drunk, a government review has found. The review concluded
that lowering the blood alcohol limit alone did not demonstrably
reduce the number or severity of alcohol-related car crashes.
</P>
<P>
   The review, by the General Accounting Office, challenged the
findings of the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration in
several published studies commissioned by the safety agency, which
supports tighter restrictions on drinking and driving.
</P>
<P>
   In its analysis of the data from the studies, the accounting
office found little statistical evidence to confirm that lowering
the permissible blood alcohol concentration to 0.08 percent, from
0.10 percent, significantly reduces the number of automobile
crashes. Rather, the accounting office concluded that the best
countermeasure against drunken driving was a combination of
vigorous enforcement of blood alcohol-level laws, strong laws
requiring that the licenses of violators be revoked and sustained
public education.
</P>
<P>
   The accounting office's finding undermines efforts by the
Clinton administration to establish a national standard of 0.08
percent. While 16 states and the District of Columbia have adopted
the 0.08 standard, most states, including New York, Connecticut and
New Jersey, have a limit of 0.10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, President Clinton endorsed a bill that would have
required the 35 states with a threshold of 0.10 percent to adopt a
standard of 0.08 percent within three years or lose 5 percent of
federal highway money the first year and 10 percent each succeeding
year. The Senate approved the proposal, but it was rejected by the
House.
</P>
<P>
   The accounting office, the congressional investigative agency,
concluded that the highway safety agency's position that the
evidence supported the stricter standard was ``overstated.'' The
accounting office report, released last month, criticized the
methodology of seven published studies on how motor vehicle crashes
and deaths had been affected by laws requiring the threshold of
0.08 percent.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   One group of studies conducted by the highway safety agency from
1991 to 1995 cited California's law, which sets a limit of 0.08
percent, as evidence of the effectiveness of such limits in
general. But after reviewing the studies, the accounting office
report concluded that while a 1991 study by the safety agency did
find a 12 percent decline in alcohol-related deaths after the 0.08
percent law took effect in 1990, the study used only one year's
worth of data.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, six months after the 0.08 percent limit took effect,
California also subjected violators to the possible suspension or
revocation of their driver's licenses, a provision that could have
skewed the results, the accounting office said.
</P>
<P>
   The accounting office also faulted the methodology in a 1996
Boston University School of Public Health study published in the
American Journal of Public Health. This study sought to compare
drunken-driving deaths in the first five states to adopt the 0.08
percent standard with five nearby states that retained laws with
the 0.10 percent standard. According to the accounting office, the
Boston University study used one state as a yardstick to assess the
effectiveness of a new law in another state, incorrectly assuming
that all other conditions were equal. Three of the five states also
enacted laws to revoke driver's licenses within 10 months of
enacting laws for the lower limit.
</P>
<P>
   Mothers Against Drunk Driving favors a national 0.08 percent
standard but supports the accounting office's conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Research shows that virtually all drivers are substantially
impaired at 0.08 BAC and that 0.08 is a reasonable limit to set,''
said Karolyn Nunnallee, the organization's national president.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to the review, the Department of Transportation said
there was ``consistent evidence supporting the effectiveness of
0.08 BAC laws in reducing alcohol-related fatalities.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
