<SLUG> BC-FOOD-OWEN-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DON'T WORRY THAT THERE ARE TOO MANY COOKBOOKS IN THE KITCHEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN OWEN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``John, we have too many cookbooks.''
</P>
<P>
   The first time my wife uttered that complaint, she was gazing at
5,000 copies of the first ``Intermediate Eater Cookbook,''
delivered to our basement.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Intermediate Eater cookbooks are distributed by this
newspaper. So when Alice complains that we have too many cookbooks,
she means the collection of other people's books lining two walls
of a study.
</P>
<P>
   OK, maybe we do have an excess. But what am I going to throw
away?
</P>
<P>
   Certainly not the ``Eskimo Cookbook'' prepared by students of
Shishmaref Day School in Alaska. Where else am I going to find
recipes for soured seal liver or oogruk flippers?
</P>
<P>
   And no, no, don't touch that 1943 copy of the ``Russian War
Relief Cookbook'' or the publication ``What's Cookin' With the
(Green Bay) Packer Wives?''
</P>
<P>
   Some pages are missing from a cookbook published in 1916 in
Montana's Judith Basin, but where today are you going to find a
recipe advising you to ``place small chicken in drip pan and cover
with sweet cream and butter. By the time cream has cooked away,
chicken will be done.''?
</P>
<P>
   My copy of ``Sudeley Castle Recipe Book'' tells me how to make
cowslip wine, pig's liver pudding and ``a medicine for the piles.''
A publication from Vinton, Iowa, contains Inge Schminke's recipe
for Napfkuchen and the authentic formula for the famous chicken
salad puffs served at Dubuque's Ham House Museum.
</P>
<P>
   I've got Shirley Fong-Torres' ``San Francisco Chinatown
Cookbook,'' Gordon Nelson's ``Lowbush Moose Cookbook'' from Alaska,
``Mama Leah's Jewish Kitchen'' from New York City and Buck
Peterson's ``International Road Kill Cookbook'' from Highway 99.
</P>
<P>
   I've got community cookbooks from Natchitoches, La., from the
Madison County Farm Bureau Women's Committee in Illinois, and from
Nancy Axell's 1980 kindergarten class on Mercer Island.
</P>
<P>
   I've got the ``Hotter Than Hell Cookbook,'' the ``Chili Lovers
Cookbook,''``Cow Country Cookbook'' and ``Dining with Charles
Dickens.''
</P>
<P>
   They are all absolutely indispensable. Somewhere in this
collection I found the inspiration or instructions for recipes like
these.
</P>
<P>
   Pot Lucky
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds lean ground beef or ground turkey
</P>
<P>
   2 medium onions, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 pound fresh mushrooms, sliced
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons oregano
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter teaspoon garlic powder
</P>
<P>
   Salt
</P>
<P>
   4 packages (10 ounces each) frozen spinach, thawed
</P>
<P>
   2 cans cream of celery soup
</P>
<P>
   1 carton (1 pound) sour cream
</P>
<P>
   1 cup uncooked Minute Rice
</P>
<P>
   12 slices Monterey Jack cheese
</P>
<P>
   Saute the first three ingredients until the meat is brown and
the onions have softened. Stir in the oregano and garlic powder.
Add salt to taste. Dump this mess into a 11-by-16-inch oven dish.
</P>
<P>
   Drain the thawed spinach by squeezing it in your fist, then
distribute it over the meat mixture. Moosh everything around with a
wooden spoon.
</P>
<P>
   Mix the undiluted soup with the sour cream and stir into the
casserole. Add the rice, then moosh again.
</P>
<P>
   Add a top layer of cheese slices then shove the dish into a
350-degree oven and bake until bubbling, 20 to 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 10 to 12 residents of Judith Basin, Mont. or
Natchitoches, La., with salad and hot French bread.
</P>
<P>
   Pasta Tuna Salad
</P>
<P>
   One-haf pound small penne pasta
</P>
<P>
   3 red peppers, seeded and cubed
</P>
<P>
   1 bunch broccoli
</P>
<P>
   12 black olives, halved
</P>
<P>
   27-ounce cans solid white tuna
</P>
<P>
   One-half cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons red wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons drained capers
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon crumbled oregano leaves
</P>
<P>
   Three-quarters teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 small clove garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter teaspoon black pepper
</P>
<P>
   Peel broccoli stems and cut diagonally one-half inch thick.
Divide florets into 1-inch pieces. Steam the broccoli until crisp
but tender and cool under running water. (If you can't stand
broccoli, substitute an equal amount of Chinese pea pods, which you
have blanched for one minute.)
</P>
<P>
   Cook the pasta according to package instructions or until it is
tender to the bite. Drain and dump into a tub of cold water.
</P>
<P>
   In a jar combine the olive oil, vinegar, capers, oregano, salt,
garlic and pepper. Shake to combine.
</P>
<P>
   Use paper towels to pat dry the pasta and broccoli. Lay out in a
bowl with the red pepper hunks and olives. Toss with some dressing.
Add the tuna. Add more dressing if needed and toss again, lightly.
</P>
<P>
   Chill until ready to serve and with French bread on the side
this should suffice as the main dish for four farm wives or one
Green Bay Packer nose tackle.
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend Alice and I checked out the tent sale at Third
Place Books in Seattle's Lake Forest Park neighborhood. We found
some bargains we absolutely could not pass up.
</P>
<P>
   We now have too many cookbooks _ plus eight.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
