A6094 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-WCUP-CHINA-NYT &LR;      07-11 0917
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WCUP-CHINA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA FEELS PAIN OF SOCCER LOSS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: See also SOC-WCUP, SOC-VECSEY-COLUMN) 
(mk) 
 By SETH FAISON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Those fateful penalty kicks.
</P>
<P>
   They were played and replayed over and over on television all
over China Sunday, stinging each time like pinpricks in the
consciousness of a nation whose hopes were deflated when Brandi
Chastain made the last of the penalty kicks to give the United
States a victory over China in the Women's World Cup final.
</P>
<P>
   ``So close, so close,'' said Ren Yihong, a 27-year-old computer
engineer, as he watched the replay as it was magnified by a row of
display television sets tuned to the same channel in a store on
Dongdan Street in central Beijing. ``It was a very close game. I
really thought we would win, but we were unlucky in the end.''
</P>
<P>
   Chinese soccer fans, as well as untold millions of other people
who were drawn in by contagious excitement and swelling national
pride at the Chinese team's success in getting to the tournament
final, were understandably crushed by the game's outcome.
</P>
<P>
   In Beijing, it was a drizzly and quiet day of mourning. Many
people on the street expressed disappointment, and the mood on
normally busy shopping streets was quiet, maybe because so many
viewers stayed up all night to watch the game, whose broadcast
began here at 4 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   The Beijing Youth Daily reported before the game on Saturday
that 91.4 percent of those polled said they planned to watch the
game, though how many actually did was anyone's guess.
</P>
<P>
   A Chinese victory, had those penalty kicks gone the other way,
would doubtless have provoked a spirited response. In fact, the
authorities here were apparently concerned at the possibility that
spontaneous demonstrations might break out, and they posted a
busload of armed police near the U.S. Embassy, just in case.
</P>
<P>
   Only two months ago, when NATO bombed the Chinese Embassy in
Belgrade, Yugoslavia, Chinese students paraded through the streets
for several days, throwing rocks at the U.S. Embassy as a wave of
virulent anti-Americanism swept through the nation's capital.
</P>
<P>
   A high-pitched World Cup final between teams from these two
nations might have been expected to reignite some of those
passions, since the issue is not officially over, with the Chinese
government still saying it does not accept Washington's explanation
that the bombing was accidental.
</P>
<P>
   Yet relatively little of that anti-Americanism seemed to be
fueling the enthusiasm of the fans, who appeared to cheer their
national team the same way they would have had the opponent been
Brazil, a semifinalist in the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Chinese team has played so well, I felt sure they would
win no matter who they played against,'' said Lang Min, a
24-year-old store attendant. ``I think it was American food. If
they had been eating Chinese food, they might have played better.''
</P>
<P>
   Tellingly, Lang said she was the lone soccer fan among her
friends who are women, who are not nearly as interested in soccer
as Chinese men are, though many decided to tune in for the final.
</P>
<P>
   ``Normally, if I want to talk about a game, I have to talk to my
brother,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Women's soccer has not yet captured the attention of Chinese
fans quite the way it has in the United States. That may seem odd,
since China is indeed a soccer-crazy nation, where domestic games
draw enormous attention and the men's World Cup is widely
considered the most important sports event in the world, even
though China has never qualified.
</P>
<P>
   Like many countries in Europe and in South America, China has a
madness for soccer that sometimes seems the rough equivalent of the
American passion for baseball, football, basketball and hockey
combined. Yet that enthusiasm did not cross over to this year's
appearance in the final by the women, since soccer is still seen by
many fans as more suitable for male athletes than female.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, women's volleyball, Ping-Pong and even weight
lifting are widely popular spectator sports.
</P>
<P>
   At the few sports bars sprinkled around Beijing, and at many of
the universities and schools where soccer fans gathered in large
groups to watch the game together, men appeared to outnumber women.
</P>
<P>
   Experienced soccer fans had various theories about why China
lost, close as the match was. Some fans were miffed that a header
by Fan Yunjie, blocked by Kristine Lilly close to the goal line,
was not actually called a goal. Others complained that the Chinese
team was tired from flying all over the United States for matches
on both coasts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Home advantage, the Americans had that all through the
tournament,'' said Wang Longhai, 39. ``That's a big help.''
</P>
<P>
   His friend Shan Lihong had a different view on what the critical
element of the game was.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Americans were stronger midfield,'' Shan said. ``Both
sides have talent, both sides played well, both have good goalies.
Midfield was the American advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   China's media, often seeming eager to stir nationalist sentiment
in their coverage of the Women's World Cup, reported that President
Jiang Zemin was closely watching the team's progress and had
telephoned with encouragement before the game on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have demonstrated fully the aspiration to win honors for
the motherland,'' Jiang said, according to the New China News
Agency. ``Whether you win or lose, the whole nation and the people
will extend their warmest greetings to you.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
