<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-11 19:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6098 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-HITECH-HNS &LR;      07-11 1371
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-HITECH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH SEEKS SUPPORT AND MONEY FROM SILICON VALLEY
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)
<TEXT>
<P>
   By ALAN BERNSTEIN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   c. 1999
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
HOUSTON _ As fast as you can send e-mail, the computer industry and
its enterprising moguls are getting special attention from the
presidential campaigns of Gov. George W. Bush, Vice President Al
Gore and other leading contenders.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, the early Republican front-runner, delivered his most
specific policy proposals so far to an audience of high-tech
honchos in California's Silicon Valley this month. Several of the
executives have signed onto his campaign, and last week he
appointed a ``technology advisory council'' headed by Texas
computer tycoon Michael Dell.
</P>
<P>
   Democrat Gore, a cyber-technology expert since his days in
Congress, has unveiled his own proposals aimed at helping the
computer sector, and he is backed by several industry leaders. His
circle of high-tech advisers includes a co-founder of Yahoo! Inc.,
Jerry Yang.
</P>
<P>
   Not to be outdone, Republican candidate John McCain and
Democratic hopeful Bill Bradley, among others, have secured
political alliances with some Silicon Valley leaders.
</P>
<P>
   After moving to the cutting edge of the U.S. economy, the
captains of computing now find themselves on the cutting edge of
national politics.
</P>
<P>
   Holly Bailey, who tracks campaign contributions for the
nonpartisan Center for Responsive Politics in Washington, said the
industry's ``new rich'' provide only about 1 percent of the
campaign contributions raked in by Bush, Gore and others.
</P>
<P>
   Candidates make their Silicon Valley pilgrimages not just for
campaign money, but to show the nation that they are in tune with
one of the engines driving the national economy, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is some sort of status symbol whenever you align
yourself with the economy of the future,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, an approving nod from a Bill Gates type might be
worth a few million dollars worth of campaign advertising. Bush
held private discussions last week with executives at the
Seattle-area offices of Gates' company, Microsoft. This week he
attends a fund-raiser with a ``high-tech focus'' in McLean, Va.,
just outside Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the engine driving our economy,'' Bush spokesman David
Beckwith said about the computer industry. ``It is important that
government and politicians get high-tech right.''
</P>
<P>
   The economy grew during the Clinton administration, and Gore
advertises himself as the best choice to continue the federal
policies that seeded some of that growth. Having made technology
one of his pet issues as vice president, Gore also wants to be seen
as the one contender who aligned himself with the computer industry
before the Internet and e-mail came into popular public use.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vice president has always been there for the high-tech
community ... before the industry even displayed the tremendous
impact that it currently holds,'' campaign spokesman Roger Salazar
said.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Bush's campaign operatives confide that they
are trying to position him as the best choice to lead ``the new
economy'' _ a phrase that pops often in Silicon Valley, the area of
California from the southern border of San Francisco to San Jose,
where dozens of computer companies are headquartered.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's emphasis on education and limited government, plus his
ties to high-tech firms that have created more jobs in Texas than
the oil industry in recent years, make him attractive to the
computer industry, his aides say.
</P>
<P>
   Added to the mix is the fact that computer industry has been
identified as Democrat-leaning because of the liberal atmosphere of
California, Republican-leaning because of interests in low taxes
and Libertarian-leaning because of its aversion to government
regulation.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are all of those things,'' said Richard Brody, a
political science professor at Stanford University in Palo Alto,
Calif., the heart of Silicon Valley. ``What unites them, if
anything, is a belief in technology and a desire to kind of be left
alone to do the job.''
</P>
<P>
   As the economy rebounded during the Clinton administration, the
computer industry generally supported the Democrats, Brody said.
Now Bush is raising eyebrows by raising campaign money from some of
the executives, he explained.
</P>
<P>
   One of the reasons for the shift, Brody said, is ``a natural
return to Republicanism'' by business leaders who are concerned
about their stock portfolios and tax liabilities. Another reason,
he continued, is that Bush is leading the early voter polls and is
telling the computer industry what it wants to hear.
</P>
<P>
   Bush pointed out to industry leaders this month that Texas
became one of the first states to enact a law restricting lawsuits
based on the so-called Y2K computer problem, which he described as
``the biggest potential ambulance chase in a millennium.''
</P>
<P>
   His policy proposals included making the Internet duty and
tariff-free worldwide, stepping up government efforts against the
piracy of American-made computer software, increasing the
immigration of high-skilled foreign workers and making permanent
the federal tax credits for industrial research and development.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's speech came a few weeks after Gore laid out some of the
same high-tech proposals in New Hampshire, which has enjoyed an
economic resurgence thanks to the computer industry.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, too, wants to make the tax break on research and
development permanent, and more accessible to smaller businesses.
He pledged to press for international agreement making the Internet
free of duties and tariffs. He wants to double the government's
investment in high-tech research.
</P>
<P>
   And his boss, Clinton, sided with the Republican-controlled
Congress on a bill shielding businesses from Y2K lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   So from the leading Republican and Democratic candidates, this
is stereo music to the ears of Technet, a computer industry
lobbying group that is stepping up Silicon Valley's relationship
with federal lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   Computer industry executives gave a total of only $200,000 to
the presidential candidates in 1996, according to the Center for
Responsive Politics. For the 2000 election, such contributions have
already exceeded that amount. Many observers say the government's
antitrust case against Microsoft was a wake-up call for computer
executives to become more conscious of government policies and
campaign politics.
</P>
<P>
   The bulk of this year's contributions in the first three months
of 1996 went to Bush and Gore. Industry wizard Steven Jobs from
Apple Computer gave money to Bradley's campaign, symbolizing that
Bush and Gore do not have a lock on the support.
</P>
<P>
   The computer industry contributed $8.8 million to 1996
congressional candidates, with 56 percent going to Republicans,
according to the center.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people have deemed Silicon Valley as Clinton-Gore
country, and that is completely inaccurate because a lot of
computer gurus are both Democrat and Republican,'' Bailey said.
</P>
<P>
   For computer industry leaders aggravated by government
interference, there is the irony that the Internet grew out of a
government system used by the Department of Defense. Also, industry
trade groups are lobbying for more government investment in basic
computer research,which Gore has promised.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Lezlee Westine, a Bush supporter who works for the
bipartisan Technet, contended that the Texas governor attracts
Silicon Valley support because his ``basic instincts'' are to keep
government out of the industry's way.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of how the executives line up in the presidential
race, Bailey warily sees the current campaigns as the beginning of
a long political tango between politicians and the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians will continue to covet contributions from people
acquiring new wealth, and the newly wealthy will continue to fend
off policies that could limit the wealth, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Should voters be concerned about the rise of a new special
interest group?
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever you see politicians out there mining contributions
from anybody who looks to be profiting off the booming economy, I
think there is some cause for concern,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
