<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-11 19:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6099 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOP-CONGRESS-HNS &LR;      07-11 1279
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-CONGRESS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
GOP SCRAMBLES TO FIND RIGHT MESSAGE AND MESSENGER
<TEXT>
<P>
   By GREG McDONALD &QL;
</P>
<P>
   c. 1999 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republicans edgy about the prospect of losing their
majority hold on Congress are shifting strategies for getting their
message out to the American people. Complicating their effort are
the lack of a unified message and congressional leaders adroit at
communicating one then following through.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., for example, has abdicated
his leadership role on a number of issues, particularly during the
recent gun control debate. Or he has yielded to House Majority Whip
Tom DeLay, R-Texas, who has emerged this year as a leading voice of
the GOP's right wing in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., meanwhile, has
alienated many GOP colleagues by refusing to accommodate their
concerns on several key legislative matters and by yielding to
conservative members opposed to everything from campaign finance
reform to U.S. involvement in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   With Lott and Hastert struggling to keep order in the ranks as
the 2000 elections draw near, some Republican lawmakers have begun
looking for signals from Gov. George W. Bush on issues ranging from
gun control to spending and tax matters.
</P>
<P>
   Following the lead of the GOP presidential front-runner poses
other problems for lawmakers. Sometimes his counsel is out of step
with a majority of Americans _ he said no to a three-day waiting
period on gun purchases while most of the nation was saying yes.
Also, Bush has yet to fully formulate or lay out his positions on a
wide range of key issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hunger for a winner as much as anything has caused
(Republicans in Congress) to look for a candidate they can unite
behind. And George W. is the guy who has emerged, partly because of
his own qualities and partly because they don't see anyone else out
there,'' said Norman Ornstein, a congressional scholar at the
American Enterprise Institute.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is that the message he has may fit Texas, but
doesn't fit the rest of the country.''
</P>
<P>
   If Republicans are serious about keeping their majority hold on
Congress next year, Ornstein said there will have to be ``a natural
leadership'' from Congress that can help lawmakers develop a
message that resonates with local voters, if not the nation as a
whole.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're clearly foundering and floundering inside Congress.
... There seems to be no strategic capability at all, no sense of
what (legislative) ends they want to achieve,'' Ornstein said,
adding that Hastert, whom he calls, ``the accidental speaker,''
still ``hasn't figured out how to be a leader.''
</P>
<P>
   Hastert is trying to change that. He and his lieutenants have
devised a plan to speak out more forcefully on issues like Social
Security, Medicare, education and taxes. Later this month, Hastert
will seek more exposure outside the Capitol, like on the Sunday
television talk shows, in an attempt to get some sort of consistent
message out to voters about what electing Republicans to Congress
next year means for the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Charles O. Jones, a political science professor at the
University of Wisconsin and a senior fellow of government studies
at the Brookings Institution, says none of that will matter in the
end if GOP lawmakers cannot overcome the differences within their
own ranks over key issues like spending and tax cuts. Moreover,
Jones says the lack of strong Republican leadership in the 106th
Congress may be more a result of numbers than any lack of ability
on Hastert's part.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got one of the narrowest margins ever in the House,''
Jones said, referring to the Republicans' 11-seat edge over the 211
Democrats and one independent in the House. That means that the
defection of only six Republicans on an issue can jeopardize GOP
priorities.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert, Jones said, has to be ``constantly supersensitive'' to
the differing views within his conference, ``because if he loses a
few (votes), the only way he can win is to get a fair number of
Democrats.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's staring at a kind of nonmaneuverable Republican majority
in many ways ... with many members having competing interests,''
Jones added. ``Under these circumstances, it's hard to imagine how
you can be forceful and say `this is what our message is going to
be, now you guys toe the line.'''
</P>
<P>
   Jones said he could not imagine former Rep. Bob Livingston, who
stepped down earlier this year before being confirmed as speaker,
or former House Speaker Newt Gingrich for that matter, doing much
better given the current divisiveness within the GOP.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't expect really effective leadership ... could operate
under these present circumstances. The best you can do is
essentially keep your mouth shut, listen, try to find out where the
hell you can put together a majority, and stop announcing
deadlines'' for passing legislation, Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   He added that Hastert would do well to emulate the leadership
style of former Speaker Sam Rayburn, a Texas Democrat who wielded
immense power a half-century ago with a slim majority by working
quietly behind the scenes and not announcing what he intended to
accomplish.
</P>
<P>
   Public pronouncements, however, are part of the GOP's strategy.
Sometimes the Republicans' public declarations come back to haunt
them, as in 1995 when they promised not to budge on spending
levels, then took the blame for shutting the government.
</P>
<P>
   The miscalculation still lingers in the public's mind. A recent
poll by Western Wats Opinion Research Center found 41 percent of
Americans rating the Republican-controlled Congress as doing a fair
job. Another 37 percent say Congress is doing a poor job of
attending to the interests of the nation.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the Republican leadership has pledged publicly to
push through all 13 appropriations bills before the Oct. 1 start of
the new fiscal year. They plan to do it without lifting any of the
spending caps set in 1997 to help balance the budget.
</P>
<P>
   With Clinton threatening to veto many of the spending bills,
Republicans face having to negotiate with the Democratic president
so they can avoid having to pass temporary spending bills, as they
did last year, or, worse yet, shuttering the government again on
the eve of the 2000 elections.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert already has signaled that he wants to work a deal with
Clinton, but any overtures to the White House could alienate the
GOP's hardline conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   Still, bargaining with a Democratic president, whose approval
ratings remain much higher than the Republican Congress, may be the
only choice Hastert and Lott have if they are to complete this
year's legislative work on time.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got a serious migraine ahead,'' Ornstein warned. ``The
fact is that if you do not begin to adjust the caps on
discretionary spending, the budget is a dead issue.... If they get
into a position of where they have a government shutdown and then
have to cave to the president, they'll have a disaster on their
hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones predicted that Hastert and Lott will end up doing what
smart leaders always do when its called for _ compromise, even if
it doesn't sit well with some of their members.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody has a stake in there being accommodation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clinton is thinking about his legacy and doesn't want to go
out being known as the veto president. And (the Republicans) don't
want to go into the election ... without a semi-productive session
of Congress,'' Jones said. ``There's just too much riding on going
into the election with a positive rating rather than a negative
one.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
