<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-11 19:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6100 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAMPAIGN-CASH-GLUT-55     07-11 0604
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-CASH-GLUT-550(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ECONOMY CREATING BULGING WAR CHESTS FOR ALL LEVELS OF CANDIDATES
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Kan., Ky., Md. Mich., Nev., N.J., S.C., Texas)   (rk) 
 By ADAM CLYMER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Rep. Shelley Berkley, a freshman Democrat from
Nevada, has raised nearly half a million dollars in 10 weeks.
Mayoral candidates who are not even favorites are also filling
their war chests. And the Democratic National Committee is out of
debt.
</P>
<P>
   At all levels, the political system is awash in money. Gov.
George W. Bush of Texas may have the most startling bankroll _
$36.3 million _ but he is part of a phenomenon and not the
phenomenon itself.
</P>
<P>
   As candidates for federal office and the national party
committees prepare to file their midyear fund-raising reports with
the Federal Election Commission, it is becoming clear that money
for the 2000 elections is rushing in faster than ever. The strong
economy has made it easier to get contributions, and candidates are
mobilizing their fund-raising efforts earlier than in previous
election cycles.
</P>
<P>
   Fund-raising has become the chief barometer of early political
strength, so candidates have been working feverishly to fortify
their war chests. And lack of money can be a sign of terminal
weakness.
</P>
<P>
   For example, one major factor when Dennis Moore ran in 1998 for
a Kansas congressional seat where no Democrat had won in 40 years
was that Rep. Vince Snowbarger's June 30, 1997, campaign finance
report showed he had only $9,567 in cash on hand. Moore won a
narrow victory.
</P>
<P>
   In the six months since he was sworn in, Moore has worked the
phones almost every day to make sure no one sees him as financially
vulnerable this year. ``I like to learn from other people's
mistakes, not my own,'' he said. Next week his campaign will report
about $310,000 cash on hand, a startling total for a freshman.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. James E. Rogan of California read that President Clinton
and various Hollywood figures had targeted him for defeat after his
role as an impeachment manager. But other people read that too, and
1,000 of them sent him campaign contributions. So he started a
direct mail campaign that has succeeded beyond all expectations,
and he will report more than $750,000 in the bank next week.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's $36.3 million presidential take is spectacular, but
others are raking it in, too. Bill Bradley, basically running as
``not Al Gore,'' took in $11.5 million. The National Republican
Congressional Committee reports a record haul. The Democratic
National Committee is, of all things, out of debt for the first
time since September 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Political consultants of both parties report that money is
easier to raise than they can remember.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've even seen it in a few mayoral campaigns this year,'' said
David Dixon, a Democratic operative here. ``Even the sort of
midlevel candidates are raising more money than ever before.''
</P>
<P>
   Consultants and political strategists start with a predictable
set of explanations, largely independent of party.
</P>
<P>
   First of all, they say, their candidate or party has really
caught the national mood and people want to help. Secondarily,
their staffs have done a terrific job.
</P>
<P>
   And finally _ eagerly from the Democrats and in passing from the
Republicans _ they add, in the words of Shelly Kamins, a developer
from Potomac, Md., who runs Bush events here: ``Certainly one of
the factors is the prosperity in the country. You've got a lot more
people who are able to give a thousand dollars.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Dixon said local contributions were increasing, as new
businesses were turning good profits. ``Fifteen years ago you asked
them to work phone banks,'' he said of these donors. ``Now you ask
them to contribute.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, donors sometimes do not have to be asked. Ronald
Weiser, Bush's chairman in Michigan, said he found the enthusiasm
for his candidate ``absolutely amazing.'' In past campaigns, he
said, it was hard work to find supporters, especially people who
would take on fund-raising. ``This year they are coming to us,
asking if they can raise money for Bush. We say yes, they can.''
</P>
<P>
   For most candidates for Congress _ an intense battleground
because a six-seat shift would give Democrats control _ the calls
have to be made. Steve Gray-Barkan, a California consultant working
for Adam Schiff, Rogan's likely opponent, hails his client as ``a
fanatical phoner.'' Berkley of Nevada, who has raised $485,000 this
year, almost all of it since she returned from a honeymoon in
April, said, ``I'm relentless on the telephone.''
</P>
<P>
   ``After you've been turned down 10 times,'' she said, ``picking
up the phone and making the 11th call, that's the secret.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore said: ``I hate to make these calls, but it's a fact of
life. You've got to do it if you want to stay in Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   Rachel Gorlin, a Democratic consultant, said those calls may be
easier to make than they used to be, when ``candidates just dreaded
picking up the phone and calling people _ likely as not to hear
complaints.'' Now, she said, the reception is likely to be civil
and to lead to a contribution.
</P>
<P>
   Where is this leading? Norman J. Ornstein, a congressional
scholar at the American Enterprise Institute, an economic and
political research foundation here, sees one likely impact of all
the money that seems to be available.
</P>
<P>
   In the race for the House, he said, there will probably be only
25 or 30 districts that seem competitive by the fall of 2000,
``races where both sides spend $2 million and where you get outside
groups spending a few million more.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result of a 1996 Supreme Court decision, those ``outside
groups'' will include, in a big way, the national party committees.
Some of them will not file reports until July 20, but what their
spokesmen say indicates they are all sharing in the wealth. Even
the Republican Senate Campaign Committee, whose reports through May
show lower receipts than two years ago, is comfortably in the
black, and will be more so in a couple of weeks when it receives
its half of a record-breaking $9 million joint House-Senate dinner.
</P>
<P>
   At the Republican National Committee, prospecting for new
donors, while expensive, has turned up 51,000 fresh checkbooks _
``a huge number of people to join a party in an off-year,'' said
Mike Collins, the press secretary. The National Republican
Congressional Committee will report a record-breaking $26 million
take, and, more to the point, its cash on hand is at $9.3 million,
compared with $5.7 million two years ago and $4.5 million four
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Among the Democratic committees, the House campaign committee
expects to report more than $14 million raised, or more than twice
as much as it took in two years ago. The Senate campaign committee
will report $3.9 million in cash on hand, eight times as much as
two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Jordan, the committee's political director under Sen. Bob
Torricelli of New Jersey, the chairman, called the haul a tribute
``as much to hard work and a talented staff and a determined
chairman as to economic conditions or macro political issues.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Democratic National Committee expects to report $21
million in fund-raising and a surplus of $500,000 to $700,000. The
chairman, Joe Andrew, said the high numbers were attributable
largely to ``the Clinton-Gore economy, the best in a generation.''
</P>
<P>
   Fred Wertheimer, an architect of the 1974 Federal Election
Campaign Act who now leads an advocacy organization called
Democracy 21, sees prosperity as only one factor in the torrent of
money available.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the brakes are off the system,'' Wertheimer said. When
Bush's ``Pioneers,'' his club of leading fund-raisers, ``are
raising $100,000 at $1,000 a contribution,'' Wertheimer said,
``they will be raising a million or more each when they start
collecting soft money.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in a different stratosphere here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Mitch McConnell of Kentucky, head of the Republican Senate
Campaign Committee and his party's chief opponent of change in the
campaign finance laws, disagreed. ``For most Americans if they are
interested in politics at all,'' he said, ``the way they express
that is they write out a check for their favorite candidate or
cause.''
</P>
<P>
   The big ideological causes whose backers send money are likely
to be the usual ones: guns, abortion and gay rights. But there is
one new one, impeachment. There is even an Impeachment Managers
Political Action Committee, which hopes to raise $130,000 through
an Internet site that has brought in some money already without an
official start-up. The modest financial goal would be enough to
give each of the 13 impeachment managers $5,000 for a primary and
$5,000 for the general election.
</P>
<P>
   But even if ideology directs some of the dollars, it is the
economy that is providing them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody is pouring money in,'' said Tom Downey, a lobbyist
here who raises money for various Democrats. ``They are rich and
the economy's strong. At every level there is more money.''
</P>
<P>
   Warren Tompkins, a Republican consultant in Columbia, S.C.,
said, ``People are making more money and they are willing to let go
of a little of it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
