<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-11 19:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6102 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MINORITY-JOURNALISTS-     07-11 1159
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINORITY-JOURNALISTS-615&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NUMBER OF MINORITY JOURNALISTS IS NOT GROWING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wash., Calif.)  (lb) 
 By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ If the gathering here last week had been a medical
convention, it would have been billed as a gathering of experts
seeking cures for terminal nearsightedness. More than 5,000
minority journalists _ and hundreds more people who train them,
hire them, study their work, make their computers and advertise
with their news organizations _ spent days debating what news
organizations must do to put the world in focus.
</P>
<P>
   The overarching assumption was that major news organizations
will have continuing trouble keeping their audiences.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to paint a more complete picture of America,'' was the
way that Catalina Camia, the president of Unity: Journalists of
Color Inc., put it at the opening session of the group's second
national convention, which brought together members of the National
Association of Black Journalists, the Asian-American Journalists'
Association, the Native American Journalists Association and the
National Association of Hispanic Journalists.
</P>
<P>
   The event nearly foundered nine months ago when a faction of the
black group said that Washington state was not a fit site because
it passed an anti-affirmative-action initiative. But after
rancorous debate, the groups voted to keep the gathering in
Seattle. So for some, the existence of the convention was a
victory. But for many, jobs mattered most.
</P>
<P>
   ``More people of color in the newsrooms _ that's the bottom-line
goal of all of the four organizations,'' said Sheila Brooks, a
member of the National Association of Black Journalists who is
chief executive of SAB Productions Inc., a television and video
production company. ``But it's not going to change unless we pound
and pound and pound.'' The convention included a job fair where
scores of news organizations interviewed minority candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've made at least one hire here _ at least,'' said Leonard
Downie Jr., the executive editor of The Washington Post. Rob Dean,
the managing editor of The New Mexican in Santa Fe, with a
circulation of 25,000, had not filled the job opening he had, but
said he talked to about 15 candidates and is taking six resumes
home.
</P>
<P>
   Telly Hughes, a recent graduate of Illinois State University
who, at 21, is looking for an entry-level job in broadcasting, came
away with a fistful of business cards and a headful of advice. ``I
can't believe these established people take time to talk to me,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   But hovering near the surface of this gathering was the
knowledge that in the years since Unity had its first convention in
Atlanta in 1995, the number of Hispanic, Native American, Asian and
black newspaper journalists has risen to only 11.55 percent from
10.49 percent, for a total of 6,365 journalists out of 55,100 in
newspaper newsrooms, according to an annual diversity survey of the
American Society of Newspaper Editors.
</P>
<P>
   But in local television stations, minorities in the work force
dropped to 19 percent in 1998 from 21 percent in 1996, according to
the Radio-Television News Directors Association.
</P>
<P>
   The Census Bureau estimates that 28 percent of the country's
population belongs to one of those four minority groups; that
figure is expected to reach almost 38 percent by 2025.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the stubbornness of the statistics and the sense at the
convention that minority journalists are leaving the profession
faster than they can be replaced did not dampen the spirits of some
for whom the convention is like a family reunion.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers were pleased to see network correspondents and the
publishers or editors of the United States' five largest newspapers
who came to recruit, and three presidential candidates who
addressed the group.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The jam-packed schedule featured multiple seminars by day _
sometimes six at a time _ and multiple parties by night, at least
six at a time. Sponsors included companies like Knight-Ridder Inc.,
Apple Computer Inc. and Adolph Coors Co.
</P>
<P>
   As the convention started, the Freedom Forum, a foundation based
n Washington, D.C., released a survey showing that more than half
of minority journalists plan to leave the business in the next five
years, even though 60 percent of them said that they liked their
jobs ``very much.'' Figures for nonminority journalists were
unavailable.
</P>
<P>
   The apparent paradox in the survey can perhaps be explained by
ex-journalists like Mary Lou Fulton and Ron Funabiki. Ms. Fulton,
whose mother is Mexican, describes her eight-year journalism
career, mostly at The Los Angeles Times, in tones that mix real
gratitude with deep dissatisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Newspapers often believe that if you have enough
different-colored noses in a newsroom, that's going to make a
better newspaper,'' said Ms. Fulton, who was by turns a local
reporter and the editor of The Los Angeles Times' short-lived City
Weekly. ``I think having enough noses is essential, but you also
have to have different coverage strategies.''
</P>
<P>
   She praised the newspaper's new Hispanic desk, saying that
earlier coverage of minority communities was one-dimensional.
</P>
<P>
   But for all that, she said, nothing could have kept her from the
lure of the Internet, which she discovered five years ago after she
had received a master's degree in public administration. Now 35,
``an old woman'' in her new world, she is leaving her job as a vice
president for editorial operations of Yahoo's Geocities unit and is
being interviewed for top jobs at two Internet start-ups, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Funabiki, 50, who is Japanese-American, spent twice as much time
in the business as Ms. Fulton, but reflected the same mix of
satisfaction and frustration. At The San Diego Union, he had some
choice assignments, including a self-designed beat covering the
economics of the Pacific Rim. But Funabiki said he felt his career
prospects were limited.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't really angry or upset, but I wasn't satisfied with
things, either,'' he said. In 1990, after 19 years in the business,
he accepted an offer to start a new program at San Francisco State
University focused on analyzing mainstream journalism. After five
years, he moved to the Ford Foundation as a program officer.
</P>
<P>
   Both Funabiki and Ms. Fulton came back to Unity this week _ Ms.
Fulton as a panelist for a session on high-technology with Vice
President Al Gore, and Funabiki to see how Unity used some of the
$400,000 in grants Ford has made to it in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   The reality of attrition, however, is making it hard to keep the
minority numbers rising. A recent article in American Editor cited
studies showing that journalism schools overall are producing about
750 minority print journalists a year _ exactly the number of
people who, like Funabiki and Ms. Fulton, have been lost to
attrition.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
