<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-PROTEST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICO STUDENTS CONTINUE STRIKE ON EMPTY CAMPUS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JULIA PRESTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Digging in their heels, student protesters have
decided once again to continue their strike at Mexico's huge
national university, now in its 12th week, even though there are no
longer any classes for them to strike.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the despairing authorities of the National Autonomous
University of Mexico declared a formal end to the spring semester,
which they had extended several times while trying to resolve the
strike.
</P>
<P>
   Since there is no summer session, no one will even try to give
classes on the vast campus until mid-August. But the strikers voted
in a midnight session Saturday to maintain their shutdown even
though the university is shutting down on its own.
</P>
<P>
   Figures offered by the administration reveal the dimensions of
the political confrontation at the university, the largest and once
one of the most prestigious in Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   About 192,000 students who did not support the strike attended
classes that were held off campus to avoid the demonstrators, and
were able to complete the semester with credit, officials said. But
78,000 students backed the strike and failed to finish their
courses.
</P>
<P>
   Brigades of students still occupy the campus and guard
barricades blocking the entrances. Hundreds of strikers have been
in residence on the campus, which has no dormitories, since the
strike began. Their blankets and freshly washed socks hang from
classroom balconies.
</P>
<P>
   The largest union of blue-collar workers at the university
announced that some of its members had agreed to work without pay
to help the strikers through the summer break.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, strikers and university officials began talks. But
they immediately argued about procedure, with the administration
calling for a closed negotiation and the students demanding to have
the talks broadcast live on television.
</P>
<P>
   While the government has said it does not want to use force to
evict the strikers, that option seemed to be an increasingly real
possibility.
</P>
<P>
   The defense minister, Gen. Enrique Cervantes, ruled out any
action by the military, to avoid a repeat of what happened during
the 1968 student movement. A whole generation of Mexicans turned
against the army after it killed dozens of protesters during a
Mexico City demonstration that year. But Attorney General Jorge
Madrazo Cuellar was less categorical, saying only that he hoped he
would not have to dispatch federal police to take back the campus.
</P>
<P>
   The strike began as a protest of a plan by the university
president, Francisco Barnes de Castro, to charge a modest tuition
for those who could afford it. But it quickly swelled into a
movement against all cutbacks on federal spending for higher
education in Mexico and any efforts to tighten academic standards
at the university.
</P>
<P>
   At the outset Barnes badly miscalculated the strength and
determination of the student movement and went from blunder to
blunder in handling the strike. On June 7, he withdrew his plan to
raise tuition to about $150 a year from its current rate,
equivalent to about 2 American cents. But he did not approach the
strikers ahead of time to see how they would react. Strike leaders
spurned his initiative as too limited and pressed on with the
shutdown.
</P>
<P>
   The strike movement has become dominated by unbending leaders,
some of whom have made careers of activism at the university and
have shown no solid interest in settling with the administration.
</P>
<P>
   While the public seems largely fed up with the strike, the
protesters have picked up some outside support. Consulta, a polling
firm, found that 83 percent of the people surveyed in Mexico City
were in favor of raising tuition at the university before the
strike, but by mid-June only 55 percent supported the change.
</P>
<P>
   Many passers-by signaled their support for the students, who
marched to the capital's central square on Friday to announce they
were not giving up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm an old man and I've seen how this country runs,'' said
Salvador Perez Gomez, a 68-year-old merchant who watched the march
from the sidelines. ``We have to defend ourselves against this
lousy government and make sure they don't take away our children's
right to an education.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
