<SLUG> BC-SOC-WCUP-TV-NIELSEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV RATING FOR U.S.-CHINA SOCCER MATCH SURPRISES ABC 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Women's World Cup victory by the U.S. team over China on
Saturday produced an astonishing 13.3 overnight Nielsen rating, at
least doubling ABC's expectations.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, the National Basketball Association finals
between the Knicks and San Antonio Spurs generated an 11.3 average
national rating.
</P>
<P>
   The network estimated that about 40 million viewers watched all
or part of the Women's World Cup game.
</P>
<P>
   The game started at 3:30 p.m. with a 7.6 rating, rose to an 18.8
from 6:15 to 6:30 p.m., and concluded with a 16.1 from 6:30 to 6:45
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The rating nearly doubled last year's 6.9 overnight rating for
the men's World Cup final between Brazil and France, and edged out
the 12.8 for the 1994 Italy-Brazil World Cup final that was played
in the U.S. The highest-rated U.S. game that year was a 10.4,
against Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very gratifying to know that huge events still have the
power to bring in huge ratings on network TV,'' said Mark Mandel, a
spokesman for ABC Sports. ``Clearly there are still opportunities
for networks to bring in huge numbers when games are highly
dramatic.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
