<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-11 19:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6110 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGOSLAVIA-U.S.-840(2     07-11 0885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-U.S.-840(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. WANTS MILOSEVIC OUT BUT WAVERS OVER SUPPORTING A SUCCESSOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: With optional trims.) 
(js) 
 By JANE PERLEZ    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Despite its clear desire to see President Slobodan
Milosevic of Yugoslavia ousted, the Clinton administration is
finding it difficult to capitalize on the opportunity presented by
the opposition protests that have bubbled up across Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   The question of new leadership in Yugoslavia is as troubling as
it is important, not only because Milosevic has been indicted on
charges of war crimes, administration officials said, but because
without the participation of Yugoslavia it will be hard to build
stability in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   But for the moment, a wait-and-see attitude prevails in
Washington, even though the Clinton administration has made clear
that it considers Milosevic an international outlaw who should be
brought to justice.
</P>
<P>
   The main problem, administration officials acknowledge, is that
they are wary of the current opposition leaders who might succeed
Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the administration had a favorite successor, its ability
to advance that person decisively is limited, the officials said.
Further, after 11 weeks of NATO bombing, even tacit support from
Washington might only taint a successor's standing with the Serbian
public.
</P>
<P>
   Thus administration officials said they were being careful not
to back anyone in particular and have instead decided to stick with
their policy of trying to isolate Milosevic and generate hardship
for his powerful circle of cronies.
</P>
<P>
   The officials said they are disillusioned with the opposition
leaders who galvanized crowds in Belgrade against Milosevic in the
winter of 1996-97.
</P>
<P>
   One official said the administration has written off as an
``opportunist'' Vuk Draskovic, one of the leaders of the street
demonstrations who later joined the Milosevic government and has
now been ousted.
</P>
<P>
   Another leader of that period, Zoran Djindjic, who remained in
opposition and lived in Montenegro during the Kosovo war, is not
favored by Washington either, said a senior administration official
involved in trying to find some cohesion in the emerging
anti-Milosevic movement. Officials say they believe that Djindjic
lacks the necessary support and leadership skills to propel the
anti-Milosevic movement forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``We shouldn't pick a winner,'' this official said, as he left
over the weekend for Europe, where he planned to meet some
anti-Milosevic activists, whom he refused to identify. ``The
Europeans are making a dramatic mistake by picking Djindjic as
their poster boy. He has very little support. We should let the
people pick a winner.''
</P>
<P>
   In trying to foster an opposition to Milosevic, the
administration faces tough hurdles, some of which stem from having
just waged a war against Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   The United States no longer has an embassy in Belgrade, and has
no plans for one, according to the State Department. Thus, making
contact with opposition party mayors in towns where the protests
have sprung up is almost impossible. Even in 1996, with an embassy,
U.S. officials had trouble forging links to the anti-Milosevic
opposition.
</P>
<P>
   The tougher hurdle is the nature of the problem: Undermining
Milosevic is not as easy, some argue, as was unseating the regimes
in Eastern Europe during the dying days of the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Milosevic is an ultra-nationalist,'' said James R. Hooper,
executive director of the Balkan Action Council, an independent
group specializing in Balkans policy. ``He's not a Communist like
those in Eastern Europe who were held in power by the Soviet Union.
Here the roots go very deep, lots of Serbs have given real or
passive support. There have been few regimes like this before.''
The closest similarity could be made with fascist Italy or Nazi
Germany, Hooper said.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM HERE)
</P>
<P>
   But Hooper suggested that the model of Portugal in the 1970s was
a helpful one. There, he said, the United States _ and especially
German political parties _ encouraged Mario Soares, the founder of
the anti-Communist Party Socialist Party. In the aftermath of the
1974 army-led revolution, Soares came to power and eventually
helped lead Portugal into the European Union.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM HERE)
</P>
<P>
   In Serbia, the Yugoslav army is one element that remains an
uncertainty. Historically, the army has been a proud institution of
the Yugoslav nation. Milosevic has repeatedly purged its ranks,
leaving his ciphers at the top. But disgruntled army reservists,
talking darkly about the war in Kosovo and bitter about their lack
of pay, participated in some anti-Milosevic rallies last week,
particularly in Leskovac, a longtime stronghold of the Yugoslav
leader.
</P>
<P>
   But what practical effect such sentiments would have in the
coming months is difficult to judge. ``The Yugoslav army does not
have a history of coups,'' a senior administration official said.
``This is not Latin America.''
</P>
<P>
   The tactic most favored for encouraging the unrest appears to be
isolation of the regime. With a little pressure here, a little
pressure there, the hope is that Milosevic will be asphyxiated.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But the administration is beginning to consider how to help some
areas of Serbia where opposition party mayors are in power.
Reconstruction aid has been ruled out but humanitarian aid will be
considered, President Clinton has said. One way to use humanitarian
aid as an example against Milosevic would be to restore power at a
hospital in a municipality where the opposition is in control,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Another isolation tactic is of symbolic importance. Much of
Milosevic's standing with his own people was bolstered by the
continual bustle of international figures who came to visit him,
often on ``last ditch'' missions to warn against his policies,
which Serbian television would then transform into spectacles
aggrandizing Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Now, those visits have stopped. And he, his family and his inner
circle are marooned inside Serbia. Milosevic rarely traveled
anyway, but now there are few places he can go without being
arrested.
</P>
<P>
   Of personal annoyance to his tight knit family _ consisting of
Milosevic; his wife, Mirjana Markovic; their son, Marko; daughter
in law, Milica, and daughter, Marija _ was the recent refusal by
the Greek Embassy in Belgrade to grant Marko Milosevic a visa for
travel to Greece.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM HERE)
</P>
<P>
   According to accounts in Belgrade, the young Milosevic, who
carries a diplomatic passport, applied for a visa to Greece after
the Kosovo war. After about 10 days, according to one account, the
Greek Embassy returned the passport without explanation and without
a visa.
</P>
<P>
   About 300 of the elder Milosevic's cronies, most of whom hold
sizable bank accounts and property holdings abroad, are on a visa
ban list that was created by the European Union before the NATO air
strikes. Some of them, including Bogoljub Karic, the owner of
Serbian banks and a television station that toes the Milosevic
political line, are getting restless.
</P>
<P>
   Karic is reported to have been turned back at the Serbian border
with Hungary and is known in Belgrade to be complaining that he is
unable to tend to his investments in London. In the weeks leading
up to Milosevic's agreement with NATO, Karic and other loyalists
who have become wealthy through Milosevic's favors are believed to
have encouraged the settlement, administration officials said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Alongside this isolation strategy, the administration is also
trying to provide the Serbian opposition with some encouragement
and role models. Clinton is planning at the end of the month to
attend a one-day jamboree, scheduled for Sarajevo, of 30 Western
European and Balkan leaders. It will be a day, administration
officials predict, of grand proclamations of a new dawn for the
Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   Absent will be Slobodan Milosevic. Present will be Milo
Djukanovic, president of Montenegro, the junior republic to Serbia
in Yugoslavia. It was Djukanovic who broke with Milosevic two years
ago and who received moral and financial support from the West
during the Kosovo war.
</P>
<P>
   These days, he is the State Department's model of an opposition
leader.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
