<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLOMBIA-REBELS-890&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS COLOMBIA DECLARES AN ALERT, REBEL OFFENSIVE RAGES ON
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By LARRY ROHTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil _ Leftist guerrillas in Colombia renewed
attacks on more than twenty towns Sunday after a government decree
set a dusk-to-dawn partial curfew in nearly one-third of the
country and ordered the armed forces into a state of alert.
</P>
<P>
   Clashes between the army and units of the Revolutionary Armed
Forces of Colombia were reported to have left more than 180
guerrillas, soldiers, police officers and civilians dead in several
areas of southeastern Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   News reports from Bogota, the capital, said the guerrillas had
even attacked military barracks with homemade tanks built from
tractors, and missiles constructed from gas canisters.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an escalation that is going to continue,'' Gen.
Fernando Tapias, commander-in-chief of the Colombian armed forces,
said on Saturday in announcing the military alert for the 120,000
members of the armed forces.
</P>
<P>
   He said his troops had ``neutralized 98 percent'' of what he
described as ``these insane terrorist actions,'' but that
assertion, as well as official estimates of the death toll, could
not be independently confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   The emergency measures announced late Saturday prohibit all
highway and river travel between sunset and dawn in most of the
southeastern part of the country and give mayors there authority to
extend the ban to daylight hours. But Interior Minister Nestor
Martinez sought in television interviews to play down the
importance of the restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   The provinces covered by the order encompass areas that the
government has formally ceded to the guerrillas in an effort to
jump-start peace negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a curfew,'' Martinez said. ``What we are doing is
limiting the free circulation of vehicles between municipalities.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez said ordinary Colombians should not be affected,
because the restrictions applied only to places ``where private
citizens should not be.'' The travel prohibitions will last, he
said, ``as long as necessary to assure that the insurgents cannot
be reinforced.''
</P>
<P>
   The limited curfew applies to all or part of 10 of Colombia's 32
provinces. Most of the areas affected are sparsely populated jungle
and savanna areas, but one, Cundinamarca, borders the capital. It
was the focus of a fierce guerrilla attack barely 25 miles from
Bogota on Thursday that resulted in the deaths of at least 78
soldiers and guerrillas and signaled the start of a stepped-up
campaign by the rebel group.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the Colombian military said, a radio message was
intercepted in which Jorge Briceno, the second in command of the
guerrilla group, was heard ordering a subordinate to ``blockade
Bogota by the roads, and then we will advance.''
</P>
<P>
   Military spokesmen have suggested that the rebels' aim was to
reach the outskirts of the capital, perhaps to free leaders and
fighters of the rebel group held in prisons there.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to calm the population in the capital, Tapias said
his troops had taken ``all the security measures necessary to avoid
terrorist acts in Bogota,'' which has a population of seven
million.
</P>
<P>
   ``An action of that sort would cause great impact among the
population and have grave repercussions for the economy and foreign
investment,'' he acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   The rebel group has been seeking to install a revolutionary
Marxist state in Colombia since the 1960s but has usually confined
its attacks to rural areas and stayed away from cities.
</P>
<P>
   But its strength has grown in the last three years to about
15,000 fighters. In a show of increased mobility and firepower late
last year, the group attacked and briefly held Mitu, a remote
provincial capital in the Amazon.
</P>
<P>
   In the absence of any public declarations, the reasons the
guerrillas have mounted an offensive now are unclear. They were
scheduled to begin formal peace negotiations with the government on
July 7, but a two-week postponement of the talks was announced less
than 24 hours before they were to begin. A statement by both sides
said some members of the rebel delegation could not reach the site
of the talks in time.
</P>
<P>
   Conventional wisdom is that the guerrillas are seeking to
improve their bargaining position when the talks finally get under
way. ``This offensive intends to show an image of strength before
the opening of peace negotiations with the national government,''
Tapias said on Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   But there is also speculation that the ``initiation of talks was
itself a tactic of war'' designed to lull the government into
complacency, as the daily El Pais in Cali put it Sunday. The paper
said the guerrillas also wanted to intimidate ordinary Colombians
into thinking that ``they are in better conditions than the armed
forces to produce a military victory.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, guerrilla leaders warned that they were
preparing a ``first great offensive'' to be carried out if they
were not satisfied with the course of the peace efforts. Those
threats were amplified last week by a rebel commander and
spokesman, Javier Calderon, who warned in an interview published in
an Argentine newspaper that the talks were ``the last flame of
hope, and if that flame goes out, there will be total war.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want total war,'' Calderon said. ``We don't want the
Colombian people to continue immersed in this war. But we will wage
it if necessary.'' And he added, ``We are prepared for it.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Such threats appear to have eroded the rebel group's standing as
a political force.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guerrillas cannot take power without political backing,
and right now their popularity is at its lowest level,'' Defense
Minister Luis Fernando Ramirez said in an interview published
Sunday in the Bogota daily El Espectador.
</P>
<P>
   But the offensive is also a setback for President Andres
Pastrana, who has staked his presidency on a pledge to bring an end
to a conflict that has killed 35,000 Colombians in the last decade
alone.
</P>
<P>
   Since taking office in August 1998, Pastrana has made a series
of concessions to the rebels as good-faith gestures, including
giving them control of a Switzerland-size region that they appear
to have used as a base to mount the attacks of recent days.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels have not made similar concessions. They have refused
to decree a cease-fire while talks are held, and public support for
the peace talks is diminishing. In a poll published this month, for
instance, nearly three-quarters of those surveyed described the
rebels as a terrorist group with no ideology other than kidnapping
and drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
   Even the influential Roman Catholic Church, which has strongly
supported Pastrana's peace efforts, appears to have joined the
skeptics.
</P>
<P>
   In a pastoral letter issued on Saturday at the conclusion of its
annual assembly, the national bishops' conference warned of ``a
dark panorama that has no limits,'' saying that ``clear
possibilities of success cannot be seen, and the civilian
population is less and less secure in a country buffeted by the
winds of war and death.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
