<HEADER>
A6119 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEVICE-NONWINDOWS &LR;      07-11 2038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEVICE-NONWINDOWS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMASHING WINDOWS: UPSTART COMPANIES SET TO LAUNCH CHEAP,
SIMPLE  INTERNET PCS
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By HENRY NORR 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Bill Gates may not be quaking in his boots just yet, but a new
generation of personal computers without Windows will soon begin
tempting consumers looking for a cheap, simple and reliable way to
join the Internet revolution.
<P>
   Aside from the Apple iMac's growing but still modest market
share, virtually every home computer sold today comes with Windows
pre-installed. But in recent weeks several manufacturers have
announced new PCs, due over the next few months, that won't have
Windows or any other software from Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, these unorthodox PC-makers are turning to alternatives
old and new to control their computers' basic operations and create
their look and feel. By Christmas, shoppers in the market for a
cheap PC will be able to choose among products that run the BeOS, a
modern multimedia-oriented system developed by Be Inc. of Menlo
Park, Calif.; Linux, the cooperatively developed, freely
distributed operating system that's recently made a splash in
corporate and technical markets; and even a new version of GEOS, a
decade-old graphical software environment that appeared to have
succumbed to the Windows tide years ago.
</P>
<P>
   PIA
</P>
<P>
   Ebiz Enterprises, a PC vendor in Scottsdale, Ariz., last week
disclosed plans for a Linux-based device called PIA, for Personal
Internet Appliance, which it plans to release next month at $199,
sans monitor. Aimed both at first-time buyers and at families
seeking a second or third PC, it will be sold through the company's
online outlet, the Linux Store (www.cpumicromart.com), and through
Internet service providers.
</P>
<P>
   Prodigy, a national ISP that claims more than 600,000
subscribers, was the first to announce its intent to market the
device _ part of a rapidly emerging trend for ISPs to offer
subsidized hardware for customers who commit to use their service.
</P>
<P>
   Ebiz officials last week were keeping mum about product details,
pending a preview on ``Good Morning, America'' on  &LR; July 15 &LR;  and a
formal unveiling at next month's LinuxWorld trade show in San Jose.
But they confirmed that the machine will come in a conventional PC
case and include an AMD chip, 32 megabytes of memory, a
2.1-gigabyte hard drive and a slot for expansion cards, such as a
network adapter or 3-D graphics accelerator.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Linux and the Gnome point-and-click interface for
it, bundled software will include Netscape's Communicator Web
browsing and e-mail software, plus a variety of Web plug-in
programs, an MP3 digital music player and an undisclosed word
processing program.
</P>
<P>
   iToaster
</P>
<P>
   Microworkz Inc. (www.microworkz.com), a Linwood, Wash., &LR; 
 &LR; company that first attracted national attention when it introduced
a stripped-down Windows PC at $299 earlier this year, is slated to
begin shipping a BeOS-based box priced at $199 later this month.
Designed to look more like a component in a home-entertainment
system than like a traditional PC, it will come with a keyboard,
mouse and standard PC ports, but no monitor, floppy drive, CD-ROM
or expansion slots.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of DEVICE12 () &QL; 
 &LR;  Customers for whom even $199 is out of range can opt for an
installment plan that provides the iToaster, a 15-inch color
monitor, technical support and 150 hours per month of Internet
access through Microworkz for $19.95 per month for two years.
</P>
<P>
   The device will run on a stripped-down version of the modular Be
system. Microworkz has developed a custom look for it, including a
main screen with large icons that will take users directly to
popular Internet sites, such as online booksellers and travel
agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Microworkz spokeswoman Luanne Brown denied published reports
that the machine will use a hybrid of Linux and the BeOS.
</P>
<P>
   Industry sources said Microworkz has also licensed Gobe
Productive, a BeOS application suite from Gobe Software of
Portland, Ore. Created by the original developers of Apple's
ClarisWorks suite, it includes word processing, spreadsheet,
graphics and other modules.
</P>
<P>
   The BeOS, which Apple once considered buying for its Macs, was
designed to excel in processing digital audio and video, and until
now it has mainly been used in machines aimed at professional
multimedia producers. But in recent months Be has also been
promoting the system's suitability for use in simplified ``Internet
appliances'' like the iToaster.
</P>
<P>
   Be, ironically, is now partly owned by Microsoft's longtime PC
partner, chip giant Intel, which took a 10 percent stake last year.
Be's initial public offering is scheduled for later this week.
</P>
<P>
   GlobalPC
</P>
<P>
   The most surprising entry in the emerging non-Windows PC
marketplace is due this fall from an Alameda, Calif., startup
called GlobalPC. The company has licensed GEOS, a graphical
environment and application suite that runs on top of DOS, from its
original creator, Geoworks, an Alameda neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   When first released in the late 1980s, GEOS won critical acclaim
as an efficient and easy-to-use alternative to the complexities of
DOS, which required users to type in arcane commands.
</P>
<P>
   But when Microsoft released Windows 3.0 in 1991, GEOS' fortunes
faded fast. In recent years Geoworks has moved in new directions _
it now markets software for sending travel and consumer information
to cell phone users _ and is no longer investing in GEOS. But
GlobalPC officials said their own engineers have modernized the
system.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to integrating Internet software, they have further
simplified the user interface for novice users, according to Peter
Dille, GlobalPC vice president of marketing.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of DEVICE12 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  GlobalPC's hardware, as yet unnamed, will be released in selected
markets this fall, with national distribution slated to begin next
year. It will cost $299, without monitor, but owners will able to
use a standard TV screen as a display.
</P>
<P>
   While acknowledging that it has yet to sign any distribution
agreements, the company said its plan is to market the system
through mass-market outlets such as Wal-Mart and Kmart, in hopes of
reaching customers intimidated by the prospect of shopping in a
computer store or even an electronics outlet.
</P>
<P>
   The GlobalPC story took an intriguing twist last month, when a
Jacksonville, Fla., company named Compu-DAWN signed a letter of
intent to acquire it. Compu-DAWN's chairman is R. E. ``Teddy''
Turner IV, son of media magnate Ted Turner. (The younger Turner is
also chairman of the board of U.S. Bison Co., an Atlanta bison
ranching company, according to Compu-DAWN filings with the
Securities and Exchange Commission.)
</P>
<P>
   Compu-DAWN was previously involved in several lines of business,
including marketing specialized hardware and software to
public-safety agencies and Amway-style ``multi-level marketing'' of
telecommunications services and digital set-top boxes to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, however, the company has sold its public-safety
product group, announced plans to phase out direct marketing in
favor of distribution through mass merchandisers, adopted a new
moniker (e.TV Commerce, a name formerly used by a subsidiary), and
proclaimed its intent to refocus around the opportunities it sees
in GlobalPC.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to hardware sales and Internet access fees,
according to a press release issued last week, those opportunities
include ad sales and e-commerce on the portal site to which
GlobalPC users will be automatically connected.
</P>
<P>
   The company also said it plans to generate revenue by inviting
prominent e-commerce sites, including online banks and book and
music vendors, to pay for ``hot links'' to their sites from special
buttons on the GlobalPC keyboard.
</P>
<P>
   Two factors _ cost and complexity _ are driving the new interest
in alternatives to Windows, industry execs and analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line, of course, is economics. Windows is the one
component of standard PCs that hasn't plummeted in price in recent
years. Hardware manufacturers still fork over an estimated $45 to
$65 (depending on volume and contract terms) to Gates and company
for every Windows-equipped system they ship. Some industry insiders
refer to these Windows license fees as ``the Microsoft tax.''
</P>
<P>
   Linux, by contrast, is free, and while neither Microworkz nor
GlobalPC would disclose what they're paying for the BeOS and GEOS,
the amounts are undoubtedly below what Microsoft charges.
``Obviously, we're being aggressive with our pricing,'' said Lamar
Potts, who joined Be as vice president of Internet appliances in
February.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 3 of DEVICE12 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Over and above differences in license fees, Windows requires more
hardware resources _ faster processors, bigger hard drives, more
disk space _ than more efficient competitors. By switching systems,
proponents of the non-Windows approach say, they'll be able to
deliver more than enough performance for surfing the Web and other
routine home applications with less expensive components.
</P>
<P>
   Companies promoting these Windows-less PCs are hoping that the
lower prices resulting from software-licensing and hardware savings
will help them to reach the 50 to 60 percent of American households
that currently remain computerless, and will also help them open
new markets abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts, however, are skeptical about this argument, given
that full-blown Windows PCs can now be had for less than $500. ``I
question whether there are a lot of incremental users who will buy
at $199 instead of $399 _ especially when they figure out that it's
really $299 versus $499 when you count in the monitor,'' said
Stephen Baker, an analyst at PC Data in Reston, Va.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great that there are people willing to spend their money
on experiments like these,'' Baker said. ``I'm just glad it's not
my money.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Slater, principal analyst at Microdesign Resources in
Sebastopol, took a similarly dim view of the argument that the
lower costs of non-Windows systems will significantly expand the
market, but he said simplicity could be a stronger selling point _
if the alternative PCs really deliver it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their best bet is to deliver non-threatening, highly reliable
systems that really are easier to use than Windows systems,'' he
said. ``It remains to be seen whether they can do that, but if they
can, they could make a dent at the low end.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, even if the alternative PC operating systems
eliminate some of the hassles associated with Windows, they'll
create some new issues of their own. Because widely used
applications such as Microsoft Office won't be available on the
alternative systems, users could have trouble reading files
attached to e-mail messages they receive.
</P>
<P>
   ``And what happens,'' PC Data's Baker asked, ``when your kid
sees KidPix or Reader Rabbit on the neighbor's PC and wants you to
get them a copy?'' (These popular children's programs run only on
Windows and the Mac OS.)
</P>
<P>
   As computing becomes more Internet-centric and more programs are
written in the cross-platform Java language, online services such
as Web calendars are beginning to replace some applications users
previously had to install on their own systems.
</P>
<P>
   But even on the Web, not all operating systems are equally
privileged: Users running ``non-standard'' system software are
likely to find themselves excluded from sites that require
particular browsers or special plug-ins.
</P>
<P>
   Developers of the alternative operating systems are working hard
to solve such problems by writing or commissioning new software to
translate file formats and to fill other gaps in their offerings.
But that's a daunting task, considering that software for Windows
itself continues to advance at a rapid rate.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the combination of low prices and reduced complexity
could be a compelling proposition for some first-time buyers, as
well as for families that already have a PC but now want an extra
Internet-access station.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would buyers come if someone really could deliver a real
improvement in usability and market it effectively at attractive
prices?'' PC Data's Baker asked. ```Absolutely.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 5 of DEVICE12 () &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
