<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TREK-INTERNET </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEACHERS TAKES STUDENTS ON ROUND-THE-WORLD FIELD TRIP, VIA
THE  INTERNET
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By DEBORAH SOLOMON 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
SAN FRANCISCO _ As a teacher at Mission High School in San
Francisco, Jeff Golden was all too familiar with the high drop-out
rates, low grades and student apathy plaguing many urban schools.
<P>
   But Golden, 29, was convinced that if he could just get students
excited about learning, the grades and graduation rates would
improve. He knew that lectures and books weren't enough, so he
tried to remember what it was that piqued his interest when he was
in school.
</P>
<P>
   The answer: traveling the world.
</P>
<P>
   Since he couldn't afford to physically take all his students on
a trip, Golden set up a nonprofit called the Odyssey and created a
Web site to transport students on a virtual journey led by
real-world travelers.
</P>
<P>
   He recruited five twentysomethings to trek to places like Peru,
Guatemala and South Africa, all the while sending dispatches to the
Odyssey's Web site operated out of a building South of Market.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a person who lived abroad, I, along with other teachers,
started thinking about how traveling had given us such different
perspectives,'' said Golden, who launched the site about two years
ago. ``I started thinking about ways to use the Internet to take
students out of the classroom and see the world.''
</P>
<P>
   With the help of other teachers and Web designers, he created an
interactive site that combines reports on the society, culture and
geography of places visited by the Odyssey team with live
interviews of prominent international figures.
</P>
<P>
   The five trekkers are making a two-year worldwide journey to 10
regions in the developing world. After starting in Mexico and South
America, the group now is in Africa and plans to head to the Middle
East, China and India next year. A sixth team member may join the
group if the Odyssey can find the funds.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the group has interviewed people like Mary Burton of
South Africa's Truth and Reconciliation Commission and 1992 Nobel
Peace Prize Laureate Adolfo Perez of Argentina. They've visited
Mayan ruins and a palace in Peru and spoken with a shaman.
</P>
<P>
   They've also been thrown in jail. When they arrived in Cape Town
from Buenos Aires, group members were arrested when they were
unable to show proof that they would be continuing their travels.
After paying about $170 each, they were freed.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of TREK12 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  All the while, they've catalogued their trip on the Web site with
twice-weekly updates from each country.
</P>
<P>
   So far, more than 800 teachers have signed up to use the Odyssey
in their classrooms. The site _ www.worldtrek.org _ gets between
25,000 to 40,000 hits per weekday.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I couldn't do in my classroom was reach a large number of
students,'' Golden said. ``Using the Internet, we can transform the
way a large number of students see the world and their role in it.
I hope to impact more than 1 million students and get them much
more aware of global issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Teachers like Wendy Elman say the site has helped expose her
students to a world outside their immediate environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The site allows the kids to interact with different
environments _ human, natural and political _ beyond San Francisco
in a colorful, creative way,'' said Elman, who teaches fourth grade
at The Hamlin School, a private all-girls school.
</P>
<P>
   She points to a dispatch the team sent back from Nicaragua about
big dolls or gigantones _ giant, 15-foot dolls that make an
appearance in an annual parade.
</P>
<P>
   ``They loved when the team talked about the big dolls,'' Elman
said. ``It was perfect material. They wanted to know how they were
made, how they worked and they were using the word gigantones,
which is Spanish, a language they don't speak.''
</P>
<P>
   The team also answers messages from students and hosts live
chats from different regions.
</P>
<P>
   Golden said he wants to organize another trek in 2001, as long
as he can get funding. The Odyssey started with $15,000 in funding
from the Walter and Elise Haas Fund and ``a lot of maxed-out credit
cards,'' Golden said. The Haas fund is offering another $15,000 if
the Odyssey can match it.
</P>
<P>
   While Golden is paid, most of the Odyssey's employees are
volunteers. The group gets its Internet connection and space free
of charge from Viant Corp. and has some corporate sponsors, such as
Eastman Kodak and Patagonia.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of TREK12 () &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
