<SLUG> BC-CONGO-ASSESS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS ANALYSIS: MORE QUESTIONS THAN ANSWERS IN A CONGO CEASE-FIRE
PACT
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By DONALD G. McNEIL Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUSAKA, Zambia _ While its authors pitched it as a triumph,
Saturday night's signing of a cease-fire deal to end the war in
Congo had something of an air of fiasco about it.
</P>
<P>
   The unexpected occupation of a chair at the conference table by
an ousted rebel leader meant that Congo's two main rebel groups
have not, at least for the moment, signed the accord. Their foreign
backers, and foreign foes _ the outside powers that have made the
war a dangerous regional conflict _ all signed.
</P>
<P>
   Fully signed or not, the deal will still be tested on the
confused jungle-green battlefield in the heart of Africa.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, after the presidents and foreign ministers of a
dozen countries had spent nearly 13 hours in a conference hall
waiting for Zambian President Frederick T.J. Chiluba to announce
the signing ceremony, the upshot was that everyone had endorsed it
by 11 p.m. _ except the rebels who started this latest round of the
war.
</P>
<P>
   Chiluba said the rebels had disagreed with nothing in the
document and would feel morally obliged to abide by it.
</P>
<P>
   But both rebel groups later contradicted him. On Saturday night,
Olivier Kamitatu of the Movement for the Liberation of Congo
quietly said, ``We have not signed, so we are not bound.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday the Congolese Rally for Democracy was blunter. Asked if
it considered the war still on, Bizima Karaha, the group's chief of
security, answered, ``Of course.''
</P>
<P>
   This left the rebels in the dicey position of shunning a
cease-fire that their chief sponsors, Uganda and Rwanda, had
joined. Unless they get covert support, they should run out of
supplies.
</P>
<P>
   Military analysts said that even a fully subscribed cease-fire
document would have proved difficult since crucial issues _
particularly disarming the genocidal Hutu militia loose in eastern
Congo _ were left vague.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, a leadership spat within the Congolese Rally for
Democracy halted the peace process, and the assembled presidents
finally decided that the best course was that no rebels would sign
until Chiluba could fly to eastern Congo and personally decide who
the Rally's real leader is.
</P>
<P>
   No date has been set for that trip, nor could Chiluba say Sunday
how he will make the decision. It was a quick fix since all the
presidents were hurrying to Algiers for the annual summit of the
Organization of African Unity, which opens on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   At a brief press conference Sunday morning, Chiluba declined to
detail what happened behind the scenes between 10 a.m. Saturday,
when 300 diplomats and journalists assembled to watch the
celebratory signing, and 11 p.m., when it was finally signed.
</P>
<P>
   Information filtering out from the back rooms suggested that
three things had gone wrong. Besides the rebel leadership dispute,
officials said that Zimbabwe's President Robert Mugabe, chief ally
of Congo President Laurent Kabila, objected to the rebels sitting
alongside the presidents, and also wanted the document to name
Burundi as a belligerent. Burundi, which like Uganda and Rwanda has
a Tutsi-dominated government, has never admitted having troops
fighting in Congo.
</P>
<P>
   Chiluba made an oblique reference to that Saturday night, saying
the joint military command envisioned in the cease-fire would
``work closely with Burundi to address its security concerns.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Burundi has suffered spasms of Tutsi-Hutu genocide as Rwanda
has, but not on the scale that Rwanda did in 1994, when 500,000
people were killed in 100 days.
</P>
<P>
   The audience waiting for the cease-fire to be signed had
realized there was a problem with the Rally when its founder,
Ernest Wamba dia Wamba, quietly took the red seat with the Rally's
placard on it.
</P>
<P>
   The professor, who now heads a splinter faction, said he wanted
to be a third signatory on the document, which had only two dotted
lines for rebels. His rivals, Emile Ilunga and Karaha, never
entered the room. On Saturday night, as other combatants signed,
the professor kept flipping the pages of the blank yellow legal pad
left at his place.
</P>
<P>
   The cease-fire document itself, which went through eight drafts
over weeks of negotiations, sets a timetable for events: a
battlefield cease-fire, the creation of a joint military command by
the warring sides, the picking of a ``facilitator'' to lead an
``open national dialogue'' about the future of Congo, the eventual
placing of all territory under the sole control of one government,
the withdrawal of foreign forces and, eventually, free elections.
(Kabila is a self-declared president, having overthrown dictator
Mobutu Sese Seko in 1997. Kabila's allies in that assault, the
rebels and their backers in Rwanda and Uganda, turned on him last
August.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Where hostility had characterized the relationship, let joy
and understanding replace that,'' Chiluba said Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We Africans are not people from a dark continent,'' he added.
``We want peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Kofi Annan, secretary-general of the United Nations, is reported
to favor sending up to 20,000 peacekeepers, mostly drawn from
African countries, to Congo, feeling that the organization must do
at least as much as in the Balkans to keep peace.
</P>
<P>
   Chiluba Sunday morning criticized the United Nations, and
particularly its American and European members, for spending $1.50
per Kosovo refugee but only 11 cents per African refugee. He called
the disparity ``discrimination of the worst kind.''
</P>
<P>
   The cease-fire document calls for a ``neutral facilitator''
distinguished by moral virtue, international credibility and
experience. But it fails to define the powers he or she would have
to prevent, for example, an embarrassing breakdown like Saturday's.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats said no one had been chosen, but several names came up
repeatedly: Zuppi Matteo, an Italian priest who helped run peace
talks for Mozambique; Salim Ahmed Salim of the Organization of
African Unity, and the recent former presidents of South Africa,
Botswana and Benin.
</P>
<P>
   But the most obvious sticking point is the disarming of the Hutu
militia. They were not represented at the talks, and have
everything to lose. Although the cease-fire recognizes the
possibility of amnesty, those suspected of genocide could be
deported to Rwanda, tried and executed.
</P>
<P>
   The cease-fire document is also vague about who must take the
risk of enforcing peace by disarming the various warring parties.
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear that U.N. peacekeepers would be willing to take
heavy casualties to disarm any of the factions. The United Nations
pulled back its forces in Rwanda just before the genocide, while in
Angola it spent three years, at $1 million a day, collecting the
Unita rebels at camps and disarming them. Playing for time, Unita
turned in old men and boys with broken weapons. Now, rearmed with
heavy Ukrainian weapons it bought with diamond money, it is back at
war.
</P>
<P>
   In Congo, both sides' troops are scattered over a country 215
times the size of Kosovo, and often divided by ethnic group loyalty
or personal loyalty to a commander. The rebel groups are supposed
to hold the territory they have captured, disarm Hutu or Unita
fighters they meet and then merge their armies.
</P>
<P>
   Chiluba said he is optimistic. ``I have convinced myself that we
in the region have the political will'' to make peace a reality, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Jean-Pierre Bemba, the leader of the Movement for the
Liberation of Congo, did not attend the signing at all because he
was still consolidating his capture of Gbadolite, Mobutu's
birthplace, which is full of decaying palaces.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
