<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990711.0135 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-11 20:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6136 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-FENWAY-HNS &LR;      07-11 1498
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-FENWAY-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALAN TRUEX  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
When the taxi pulled up to Fenway Park and the driver said, ``This
is it,'' the passenger was surprised. And a bit disappointed.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Roger Clemens, the then-21-year-old pitcher who had grown up in
Houston, had just been called up to the Boston Red Sox, and he
asked, ``This is Fenway Park?''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the site of Tuesday night's All-Star Game is
unimpressive at first glance. Fenway Park is a squatty, red-brick
wedge jammed into a commercialized urban neighborhood. It has dim
lighting, virtually no parking lot and no soaring facade like
Yankee Stadium or graceful contours like Wrigley Field.
</P>
<P>
   But when you enter the arched doorways, you are in a magical
place _ ``a lyric little bandbox of a ballpark,'' New Englander
John Updike best described it.
</P>
<P>
   Not that everyone sees it that way. To the objective visitor
from out of town, this may seem like a dark, decaying dungeon of a
ballpark. There are too few restrooms and little leg room. The
aisles are so narrow that no vendors traverse them.
</P>
<P>
   Many sight lines are blocked by posts. And at night the lighting
is so weak in some places that you can't read a scorecard.
</P>
<P>
   But what genuine baseball fan can be objective about Fenway
Park?
</P>
<P>
   History breathes in the dust and mold of its rafters. Babe Ruth
not only hit but pitched here. Smoky Joe Wood outdueled Walter
Johnson. Tris Speaker roamed the lush bluegrass of center field.
Ted Williams played his last game here, homering in his final
at-bat. Clemens set a strikeout record here.
</P>
<P>
   The fabled wall known as the Green Monster _ far more dominating
than it appears on television _ still rules over left field,
dispensing its wicked brand of justice.
</P>
<P>
   From an infield roof seat you can scan Boston's skyline _ as
spectacularly jagged as Fenway's outfield. What greater privilege
is there than to be one of the 33,925 who can sit in these tight,
hallowed quarters?
</P>
<P>
   Creature discomforts aside, many observers believe the essence
of baseball, a sport like golf and tennis that defies the
constraints of time, is never more gloriously presented than at
Fenway Park, which opened in 1912.
</P>
<P>
   A former Boston All-Star catcher, Carlton Fisk, summarized the
park's magnetism: ``If you want to see everything baseball can
provide, Fenway is the place to see it.''
</P>
<P>
   It's the nation's coziest, craziest baseball arena, though not
exactly by design. It was cobbled together, in stages, in a
confining area, with its shape contrived to fit the jumbled layout
of city streets.
</P>
<P>
   The Green Monster was an afterthought _ not added until 1934,
when the stadium was expanded from its original seating capacity of
27,642.
</P>
<P>
   Because of long-standing buildings adjacent to the ballpark,
there wasn't room for a properly sized left field. Some sort of
barrier was needed to maintain a semblance of balance between
offense and defense.
</P>
<P>
   Originally, a 10-foot-high embankment stretched from the
left-field foul line to the flagpole in center. It became known as
Duffy's Cliff, after Red Sox left fielder Duffy Lewis, who scaled
the terrain to retrieve rocketing drives.
</P>
<P>
   But to less adroit outfielders, the hill was so hazardous that
alternative landscaping was recommended. So the mound was leveled
and the Green Monster created: an 18-foot-high base of concrete
topped by 19 feet of tin stretched across railroad ties _ 310 feet
from home plate.
</P>
<P>
   Although it was designed to frustrate hitters, the Monster
quickly became their best friend. Since 1934, Fenway has seen 13
percent more runs scored than has the average big-league venue.
</P>
<P>
   By 1936, so many fly balls were plunking windows on Lansdowne
Street that a 23-foot net was erected above the left-field tin to
catch the home runs.
</P>
<P>
   At Fenway, a lazy fly ball is often lifted by wind over the
wall. A home run of that dubious nature _ by New York Yankees
shortstop Bucky Dent _ cost the Red Sox a divisional championship
in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   The Green Monster also spawns fluke doubles and triples (flyouts
everywhere else), though it sometimes reduces legitimate line-drive
doubles to singles. Baseballs bounce weirdly all along the
multi-angled outfield fence, causing purists to debate whether
Fenway is good or evil for the game.
</P>
<P>
   This fence zigzags (no Wrigley curving here) and drops off,
step-like, from left field to right _ from 37 feet tall to 17 feet,
then to five and 3.25. The manually operated scoreboard at the base
of the Green Monster causes still more unusual ricochets. Opposing
outfielders usually reserve an extra 20 minutes of pre-game
practice to study the myriad caroms.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, the most famous inhabitant of Fenway's left field,
said, ``If the ball hit the tin, it dropped straight down; if it
hit the cement, it would bounce back hard; if it hit a bolt,
anything could happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Quirks and quaintness aside, what makes Fenway so lovable in its
enduring obsolescence is the way it reaches out to the fans.
</P>
<P>
   The foul area is the smallest in the majors, which means a box
seat along the first-base or third-base line puts you nearer the
action than any other ticket in any other stadium. Some seats at
Fenway are closer to the field than the dugouts are.
</P>
<P>
   One cherished section is the bleachers, where patrons know to
beware of beach balls and other flying objects. Opposing pitchers
warm up in front of the right-field fans and are frequent targets
of paper cups and airplanes.
</P>
<P>
   The favored bleacher seat is the red one in row 33, which was
struck by the longest home run ever to right field _ a 502-foot
blast by Williams.
</P>
<P>
   But a typical right-field home run in Fenway is a short one. At
302 feet, the right foul pole _ ``Pesky's Pole'' _ is even closer
to home plate than the one in left.
</P>
<P>
   Fenway's intimacy is a product of the ``dead ball'' era in which
this park was built. Back in the days when the baseball didn't
travel as far off the bat, this was a more compact game.
</P>
<P>
   When it opened, Fenway was one of the largest of ballparks.
Ebbets Field would debut a year later in Brooklyn with a capacity
of 18,000.
</P>
<P>
   Fenway's dimensions were comparable to those of its contemporary
stadiums. In fact, its center field _ originally 488 feet (later
shortened to 420) _ was one of the deepest.
</P>
<P>
   And its foul lines were longer than many. The Polo Grounds of
New York had a left-field distance of 277, while right was 257.
Even so, few fly balls made it that far before the 1920s.
</P>
<P>
   Besides its fascinating physical attributes, Fenway appeals for
the passion that is associated with it. It harks back to a time
when baseball owners were devoted to winning games rather than to
earning maximum revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Yawkey, owner of the Red Sox for 44 years until his death in
1976, was a sportsman whose love for baseball often transcended his
pursuit of money. Red Sox fans fondly recall the late 1960s, when
seats in the triangular Section 34 in center field were withheld
from sale to provide a dark background for prolific young slugger
Tony Conigliaro.
</P>
<P>
   But this is a different time, and the current owners of the Red
Sox want to dismantle Fenway Park. They say its miniature size and
paucity of luxury suites render it ``not economically feasible.''
</P>
<P>
   Red Sox chief executive officer John Harrington insists a new
stadium is necessary ``to continue fielding a competitive team.''
</P>
<P>
   Harrington recently presented plans for a $545 million ``New
Fenway'' patterned after the old but with seating for 44,140. He
said the new stadium, which he hopes will open in 2003, will
provide ``unobstructed views, wider seats, easier access and egress
and a decent number of restrooms for women and families. We're more
enlightened now than we were in 1912 in that regard.''
</P>
<P>
   But tears glinted in his eyes, and his voice cracked as
Harrington acknowledged ``very strong mixed emotions. Fenway is
special. I used to come here with my father, and I know what the
Red Sox can mean to the people of New England. And I know Fenway is
part of that.''
</P>
<P>
   For however long Fenway remains in existence, none can dispute
that it offers a unique baseball experience. Even the food
concessions are special, though you usually must stand in a lengthy
line to purchase the famous Legal Seafood clam chowder.
</P>
<P>
   While New York's Yankee Stadium is more majestic and Chicago's
Wrigley Field is better preserved, Fenway, tied with Tiger Stadium
as the oldest major-league park still in operation, may be the most
fun of baseball's shrines.
</P>
<P>
   Gushed veteran baseball writer and columnist Joe Falls of the
Detroit News: ``If I could have my choice of where I could die, it
would be in the press box at Fenway Park on a fresh afternoon in
June.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a month past the ideal time. But to many ardent baseball
fans, there's never a better place to die or live than Fenway Park
_ all the more precious with its own long life being threatened.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
