<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-11 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6140 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDIA-PAKISTAN-440&AMP;AD     07-11 1193
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIA-PAKISTAN-440&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIA AND PAKISTAN ANNOUNCE WITHDRAWAL OF FIGHTERS IN KASHMIR 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By BARRY BEARAK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISLAMABAD, Pakistan _ India and Pakistan said Sunday that rival
forces battling for the last two months over the icy ridges and
mountain tops of the Indian state of Kashmir would begin a phased
withdrawal, heralding an end to the latest confrontation between
the world's newest nuclear powers.
</P>
<P>
   The two nations, which have fought two wars over Kashmir since
winning independence from Britain in 1947, were very cautious with
their statements Sunday, carefully portraying any silencing of the
guns in terms of victory for their sides.
</P>
<P>
   The recent conflict has been depicted so differently in each
country that the citizens of one would barely recognize the war
that their counterparts have been following in the news.
</P>
<P>
   While the Pakistanis were terming the development something of a
gradual cease-fire between warring parties, the Indians explained
things more as the recognition of a fait accompli: Most of the
invaders into its territory had already been killed or thrown out.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, if the calm in the mountains holds _ and the
step-by-step process is continued _ it would bring to an end the
most serious tension between India and Pakistan in 30 years and to
the first major confrontation since the nations tested nuclear
weapons in May 1998.
</P>
<P>
   In a hastily called news conference Sunday night, Pakistan's
foreign minister, Sartaj Aziz, said that a ``disengagement'' was
underway from the fierce fighting, some of it hand-to-hand, that
has taken place in the strategic heights above a vital Indian
supply route.
</P>
<P>
   ``The director-generals of military operations of the two
nations met today and agreed on the modalities of de-escalation,
including sector-wise cessation of ground and air operations,''
Aziz said. ``We have been informed that disengagement in the Kaksar
sector, which began yesterday, has been proceeding satisfactorily.
The disengagement for the Mushkoh sector will begin tonight.
Gradually, the disengagement will be completed in the entire
area.''
</P>
<P>
   The move toward peace comes exactly a week after Prime Minister
Nawaz Sharif of Pakistan made a sudden trip to Washington and
promised President Clinton that he would take ``concrete steps'' to
end the crisis. He returned with a promise that the president would
take a ``personal interest'' in solving the 52-year-old dispute
over Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
   Although statements from both sides in recent days had hinted at
a shift away from diplomatic stalemate, neither India nor Pakistan
gave any account of what exactly had led to Sunday's meeting of
their senior military chiefs, and the plans for phased withdrawal.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   India's leaders have insisted that the militant Muslim invaders
in Kashmir were thick with Pakistani army regulars, and that the
infiltration was a long-planned Pakistani military operation. For
the Indians, then, what is taking place now is an anti-climactic
withdrawal of defeated remnants. They had already declared that 95
percent of the intruders had been driven out.
</P>
<P>
   There is ``some evidence of withdrawal,'' Brajesh Mishra,
India's national security advisor, said Sunday in New Delhi after a
meeting of the leaders of political parties was convened by Prime
Minister Atal Behari Vajpayee.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is our hope that in seven days, the status quo of the LOC
will be restored if it goes according to plan,'' he said, referring
to the 450-mile Line of Control that divides the Indian and
Pakistani-controlled parts of Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1947, when India and Pakistan were carved from the British
Empire, dominion over the storied Himalayan area of Kashmir has
been in dispute, and was the direct cause for two of the three wars
between the two nations.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, the Indian Maj. Gen. J.J. Singh said, ``A decisive
moment has now arrived for army operations to finish,'' adding
stiffly that the military will not halt its offensive until every
invader has been driven from the mountains.
</P>
<P>
   The matter of whether retreating soldiers would be allowed
``safe passage'' has been a contentious issue in India since the
tide began going its way on the battlefield.
</P>
<P>
   Mishra was not so tough-talking. When asked if the Indian army
was slowing its attack, he said, ``The Indian army has no tradition
of shooting at the backs of people.''
</P>
<P>
   In Islamabad, the attempt is to paint the latest turn as a
diplomatic achievement for Sharif and a military victory for the
Kashmiri mujahedeen, the Muslim guerrillas who the government says
have challenged the Indians with only moral support from Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past few weeks, the mujahedeen action has been
gloriously successful as the just and legitimate cause of Kashmir
has engaged the international community's undivided attention
throughout the period,'' Aziz said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the focus must now ``shift to the expeditious solution
of the Kashmir dispute, so that 1 billion people who inhabit South
Asia can lead a life of peace and engage in the endeavors for
economic development and presperity.''
</P>
<P>
   Brig. Rashid Qureshi, Pakistan's top military spokesman, sat
beside Aziz at the news conference and boasted repeatedly of how
the mujahedeen had gotten the best of the Indian army.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians ``have been talking about spectacular victories
without having lost any casualties,'' he said. ``That has been done
to uplift their sagging morale because they have suffered
tremendous casualties.''
</P>
<P>
   But such consistent praise for the mujahedeen's battlefield
successes has created a problem for Sharif, whose trip to the
United States was seen by many here as a ``sell out'' of the
freedom fighters who, from most Pakistani accounts, have been
heroically prevailing in a holy war.
</P>
<P>
   In denying that any of the invaders are Pakistani soldiers _
something that many Western observers have openly called
disingenuous _ the prime minister is now left to answer this
troubling question: Who is it that is ``disengaging'' from the
mountains, since the mujahedeen have in that last few days
proclaimed that they will hold out till their last breath?
</P>
<P>
   Such stirring defiance was reaffirmed earlier Sunday by the
United Jihad Council, an umbrella group of Kashmiri mujahedeen
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   After Aziz's news conference, however, the council made no
immediate comment.
</P>
<P>
   Sharif is scheduled to address the nation Monday night, when he
is likely to reiterate earlier assertions that he in fact does have
the mujahedeen's support for a strategic withdrawal _ and that he
has convinced them that they have little more to gain from
remaining in their bunkers in the wind-swept mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Qureshi said Sunday night that he had no information about where
the mujahedeen would now go, but he said he was sure they would be
able to disperse without the Indians doing them harm and move on to
continue their holy war elsewhere in Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
   ``One must understand that the mujahedeen are fully capable of
taking care of themselves,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-11-99 2011EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
