<HEADLINE>
50 YEARS AGO, VAN BROCKLIN LEFT COLLEGE FOR RAMS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ As the year 2000 approaches, here's a look at some
of the interesting anniversaries that will occur this week in Los
Angeles sports history:
</P>
<P>
   July 12, 1912: Fred Kelly becomes the first USC athlete to win
an Olympic gold medal, taking the 110-meter hurdles at the
Stockholm Games.
</P>
<P>
   July 12, 1949: University of Oregon quarterback Norm Van
Brocklin decides against another year of college and signs a pro
contract with the Los Angeles Rams.
</P>
<P>
   July 13, 1972: The Los Angeles Rams acquire a new owner _ in a
trade. Robert Irsay pays $19 million to the estate of Dan Reeves to
take over the Rams, then transfers ownership to Carroll Rosenbloom.
In exchange, Rosenbloom gives Irsay his Baltimore Colts.
</P>
<P>
   July 14, 1951: Citation, the 1948 Triple Crown winner, takes the
Hollywood Gold Cup and becomes the first horse to earn $1 million
in career winnings. The colt was retired after the race.
</P>
<P>
   July 14, 1995: The Dodgers' Ramon Martinez throws a no-hitter
against the Florida Marlins. In the 7-0 win, Martinez's only
baserunner allowed is via a walk in the eighth inning.
</P>
<P>
   July 15, 1973: The Angels' Nolan Ryan throws his second career
no-hitter and second of the season in a 6-0 win at Detroit. The
highlight: Tigers star Norm Cash comes to the plate in the bottom
of the ninth with the leg of a piano as a bat.
</P>
<P>
   July 18, 1996: Shaquille O'Neal becomes a Laker, signing a
seven-year, $120 million contract as a free agent, leaving the
Orlando Magic.
</P>
<P>
   Birthdays: Today: Former USC and Dodgers first baseman Ron
Fairly (61) and former USC football standout Charlie Weaver (50).
Tuesday: Former Lakers guard and current colorman Stu Lantz (53).
Wednesday: Former Los Angeles Rams great Rosey Grier (67) and
former Kings coach Barry Melrose (43). Saturday: Former Lakers
forward Connie Hawkins (57).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
