<HEADLINE>
THIS WEEK'S TV HIGHLIGHTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
TODAY: Mike Piazza isn't afraid of big green monsters. It's all
about taking hacks off a BP thrower and messing his swing up by
trying to hit the ball over three state lines. That's why he has
again shied away from participating in the annual home run derby
and will join ESPN's coverage team instead. With a bat or a mike,
he's gonna embarrass himself. Home Run Derby from Boston's Fenway
Park, ESPN, 5 p.m.  
TUESDAY: Fox's All-Star Game producer Michael Weisman justifies
this year's increases in staff (three broadcasters in the booth and
three reporters in the stands) and equipment (20 cameras, 15 replay
machines and 60 microphones positioned around the field). ``This
will be one of the greatest assemblages of baseball talents at one
time in the history of the All-Star Game,'' Weisman said. ``There
will never be a moment like this again. Think about it. There will
be 50 of the greatest legends walking to home plate from center
field. Then there will be the current All-Stars. They will be
followed by Ted Williams, coming in a golf cart from center field,
throwing out the first pitch to none other than Carlton Fisk. We're
talking goose bumps here. It will be the field of dreams.'' Oh, and
then the game starts. Major League Baseball All-Star Game from
Boston's Fenway Park, Channel 11, 5 p.m.  
WEDNESDAY: A little presumptuous, don't you think? WNBA All-Star
Game from New York's Madison Square Garden, ESPN, 4:30 p.m.  
THURSDAY: By pitting them against each other, baseball has managed
to prevent both the Dodgers and Angels from getting off to rousing
starts in the second half of the season. Dodgers at Angels, Fox
Sports West, 7 p.m. (KTLA Channel 5 has Friday's game at 7 p.m. and
Fox Channel 11 has Saturday's game at 1:05 p.m.)  
FRIDAY: The Davis Cup began 99 years ago at the Longwood Cricket
Club in Brookline, Mass., and that's where Pete Sampras comes back
to help the U.S. team take on Australia in 1999. Davis Cup: U.S.
vs. Australia, ESPN, 11 a.m. and ESPN2, 1 p.m.  
SATURDAY: The first rule for a city hosting a league's all-star
game should be to have a team that plays in that league. Which is
why soccer makes no sense. Major Soccer League All-Star Game from
San Diego, Channel 7, 12:30 p.m. (ESPN2 has the MSL Skills
Competition, Friday at 9 p.m.)  
SUNDAY: Sixteen years ago, Tom Watson defended his British Open
title. It hasn't happened since. That turned out to be Watson's
last major championship, by the way. Mark O'Meara (pictured) isn't
likely to make a successful defense _ or win another major, either.
The 42-year-old has been too busy flying around the world and
cashing in on his unbelievable '98 season, when he also won the
Masters. In majors this year, O'Meara was 31st at the Masters and
missed the cut at the U.S. Open. British Open final round, Channel
7, 8 a.m. (ABC has third-round coverage Saturday at 8 a.m.; ESPN
has first- and second-round coverage Thursday and Friday at 6 a.m.)
<TEXT>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
