u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTES12-CO     07-11 0722
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTES12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Smoltz to give elbow first test in AA game
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ John Smoltz is planning to test his inflamed elbow
Thursday in Jacksonville by pitching an inning for the Class AA
Greenville Braves. It will be the first time he's pitched in 10
days since going back on the disabled list for the second time this
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just to get back in it and see how my elbow is,'' Smoltz
said. ``I can't find that out in a side session. ... I can throw in
a side session and not feel any pain. When I fire up in a game,
that's different. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``What Jacksonville is going to be is a steppingstone to say
`proceed' or `retreat.'''
</P>
<P>
   If it's to retreat, Smoltz will shut the elbow back down for an
undetermined amount of time. If it's to proceed, he plans to pitch
another couple innings with Greenville, rejoin the Atlanta Braves
in Florida on July 21 and 22 and work his way back into the
rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, his main goal is to be ready at the end of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to pitch three or four games for the sake of
pitching,'' Smoltz said. ``Obviously, I'd like to contribute, but
at the same time the contributions I want to make are at the end of
the year.''
</P>
<P>
   Bombs away
</P>
<P>
   Ryan Klesko came up with two more home runs Sunday to bring his
season total to 13, which is fourth on the team behind Chipper
Jones (21), Brian Jordan (17) and Andruw Jones (16). To go along
with that is a .303 batting average, third-highest on the club.
</P>
<P>
   One key to having both of those elements working for him is
consistently using a more controlled swing at the plate, something
hitting coach Don Baylor has stressed to him this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a more experienced hitter,'' Klesko said. ``I'm not
swinging all crazy. I go up there and if I get extended it's going
to go out of the park anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Plans for Lopez
</P>
<P>
   For now, manager Bobby Cox said he's planning to use Javy Lopez
as a designated hitter when he's activated Thursday in New York for
the series against the Yankees. After that first game, he might
decide to catch him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't mind taking six days off and DH,'' Lopez said,
referring to the three games in New York and three in Toronto.
``Another week is less pressure for my knee, but it's whatever they
want me to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Lopez continued his comeback from a sprained knee Sunday by
running the bases, doing some sprints and practicing a slide in the
outfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``Especially with the brace, everything I do, I don't feel it,''
Lopez said.
</P>
<P>
   A start for Hunter
</P>
<P>
   Brian Hunter got the start at first base Sunday against
right-hander Jin Ho Cho just so he could get some more at-bats
before the All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   Hunter had started only once since June 16, when he sprained an
ankle in Houston. Outside of his start July 3 in New York, Hunter
had only eight at-bats until Sunday and was hitless in them. He
went 0-for-3 with a walk Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't try to put too much into every at-bat. Just try to
be comfortable, try to relax,'' Hunter said. ``It's hard to do,
seeing as how you don't play much.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunter said his sore ankle bothers him more when he pinch hits,
so he's been running in the dugout tunnel every couple innings in
games when he might pinch hit. He said the ankle is much improved
in that past two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Post All-Star rotation
</P>
<P>
   Cox said he's planning to start the rotation over when the
Braves resume their season Thursday against the Yankees in New
York, with Tom Glavine starting Thursday, Greg Maddux on Friday and
Kevin Millwood on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   McGlinchy a spectator
</P>
<P>
   During his trip home to Boston over the All-Star break, rookie
reliever Kevin McGlinchy figured he'd take in the All-Star Game at
Fenway. He has four tickets in the bleacher seats and plans to take
a former high school coach and a couple buddies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured it'd be a good time to see it at Fenway, since it'll
probably be the last All-Star Game there,'' said McGlinchy, who's
from the Boston suburb of Malden.
</P>
<P>
   He might check out the home run derby tonight as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather see that than the game,'' McGlinchy said. ``I've
seen a lot of baseball. I'm pretty tired of it.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
