</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-LOUDON12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Burton: From 38 to first in a Jiffy
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUDON, N.H. _ With about 10 laps remaining in Sunday's Jiffy
Lube 300 at New Hampshire International Speedway, NASCAR rookie
Tony Stewart asked crew chief Greg Zipadelli how big his lead was
on the second-place car of John Andretti.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to know how much so I can ease up,'' Stewart said over
the radio in his No. 20 Pontiac.
</P>
<P>
   ``Almost a straightaway,'' Zipadelli said. ``He's doing the same
thing we're doing, so go nice and easy. Just float it in and go
easy on the gas.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, looking for his first Winston Cup victory in only his
18th start, was concerned because he didn't make a pit stop in the
final 105 laps of the 300-lap event.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the 43 teams in Sunday's race calculated that a full,
22-gallon tank of gas would last about 95 laps on the flat,
1.058-mile oval. But Stewart's team gambled that their fuel would
last longer.
</P>
<P>
   So did Andretti, who also made his final pit stop on lap 196.
But Jeff Burton, who was running third, took a late splash of gas,
making a 2.6-second pit stop with only 11 laps remaining.
</P>
<P>
   As Stewart slowed in the final laps to conserve what little fuel
remained, his lead slowly diminished. As Andretti and Burton got
closer, Stewart's fuel tank got emptier.
</P>
<P>
   And, with less than three laps left, Stewart barked the words
Zipadelli didn't want to hear: ``We're out of gas.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart's car stalled on the back straightaway, and then
Andretti's No. 43 Pontiac ran out of gas only seconds later.
</P>
<P>
   That opened the door for Burton, who started 38th but won the
July race in New Hampshire for the third year in a row. It was the
biggest comeback victory in a Winston Cup race since Bill Elliott
started 38th and won the Firecracker 400 at Daytona International
Speedway in July 1988.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel bad for those guys because it's a bad way to lose a
race,'' Burton said. ``But I knew how far the car would run on the
amount of gas, so I knew that we had to pit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had some fortune at the end, obviously, with the No. 20 car
running out of gas. But after starting 38th and making all those
big changes to the car, you're just looking to put yourself in a
position to win and we did that.''
</P>
<P>
   Ninth-year driver Kenny Wallace finished second for the first
time in 169 career starts. Two-time defending Winston Cup champion
Jeff Gordon was third, followed by points leader Dale Jarrett and
Elliott. Stewart, who led 103 of the final 105 laps, finished 10th.
Andretti fell to 18th.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went for it and, obviously, we went with the wrong
decision,'' Zipadelli said. ``We thought we'd be about half of a
lap short on fuel, and we were short a little more than that. I
guess we could have pitted for gas, but it's easy to look back and
say what's right and what's wrong. We'll just have to live with
this and move on.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, 28, stormed out of his car after the race, and quickly
changed clothes in his hauler. The former Indy League Racing
champion left the speedway with his fiance, Krista Dwyer, without
answering reporters' questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't even bother with it right now,'' Stewart said. ``I don't
want to talk about it. I'll talk about it next week.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Washington Redskins coach Joe Gibbs, who owns Stewart's
car, said Zipadelli made the decision not to make a pit stop.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Stewart) wants to win as badly as everybody else and he wants
to win every race,'' Gibbs said. ``I think he would have had the
same vote and he wanted to try and go for it. We all did.''
Apparently, Stewart took out his frustration before leaving the
track. His car was damaged in the rear after he apparently scuffed
Ernie Irvan's No. 36 Pontiac in turn 2 of the final lap.
</P>
<P>
   ``He must have been mad at me for something,'' Irvan said. ``He
hit me in the back and he hit me in the side, so I hit him back. I
guess he ran out of gas and was mad at me because I didn't get his
car full.''
</P>
<P>
   With his fourth victory of the season, Burton moved into second
place in the points standings, trailing Jarrett by 240. Burton
moved past Mark Martin, who finished sixth, and Bobby Labonte, who
finished a season-worst 38th after wrecking on lap 204.
</P>
<P>
   Burton says he isn't worried about the belief that Stewart lost
the race, rather than him winning it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care one bit,'' Burton said. ``It doesn't matter to
me. We got that trophy and we got those points. I don't care how we
did it. You win a lot of races different ways, and to win races
you've gotta put yourself in position. We put ourselves in position
and did a better job than they did.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
