<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-NOTES12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Unfriendly day of racing has drivers fuming, feuding
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUDON, N.H. _ Tempers on the track and in the garage at New
Hampshire International Speedway on Sunday left little doubt that
NASCAR has reached the second half of its Winston Cup schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Ernie Irvan was mad at rookie Tony Stewart. Dale Jarrett and
Rusty Wallace were venting at Jeff Gordon. And Stewart seemed upset
with everyone.
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett, the Winston Cup points leader, lost third place in the
Jiffy Lube 300 to Gordon, whose No. 24 Chevy made contact with
Jarrett's No. 88 Ford as both cars left turn four on the final lap.
</P>
<P>
   When the drivers left their cars in the garage, Gordon and
Jarrett screamed at each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``You came down into the grass and then across in front of me,''
Gordon said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hit me three times,'' Jarrett replied. ``You're taking up
the race track.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, Jarrett didn't seem too amused with Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a little rubbing coming in,'' Jarrett said. ``Gordon
caught me at the end. He hit me once down turns one and two, and
then I blocked him down the backstretch. Then he ran in the back of
me, not once, but three times in turns three and four. We have a
lot of racing to do. We'll see each other again.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon and his crew chief, Ray Evernham, were admonished by
NASCAR officials after the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a slick, one-groove race track, tough to pass and the
tires were really old,'' Gordon said. ``We came down the last lap
and we were slipping and sliding around. I felt like I got at least
a wheel inside D.J., down the back straightaway.
</P>
<P>
   ``He crowded me quite a bit. I got in the back of him in turn
three and finished third. There's nobody I want to race any cleaner
than D.J., but I think the heat of the moment kind of got to both
of us. We'll patch things up. Me and D.J. are fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett wasn't the only driver upset with Gordon. On lap 141,
Wallace's No. 2 Ford appeared to hit Gordon's car between turns
three and four. Wallace's car made a 180-degree turn and hit the
outside wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``We both went down into the turn; he was on the apron and I was
on the race track,'' Wallace said. ``He stayed on the apron and
when I came off of turn four, he just got into my quarter-panel and
that was it. I just wish he could have been a little more
patient.''
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt Jr.'s short day
</P>
<P>
   Dale Earnhardt Jr., making his second Winston Cup start,
finished last after completing only 44 laps because of mechanical
failure. Earnhardt Jr., who chipped his right shoulder during an
accident in a Busch Grand National race last week, was running in
the top 15 before leaving the track. Awesome again
</P>
<P>
   Bill Elliott calculated his fuel mileage correctly, and finished
fifth, snapping a drought of 55 races without a top-five. He
started 43rd after wrecking his primary car on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm tickled considering how we started the weekend,'' Elliott
said. ``The fuel mileage was key. The car was not good in the
beginning, but we kept on making the right adjustments and it sure
paid off.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Elliott's best finish since he was fifth at Martinsville,
Va., on Sept. 29, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Endurance
</P>
<P>
   Mark Martin, who underwent arthroscopic knee surgery on
Wednesday, finished sixth and moved past Bobby Labonte in the
points standings to third. Martin completed all 300 laps, despite
having Busch driver Matt Kenseth standing by as a relief driver.
</P>
<P>
   ``I called him the other day and, no kidding, he had his leg in
the MRI tube and he was talking on the phone about race cars,''
Kenseth said of Martin. ``That's the truth. That's the way he is.
He's tough. He's real tough.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
