<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-11 20:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6156 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-BROPEN-GARCIA12-C     07-11 0959
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BROPEN-GARCIA12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Spain's Sergio Garcia: An eye on the Tiger
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARNOUSTIE, Scotland _ Maybe we should all forget about this
forced, fairly fabricated ``rivalry'' between Tiger Woods and David
Duval and ponder the bigger, more global picture. The true rivalry
for the next millennium might have germinated nine days ago, when
Woods won at the Western Open and Spanish teenager Sergio Garcia
scored his first European Tour victory at the Irish Open.
</P>
<P>
   Forget about waiting for the staged, 18-hole, made-for-TV
exhibition next month between Woods and Duval. What will be
settled, the International Management Group Cup? The tastier
confrontation could be happening, beginning with this week's
British Open, on every occasion when Woods and Garcia peg it up in
the same major championship. And you can sit back and relax. There
are probably about 100 of them remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Could Garcia come to Carnoustie and his third British Open,
though only 19, as a hotter property? Hardly. With a pro debut
flurry reminiscent of Woods' 1996 start that produced two quick PGA
Tour victories, Garcia won in Ireland than almost won Loch Lomond
after an opening 62.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, the comparison with Tiger, being called Europe's Tiger
Woods, does not bother me,'' says the youngster known as ``El
Nino'' (The Kid). ``I have always said that if you are compared to
other players, that means I have done something good. ... But I
don't want to read in the newspapers that `The European Tiger Woods
Wins Irish Open.' I want to read that Sergio Garcia wins it. I want
to be recognized as Sergio Garcia.''
</P>
<P>
   No problem there. Leaving the scoring tent at Loch Lomond, he
found his toughest obstacle all day, a unyielding herd of kids
perhaps just a few years younger. Mothers and daughters scurried to
pose with Sergio and he gladly obliged with outstretched arms. He
not only has all the shots, he has all the charm and composure _
things that it took Woods a few years to discover.
</P>
<P>
   He is a lock for the European Ryder Cup team, moving to seventh
after a tie for second at Loch Lomond. He's one of the favorites
here, although he never has played the treacherous course. He'll
play a practice round today with countryman Jose Maria Olazabal,
his likely partner in September at Brookline. Just to keep him
further informed, Garcia employs the man who caddied for Mark
O'Meara last year at Royal Birkdale, Jerry Higginbotham.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard it's the probably the most difficult golf course in
the world,'' Garcia said, ``but I will have the mentality that pars
are going to be good. If I make a lot of pars and some birdies and
try not to make too many mistakes, I will be up there. I'll try to
shoot as low as I can and see if I have a chance to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody would be surprised if Garcia, who broke 80 at the age of
10 and became a scratch player at 13, contended this week. As a
16-year-old, he competed in the British Open at Royal Lytham in
1996, missing the cut, then tied for 28th last year at Royal
Birkdale. Garcia finished third in his first PGA Tour event, the
Byron Nelson Classic in May. Both the U.S. and European Tours will
be tugging at him to make a full-time commitment for 2000,
regardless what this week brings. He will play in the U.S. next
month in the PGA Championship and the Sprint International.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't seem to have a nerve in his body,'' said Mark
James, the Ryder Cup captain. ``A lot of guys look amateur when
they turn pro, but he doesn't.''
</P>
<P>
   The headlines out of Ireland declared: ``El Nino Storm Warning
... El Nino Cloud Nine-O.'' For once around here, they weren't
exaggerations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody had been looking for these young guns for such a
long time and nothing really happened,'' said Sweden's Jesper
Parnevik. ``Then Tiger came along and he just blew everybody's mind
the way he played when he turned professional. Now Sergio has the
same mindset that he was going to come out and beat everyone. He is
proving that he has the ability to do it. He just doesn't hit any
bad shots.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Scotland's Colin Montgomerie zinged Garcia a bit for
some tabloid-inspired brashness last week, when Garcia was quoted
as saying his 62 could have been a 59, the veteran is most
impressed. Then again, why not? If you combined the fire and
short-game creativity of Olazabal and Seve Ballesteros and tossed
in monster length and pinpoint irons, this is the package Garcia
carries around the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every so often a player like this comes along,'' Montgomerie
said, ``and we are lucky on this occasion that he's European.''
</P>
<P>
   The success has not come without explanation. Garcia played in
nearly 30 pro tournaments as an amateur.
</P>
<P>
   ``He seemed to be brought up and bred for golf like Tiger Woods
was,'' observed Georgia Tech's Matt Kuchar, whose defense at last
year's U.S. Amateur was ended by Garcia in the quarterfinals. ``I
think he was taught what to expect. I don't think Justin Rose and I
had that preparation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a lot of fight in him,'' Woods said. ``I pride myself
in that I never gave up on the golf course and he's the same. He's
more prepared at a younger age than I was.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods, if you recall, took a few years to realize that not every
green is to be approached from high rough. Garcia's already
demonstrates a mature, major championship mindset. He is excited
about executing the low, bump-and-run shots of links golf, and
merely to be here.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I can win or finish second or third or whatever I do, the
British Open is just like a big present for me,'' he said. ``I'm
just glad I got in without having to qualify.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
