<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-11 20:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6160 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-WCUP-1000&AMP;ADD-NYT     07-11 1333
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WCUP-1000&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD CUP WINNERS NOW FACE UNCERTAIN FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Having won the Women's World Cup, the U.S.
soccer team paraded around Disneyland Sunday morning and then
headed East for a blizzard of morning television shows and magazine
covers. An international tour is being planned for later this year,
and the team is expected to remain largely intact for the 2000
Summer Olympics in Sydney, Australia. Beyond that, the financial
and professional future of the players remains uncertain as the
euphoria from Saturday's victory wears off like a champagne
hangover.
</P>
<P>
   While the World Cup was a galvanizing event for three weeks,
like the Olympics it figures to be as disposable as it was
riveting. There is no women's professional league to sustain
interest, although the feasibility of one is being studied with a
target date of 2001. Even as they celebrated Saturday's tense,
penalty-kick victory over China, organizers were quick to say that
no one should expect 90,000 fans in the Rose Bowl any time soon,
unless it happens to be college football season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NFL had its breakthrough in the Colts-Giants championship
game in 1958, but by that time the league was more than 30 years
old,'' said Alan Rothenberg, chairman of the board of directors for
the 1999 Women's World Cup. ``These things don't happen overnight.
It's a long, slow build to get there.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, however, as it set attendance records and brought
unprecedented interest to the sport, the Women's World Cup was a
landmark event. Saturday's final was the most-watched soccer game
in this country, drawing an estimated 40 million viewers on ABC.
More than 650,000 tickets were sold for the World Cup, making it
the largest sporting event ever held for women.
</P>
<P>
   Not since the men's hockey team won the 1980 Winter Olympics has
a U.S. team so enamored the American public, said Marla Messing,
the president of the Women's World Cup organizing committee.
Breakthroughs were achieved in inspiring young girls and boys, in
shattering the myth that spectators would not pay to see women's
sports and in rebuffing any lingering belief that women do not play
as fiercely and entertainingly as men.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're on the cutting edge of one of the most
significant cultural revolutions in the world,'' said Hank
Steinbrecher, the executive director of the U.S. Soccer Federation.
``It states that in team sports, women are full partners of men,
not subordinates.'' He added: ``Ten to 20 years from now, those
young girls watching will be playing.''
</P>
<P>
   The most urgent concern for the American women, aside from
preparing for the 2000 Olympics, is establishing a professional
league to extend their careers and secure their place atop the
sport. The United States got a jump on the world in women's soccer
with a lack of cultural restraints and a well-organized grass-roots
system, but the rest of the world is catching up.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we want to remain among the best teams in the world, we
need a league,'' coach Tony DiCicco said.
</P>
<P>
   Rothenberg said that a women's league seemed inevitable as early
as 2001, but what form it would take is anyone's guess. Even after
the success of this Women's World Cup, much skepticism remains
about the viability of a women's league. Keith Cooper, a spokesman
for FIFA, soccer's world governing body, cautioned that there were
only about 30 superstars in the women's game worldwide, which would
leave only three per team in a 10-team league.
</P>
<P>
   One of the women's professional basketball leagues folded last
December, and the surviving Women's National Basketball Association
is being bankrolled by the deep pockets of the NBA. Major League
Soccer is struggling to keep itself alive as a men's professional
league and does not appear capable of sustaining a women's league.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a big difference between the shop-window effect of a
World Cup and a week-to-week league,'' Cooper said.
</P>
<P>
   Soccer officials and sports marketing experts said they believed
a women's league might survive for several reasons. Unlike MLS, a
women's league could attract the best players in the world.
Advertisers are looking to expand their limited choices in women's
sports. And families seeking moderately priced entertainment might
be attracted to a game that both their sons and daughters play.
</P>
<P>
   The suburban, college-educated, mostly white, ponytailed
American team ``is the demographic of the American public,'' said
Allan Brown, the chief executive of Simon Marketing of Los Angeles,
which does promotional work for McDonald's, a Women's World Cup
sponsor. ``I've been in sports marketing 25 years, and this is the
most refreshing group of athletes. They show a lot of gratitude for
what they've accomplished.''
</P>
<P>
   George Taylor, the president of Sports Mondial Inc., a New
York-based sports marketing firm, said he believed a women's league
could survive if it were placed in small stadiums, because empty
seats ``say to the viewers that this is not big time, and when it
is not considered big time, it's over.''
</P>
<P>
   The American women are expected to begin training again in
August, with a tournament scheduled in the Midwest in early
October. Later matches are being planned in South Africa and Egypt
as the Americans seek to export their skills and their message of
gender equity. The players' contracts with the soccer federation
expire in August, however, and renewal could prove thorny, given
that salaries average $25,000 to $40,000 a year _ meager by men's
standards.
</P>
<P>
   The 20 American players are scheduled to receive paltry World
Cup bonuses of $12,500 apiece even though they comprised the most
watched team in the history of women's sports, and they are
expected to provide a profit of $1 million to $4 million to World
Cup organizers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm thrilled about what they've done, but it drives me crazy
how much these women are getting paid,'' said Billie Jean King, the
tennis great and activist for women's sports. ``It reminds me of
tennis in the '60s and early '70s. One or two were making decent
money, but no one else was. That's not good enough.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Robert Contigulia, president of the national soccer federation,
said that additional bonuses were being considered for the women's
team. Perhaps the federation will draw on the $60 million legacy
from the 1994 men's World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're at the top of the list of women's professional team
sports, but our job is to do better,'' Steinbrecher, the U.S.
Soccer Federation official, said. ``We intend to do that.'' He
added: ``This is lightning in a bottle. The queen mother doesn't
have enough money to pay them what they deserve.''
</P>
<P>
   Steinbrecher said the federation also had to seek more
involvement by black and Hispanic players.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about giving kids choices,'' said goalkeeper Briana
Scurry, one of two blacks on the team. ``You've got to go in the
inner city, where the African-American and Hispanic athletes are.
Then you'll have a better depiction of the country as a whole at
some point.''
</P>
<P>
   Players and team officials said they expected DiCicco and
Michelle Akers, the defensive midfielder, to return for the Olympic
season. Despite suffering from chronic fatigue syndrome, Akers
demonstrated during the World Cup that she, not Mia Hamm, was
perhaps the most vital component of the American team and was
deserving of the label of world's best player.
</P>
<P>
   But that was a matter to debate at another time. Sunday was a
day of celebration at Disneyland, the players realizing that what
they had done was no Mickey Mouse accomplishment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope this gives people the courage to put on other big
events,'' said Julie Foudy, the American co-captain. ``We've always
watched men do great things in front of crowds. After watching
women do great things in front of crowds, I'm looking forward to
seeing the repercussions.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
