<HEADER>
A6163 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BRAVES-REDS12-COX     07-11 0460
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-REDS12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves stomp Reds 8-1
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ That the Braves beat the Boston Red Sox 8-1 Sunday
afternoon was gravy.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves sealed the first-half deal with back-to-back stellar
outings by Tom Glavine and Greg Maddux to give the team eight wins
in the past 11 games. They're sitting at 55-34 at the All-Star
break, tops in the National League and not far off last year's
59-29, which came with two fewer serious injuries to combat.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ended the first half on a real positive note with a great
team win,'' Chipper Jones said. ``We executed everything
possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Ending a season series that had been pretty tense thus far, the
Braves managed to run with this one without much ado. Maddux rolled
to his 10th win, Ryan Klesko hit two home runs to give him 13 for
the season, and Walt Weiss got it all started with a couple of hits
and a couple of runs his first two times up.
</P>
<P>
   Weiss drove in a run, then scored his second on Jones' second
sacrifice fly to put the Braves up 3-1 on Korean rookie pitcher Jin
Ho Cho in the third inning. With the way Maddux pitched, that lead
was plenty.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux pitched eight innings and allowed only a run after Darren
Lewis singled to lead off the game. Maddux cruised into the break
with his fourth win in a row, five in his past six starts, to boost
his record to 10-5 at the break and lower his ERA from 4.64 to 3.40
in the process.
</P>
<P>
   ``Inconsistent, but I survived pretty much,'' said Maddux of his
first half.
</P>
<P>
   He's allowed only four earned runs in his last 41 2/3 innings
for an ERA of 0.80 over that span. One big difference catcher Eddie
Perez has seen is in Maddux's change-up, ever since Maddux told
Perez he was going to focus on the quality of that pitch and its
downward break instead of trying to pinpoint it on the corners.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're not doing things properly you have to start from
scratch,'' Maddux said. ``Trying to locate a change-up is one of
the hardest things to do; you have to be really locked in. It's
just as effective down in the middle of the plate sometimes as one
up on the corner.''
</P>
<P>
   But still Maddux says his run of success is mostly about
locating his fastball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything else works off that,'' Maddux said.
</P>
<P>
   His win backing up to Glavine's nine-inning performance in the
Braves 2-1 victory on Saturday has the Braves looking an awful lot
like the Braves at the break.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the way Glavine pitched (Saturday) and Maddux pitched
today, our starting pitching is probably as strong as it's been all
season,'' manager Bobby Cox said. ``Looks like our starters are
going to be fine.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
