</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-YANKS-METS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRABU COMES THROUGH AS YANKS AVOID SWEEP BY METS  
</HEADLINE>
 (rk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Hideki Irabu was exiled to the bullpen at the start
of this season, branded as the ``fat toad'' by New York Yankees
owner, George Steinbrenner, and he wondered if he would ever fit in
with teammates who did not share a language with him.
</P>
<P>
   Fast forward three months to Sunday. Now a vital contributor to
the Yankees' pitching staff, Irabu pitched and grittily prevailed
in the most crucial game of his three-season tenure in pinstripes,
beating the New York Mets, 6-3, and preventing his team from
getting swept in a series closely watched by the city _ and, of
course, by Steinbrenner.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees, who had five runs batted in from left fielders
Ricky Ledee and Chad Curtis Sunday, went into the three-day
All-Star break with a 52-34 record, four games ahead of Boston in
the American League East, and on a pace to win 98 games. The Mets
are 50-39, five games behind the Atlanta Braves in the National
League East.
</P>
<P>
   Fans of both teams need a breather, too, after three days of
suspenseful baseball played to sellout crowds. Shea Stadium housed
53,869 Sunday, and the three-day total of 161,481 was the largest
in club history. By beating the Mets Sunday, the Yankees managed to
split the six games between the teams this year.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Piazza, who slammed memorable three-run home runs Friday
and Saturday, scoffed at the idea that six games between the Mets
and Yankees were too much. Maybe, Piazza said, there should be
more.
</P>
<P>
   A substantial portion of the Yankees' family would disagree, for
many within the organization _ players and staff _ believe they
have little to gain. They are expected to win, and if they lose,
well, then there is always the possibility Steinbrenner will react.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees called up talented left-hander Ed Yarnall Sunday and
sent Todd Erdos to Triple A Columbus, and nobody could really
figure out why, because Yarnall is a starter and the Yankees needed
a reliever. ``This was thrown at us by the organization,'' said
manager Joe Torre. ``He's been throwing lights out and we
anticipated seeing him, but yesterday after the game, we got the
call.''
</P>
<P>
   The move smacked of Steinbrenner backlash. The Yankees were all
aware of the stakes going into Sunday's game, when Irabu pitched to
avoid the sweep.
</P>
<P>
   Irabu (6-3) pitched the first inning somewhat unsure how good
his stuff was, or how he was going to beat the Mets. He has been
using his curveball to get ahead in the count, but Sunday, he
wasn't able to throw his curve for a strike until the end of the
second inning. And he was seeing some very strange readings from
the Shea Stadium radar on his fastball.
</P>
<P>
   When Irabu pitches in parks where the radar results are posted,
as they are in Shea Stadium, he will sometimes glance to see how
hard he is throwing, to gauge how he should use his fastball. If
he's throwing 94-95 mph, then he can feel free to attack. If he is
throwing 89-91 mph _ and that's about as low as Irabu throws his
fastball _ then he'll adjust accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   Irabu's fastball was popping in the first inning, registering
90-93 mph on other radar guns located in the section behind home
plate. But the readings shown at Shea were much worse: 86 mph
sometimes 87 mph, and there were those among the Yankees who
wondered if the low numbers were posted to play a head game with
Irabu.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was throwing as hard as I could,'' said Irabu, grinning,
``and I looked up there and saw 85 mph, and I said, `You've got to
be kidding me. I might as well give up on the fastball.'''
</P>
<P>
   Irabu labored early, and after the Mets scored a pair of runs in
the third, he had thrown 64 pitches. Ledee hammered his three-run
homer off Orel Hershiser in the fourth, giving the Yankees a 3-2
edge, but Irabu quickly pitched into another mess in the bottom
half of the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Cedeno singled to lead off, stole second and raced home
when Rey Ordonez doubled into the gap in left-center. Orel
Hershiser attempted a sacrifice bunt, but when Tino Martinez made a
poor choice and tried to throw out Ordonez at third,
unsuccessfully, Irabu and the Yankees were in deep. The score was
tied, Irabu already had thrown 80 pitches and there were two
runners on and nobody out. ``I just didn't want that situation to
get any worse,'' said Irabu.
</P>
<P>
   Pitching to Rickey Henderson, Irabu twice threw his curve in the
dirt, and both times catcher Jorge Posada blocked the ball and kept
the runners in place. Then Irabu struck out Henderson with a
fastball inside, 94 mph. One out.
</P>
<P>
   Edgardo Alfonzo followed, and with his first pitch, Irabu tried
a splitter _ low and in the dirt _ and Posada blocked this as well.
When a catcher saves a run like this, Joe Girardi noted later, it's
just as good as an RBI hit. Irabu threw a fastball away and Alfonzo
flied to short right, too shallow for Ordonez to score. Two outs.
</P>
<P>
   John Olerud, the Mets' lanky .300-hitter, was next, and in his
first two plate appearances, Irabu hadn't thrown him a strike and
Olerud walked twice. Trying to get ahead in the count, Irabu threw
a first-pitch fastball to Olerud, who almost never swings at the
first pitch and Olerud stroked a looping line drive to left.
</P>
<P>
   The second baseman, Chuck Knoblauch, was sure it was going to
drop, and so was David Cone and others watching from the Yankees'
bench. It was a bright day and the outfielders had been having a
hard time picking up the ball. But there was Ledee racing in,
running and running and reaching down and snaring the ball knee
high. The threat was over, Irabu had survived.
</P>
<P>
   But Hershiser (9-6) would not get through the fifth. O'Neill and
Bernie Williams singled, Tino Martinez walked to load the bases and
Scott Brosius singled in front of Cedeno, who appeared to lose
sight of the ball. O'Neill scored the tie-breaking run. After
left-hander Rigo Beltran relieved Hershiser, the
right-handed-hitting Curtis pinch-hit for Ledee and dumped a
two-run single to left. Yankees 6, Mets 3.
</P>
<P>
   Irabu pitched three more innings, throwing a total of 127
pitches _ more than in any start in his Yankees' career. ``He made
pretty good pitches the rest of the game,'' said the Mets manager
Bobby Valentine. ``The balls that we hit hard were not much to
speak of.''
</P>
<P>
   And thus, the Mets went into the All-Star break feeling good
about taking 2 of 3 from the Yankees for the first time, and the
Yankees felt good about getting through the weekend mostly intact.
``We can all sleep a little better,'' said O'Neill.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-11-99 2042EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
