<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-11 20:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6166 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-BERKOW-COLUMN-NYT     07-11 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-BERKOW-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: TWO SERIES AREN'T ENOUGH 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: The IRT, IND and BMT are abbreviations of former New York
City subway lines.) 
 (rk) 
 By IRA BERKOW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The town was clamorous in partisanship. Mike Piazza
recalled hearing it from both sides, even over the ritualistic
cacophony of sirens, horns and assorted denunciations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beat them Yanks!'' someone shouted to the New York Mets'
catcher on the street.
</P>
<P>
   A New York Yankees fan, somewhere else, put him on notice.
``We're gonna kick your butt!'' Piazza was informed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This series held so much emotion,'' said Piazza, who enjoyed
the series of his life for the Mets, ``especially for the middle of
the season. I've never felt this way before. And because of it,
because we'd gotten the short end of the stick in the past in this
series, you were made to feel like an outcast, like you were a bad
neighbor or something.''
</P>
<P>
   It seems New Yorkers haven't reviled one another so happily
since the Dodgers and Giants moved to the West Coast and desisted
from playing their version of the IRT, IND and BMT series with the
Pinstripers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Welcome,'' read the Shea Stadium message board in center field
before Sunday's game, ``to the Subway Series.'' And when the
lineups were announced, the 53,869 fans who squeezed into the
ballpark this sunny, breezy, gorgeous summer Sunday afternoon booed
and cheered as their partial Big Apple hearts dictated.
</P>
<P>
   This was the largest regular-season crowd at Shea Stadium since
1972, and the three-game attendance over the weekend of 160,740 _
each game a sellout _ was the greatest weekend box-office series in
Mets history, beating last year's three-game series against this
same cross-town rival by about 700 patrons.
</P>
<P>
   The same kind of tumult occurred at Yankee Stadium on the first
weekend of June when the two teams hooked up there. The Sunday
night game, on June 6, drew 56,294, the largest night crowd since
the Stadium was remodeled, in 1976. And the three-game attendance _
each game a sellout as well _ was 168,404, also a record for a
three-game series for the remodeled park.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees won 2 of 3 at the Stadium, exactly as they had in
1997, when interleague play was inaugurated, and again last season,
but the Mets won the first two games at Shea and were going for a
sweep.
</P>
<P>
   While the defending World Series champion Yankees were having
some problems, the mercurial Mets were on a hot streak, having
posted the best record in baseball, 23-10, since the ``Valentine's
Day Massacre,'' as some of the Mets call it, in which General
Manager Steve Phillips fired a few of manager Bobby Valentine's
coaches during a lackluster period.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza had been in the thick of things in the first two games at
Shea, having hit two homers _ the one on Saturday afternoon was
like a cannon shot and players were still talking about it a day
later _ and batting in seven runs, as well as throwing out three
baserunners. He is almost quietly becoming one of the great ball
players in New York history, and will soon be in Fenway Park, where
he will start his sixth straight All-Star Game. And he did what he
could to keep the sweet hopes of a sweep alive.
</P>
<P>
   He singled in the first inning to move a baserunner along with
two outs, but nothing else happened for the Mets. In the third,
with two outs and runners on first and third and the scored tied
0-0, he singled to center, driving in the lead run.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the joint was jumpin', though a considerable portion of
the mob, including one particular Yankee fan in the front row, the
city's first son, Andrew Giuliani, wearing a Tino Martinez T-shirt
(No. 24 on the back) in tribute to the Yankees first baseman, sat
on his hands, more or less like his dad, a lifelong Yankee fan.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees stormed back and took a lead that they would not
relinquish, as the Bronx boosters beat their palms and whooped
while the Flushing fans ground their teeth.
</P>
<P>
   In the fifth, Piazza, leading off, beat out a ground ball to
shortstop for his third straight hit of the game, and was stranded
there. He struck out in the seventh to end the inning and his day
at the plate, but the experience over all was one of exhilaration.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have to guard against,'' Piazza said, ``is a letdown
when we play Tampa Bay and Baltimore next week. Sure, we lost this
last game to the Yankees, but we played well. We have to keep this
excitement, this series in perspective. We have to remember,
there's still a lot of season left.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the series itself, and the positions taken by some that
it dilutes what might be a dream of a Subway World Series, or that
two series in one season between rival teams is redundant, Piazza
said: ``I think we've all heard the arguments, is it overkill, or
too many games. You look at this series and wonder if it's not
enough games. Maybe they should break up both leagues and put us in
the same division.''
</P>
<P>
   Interesting thought, but probably untenable. Even New Yorkers
might have a limit to unbridled passion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
