u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-JETS-BRAWL-NYT &LR;      07-11 0490
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-BRAWL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELLIOTT MAY FACE SUSPENSION FOR ARREST 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By GERALD ESKENAZI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Jets' Jumbo Elliott faces disciplinary action by
the National Football League _ perhaps including a suspension _
after what the police said was a brawl in a bar.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott, 34, the Jets' left tackle and a key member of the
offense that was the fourth-highest scoring in the NFL last season,
was arrested at Bogart's, a popular team hangout in Long Beach,
N.Y., about midnight Friday. Also arrested were his former teammate
Matt O'Dwyer, 26, and Jason Fabini, 24, the club's top rookie last
season.
</P>
<P>
   The players will be arraigned Monday morning in Long Beach.
O'Dwyer faces the most serious charges; the police said he kicked
out the window of a patrol car after he was placed inside, sending
glass flying into the faces of two police officers. According to
O'Dwyer's father, Gerald, his son was to have left Sunday for
Cincinnati and his new team, the Bengals.
</P>
<P>
   The league takes a serious view of off-the-field situations
involving alcohol, drugs or violence, and each incident requires
counseling and adherence to strict guidelines of conduct.
</P>
<P>
   Last September, Elliott pleaded guilty to driving while
impaired, and he was fined $350 and his driver's license was
suspended for 90 days. He also had to undergo counseling. Because
of that arrest, Elliott now faces more severe disciplinary action.
</P>
<P>
   The league also has a policy for dealing with charges of violent
crimes, whether or not the person is convicted. Once charged with a
violent crime, the player is subject to counseling as well as
disciplinary action by NFL Commissioner Paul Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   The police said that Elliott urinated in the wash basin in the
women's bathroom of the bar. Confronted by a patron in the
restroom, the police said the 6-foot-7-inch, 300-pound Elliott
punched her in the stomach. Returning to the restaurant, he then
hit a male patron, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott's charges included assault and public lewdness, while
O'Dwyer was charged with criminal mischief, among other charges.
Fabini was charged with disorderly conduct. All three posted cash
bail _ $100 for Fabini, $10,000 for Elliott and $50,000 for
O'Dwyer.
</P>
<P>
   Fabini recently returned from a panel in Washington that
counseled this season's rookie crop about what it is like in a
player's first year in pro football and what dangers to avoid.
</P>
<P>
   A league spokesman, Greg Aiello, had no comment Sunday. The Jets
did not return phone calls asking for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Jets Coach Bill Parcells had nothing to say publicly
about Elliott's arrest when it happened, but the coach has a
history of not allowing his players' off-the-field problems affect
their status on the team. His most troubled player was Lawrence
Taylor, who had many run-ins with the law while he played for _ and
Parcells coached _ the Giants. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
