</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-METS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FLAT NOTE FOLLOWS A HIGH ONE FOR METS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The All-Star break came a day too late for the New
York Mets.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of heading into the three-day respite on their highest
note of 1999, the Mets' final memory of the first-half of this
season will be of leaving runners at first and third with nobody
out in the fourth inning, after they had tied the score at 3-3.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets were shut out the rest of the way Sunday, while the New
York Yankees rallied for three runs in the fifth for a 6-3 victory
to avoid a humiliating sweep. And while the crowd of 53,869 was the
largest at Shea Stadium since June 10, 1972, it was a passive
atmosphere inside the ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   The game seemed to be let-down after Saturday's riveting 9-8
Mets' victory, which pinch hitter Matt Franco had won with a
two-out, two-strike, bases-loaded single in the bottom of the
ninth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we came out with any lack of intensity today,''
Mike Piazza said. ``But I think that any game would be
anti-climatic compared to yesterday.''
</P>
<P>
   General manager Steve Phillips agreed. ``Any game today in
comparison to yesterday would have come up short,'' he said
</P>
<P>
   And so the Mets head into the break at 50-39. Last season, the
Mets were 44-39 at this point, after the Braves had swept three
games from them in Atlanta in the weekend before the break. Then,
the Mets were 12 1/2 games behind Atlanta in the National League
East. Now, the Mets are five games behind the first-place Braves
and just one game out of the wild card spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been through the tough times and a lot of teams
haven't,'' manager Bobby Valentine said. ``What doesn't kill you
makes you stronger. And I think we're a real strong team.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets are a major-league best 23-11 since June 6, the day
they ended a season-high eight-game skid with a victory over the
Yankees to avoid a sweep. That was the day after Phillips had fired
three of Valentine's coaches.
</P>
<P>
   There have been plenty of other controversies this season,
including the ongoing saga of Valentine and Bobby Bonilla. The feud
reignited over the weekend, and Sunday morning, as Valentine,
Phillips and Bonilla were swarmed by reporters asking questions
about Bonilla's place on the team, Saturday's victory was all but
ignored, taking away from what should have been the Mets' finest
moment of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday was a forgettable day for the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we'd probably want to remember Saturday more than
today,'' Piazza said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Orel Hershiser definitely feels the same.
</P>
<P>
   Hershiser (9-6) was sharp early, but then allowed three runs in
the fourth. And after the Mets tied the game in the bottom of the
inning, Hershiser, who was going for his 200th career victory,
could not record an out in the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a good sinker most of the game,'' said Hershiser, who
was charged with six runs on 10 hits in 4-plus innings. But he did
not have much else.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's thrown better,'' Valentine said of Hershiser. And after
the Yankees grabbed the lead, Hideki Irabu was able to shut down
the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   Irabu battled in the fourth, after the Mets had tied the score
and had runners on first and third and nobody out.
</P>
<P>
   But Rickey Henderson waved at a full-count pitch for the first
out. ``His fastball moved,'' Henderson said. ``It tricked me.''
</P>
<P>
   Edgardo Alfonzo followed with a fly-out to right. ``He threw me
a good pitch, I just missed it,'' Alfonzo said.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Rickey Ledee made a nice, running one-handed catch of a
John Olerud fly to left, and the Mets had wasted a golden chance to
knock out Irabu.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until he made those pitches, it seemed like it was going to be
another barn-burner to me,'' Valentine said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Yankees snatched the lead right back and took the
crowd out of the game in the process.
</P>
<P>
   ``No runs were being scored,'' Brian McRae said. ``There wasn't
a whole lot to get excited about.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It definitely wasn't as exciting as yesterday,'' Henderson
said. ``It was like there was a little burnout.''
</P>
<P>
   But now the Mets can look forward to the second half of the
season, free of the Yankees, finally free of the burden of never
having taken a series from their cross-town rivals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played them, we're healthy, we got through everything and
we probably don't have to answer any questions about them any
more,'' Valentine said. ``The series is over. You'd like to win the
series. We did. Now we hope we can build on it in the second half
and go to Tampa rested and ready to go.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
