<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: WILL WOMEN ENJOY A LEAGUE OF THEIR OWN? 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The advertisement was up and running in the Sunday
edition of The Los Angeles Times:
</P>
<P>
   ``On Sale Monday: World Soccer Champions and Gold Medalists _
For the First Time Anywhere, Indoors _ All-American Soccer Stars
vs. The World _ Featuring Hamm, Foudy, Overbeck, Akers, Lilly,
Scurry, Chastain, Milbrett, Venturini, Fawcett and More. Dec. 9,
7:05 p.m., Arrowhead Pond, Anaheim.''
</P>
<P>
   They don't waste any time, do they?
</P>
<P>
   America's newest sensations are going back on the road, not as
the national team, but as instant celebrities. They are going out
to strut their stuff the way Babe Ruth and Lou Gehrig used to
barnstorm back in the '20s, to make a few extra dollars and take
their game to the hinterlands.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are a cult,'' mused Keith Cooper, the director of
communications for the world soccer body known as FIFA. ``But most
cults take longer to develop than this one.''
</P>
<P>
   The women came from way off the pop-culture map. A month ago,
when I tried to tell colleagues and friends about these American
women, I would be aware of them casting discreet glances at their
watches and shuffling their feet.
</P>
<P>
   Now the American women are hot, but then again, America lives
for temporary diversion and instant gratification _ new pop groups,
new sunglasses, new cars, new Internet stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Did something significant really happen here, or was it a case
of an attractive event coming along during an interlude when
Americans were sated with loutish male basketball and baseball
players?
</P>
<P>
   After years of washing and lugging their own gear, the women are
going to cash in, a little bit, anyway. Now it is up to the people
with the decimal points in their attache cases. Can the Women's
World Cup champions make any real money flexing their smiles and
flashing their abs, or is it the other way around?
</P>
<P>
   These people are not exactly babes in the woods. Do you really
think Brandi Chastain whipped off her game jersey in ``momentary
insanity'' or had she contemplated the potential of displaying a
little more of the best-buffed body on the team?
</P>
<P>
   What is the near future for these women? On Sunday morning I
consulted an expert, Marla Messing, the chief executive officer of
this World Cup, who put 658,000 fannies in seats by going out and
pitching to the established recreation leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Some positive thinkers have linked Mia-mania and
Brandi-tipsiness with the dawning of a new age of women's sports,
but Messing, ever the businesswoman and lawyer, was somewhat
cautious.
</P>
<P>
   Messing was quite positive that Americans would follow
qualifying rounds for the next Women's World Cup in 2003, might
even travel to Australia, the presumed host.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope we have demonstrated this is a legitimate sport,''
Messing said. ``The handlers must care about it. Australia doesn't
have to accomplish what we accomplished, but I think people care
about authentic sports at the highest level _ women playing for
pride, playing their hearts out. That's how I would market this
event.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the U.S., we had young women really connecting, this was a
celebration of the female athlete, but we never tried to exclude
anybody. We went after male fans. So much has been written about
sex appeal, but there are beautiful women all over the place. If
they were not great athletes, nobody would care.''
</P>
<P>
   Messing was cautious about prospects for some kind of women's
league. Citing ``growing pains'' of major-league soccer, struggling
along in its fourth year, Messing said ``the real legacy'' of the
1994 men's World Cup was ``interest in the World Cup and the men's
national program.''
</P>
<P>
   Could there be a women's league by 2001? Messing said: ``I
haven't had time to think about the league but I look at baseball,
basketball, hockey, and I don't think we can put a league that
looks anything like that. We need a new model. I don't know what
that model would look like.''
</P>
<P>
   Messing has been saying that ``hundreds of thousands of girls''
would register for soccer leagues this fall, because ``They want to
be like Mia Hamm and Julie Foudy and play in a Women's World Cup.''
</P>
<P>
   While waiting to close the books on this adventure, Messing said
she has ``no plans.'' She added, ``I have two children and I owe it
to them and my husband to be around for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   The American women are making their own plans _ unofficial
barnstorming, a national overseas tour next year, trying to squeeze
20 world champions onto an 18-player roster for the 2000 Summer
Games in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   If Michelle Akers did not suffer from chronic fatigue syndrome,
I would not offer her gratuitous advice about quitting on top. It
might, however, be time for her to stop pounding herself into
fences, goal posts, other players and the turf, start taking
medicine, and enjoy life as the greatest female player in the
game's history.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese will be back. Next time, I hope ABC does better with
camera angles and pays more attention to foreign athletes who were,
essentially, co-champions.
</P>
<P>
   The American women have earned their place not only in our
memories and hearts, but also on our television screens, our
magazines, our Web sites and mostly our stadiums. They thrilled us,
they entertained us, and they respected their audience, too.
</P>
<P>
   Women's soccer is viable for itself, with no apologies. They
have ball skills. They can run for 90, make that 120, minutes. They
are innately good teammates. They have not yet developed the
sophisticated game of the men _ but neither do they have the
cynical fouls and flagrant flops of the men. They are a joy to
watch. They have sensational personalities. I would not mind seeing
a whole lot more of them and their game in the next century.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-11-99 2110EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
