<SLUG> BC-METLIFE-DEAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MET LIFE IS SAID TO BE NEAR DEAL FOR ST. PAUL AUTO AND HOME UNIT 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JOSEPH B. TREASTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Metropolitan Life, one of the country's largest life
insurance companies, is expected to announce Monday that it is
sharply expanding its auto and home insurance subsidiary by buying
a unit of St. Paul Cos., a leading corporate insurer, for more than
$500 million, executives close to the negotiations said.
</P>
<P>
   With the acquisition, the number of cars and homes insured by
Met Life would nearly double, to 4.35 million, analysts estimated.
The deal would also increase the reach of Met Life's auto and home
insurance business from its stronghold in the Northeast to towns
and cities throughout the Midwest and parts of the South.
</P>
<P>
   The deal would be the first of several that Met Life executives
have previously said they intended to make in a bid to catapult
their company into the top ranks of the auto and home insurance
business, thrusting it into head-to-head competition with such
giants as Allstate, State Farm, Progressive and Geico. If the St.
Paul deal goes through, Met Life would jump from 20th in the field
to about 12th, with annual premium revenues rising to $2.6 billion,
up from $1.4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Met Life plans to pay cash for the St. Paul unit. As a mutual
company, owned by its policyholders, Met Life has no stock to use
in acquisitions. But the parent company, which had revenues last
year of $11.5 billion, is in the midst of a reorganization that
will remedy that. An initial public offering is expected early next
year.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the relatively small size of its auto and homeowners
business, Met Life has already developed a reputation for
efficient, low-cost operations. In 1998 the auto and homeowners
unit reported an 18 percent increase in operating earnings to $81.3
million.
</P>
<P>
   For St. Paul, a sale would provide a way out of a line of
business that has been limping along and would enable it to
concentrate on the coverage of corporations and professionals for
which it is best known.
</P>
<P>
   Besides providing broad coverage for some of the nation's
biggest corporations, St. Paul is a leader in medical malpractice
and construction industry coverage. It also does a big business in
liability policies for small banks and municipal governments, as
well as for lawyers and financial specialists like accountants and
for high-tech companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``St. Paul is doing this to sharpen its focus,'' an executive
close to the company said of the Met Life deal. ``The company has
some unique competitive advantages in commercial insurance. It is
going to build on its success rather than invest more in the
personal lines _ auto and homeowners.''
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Foley, the chief spokesman for Met Life, and David
Monfried, the senior spokesman for St. Paul, said they could not
comment.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when most corporate insurers have been averaging a
return on equity of 5 percent to 8 percent, St. Paul Cos. have been
chalking up a healthy 11 percent return. But the return would have
been better without the auto and homeowners business, which was in
the red last year after a modest gain in 1997. St. Paul executives
forecast at least a modest gain this year.
</P>
<P>
   Weston Hicks, an analyst for J.P. Morgan Securities, said that
in the hands of a specialist in auto and home insurance it was
likely that the St. Paul business could turn a nice profit.
``Specialists in auto insurance have the ability to deliver the
product at lower costs,'' he said.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-11-99 2111EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990711.0164 </DOCNO>
