<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-11 21:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6188 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-YANKS-LEDEE-NYT &LR;      07-11 0834
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-YANKS-LEDEE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEDEE ENTERTAINING TEAMMATES BOTH ON AND OFF FIELD 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Ricky Ledee innocently exited the bathroom of the
visitors' clubhouse Sunday with toilet paper tucked into the back
of his uniform pants. Ledee walked across the clubhouse, and the
paper unraveled behind him for 20, 30, 40 feet before finally
ripping. As teammates giggled, Ledee was oblivious.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he was joking,'' said Chuck Knoblauch, who said the
mishap did not result from a prank. ``But the roll kept going and
going.''
</P>
<P>
   The comical incident was not the only time Ledee provided
entertainment for the New York Yankees on a day when they calmly
defeated the New York Mets, 6-3, and restored some sanity in
Yankeeland. George Steinbrenner would surely have wounded Brian
Cashman's ears with calls if the Mets had completed a stunning
three-game sweep at Shea Stadium, but the Yankees avoided that by
getting production from a position that has been disastrous all
season: left field.
</P>
<P>
   Ledee played the first four innings in left, ripped a three-run
home run and raced in to make a sweet catch, while Chad Curtis
pinch-hit for him in the fifth, belted a two-run single and later
retreated to make a nice over-the-shoulder catch. They combined for
five runs batted in, which, amazingly, is one fewer than Yankee
left fielders mustered in June.
</P>
<P>
   Shane Spencer had snatched the left field job by starting 17 of
his last 18 games, but he was hospitalized with an irregular
heartbeat on July 3 and cannot be activated until Sunday. Even
after Spencer helped fatten the statistics recently, the left
fielders entered Sunday's game with a .210 average, nine homers and
25 RBI. Joe Torre loves riding streaky players, especially in an
unsettled position, so Ledee, now batting .242, might keep himself
in the lineup and keep entertaining the Yankees if he keeps
hitting.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way I go,'' Ledee said. ``I want to prove something
to them. I just have to take it one game at a time. If they give me
the chance to play and start some games, I have to contribute.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes it is easy to forget how dynamic Ledee was in the
World Series with six hits in 10 at-bats because he has looked so
lost this season. He failed to win the left field job, was demoted
to Triple A Columbus and then came back and watched Spencer
dominate the position he desperately wants. Sunday, Ledee made an
impression with his power, his speed and his defense and even by
getting perturbed when he was removed from the game. Torre seemed
pleased that the mild-mannered Ledee was angry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I could have played nine innings,'' Ledee said.
</P>
<P>
   After Ledee looked feeble while flailing at Orel Hershiser's 1-2
sinker in the second inning, he batted with runners on second and
third in the fourth. Ledee etched a cross in the batter's box with
his bat, as he always does, and told himself to stay relaxed, as he
always does.
</P>
<P>
   Hershiser tried to sneak a first-pitch fastball by Ledee, who
drilled it to right-center field. Roger Cedeno backed up against
the wall and misjudged his leap as Ledee's shot bounced off the top
of the fence and over it to put the Yankees ahead, 3-2. Ledee
pumped both fists three times between second and third after his
second homer in two days and second of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to hit the ball to the right side,'' Ledee said.
``He gave me a pitch that was up. I was real happy with that.''
</P>
<P>
   In the bottom of the fourth, Ledee made Hideki Irabu feel happy
by rushing in from deep left to catch John Olerud's soft liner in
front of his chest for the third out. David Cone raved about how
aggressive Ledee looked in getting a great jump on the ball and
outrunning it to strand two runners and keep the score tied, 3-3.
Ledee looked far different from the seemingly nervous player who
felt for the wall and turned his glove awkwardly while muffing a
fly ball on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was huge,'' Cone said of Ledee's dazzling day.
</P>
<P>
   Ledee lamented how he did not play nine innings as Torre
inserted Curtis against Rigo Beltran in the fifth, with Curtis
slapping a two-run single that boosted the Yankees' cushion to 6-3.
Like Ledee, Curtis was a defensive stalwart in the bottom of the
inning as he looked like a wide receiver while chasing down
Cedeno's deep shot with a man on first to save a run.
</P>
<P>
   ``It surprised me a little bit,'' Curtis said. ``I had to kick
it in at the end to make the play.''
</P>
<P>
   As he departed for his home in Salinas, P.R., for the All-Star
Game break, Ledee was obviously more confident. Two homers in two
games will do that. Ledee quickly said ``yeah'' twice when he was
asked if there was enough time before the July 31 trading deadline
for him to become the regular left fielder. Others agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of us have to start somewhere,'' Paul O'Neill said.
``Maybe this is it. I think a lot of people still think that Ricky
can be a big part of our season.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-11-99 2112EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990711.0165 </DOCNO>
