<HEADLINE>
BAFFERT COMPLETES SWEEP AS FORESTRY WINS DWYER 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELMONT, N.Y. _ Bob Baffert opened the second half of the racing
season on Sunday by completing a sweep of stakes for 3-year-olds in
the East: On the day after his filly Silverbulletday won the
Monmouth Oaks, Baffert won the Dwyer at Belmont Park with his
newest star colt, Forestry.
</P>
<P>
   Forestry is a son of Storm Cat who was bought for Aaron Jones at
the Keeneland auction sale two years ago for $1.5 million, and he
has taken long strides toward redeeming his cost. He won Sunday for
the fifth straight time, outrunning Doneraile Court by 2\ lengths,
and he ran his record to six victories in eight starts with one
second and one third.
</P>
<P>
   He did not race at all last year at 2, and he was too small to
try crowding into the Triple Crown races at 3. Besides, Baffert had
more horses for the Kentucky Derby than he knew what to do with, so
he bided his time with Forestry. Now Forestry has grown to full
stature and has not lost since February.
</P>
<P>
   He also provided his California trainer with his first success
at a New York track after nine setbacks, including the last-gasp
loss of the Belmont Stakes two years in a row with the Triple Crown
on the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I picked the right day to do it,'' Baffert said. ``But
that's something that doesn't bother me.''
</P>
<P>
   Something that does bother him, though, is where to align his
stable of stars. For now he is thinking roughly in these
directions: General Challenge, who ran 11th in the Kentucky Derby,
will start in the Swaps Stakes at Santa Anita next Sunday;
Silverbulletday is 50-50 to return to Monmouth on Aug. 8 for the $1
million Haskell, and Forestry might make it the same day at
Saratoga in the $300,000 Jim Dandy and then return on Aug. 28 for
the $1 million Travers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was due for something like that,'' Baffert said after
Forestry's victory. ``We paid a lot of money for him. He'll go back
to Churchill Downs tomorrow with Silverbulletday, then we'll decide
what we're going to do. A lot depends on what happens next week
with General Challenge. I've got a lot of thinking to do, a lot of
juggling.''
</P>
<P>
   In the paddock after he was saddled, Forestry reared before
Jerry Bailey approached to mount him, and it took three stablehands
plus Baffert to quiet the colt. But to his trainer, these were all
plus marks on the horse's personality chart.
</P>
<P>
   ``He got scared by something,'' Baffert said. ``But he's a good,
tough horse. If I had tried to run him in the classics earlier this
year, I would have ruined him. But he has a lot of heart. He's
wild.
</P>
<P>
   ``They ran fast fractions, and I got a little worried when I saw
they ran three-quarters in 1:08 2/5. We'll have to see how much
energy these races took out of all of them.''
</P>
<P>
   The reason Forestry went so fast so early was because Nick
Zito's Doneraile Court leapt into the lead and shot the first
half-mile in 44 4/5 seconds. But Bailey took the long view aboard
Forestry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I decided to sit back and wait,'' he said. ``I thought
Doneraile Court was the horse to beat, and he was moving pretty
quick up front. I made my move on the turn, and my horse just went
by with ease. This is a lightly raced horse, and he's got talent.''
</P>
<P>
   Forestry ran the mile and one-sixteenth in 1:41, returned $4 for
a $2 bet to win and added $90,000 to his bankroll, which still has
a long way to go _ about $1.2 million _ to earn back what was paid
for him.
</P>
<P>
   For Baffert there are also nagging problems, like the
quarter-cut in Silverbulletday's right front foot, which she
reopened during the Monmouth Oaks. But for now, he was playing his
cards like a man holding four aces, with lots of money waiting in
the pot.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
