<HEADLINE>
MURDER SUSPECTS MAY BE LINKED TO SUPREMACISTS, POLICE SAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Ind.)  (mk) 
 By EVELYN NIEVES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The two brothers, say neighbors, are
nature-loving organic gardeners, meek, respectful sorts raised by
stern, religious parents in a small farm town.
</P>
<P>
   But the authorities say that the two men, Benjamin Matthew
Williams, 31, and James Tyler Williams, 29, most recently of
Redding, Calif., may be part of a growing national white
supremacist movement that spawned a student's recent shooting
rampage in Illinois and Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the Williams brothers were arrested in connection
with the shotgun slayings of a gay couple on July 1 in a rural area
near Redding, and the authorities say they have evidence that links
the brothers with the arson fires of three synagogues on June 18 in
Sacramento. Local authorities say they are also looking into any
possible connection between the brothers and the shotgun death of
an elderly man on June 20 in his cottage, three miles from where
the gay couple were shot to death in the bedroom of their mobile
home.
</P>
<P>
   A federal task force is looking into the possibility that the
brothers are part of the World Church of the Creator, based in East
Peoria, Ill., which preaches white supremacy and hatred of blacks,
Jews, Asians and gay people. Benjamin Nathaniel Smith, 21, whose
shooting attack over the Fourth of July weekend in Illinois and
Indiana ended with two people dead and nine injured before he
killed himself, had been a member of the organization. Tracts from
the group were found among the Williams brothers' possessions.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators are also looking into whether the killings in
Redding, the arson fires in Sacramento and the killings in Illinois
and Indiana were all part of a deliberately timed hate-crime
outbreak, said Nick Rossi, a spokesman for the FBI in Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   The Williams brothers were arrested in Yuba City, about 100
miles south of Redding, when they tried to collect from a private
postal service a package that had been ordered with one of the gay
couple's credit cards. Both brothers had 9-mm handguns, and one was
wearing a bulletproof vest. A stash of weapons was found in their
car.
</P>
<P>
   They were charged with possession of stolen goods, and they
remain in the Shasta County Jail.
</P>
<P>
   Besides hate tracts, a notebook naming 32 people who had been
quoted in media reports after the synagogue fires was also found.
Capt. Ron Richardson of the Shasta County Sheriff's Department said
Sunday that investigators were analyzing other evidence potentially
linking the brothers to the fires and the killings near Redding.
Results that could lead to additional charges, including murder,
are expected in a few days, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The brothers, who had started a landscaping business in Redding,
were raised in Gridley, about 18 miles north of Yuba City and 60
miles north of Sacramento. They were taught at home until high
school by their mother, Sally. Their father, Ben, worked for the
U.S. Forest Service. Former neighbors described the family as
polite and religious, with both the father and the brothers prone
to preaching as they took walks.
</P>
<P>
   Tyler Williams _ the brothers are known by their middle names _
still lives with his parents. Matthew Williams had recently moved
to a rental house not far away, where investigators were seen on
Saturday removing bags of possible evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Both brothers knew the slain men, Gary Matson, 50, and Winfield
Mowder, 40, said Richardson. Matson and Mowder had started a
children's nature museum and founded a farmer's market in Redding
where the brothers rented a booth.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had a lot in common,'' Richardson said. ``They all grew
things.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
