<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
E-COMMERCE TWIST: FULL-SERVICE SHIPPING  
 HIGH TECHNOLOGY FOR MONEY MANAGEMENT  
 WRESTLING GAMES TROUNCE ALL COMERS ON VIDEO 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Bylines follow individual items.) 
(Eds: The word AT in parentheses has been used instead of the
symbol, which is non-transmittable to many newspaper systems.) 
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Commercekey, an Internet start-up, has come up with a business
plan with a new wrinkle in the crowded electronic commerce market.
In addition to peddling software and transaction services to help
businesses set up shop on the Web, the company, with roots in the
Greek shipping industry, has its own world-class fleet of cargo
vessels standing by to deliver customers' merchandise around the
world.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which is based in New York and plans to announce
itself later this week, is a joint venture between two Greek
industrial giants, Vardinoyannis Group of Cos. and Leventis Group.
Together, the two companies give Commercekey access to a huge fleet
of freighters along with a network of climate-controlled warehouses
throughout the world.
</P>
<P>
   Owning its own fleet of vessels could help Commercekey clear one
of the big hurdles in electronic commerce: distribution.
</P>
<P>
   ``We come from a tradition of merchants and bottlers,'' said
Alkiviades David, president and chief executive of Commercekey,
whose family has a major stake in Leventis.
</P>
<P>
   Vardinoyannis owns the biggest oil refinery in Greece, Motor Oil
Hellas, along with numerous television stations, newspapers and
Internet service providers. Leventis, meanwhile, is Greece's
primary Coca-Cola distributor and also owns an Internet
telecommunications network in Eastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
   David and Demosthenes Vardinoyannis, Commercekey's chairman, met
while they were in high school in Switzerland many years ago. The
idea for Commercekey grew, in part, out of a video conferencing
venture David had started years ago; that technology has become a
component of Commercekey's service offerings.
</P>
<P>
   Together the two companies have invested an initial $12.5
million in the U.S. arm of Commercekey, and they plan to take the
company public early next year.
</P>
<P>
   _ LAURIE J. FLYNN
</P>
<P>
   High Technology for Money Management
</P>
<P>
   You may not be a Silicon Valley gazillionaire, but here is your
chance to manage your money like one.
</P>
<P>
   James H. Clark, the entrepreneurial engineer behind Silicon
Graphics, Netscape and, most recently, Healtheon, has quietly
embarked on his fourth start-up. It's a company focused on
simplifying the financial affairs of wealthy individuals _ or
anybody else willing to pay for the service.
</P>
<P>
   The venture, called MyCFO, grew out of Clark's own need for a
personal chief financial officer to handle his affairs and track
his investments. ``It was totally out of control,'' said Clark,
whose net worth is an estimated $500 million. (Tax time was
particularly difficult, he said.)
</P>
<P>
   So about two years ago, Clark hired Harvey Armstrong, a former
KPMG manager, who came up with a Web-based system that supplies
Clark and his various financial consultants with access to all of
Clark's financial records. Late last year they decided to found a
company on the concept.
</P>
<P>
   MyCFO (www.mycfo.com), whose clients include John Chambers,
chief executive of Cisco Systems, already has some 20 employees,
including four financial managers, and offices across the street
from the Silicon Graphics headquarters in Mountain View, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   With all his recent successes, including the recent $5.5 billion
merger of Healtheon with another online health information service,
WebMD, Clark appears to have had no trouble finding investors. The
list includes Chambers, the venture capital firm Kleiner Perkins
Caufield &AMP; Byers, and Thomas Jermoluk, chairman and chief executive
of Excite(AT)Home.
</P>
<P>
   Clark is acting chief executive and chairman of the company,
while Armstrong is acting president, although Clark hopes to hire
an outsider to be chief executive and president by the fall. At
that point, Armstrong would become the lead financial consultant
for MyCFO.
</P>
<P>
   _ LAURIE J. FLYNN
</P>
<P>
   Wrestling Games Trounce All Comers on Video
</P>
<P>
   Can the professional wrestler Stone Cold Steve Austin trounce
those intergalactic ``Star Wars'' heroes wielding light sabers? Yes
_ at least in the world of video games.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of wrestling-related video games from January through May
increased by 23 percent, to $60 million, over the comparable period
last year, according to NPD Group, a Port Washington, N.Y.,
research group. That increase outpaced the growth of video-game
sales generally, which grew 14 percent, to $1.9 billion during the
same period.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite the launch of `Star Wars' in May, wrestling-related
merchandise will likely be among the industry's best sellers when
final numbers are released at year end,'' said Ed Roth, president
of NPD Leisure Activities, a Glen Cove, N.Y., research firm.
</P>
<P>
   Liz Bell, a publicist for THQ Inc., said wrestling-related video
games ``have been frighteningly successful.'' THQ publishes three
of this year's best-selling titles: ``WCW/NWO Thunder'' for Sony's
Playstation, the top wrestling title; ``WCW/NWO Revenge'' for
Nintendo 64; and ``WCW Nitro'' for Nintendo, Playstation and PCs.
</P>
<P>
   Austin is the featured character in ``WWF War Zone'' by Acclaim,
one of the year's best-selling titles.
</P>
<P>
   If the strong pace of sales keeps up, few wrestlers may be
tempted to follow the path of their former colleague Jesse ``the
Body'' Ventura into the political arena. Who needs the governor's
mansion, when there's a shot at becoming a lead character in a
Playstation title?
</P>
<P>
   _ SHARON R. KING
</P>
</TEXT>
