<SLUG> BC-CULTURE-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ART AS SEEN THROUGH FRESH EYES 
WOODY GUTHRIE FESTIVAL 
CELEBRATING THE BUGATTIS 
PAITINGS FROM HUDSON RIVER SCHOOL EXHIBITED
</HEADLINE>
  (ATTN: England, Okla., Ohio) 
 (rk) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   From sculptured giant Amazonian waterlilies to a miniature
tableau of a suicidal squirrel, the work of 15 young artists from
nine countries will be displayed beginning on Thursday at the Tate
Gallery in London. Through Sept. 26, the show, ``Abracadabra:
International Contemporary Art,'' illuminates the fantasy, humor
and invention of these artists applied to the everyday world
through sculpture, drawings, installations, painting, photography
and video. Information: 011-44-171-887-8000.
</P>
<P>
   Woody's Children
</P>
<P>
   Beginning on Wednesday, performers like Arlo Guthrie, the
Kingston Trio and Country Joe McDonald will be streaming into
Okemah, Okla., the birthplace of folk singer, guitarist and
composer Woody Guthrie (1912-1967). For the five days ending on
Sunday, Okemah will be home to more than 60 musicians performing 30
hours of music at the Second Annual Woody Guthrie Free Folk
Festival. The only nonfree event is on Wednesday: the Annual Woody
Guthrie Birthday Hootenanny (where Arlo, Woody's son, will
perform), which raises money for the festival. Thursday activities
focus on Huntington's disease, which took Guthrie's life at 55, and
culminate in a celebration of him by 20 performers from across the
United States. Information: (918) 825-5156.
</P>
<P>
   Family Ties
</P>
<P>
   Six of the most beautiful automobiles ever made will be among
the nearly 80 objects on display starting on Sunday when the
Cleveland Museum of Art celebrates the talents of the Bugatti
family. Though the name is most closely associated with the cars of
Ettore Bugatti (1881-1947) and his son Jean (1909-1939), the
family's artistic heritage begins with the patriarch, Carlo
(1856-1940), who won international acclaim for his interior designs
and furnishings. The show also pays tribute to Carlo's younger son,
Rembrandt (1884-1916), Ettore's brother, with a display of 21 of
his bronze statues. The exhibition runs through Sept. 19.
Information: (888) 262-0033.
</P>
<P>
   Inspiration
</P>
<P>
   The 19th-century painters of the Hudson River School filled
their work with poetic beauty derived from observation of nature
and shaped by Romantic sensibility. Beginning on Wednesday more
than 60 Hudson River School paintings, by artists like Thomas Cole,
Asher B. Durand, John F. Kensett, Frederic E. Church and Jasper
Cropsey, will be exhibited through Sept. 12 in ``All That Is
Glorious Around Us'' in New York at the National Academy of Design,
1083 Fifth Ave., between 89th and 90th streets. Information: (212)
369-4880.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
