</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-BUDGET-SURPLUS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE TRILLION-DOLLAR PROBLEM 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Monday, July 12:
</P>
<P>
   Only a few years ago, the idea of Congress and the president
wrangling over a trillion-dollar budget surplus would have provoked
disbelief. But it turns out that the new era of surpluses is just
as contentious as the old era of deficits.
</P>
<P>
   As Congress returns to work on Monday, House Republicans are
preparing a tax cut so large it would use up virtually all of the
surplus for 10 years, leaving no money to make Medicare solvent or
to avoid deeper domestic cuts. The likelihood that President
Clinton would veto an outsized tax cut is only spurring them on.
Lawmakers seem to favor slogans over solutions.
</P>
<P>
   But there is no reason to rule out progress this year on
critical issues, including the urgent problem of ensuring that the
baby-boom generation has adequate health care in its retirement
years. A little clear thinking will help everyone establish
priorities at a time when there is enough money to address them.
</P>
<P>
   Some gains have already been achieved. The Congressional Budget
Office projects a surplus of nearly $2.9 trillion in the next 10
years, and Democrats and Republicans agree in principle that the
$1.9 trillion generated by Social Security taxes should go back
into that system to keep it solvent well into the next century. The
fight is over the remaining $1 trillion.
</P>
<P>
   If Americans want to use that money for tax cuts, they need to
know the consequences. The surplus rests on the assumption that
Congress and the White House will carry out previously targeted
spending cuts. No one thinks that will happen.
</P>
<P>
   The budget ceilings for this year, enacted in 1997, call for
cuts that the Republican chairmen of the various appropriations
committees already say are unrealistic. But the same 1997 law
requires even more cuts in future years.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when Gov. George W. Bush is getting much applause for
his brand of ``compassionate conservatism,'' Republicans in
Congress should think twice about more cuts in health, job
training, environmental programs and research in science and
medicine.
</P>
<P>
   A more realistic approach would set aside a substantial part of
the surplus to sustain current domestic spending and perhaps expand
it in certain areas.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also wants to set aside another chunk for Medicare,
where Republicans might have some incentive to agree. After the
1995 budget shutdowns, they should realize that the public punishes
them every time they try to pay for tax cuts by trimming Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   It may be unrealistic to expect agreement on a specific plan to
revamp Medicare, although Clinton's proposal to pay for
prescription drugs has found some Republican support. But it is not
unrealistic to set aside money for the job out of the surplus.
</P>
<P>
   The reason for sequestering the money now is simple. If
Republicans persist in cutting taxes deeply, the long-term
consequences will be severe. It took 15 years of tax increases and
budget cuts to overcome the deficits created by President Ronald
Reagan's tax reductions in 1981. It makes no sense to repeat that
pattern.
</P>
<P>
   As for the 10-year $864 billion tax-cut scheme that Bill Archer,
chairman of the House Ways and Means Committee, plans to push, one
wonders what the rationale could be. With the Federal Reserve Board
raising interest rates for fear of an overheated economy, no
stimulus is needed. It is perverse to cut taxes for those who have
benefited most from the current boom.
</P>
<P>
   Any scenario for constructive engagement on the budget must
start with negotiations in the weeks ahead. The best chance for
success would come if Republicans came to their budget senses early
and designed a more realistic scheme for the next 10 years. A
signal from Bush, the party's new favorite son, might help. A
trillion-dollar budget agreement would be better for everyone than
a trillion-dollar breakdown.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-11-99 2132EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
