<SLUG> BC-NY-POLICE-480&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI REITERATES OPPOSITION TO OUTSIDE OVERSIGHT OF POLICE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Reacting to an investigation by federal prosecutors
that found widespread problems in the way the New York City Police
Department handles brutality complaints, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani
said Sunday that he would never agree to a federal monitor or other
outside oversight of the department.
</P>
<P>
   ``My administration never compromises on matters of principle,''
Giuliani replied tersely when asked whether he had considered
changing his position. The mayor has long opposed outside
supervision of the police and has twice vetoed city council
legislation to create an independent monitoring board.
</P>
<P>
   If the city does not agree to changes sought by the U.S.
attorney in Brooklyn, Zachary W. Carter, who directed the nearly
two-year inquiry into the Police Department, the Justice Department
may sue the city to seek a court-ordered overhaul and perhaps the
appointment of a monitor.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani declined Sunday to discuss negotiations between his
administration and Carter's office. Carter is due to leave his post
for private practice at the end of this week and, according to some
aides, would like to reach an agreement with the city before his
departure, but it remains unclear what steps by the city might
satisfy him.
</P>
<P>
   Under federal rules governing investigations of local police
departments, Carter must present the findings of his inquiry to the
city and seek a resolution before the Justice Department files
suit. Carter so far has declined to make public any specific
conclusions of the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Carter's office, William Muller, said Sunday
that he would not comment on what specific issues are the subject
of negotiations. At City Hall, the matter is being handled chiefly
by Michael D. Hess, the city's corporation counsel.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor, who held his daily news conference Sunday at Shea
Stadium before attending the Yankees-Mets game, repeated his
assertions that criticism of the Police Department is politically
motivated. And he reiterated his staunch defense of the city's
police officers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The New York City Police Department is the most restrained
large-city police department in the country,'' Giuliani said,
invoking what has become almost a mantra for him since the fatal
shooting of Amadou Diallo, an unarmed immigrant, by four police
officers in February.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although the Justice Department has a role in investigating
police departments,'' the mayor said, ``New Yorkers have certainly
the right to ask, `What about all the other cities where police
officers shoot people two, three, four, five times per capita more
than in New York City?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani praised the Police Department's ability to control
large crowds, and offered the handling of the blackout in northern
Manhattan last week as the latest example of the department's
improved relations with the community and its success in preventing
crime.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``I think the bashing of the NYPD has been relentless for about
four or five months,'' Giuliani said. ``What I'd like to focus on
this weekend is for the city to sit back and say maybe the bashing
has gone too far, when you can have the lights go out in a major
urban area that used to lead the Northeast in homicides five or six
years ago, was a major drug center, and the lights can go out for
18 to 30 hours and you can have virtually no violence during that
period of time, you can have 1,500 police officers there, no
incidents other than cooperation. Maybe, just maybe, the New York
City Police Department is doing something right and the bashing has
created a wrong perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Giuliani rejected the majority of recommendations
made by a task force he appointed to explore ways of improving
relations between the police and residents. Among the
recommendations rejected by the mayor was the proposal for an
auditor to monitor the Civilian Complaint Review Board, which has
the power to investigate brutality complaints but no power to
discipline officers.
</P>
<P>
   The Review Board, whose 13 members are appointed by the mayor,
has been widely criticized as ineffective.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
