<SLUG> BC-EDIT-SOCCER-GLORY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: GLORY IN PASADENA 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Monday, July 12:
</P>
<P>
   With a well-calculated guess, American goalkeeper Briana Scurry
lunged left, blocking a penalty kick from China's Liu Ying. Moments
later, Brandi Chastain's left-footed penalty kick curved past
Chinese goalie Gao Hong, into the high right corner of the goal.
Scurry's save and Chastain's goal on Saturday gave the American
women's soccer team the edge in a thrilling if arbitrary ending to
a scoreless game, as well as their second World Cup championship in
this decade.
</P>
<P>
   The effervescent Chastain fell to her knees, fists clenched in
victory, and the sellout crowd of 90,185 fans in Pasadena's Rose
Bowl stood as one to cheer this remarkable team and the lift they
have given to women athletes everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   These two well-matched teams played ferocious defense,
neutralizing two of the most prolific scorers in the game,
America's Mia Hamm and China's Sun Wen. Two hours of soccer _ 90
minutes of regulation and two 15-minute overtimes _ produced
exquisite ball control and teamwork but few scoring chances. One of
these chances, however, nearly ended the game in China's favor.
</P>
<P>
   In the 10th minute of overtime, Kristine Lilly, a superb two-way
player, headed an almost certain goal out of the net after the ball
sailed over Scurry. Lilly, Scurry and Chastain were not the only
heroes. As expected, Michelle Akers, the great warrior of women's
soccer, anchored the midfield with courage and skill until heat
exhaustion drove her to the sidelines in the game's 90th minute.
</P>
<P>
   This was yet another glorious moment for a team that has had a
sparkling run in the 1990s, including the 1996 Olympic gold medal.
These players have taken women's sports to a new level of
prominence, and in time the excitement they have generated may lead
to formation of a women's professional league. But for the moment
it is enough to savor an unforgettable portrait of determination
and grace.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
