<HEADLINE>
CAREER YEARS IS OLIVARES' ONLY FOCUS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Pitcher Omar Olivares has been the Anaheim Angels' most
consistent starter this season. He's the only starter with a
winning record (8-6), the only starter with a complete game (two)
and ranks seventh in the league in ERA (3.28).
</P>
<P>
   He also happens to be in the final year of a contract that is
paying him $1.6 million this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd love to stay here,'' said Olivares, who joined the Angels
in 1998. ``I like it here a lot. But you know how business is.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Olivares is having a career year, he says he can't
allow himself to think about his contract situation during the
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really not thinking about it or worrying about it,'' he
said. ``I've got to focus on pitching right now, and what I've got
to do. I don't want to think about anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though he's been pitching professionally since 1987,
Olivares is just 31. He's been all over the big leagues, playing
for St. Louis, Colorado, Philadelphia, Detroit and Seattle before
coming to Anaheim. He also pitches for Puerto Rico in the Winter
League each year.
</P>
<P>
   Rotation set: Manager Terry Collins has decided on his rotation
coming out of the All-Star break for the team's six-game homestand.
Chuck Finley will start Thursday against the Dodgers, followed by
Olivares and Steve Sparks. The Dodgers' starters in the series will
be Kevin Brown, Ismael Valdes and Chan Ho Park.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels will face San Diego for a three-game series starting
Sunday. Mike Fyhrie will open the series for the Angels, followed
by Ken Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Glaus cleaning up: Troy Glaus hit cleanup Sunday for the third
time this season, even though in his first two games in that spot
he was 1 for 6 with three strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   But Collins said he wanted to break up lefties Mo Vaughn and
Garret Anderson in the lineup with a lefty (Bobby Jones) pitching
for Colorado. Also, Glaus had three home runs in the first two
games of the series.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, Glaus went 0 for 4.
</P>
<P>
   Let's hear it for the O: The Angels offense has come around
lately, but their stretch of poor hitting had everybody searching
for answers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried everything,'' Collins said. ``We tried everything
from things that I learned in my first year as a player to Rod
Carew and Larry Bowa and every idea they had. We exhausted every
idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now Darin's (Erstad) hitting, Garret's hitting, Mo's hitting,
Randy's (Velarde) hitting. When you're hitting the ball well, every
matchup looks good.
</P>
<P>
   Streak on: Velarde singled in the first inning Sunday, extending
his hitting streak to 10 games.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
