<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-11 21:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6222 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-FLAG-AMENDMENT-N     07-11 0277
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-FLAG-AMENDMENT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: PATRIOTISM POLITICS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Monday, July 12:
</P>
<P>
   Surely there are better ways for congressional lawmakers to
demonstrate their love of country than to dilute Americans'
free-speech rights.
</P>
<P>
   This simple truth continues to elude the House of
Representatives. For the third time in four years, the chamber has
approved a constitutional amendment that would undermine the right
of free expression by allowing Congress to prohibit the physical
desecration of the American flag. Once again, it is up to the
Senate to block this assault on the Bill of Rights.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, supporters of the flag amendment appear just two
votes shy of the two-thirds majority in the Senate required to send
the measure to the states for almost certain ratification. That
margin is much too close for comfort given the demagogy the issue
still inspires fully a decade after the Supreme Court ruling
holding flag-burning to be constitutionally protected free speech.
</P>
<P>
   Much depends on the resolve of the two Democratic senators from
North Dakota, Kent Conrad and Byron Dorgan. In May, they announced
their opposition to the so-called Flag Desecration Amendment, and
there is bound to be enormous pressure placed on them to
reconsider. By continuing to stand firm, they will render an
enormous service to the First Amendment and to the nation.
</P>
<P>
   The flag is in no danger. Historically, there have been very few
reported episodes of flag-burning, and no new epidemic looms on the
horizon. The immediate danger is to the Constitution.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
