<P>
   (NYT17) ARMONK, N.Y. -- July 11, 1999 -- DEER-TICK-SUMMER, 7-11
-- At Fordham University's Louis Calder Center in Armonk,
Westchester County, Thomas J. Daniels, a biologist on the tick
study team, tracks the deer-tick nymph population, which generally
peaks in late June and early July. Since 1987, Daniels and his
colleagues have run what they believe to be the world's only
catch-tag-and-release study of ticks as part of their research into
what natural factors kill them. (James Estrin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) NEWTOK, Alaska -- July 11, 1999 -- ALASKA-GATHERERS-3,
7-11 -- By the Niutaq River in Newtok, Stanley and Elizabeth Tom,
with some of their children, help to preserve fish for the winter
days ahead. In August it will be time for gathering berries and
wild celery out in the bush. In the fall the men will hunt caribou.
To a remarkable degree, thousands of native people still live off
the land here in the Alaskan tundra, taking 90 percent or more of
what they eat every year from the great back country, the rivers
and the Bering Sea. (Monica Almeida/New York Times Photo)
</P>
