region. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) WASHINGTON -- July 11, 1999 -- HMO-LOBBY, 7-11 -- Karen
M. Ignagni, president of the American Association of Health Plans,
in her office in Washington. As president of the AAHP and lead
lobbyist, Ms. Ignagni has deflected much of the anger that
threatened to overwhelm HMOs just a year ago. She will lead the
industry into battle this week, as the Senate holds four days of
impassioned debate on proposals to set comprehensive federal
standards for health insurance plans. (Shana Raab/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) ORAHOVAC, Yugoslavia -- July 11, 1999 --
KOSOVO-PROTEST-2, 7-11 -- Kosovo Albanians waving anti-Russian
signs march through Orahovac on Sunday, past Dutch NATO troops, in
the fourth day of peaceful protests against plans to station
Russian troops among the NATO peacekeepers here. The Albanians
assert that Russian mercenaries fought as members of the
nationalist Serbian militias that carried out a campaign of
killing, looting and burning across Kosovo and that the Russians
would be overly solicitous of the handful of remaining Serbs.
(Tyler Hicks/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) ORAHOVAC, Yugoslavia -- July 11, 1999 --
KOSOVO-PROTEST-1, 7-11 -- Several thousand Kosovo Albanians march
through Orahovac on Sunday, in the fourth day of peaceful protests
against plans to station Russian troops among the NATO peacekeepers
here. The Albanians assert that Russian mercenaries fought as
members of the nationalist Serbian militias that carried out a
campaign of killing, looting and burning across the southwest
corner of Kosovo and that the Russians would be overly solicitous
of the handful of remaining Serbs. (Tyler Hicks/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) BOSTON -- July 11, 1999 -- BBO-MARTINEZ-PROFILE-2, 7-11
-- Pedro Martinez, 27, the star right-hander for the Boston Red
Sox, has 15 victories this season and doesn't think of himself as a
nearly perfect pitcher; he doesn't even believe he is the best
pitcher in his family. Martinez will start for the American League
in Tuesday night's All-Star game in Boston. Then later in the week,
he will begin the second half of the season slightly off a
30-victory pace. (C.J. Gunther/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) BOSTON -- July 11, 1999 -- BBO-MARTINEZ-PROFILE-1, 7-11
-- Pedro Martinez, 27, on the mound during a game against the
Chicago White Sox on April 15. Martinez, the star right-hander for
the Boston Red Sox, has 15 victories this season and has a chance
to become the first pitcher in more than three decades to win 30
games. Admired for his competitiveness and talent by those who
don't know him and for his humility and graciousness by those who
do, Martinez will start for the American League in Tuesday night's
All-Star game in Boston. (C.J. Gunther/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) BOSTON -- July 11, 1999 -- TANGLEWOOD-OZAWA, 7-11 --
Seiji Ozawa conducting the Boston Symphony Orchestra on opening
night of the Tanglewood summer season on Friday. Ozawa, who is
celebrating his 25th year as the orchestra's music director,
recently announced that he would be leaving in 2002 to become the
music director of the Vienna State Opera. (Alan E. Solomon/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- July 11, 1999 -- OZ-TV-VIOLENCE, 7-11 -- Tom
Fontana, center, with Matt Dillon, left, and Chazz Palminteri, all
enlisted as directors for ``Oz,'' this season. So far ``Oz,'' one
of HBO's highest-rated dramatic shows, has received mostly
favorable reaction. Others, however, have condemned it for its
violence. While broadcast network shows are divided into acts, each
ending in an artificial climax, ``Oz'' runs one hour straight on
HBO, a premium cable channel. ``With 'Oz' you can never break
away,'' saysFontana. ``It's unsettling in a good way.'' (Sara
Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW BRUNSWICK, N.J. -- July 11, 1999 --
BIGFILMS-SMALLBUCKS, 7-11 -- Loews is among the theater companies
investing in 'megaplexes,' which have big screens and stadium-style
seating, like the 17-screen complex, above and below, in New
Brunswick. Though audiences are flocking to the spacious
megaplexes, people are staying away in droves from the multiplexes
of shoe-box size theaters that have been a mainstay of shopping
malls and a staple of the industry for decades. So the big theatre
chains are attempting to convert multiplexes to megaplexes whenever
and wherever they can. (Norman Y. Lono/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) TIGARD, Ore. -- July 11, 1999 -- SEGA-DREAMCAST, 7-11 --
Michael Moody, 11, looks at some rental games in a Hollywood Video
store in Tigard. Sega will offer its new Dreamcast video game
console for rental before it goes on sale on Sept. 9. The company,
No.3 in the industry, hopes to attract consumers like Michael.
(Shane Young/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) BALTIMORE -- July 11, 1999 -- HDTV-STANDARDS, 7-11 --
Sinclair Broadcast engineers demonstrate two different digital
television signals at sites in the Baltimore area. Sinclair
Broadcasting Group, a maverick company that owns or operates 59
television stations nationwide, is waging an audacious campaign to
revise the digital format, saying the current version is seriously
flawed. (Marty Katz/New York Times Photo)
</P>
