<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-11 22:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6226 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-EDUCATION-2000(2     07-11 0847
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-EDUCATION-2000(2TAKES)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROOTS OF TEXAS SCHOOL SUCCESS PREDATE BUSH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By R.A. DYER 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The story of Texas education, as told by
presidential contender George W. Bush, is one of resounding
success.
</P>
<P>
   At fund-raisers and in stump speeches, the Texas governor tells
of rising test scores and improved student achievement. Minority
students have made great strides, he says. Black fourth-graders,
when compared with their peers in other states, lead the nation in
reading.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's accounts of school success in Texas have become prime
fodder for the national news media. But how much credit does the
governor deserve?
</P>
<P>
   A review of the record indicates that the state's most important
school reforms _ including standardized tests and other
accountability measures _ took root long before Bush moved into the
Governor's Mansion. Education experts, and even Bush aides, say
that his predecessors are more responsible for improvements in
Texas education.
</P>
<P>
   What Bush has done, they say, is resist making changes to the
system while advocating improvement.
</P>
<P>
   ``What he has done is tighten the educational accountability
system and made it more efficient,'' said David Beckwith, a
spokesman for Bush's presidential campaign. ``Education has been
his top priority for the state. He's proud of what Texas has been
able to accomplish.''
</P>
<P>
   Beckwith says Bush has always acknowledged the contributions of
his predecessors, such as Dallas billionaire H. Ross Perot, who led
a study of Texas education problems in 1983; Democratic Gov. Mark
White, who signed reform legislation in 1984; and Lionel ``Skip''
Meno, education commissioner under Democratic Gov. Ann Richards.
</P>
<P>
   But such acknowledgments, as might be expected during a run for
public office, have been largely absent during the campaign.
Instead, Bush points to improving scores on the Texas Assessment of
Academic Skills test, created by the Legislature in 1989, or on the
National Assessment of Educational Progress exam, a standardized
test administered to a random sampling of students in most states.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get blamed for what happens when you're governor, so you
better take credit for what happens when you're governor,'' said
White, who was governor from 1983 to 1987. ``But the fact remains
that most of the kids who graduated from high school this year
learned to read when I was governor.''
</P>
<P>
   The accountability system, touted repeatedly by the Bush
campaign, has received praise from all quarters: from business
groups, education professionals _ even the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   Developed over the past 15 years, the accountability system is
designed to ensure that all students, regardless of race, ethnicity
or household income, learn skills and facts that Texas officials
believe are central to a child's learning.
</P>
<P>
   Schools are held responsible for the performance of minority
groups, impoverished students, special education students and even
non-English speakers on the TAAS test.
</P>
<P>
   But TAAS is only one component. Schools must also meet daily
attendance and dropout prevention goals. Based on those criteria,
all schools receive a rating of exemplary, recognized, acceptable
or low-performing.
</P>
<P>
   The stakes are high. Exemplary schools are eligible for
additional state money and become desirable destinations for
students and teachers. Conversely, low-performing schools are often
stigmatized and can be taken over by the state if they don't
improve.
</P>
<P>
   Researcher Philip Uri Treisman, director of the Charles A. Dana
Center for Educational Innovation at the University of Texas at
Austin, described a growing consensus regarding Texas education.
Public schools, at least at the elementary and junior high levels,
have made real and measurable advances, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The evidence is overwhelming,'' said Treisman, a
mathematician. ``And you don't need some statistical technique to
see it. It's improving by leaps and bounds over the last four
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Between 1992 and 1996, for instance, the percentage of Texas
fourth-graders achieving the NAEP's ``proficient'' level rose from
15 percent to 25 percent _ far outpacing advances made in other
states. That placed Texas fifth among 42 states and the District of
Columbia in 1996, according to a Dana Center study. The national
average was 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, the Bush campaign has touted an improvement in
third-grade reading scores. In 1999, 86 percent of the third-grade
students passed the reading portion of TAAS, according to the Texas
Education Agency, up from 77 percent in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The achievement gap between Anglo and minority students, as
measured by those test scores, has diminished. (In 1994, for
instance, there was a 40 percentage point difference in the passing
rate between Anglo and African-American students; by 1998, that gap
had narrowed to 21 percentage points.)
</P>
<P>
   Texas high schools, however, are a different story. ``There is
no real evidence that we've made gains,'' Treisman said.
</P>
<P>
   MORE &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Despite larger percentages of 10th-graders passing the TAAS,
including more minority students, large numbers of minority and
economically disadvantaged students continue to fail some portion
of the exam.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, for instance, more than 40 percent of economically
disadvantaged students failed some portion of the 10th-grade TAAS _
a requirement for graduation. Likewise, 45 percent of
African-American students and 41 percent of Hispanics failed some
portion last year.
</P>
<P>
   The dropout rate also remains a serious concern.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Texas Education Agency reports that the rate has
declined in recent years, a 1996 state auditor's report questioned
the accuracy of the agency's figures. According to the state
auditor, the rate could be more than double what the agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
   And some groups, like the San Antonio-based Intercultural
Development Research Association, say the state attrition rate _
the number of high-school-age young people not accounted for _
increased by 30 percent between the 1985-1986 school year and
1996-1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where are these kids going? What's happening to them?'' asked
state Sen. Gonzalo Barrientos, D-Austin, citing the IDRA figures.
``You know, it's always good politics to talk about education, and
it's logical that the governor would want to take some credit.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there are some other areas that definitely need
improvement.''
</P>
<P>
   Treisman and other scholars say progress that has been made in
Texas schools this decade can be traced to legislation written in
1993 by state Sen. Bill Ratliff, R-Mount Pleasant _ two years
before Bush took office.
</P>
<P>
   Besides revamping the school finance system, 1993's Senate Bill
7 created a plan to allow the state to take control of
low-performing schools.
</P>
<P>
   Treisman and others said Senate Bill 7 was built on the
foundation of previous school bills, including 1989's Senate Bill
40, which created TAAS, and similar bills during the 1980s. Perot
led much of that early effort as chairman of a special panel on
education, appointed in 1983 by White.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1993, Ratliff and others said, lawmakers have left the
state's accountability system largely unchanged.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have done a lot of work on the education code, but the
accountability system is virtually the same as what we put in,''
said Ratliff, who in 1993 was chairman of the Senate Education
Committee. ``And I think that this is the major reason that things
are improving.''
</P>
<P>
   Rand Corp. researchers David Grissmer and Ann Flanagan, writing
in a 1998 study of educational gains in North Carolina and Texas,
agree with Ratliff's assessment, stating that Texas politicians
created ``statewide academic standards ... (by) the late 1980s and
early 1990s and supported (them) consistently thereafter.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rand researchers, however, credit Bush for building on early
reforms _ for creating a ``continuity critical to long-term
success.''
</P>
<P>
   Every newly elected governor _ especially from a different
political party _ presents the possibility of policy changes. But
the Rand researchers and others note that Bush stayed the course.
</P>
<P>
   Said one longtime Capitol observer: ``He could have just come in
and deep-sixed the whole thing, but he was wise enough to let
(others) set up the system. That's something to be said for Bush _
he never played a destructive role.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush claims credit for pushing for more basic instruction in the
state's curriculum and for promoting legislation to end social
promotion, the practice of advancing academically unprepared
students to the next grade level.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, he also signed Senate Bill 1, which revised the Texas
education code by further restricting the authority of the Texas
Education Agency and giving more autonomy to local schools and
districts. But that legislation, sponsored by Ratliff, was based
largely on recommendations predating Bush's tenure.
</P>
<P>
   In this year's session, Bush signed into law a bill providing
teachers with a $3,000 pay raise. He campaigned for a smaller pay
raise.
</P>
<P>
   ``He deserves some credit, but he's never claimed it all,''
Beckwith said. ``People needing help reading are getting help. ...
Teachers are getting better paid, and test scores are rising.''
</P>
<P>
   (Staff writers Jennifer Autrey and Bill Hanna contributed to
this report. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World
Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
