<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-11 22:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6240 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WOODSTOCK-30TH-ART-70     07-11 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOODSTOCK-30TH-ART-700(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRYING TO REKINDLE SPIRIT OF WOODSTOCK AT A RELIC OF WAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By PAUL ZIELBAUER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME, N.Y. _ If there ever was a symbol of what Woodstock is
not, the hulking gray B-52 bomber casting shadows over Chestnut
Street is it.
</P>
<P>
   B-52s, after all, were raining bombs on North Vietnam about the
time in August 1969 that Country Joe McDonald was leading hundreds
of thousands of people in a sing-along antiwar chorus of ``One,
two, three, what are we fighting for?''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the B-52 on Chestnut Street is about to become part of
rock-and-roll history: it will be the first thing that the latest
iteration of the Woodstock generation sees when the legendary
concert's third coming begins on July 23 at the former Griffiss Air
Force Base.
</P>
<P>
   Just as the original Woodstock, in Bethel, N.Y., became
synonymous with the sloping and eventually muddy meadow of Max
Yasgur's farm, the Woodstock '99 site may become part of the
concert's lore.
</P>
<P>
   ``The irony is terrific,'' said Woodstock's creator, Michael
Lang, 54, wearing blue jeans and the mop of curly brown hair he had
as a whey-faced kid in 1969, when he produced Woodstock with $2.5
million and a little help from his friends. ``Everybody gets it,''
he added, nursing a frosted mug of beer at a restaurant here
recently. ``It's almost like revenge. You get to use this
billion-dollar facility for a rock concert.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, the promoters have sold 150,000 of the $150 tickets to
the three-day festival and hope to sell twice that amount by show
time, Lang said. But based on their experience, he said, the
organizers are preparing for as many as 375,000.
</P>
<P>
   Woodstock stopped being just a rock concert some time ago. The
1969 event that defined a generation without selling a single
concert T-shirt is now Woodstock.com, Woodstock '99 Pay Per View
and Woodstock the home video and compact-disc set, due out in time
for Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   There are other notable differences, too.
</P>
<P>
   At the first Woodstock, enterprising hippies sold glasses of
water for a quarter. Woodstock '99 is trucking in 14 cash machines,
and Cellular One is building an extra transmitting tower on the
base for the thousands of mobile phones that people will be
carrying. Back then, people slept in fields of mud; this year, Ace
Hardware (``the place for Woodstock '99'') is offering free
Woodstock '99 camping sites, including toilets and showers, to
anyone who buys $100 worth of gear from its on-site store. In 1969,
moreover, Lang zipped around Bethel's green acres on an old
motorcycle and on horseback; nowadays, he negotiates Rome behind
the wheel of a black Range Rover.
</P>
<P>
   And where the fed-up townfolk of Bethel booted its supervisor
from office three months after the hordes of concertgoers clogged
roads and camped out on lawns 30 years ago, the city of Rome,
population 44,000 and dwindling, has seized on Woodstock '99 to
harvest some lost civic pride.
</P>
<P>
   ``The community is ready, poised,'' said Mayor Joseph A. Griffo,
41, a Republican who is known locally as ``the rock-n-roll mayor''
because of his taste for rock concerts and the croonings of U2.
``If the city can pull off this thing, it's a city that can make
things happen.''
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, Woodstock and Rome are perfect for each other.
Since the Pentagon closed the 3,000-acre Air Force base in 1993, as
part of an overall military downsizing, local officials have
debated what to do with Griffiss. First they considered building a
Nascar speedway on it, then using it for a concert by the band
Phish. When Lang called in November to ask for permission to hold
his $30 million show here, Rome all but named him an honorary
citizen.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, the concert's producers say that Griffiss, with its
military-sized expanses of pavement, fields, parking and chain-link
fence, is particularly well suited for the event. They say the
1,100-acre concert site should provide plenty of room for people to
park and camp and enough security to stop the gate-crashers who
made up a large portion of the crowd in Bethel and at the 1994
Woodstock concert in Saugerties.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get 250,000 people on a site like this,'' said Mel
Lawrence, a member of the 1969 crew who is Woodstock '99's special
projects director, ``it's real conducive to a mellow event.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   If not exactly mellow, the setting seems designed to capture,
even magnify, all that has changed since the summer of 1969: The
bands will play in a grass field next to a 2-mile runway built to
accommodate B-52s and not far from a compound of stubby buildings
where nuclear warheads were stored underground. On the other side
of the tarmac are two cavernous hangars once used to repair fighter
jets and bombers. Lawrence plans to convert one hangar into a
theater for a film festival. (``Woodstock,'' ``A Hard Day's Night''
and ``Sid and Nancy'' are on the movie list.) The other hangar will
become an all-night dance club with disk jockeys and live music.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the first day, it stops being a concert and becomes a
place where you live,'' Lang said, echoing a thought that many
expressed, despite the mud, the rain and the other miseries, 30
years ago. ``It's a place where you feel safe and comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the B-52 on display at the gate, the concert seems built in
mega-proportions, from the 3.6 mile ``Peace Wall,'' which will be
sold off to benefit the American Red Cross, to the 260-acre
campground and the concert's triple-layer security system.
</P>
<P>
   ``The festival site will be surrounded, for the most part, by a
12-foot wooden wall,'' Dan Flynn, the concert's security chief,
told residents of Rome at a town-hall-style gathering in late June.
Sentries will stand on the wall. In addition, 1,200 guards will
roam the grounds. New York State Police will patrol the outer
perimeter.
</P>
<P>
   Whether those efforts succeed will not be known until the
three-day festival begins on July 23. And the promoters are
certainly aware that similar measures at the 1994 festival on a
farm in Saugerties were no match for the tens of thousands of fans
who showed up without tickets and poured through the gates
unimpeded.
</P>
<P>
   Those who get in this time will have more than music to keep
them occupied: an ``extreme sports'' complex for skateboarders and
rock climbers, a sculpture park, a post office, a shopping area, a
hospital unit, a canvas-tent wedding chapel (four weddings are
scheduled) and three two-acre beer tents.
</P>
<P>
   None of this, of course, was at the original Woodstock concert,
which featured 28 bands on a single stage and 500,000 people
crammed into a 250-acre meadow. The top ticket price then was $21.
</P>
<P>
   With the exception of one of the drummers for the Grateful Dead,
none of the original performers will be at Woodstock '99. Limp
Bizkit has replaced Joan Baez; instead of Country Joe McDonald,
there will be the Insane Clown Posse; Hendrix is dead, but Ice Cube
lives on.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had no mosh pit, we had no cell phones, no MTV, no ATMs,''
said Duke Devlin, 56, a jolly, thickly bearded fellow who in 1969
hitchhiked from a New Mexico commune to attend the original
concert. Now he works for the Woodstock press office. ``Things
didn't work. We got wet. `I am you and you are me,' that was the
phrase.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the corporate tie-ins to this Woodstock concert, Lang
seems eager to rub away the commercial varnish that clung to the
1994 concert, which proffered an official soft drink (Pepsi) and
ice cream (Haagen-Dazs) as well as ``peace condoms.'' This year,
Woodstock's public relations people are saying the event has no
official sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, some critics wonder whether Woodstock spent all its
spiritual capital during the original show in 1969. ``My perception
is that it's a brand name, a kind of event that doesn't really
exist anymore,'' said Fred Goodman, author of ``The Mansion on the
Hill: Dylan, Young, Geffen, Springsteen and the Head-On Collision
of Rock and Commerce.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Woodstock happened because it wasn't well planned,'' he went
on. ``That couldn't happen now, whether it's because of insurance
reasons or the bands wouldn't stand for it. The frontier is gone.''
</P>
<P>
   But Lang, still smarting from media accounts in 1994 that
portrayed the selling of Woodstock as a kind of cultural cirrhosis,
believes such concerns become irrelevant once the music starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether you have prepackaged condoms or not, if you're
listening to this incredible music and bonding with all of these
new friends you've made around you, the experience is the same,''
he said. The Woodstock vibe, he said, ``just got bigger; it didn't
get different.
</P>
<P>
   Lang added: ``If I had a corporate sponsor who was willing to
give me $500 million, they would be here. The kids could have cared
less. It was no deal at all, except for the media.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps even more than Lang, who says he lost approximately $6
million on the two previous Woodstock shows and seems prepared to
lose more if necessary, the citizens of Rome _ a city that built a
$170,000 Museum of Cheese in 1988 to lure tourists _ need Woodstock
'99 to be a commercial success.
</P>
<P>
   For years, Griffiss supplied this region with 5,000 civilian
jobs and hundreds of millions of dollars in residual revenues. Then
it closed and left the Mohawk Valley town grasping to fill the
void.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an opportunity for us to shine,'' Sylvia Fragafane, a
local business owner, said at the town-hall-style meeting after
several people complained about the expected traffic tie-ups.
``It's also an opportunity for us to feel good about ourselves,''
she said, as dozens of people broke into loud applause. ``So let's
pull together!''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Fragafane's exhortation will be put to the test on July 23,
when Rome is expected to swell to more than 400,000 residents, 10
times its normal size. The local chamber of commerce predicts the
concert will pump $30 million into the region.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a warm and friendly people,'' Griffo, the rock-n-roll
mayor, assured his constituents at the town meeting. No one wants
to believe that more than Griffo, an ambitious politician who has
banked this, his last year in office, on Woodstock's success.
</P>
<P>
   He would not be the first politician to go down in psychedelic
flames if Woodstock gets out of hand. In the November 1969
election, the Bethel town supervisor, Daniel Amatucci, was narrowly
defeated after a campaign that had one issue: the concert.
</P>
<P>
   With the concert date quickly approaching, workers are now
beginning to build the two main stages and erect the security
barrier.
</P>
<P>
   And if Devlin is any indication, the spirit of Max Yasgur's farm
is beginning to take hold in the shadow of that B-52. ``If I walked
on this base in 1969 with a tie-dye shirt on,'' said Devlin, clad
in exactly such a garment, ``I'm sure I would have had a spotlight
on me and guns pointed at me.''
</P>
<P>
   Thirty years later, he said, ``This is Woodstock, man.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
