<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAACP-CONVENTION-460&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEST AND BRIGHTEST VIE FOR NAACP HONORS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By AMY WALDMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ One minute Dorian Logan was sneering and abusive as
Sgt. Waters in Charles Fuller's ``A Soldier's Play.'' The next he
was languid, and then quivering with fear as C.J. Memphis, the
guitar-strumming private whom the sergeant accuses of murder. And
the next, he was first cool and then explosive, as Pfc. Melvin
Peterson, who shoots Waters on C.J.'s behalf.
</P>
<P>
   One young man, three parts, one masterly performance.
</P>
<P>
   Make that one of many turns of talent at the Afro-Academic
Cultural, Technological and Scientific Olympics, or ACT-SO, which
began Friday at two hotels in midtown Manhattan and concludes
Monday. Sponsored by the National Association for the Advancement
of Colored People, the competition is held each year at the
association's convention.
</P>
<P>
   More than 800 black students from NAACP branches around the
United States, accompanied by coaches, mentors, advisers and some
parents, assembled to compete in 25 categories such as oratory and
mathematics. The winners are to be announced Monday, after the
students march en masse to the New York City Center Theater.
</P>
<P>
   Logan, who is 18 and hails from Detroit, was a contestant in the
dramatics category. The competition was stiff _ he was sandwiched,
for example, between a young woman who performed an original piece
about a young slave raped by her master, and another young woman
who composed a tribute to Paul Robeson.
</P>
<P>
   The same was true in other categories. B'Randy Brooks and
Tiffanie Gray, both 17, stood feet apart, both having performed
opera selections in the classical vocal category, both hoping
victory would be theirs, both wanting to pursue careers in opera.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Brooks, who is from Altadena, Calif., had beads in her hair
and confidence in her voice. She had just performed the Queen of
the Night's famous aria from Act II of Mozart's ``Magic Flute.''
``I presented it well,'' she said. ``I think this is the year for
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Gray was equally self-assured after singing an aria from
Pergolesi's opera ``La Serva Padrona,'' ``Stizzoso, Mio Stizzoso,''
which she translated, roughly, as ``peevish one, my peevish one.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I did really really well,'' she said. ``That's the best I ever
performed that song.''
</P>
<P>
   But while most of the participants said they certainly wanted to
win, the event's spirit was more friendly than cutthroat. ``We're
here for one thing _ to focus on what we want to do for the rest of
our lives,'' Ms. Brooks said. ``We're not killing each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Gray agreed: ``Everyone here is like you,'' she said.
``Smart, talented, into something.''
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, the participants seemed united in celebrating
their achievements, and they delighted in defying what they said
were stereotypes about young blacks.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``I enjoy being with my peers who are exactly like me _
successes,'' said Kia Marie Cook, 17, of Milwaukee, who was at
ACT-SO for the fourth straight year and had entered the sculpture
and the original essay competitions.
</P>
<P>
   Her entries reflected the strong opinions about American history
and race relations that many of the students expressed in entries
across a wide range of forms. Her sculpture, of painted clay and
acrylic, was of a woman's head on a distorted American flag _
distorted, she said, like the American dream, which has become the
empty chase of ``money, fame, riches.''
</P>
<P>
   Her essay, meanwhile, was about school violence. ``It's been
going on for years,'' Ms. Cook said. ``Once it started happening to
the suburban towns, it became a problem,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, many of the entries, in categories like biology and
computer science, were more technical than political.
</P>
<P>
   And this year there was a new category, entrepreneurship,
initiated, perhaps unsurprisingly, by the New York chapter.
Contestants had to come up with a business concept and a financial
and marketing plan. The ideas included a new magazine for black
families, a drive-through coffee shop, and a dance school in
Guyana.
</P>
<P>
   The idea was born, said Anton Tomlinson, the chairman of New
York City's ACT-SO chapter, from the queries of the event's
sponsors, businesses that wondered whether the young people would
go on to help their companies grow.
</P>
<P>
   The idea, Tomlinson said, is to teach students to build their
own communities. ``Don't just wait for someone else to do it,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
