<SLUG> BC-GLF-SENIOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EICHELBERGER HOLDS ON FOR U.S. SENIOR TITLE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By MICHAEL ARKUSH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST DES MOINES, Iowa _ On an afternoon dominated by two
surprise contenders, one slipped and the other surged. Dave
Eichelberger, and not Ed Dougherty, claimed the biggest golf
tournament of his life, the U.S. Senior Open.
</P>
<P>
   Dougherty had been the leader for the first three rounds at Des
Moines Golf and Country Club, and still had a share of the top spot
with five holes to go. But Dougherty's double bogey on the 14th,
coupled with Eichelberger's birdie moments later at No. 15, his
seventh of the day, essentially handed the championship to a player
whom nobody expected to win. Perhaps, even Eichelberger himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``After I finished, I was kind of in a state of shock there for
a few minutes and started to shake a little bit,'' said
Eichelberger, 55, who earned $315,000. ``But I recovered after a
while. I have been trying to get my name on a USGA trophy for 30
years now, and it feels good to have finally done it.''
</P>
<P>
   Eichelberger, who briefly held the lead earlier in the day after
beginning one-shot out, fell behind and then tied Dougherty with a
3-foot birdie putt at the 12th hole. After the birdie at 15 that
suddenly gave him a three-shot advantage, he played pretty
conservatively. He recorded only one bogey on the back nine for a
magnificent final-round 68 and a 7-under-par 281.
</P>
<P>
   It was then up to Dougherty to rebound from his first miscue of
the day, but it didn't happen. Dougherty, who is relatively unsung
and had been a huge crowd favorite here, was done.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is discouraging in the sense that I didn't accomplish the
win,'' said Dougherty, who shot a final-round 72 to finish in
second place, three strokes behind Eichelberger. ``But I honestly
don't feel that I blew this tournament. I hit a lot of quality
shots. Dave Eichelberger is the man who won this tournament. He
went out and shot a phenomenal round of golf. I just wasn't good
enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither, for that matter, was the defending champion, Hale
Irwin. He, like Eichelberger, was one-stroke back entering the
final round and could only manage a 73, finishing in a tie for
third, five strokes back. ``The game just wasn't there,'' said
Irwin, who missed good birdie opportunities at Nos. 6, 8 and 9.
``It wasn't there all week. Of all the times to have the putting go
south, this was not one of the days. My concentration and focus was
just not sharp.''
</P>
<P>
   It was quite a contrast to his impressive victory at the Ford
Senior Players Championship, two weeks earlier. ``I think I feasted
a couple of weeks ago,'' Irwin said. ``Now after eating the feast,
I have got to clean the dishes.
</P>
<P>
   Gil Morgan, Irwin's main rival the last two years, was also
within range for much of the day, but his putting game failed at
crucial times. He could never get closer than two shots down on the
back nine. ``There's just not really much to say,'' said Morgan,
still without a victory in 1999. ``I don't know what the problem
was, but when I needed it, it wasn't there.
</P>
<P>
   It was certainly there for Eichelberger, who won only four times
on the PGA Tour. His senior career hasn't exactly been spectacular.
In 1995, for instance, he recorded 11 Top-10 finishes, good enough
for 16th on the money list. So even though his performances had
been pretty mediocre so far this year, his emergence at such a
pivotal moment is not a complete shock.
</P>
<P>
   ``That has kind of been the gist of my career for 35 years, said
Eichelberger. ``Three weeks of great play followed by a couple of
years of mediocrity. Fortunately, the good weeks have been good
enough to kind of keep me in there.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though Dougherty lost, he will leave town with wonderful
memories of the galleries, which gave one standing ovation after
another.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody got inspired by the crowd,'' said Dougherty. ``This
crowd brought out the best.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
