<SLUG> BC-WOODSTOCK-VETERAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO NOSTALGIA, BUT AN ECHO OF OLD DRUMS
</HEADLINE>
   (With WOODSTOCK-30TH) 
(js) 
 By AARON DONOVAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Of the hundreds of musicians who will perform at Woodstock '99,
only one is a veteran of Woodstock '69.
</P>
<P>
   Mickey Hart, 55, a drummer for a quarter-century with the
Grateful Dead, is scheduled to lead his band, Mickey Hart Planet
Drum, at this year's concert.
</P>
<P>
   He says no one could ever re-create the original concert, but
feels that is no reason not to play Woodstock for a third time.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never can re-create an event exactly,'' Hart said in an
interview over the weekend. ``You can't do it. They shouldn't come
with that expectation. They should come with an expectation of
making it an event of their own. They should come with an open
heart, and an open mind, and just be.''
</P>
<P>
   As Hart looked back fondly on the original Woodstock, he said
this year's concert would be fundamentally different from the
original _ but he implied that the difference is not a bad thing.
</P>
<P>
   He said that his band should not be viewed as a nostalgia act.
``We've done that, been there. This is so much more exciting than
with the Grateful Dead. It's new. The Grateful Dead was for that
generation. It was perfect for them, but it would be out of place
now.''
</P>
<P>
   At the original Woodstock, he said, he was awed by the size of
the event and the number of famous musicians. This time, after
years of playing with the Dead, he's accustomed to playing for big
crowds.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can find magic in a lot of places,'' he said, ``but you
can't get it if you repeat it over and over again. Perfection
doesn't equal magic. The young kids just think if they keep playing
the right notes everything will be all right; but it's not the
right notes that matter. It's the magic, stupid.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
