<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BELGIAN-FEST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL CAPITAL CELEBRATES BELGIUM 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By GLENN COLLINS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   COOPERSTOWN, N.Y. _ To the uninitiated, it may seem exceedingly
odd _ daft, perhaps? _ to honor the tiny, distant nation of Belgium
at the epicenter of the great American pastime during the high
season of baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, in the first Belgium Comes to Cooperstown
festival, a two-day effusion of Belgianophilia that ended Sunday
with a beer tasting, the Belgian Tourist Office sponsored a
celebration of its nation's culture and way of life. It drew nearly
a thousand tourists, Belgium worshipers and beer lovers.
</P>
<P>
   The turnout was even more surprising since this
baseball-worshiping village that was once home base for James
Fenimore Cooper has barely recovered from a string of excitements:
the overnight ``listening tour'' invasion by Hillary Rodham Clinton
last week; the 100th anniversary bash for the town's scholarly
ornament, the New York State Historical Association, on Friday; and
the 60th anniversary celebration of Cooperstown's renowned National
Baseball Hall of Fame and Museum on June 12.
</P>
<P>
   Festivalgoers swarmed to a Belgian be-in that was a restaging of
the 450-year-old Ommegang Festival in Brussels. There was a Belgian
procession, complete with mock 16th-century costumes provided by
the Belgian government. There were Belgian sausages (flavored, of
course, with Belgian beer) and Belgian chocolates.
</P>
<P>
   Revelers waited in long lines for Belgian brews and Belgian
Liege-style waffles. There were traditional Belgian puppets,
Belgian lace trimmings and even a raffle of limited-edition comic
books featuring that Belgian icon, Tintin.
</P>
<P>
   But, Belgium?
</P>
<P>
   ``The Belgian connection makes perfect sense,'' said Elinor
Vincent, chairman of Cooperstown's weekly newspaper, The Freeman's
Journal, founded in 1808. ``A Venezuelan festival wouldn't work,
but here, as in Belgium, we are rural, and we still have a viable
farming community, as Belgium does. And Cooperstown was once the
hops capital of America.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, in the 19th century, Cooperstown village was called Hops
City, after the plant that is used to preserve and flavor beer.
</P>
<P>
   ``About 80 percent of the American hop crop was grown in this
area through the 1860s, 1870s and 1880s,'' said Dr. Gilbert
Vincent, president of the Farmers' Museum, a mile north of town
center.
</P>
<P>
   Frederique Raeymaekers of the Belgian Tourist Office noted that
the modest nation of 10 million people by the North Sea, in an area
scarcely larger than New Jersey, has been enjoying extraordinary
American visibility of late. Belgian beers, brewed for sipping with
food, have quadrupled their sales in the United States in the last
decade.
</P>
<P>
   The United States now imports $35.3 million worth of chocolate
from Belgium annually, more than from any other country, according
to the latest Customs Service statistics. In New York City, there
has been an explosion of shops that offer Belgian-style
double-fried potatoes. And no fewer than five eateries now inhabit
a new restaurant district in Manhattan known as Little Belgium,
centering on 14th Street and Ninth Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   These days, the Cooperstown region is hardly Little Belgium, but
it does boast Brewery Ommegang, a one-and-a-half-year-old maker of
Belgian-style beers that is the first and only U.S. joint venture
of three Belgian beer makers and American microbrewers.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Idelson, director of communications for the Baseball Hall
of Fame, said with a laugh that ``we do not feel any competition
with Belgium,'' noting that attendance at the Baseball Hall of Fame
was up 24 percent in the first six months of 1999, on pace to far
exceed last year's total of 331,284. ``There are no Belgian Hall of
Famers, but the brewery is definitely Hall of Fame material,'' he
said collegially.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
