<HEADER>
A6265 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  PM-BUDGET-NYT     07-11 1928
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 PM-BUDGET-NYT 
 (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For MONDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Monday, July 12.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ASIA-RECOVERY _ Just two years after it began, the financial
crisis that started in Asia and spread pain around the world
appears to be over _ leaving many to wonder if the symptoms have
abated before the disease could be treated. By David E. Sanger and
Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   CONGO-ASSESS (Lusaka, Zambia) _ While its authors pitched it as
a triumph , Saturday night's signing of a cease-fire deal to end
the war in Congo had something of a rising air of fiasco about it.
By Donald G. McNeil Jr.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Locator map has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   YUGOSLAVIA-U.S. (Washington) _ How the Clinton administration is
trying to undermine the Milosevic regime in Belgrade, and why it is
so difficult to promote opposition from outside. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ALASKA-GATHERERS (Kwethluk, Alaska) _ To a remarkable degree,
thousands of native people still live off the land here in the
Alaskan tundra, taking 90 percent or more of what they eat every
year from the great back country, the rivers and the Bering Sea.
But 40 years after Alaska became a state, 20 years after land-claim
disputes in the oil rush led Congress to give the people known as
``subsistence gatherers'' priority rights to fish and game, and 10
years after the state's highest court declared that protection
unconstitutional because such natural bounty was for the ``common
use'' of all Alaskans, the debate has reached a bitter crisis
point. By Sam Howe Verhovek.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos [NYT14,15,16) have been sent to NYT photo
clients. Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   DEER-TICK-SUMMER _ While deer tick populations are notoriously
spotty and difficult to generalize about, it has been a
particularly heavy season in some parts of the region.
Notwithstanding the introduction this year of a new vaccine, the
experts say that Lyme disease, which sickens some 7,000 to 10,000
people each year in New York, New Jersey and Connecticut and a few
thousand more in the rest of the country, is here to stay. So are
the ticks. By Andy Newman.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT17) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   PRISON-MENTAL-ILLNESS _ The first comprehensive study of the
rapidly growing number of emotionally disturbed people in the
nation's jails and prisons has found that there are 283,800 inmates
with severe mental illness, about 16 percent of the total jail
population. The report confirms the belief of many state, local and
federal experts that jails and prisons have become the nation's new
mental hospitals. By Fox Butterfield.
</P>
<P>
   WOODSTOCK-30TH (Rome, N.Y.) _ If there ever was a symbol of what
Woodstock is not, the hulking gray B-52 bomber casting shadows over
Chestnut Street is it. B-52s, after all, were raining bombs on
North Vietnam about the time in August 1969 that Country Joe
McDonald was leading hundreds of thousands of people in a
sing-along anti-war anthem of ``One, two, three, what are we
fighting for?'' Yet the B-52 on Chestnut Street is about to become
part of rock 'n' roll history: it will be the first thing that the
latest Woodstock generation sees when the legendary concert's third
coming begins on July 23 at Griffiss Air Force Base. By Paul
Zielbauer.
</P>
<P>
   GM-LIABILITY (Los Angeles) _ The huge jury verdict against G.M.
is likely be reduced significantly, but documents emerging from
that case and others elsewhere in recent years do not bode well for
GM. There are dozens of suits around the country, and lawyers
lining up to get hold of documents that could significantly hurt
the company's standing in those cases. By Andrew Pollack.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-HATE-ARRESTS (San Francisco) _ Two brothers arrested in
California charged with murdering a gay couple may now be linked to
synagogue burnings in California. And authorities are checking to
see if they are linked to other hate groups, particularly the one
in the Midwest whose membership included the Illinois man who went
on a racially-motivated killing spree last week. By Evelyn Nieves.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-CASH-GLUT _ Beyond the presidential candidates, the
coming election season is awash in cash, with congressional
candidates taking advantage of a strong economy to raise huge
amounts. By Adam Clymer.
</P>
<P>
   HMO-LOBBY _ With the Senate set to begin a weeklong debate on
HMOs on Monday, we examine the industry's lobbying campaign, aimed
mainly at slowing down the drive for a ``patients' bill of
rights.'' By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT10) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
