   &UR; CULTURE (Moved in ``e'' category) &QL; 
 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   KANSASCITY-MUSEUM _ The Nelson-Atkins Museum of Art in Kansas
City, Mo., has selected Steven Holl, the New York architect, winner
of the competition to design the museum's first expansion since its
opening in 1933. By Julie V. Iovine.
</P>
<P>
   SUMMER-BOOK-SURPRISE _ Hannibal Lecter and Harry Potter are
shaping up as the summer's must reads. Harry who? Hannibal the
cannibal is the title character of Thomas Harris' grisly new novel
who has appeared in two previous novels and two movies. But riding
broomstick high, right behind the ghoulish Dr. Lecter, is Harry
Potter, an orphan wizard with unruly hair and a lightning scar on
his forehead. This unusually adept pupil at Hogwarts School for
Witchcraft and Wizardry is the hero of two wildly successful
British children's novels by J.R. Rowling. By Eden Ross Lipson.
</P>
<P>
   OZ-TV-VIOLENCE _ Crucifixion. Cannibalism. Slow death by eating
glass. Sexual mutilation. Is there nothing Tom Fontana won't do on
his HBO prison series, ``Oz''? ``The problem with TV violence, it's
a lie,'' said Fontana, who writes most of the show's episodes and
is one of its executive producers, along with Barry Levinson and
Jim Finnerty. ``People get shot and don't bleed. They get hit and
walk away. If you have to do it, you have to do it as horrifically
as it really is.'' And Fontana is really trying as hard as he can.
By Dinitia Smith.
</P>
<P>
   TANGLEWOOD-OZAWA (Lenox, Mass.) _ The descriptive subtitle that
Beethoven provided for the first movement of his ``Pastorale''
Symphony reads, in English translation, ``Awakening of happy
feelings upon reaching the countryside.'' Perhaps by opening the
1999 summer season of the Boston Symphony Orchestra at Tanglewood
with the ``Pastorale'' the conductor Seiji Ozawa was hoping to
engender just such happy feelings among his players and the
orchestra's administration. They have all been through a lot
lately. By Anthony Tommasini.
</P>
<P>
   PROSECUTION-BOOK-REVIEW _ Christopher Lehmann-Haupt reviews
``The Prosecution: A Legal Thriller,'' by D.W. Buffa.
</P>
