r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-ANGELS-ROCKIES-LA     07-11 0631
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ANGELS-ROCKIES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FYHRIE HAS ROCKY TIME AGAINST ROCKIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ The barbecue at the Fyhrie household must have been a
bomb.
</P>
<P>
   It was just last Tuesday that Huntington Beach native Mike
Fyhrie made his first major-league start for the Anaheim Angels in
front of about 50 friends and family at Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   Fyhrie pitched well and the Angels won that one, so surely many
of the same people gathered to watch Sunday afternoon's game
against the Colorado Rockies on TV.
</P>
<P>
   Problem was, Fyhrie was done even before the grill was warm.
Fyhrie didn't make it out of the first inning, giving up seven runs
in an 8-2 loss before 42,485 at Coors Field.
</P>
<P>
   The setback ended the Angels' winning streak at four and sent
them into the All-Star break 6{ behind Texas in the AL West. It
slowed the momentum the Angels had been building, but they said it
didn't stop it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came in here and won two in this ballpark _ we've got to be
happy with it,'' Angels manager Terry Collins said. ``The last
three weeks, outside of the Texas series, we've played very good
baseball. We came in here and said we wanted to win the series and
we won it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels have won five of their past six series, so Sunday's
loss won't have an affect on the club, first baseman Mo Vaughn
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just let it go, this didn't do anything,'' Vaughn said.
``We'll be ready to go in the second half. This team's been playing
consistent. We'll be all right.''
</P>
<P>
   Fyhrie said he was all right Sunday, even if the numbers didn't
show it. His previous performance last week against the Mariners
earned him Sunday's start. He went seven innings and gave up two
runs and six hits in the Angels' 8-2 victory.
</P>
<P>
   But on Sunday Fyrhie failed to retire any of the first five
Rockies hitters he faced. Larry Walker drove in the first run with
a single and Vinny Castilla had the big blow, a bases-clearing
three-run double that made it 4-0.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I made some quality pitches down in the strike zone,
but (home-plate umpire Jerry Meals) called them balls,'' Fyhrie
said. ``I had to raise my pitches a little and in this park, balls
up will kill you.
</P>
<P>
   Fyhrie got Todd Helton to fly out for the first out of the
inning, but Kurt Abbott followed with an RBI single. One batter
later, Rockies pitcher Bobby Jones doubled home a run to make it
6-0 and Collins had seen enough.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Schoeneweis _ the first of five Angels relievers _ entered
the game and gave up an RBI double to Jeff Barry (the run charged
to Fyhrie), and when the inning was finally over, the Angels
trailed by a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   After allowing seven runs and six hits in two-thirds of an
inning, Fyrhie's ERA rose from 2.57 to 10.56.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what to say,'' Fyhrie said. ``They hit the ball
and found holes. I'm just frustrated I didn't give the team a
chance to win. I had heard all the horror stories about pitching
here.... It's very deflating, especially when the team's on a roll.
We're making a run. We had a chance to sweep.''
</P>
<P>
   None of the hits Fyhrie allowed left the park. In fact, there
were no home runs in the game for either team, only the second
homerless game this season. It was the 22nd homerless game in Coors
Field's 6{-year history.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their early deficit, the Angels were playing in a place
where seven-run deficits can disappear in a hurry. Also, the Angels
had scored nine runs in each of the first two games of the series.
</P>
<P>
   They scored two runs in the third inning on Darin Erstad's
sacrifice fly and Randy Velarde's RBI groundout, then loaded the
bases with one out in the fourth, knocking Jones out of the game.
</P>
<P>
   But the deficit didn't disappear.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
