<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RACE-VIOLENCE-2NDTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECENT VIOLENCE PROVES IT'S TIME TO REVISE STEREOTYPE OF WHITE
SUPREMACISTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICK MONTGOMERY  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hate-group watchers say educated, affluent types have long
subscribed to racist movements, including the Ku Klux Klan. In
fact, a study found that members of Idaho's ``patriot'' cause in
the late 1980s tended to have slightly higher levels of education
and incomes than white Americans as a whole.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think white supremacists have always mirrored the
demographics of the nation,'' said Devin Burghart of the Center for
New Community, which monitors hate groups in the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Ben Smith and his ilk,'' said Burghart, ``are part of a
new generation of young, articulate, self-styled, self-motivated
haters.
</P>
<P>
   ``These groups are using college campuses as fertile ground to
recruit a kind of racist intelligentsia. They've given the old,
emotional arguments a pseudo-intellectual feel.''
</P>
<P>
   Jared Taylor has emerged as one of the more scholarly champions
of the white crusade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, running around shooting people is reprehensible,''
said Taylor, a Yale University graduate and editor of the
conservative magazine American Renaissance. ``But it's not beyond
my comprehension as to what motivated this man.... Why should
whites rejoice at the prospects of their diminishing influence and
diminishing numbers in this country?''
</P>
<P>
   While branding Smith's actions as those of a ``certifiable nut
case,'' Taylor said people who share Smith's views ``live in a
country that promotes policies that will reduce their people to a
minority, and they're angry about it.'' He added: ``I suspect
there's going to be more Ben Smiths.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor stirred controversy last year with his book, The Color of
Crime, which noted that black-on-white violent crimes far exceeded
white-on-black violent crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say that such statistics overlook the fact that the vast
majority of all violent crimes are either white-on-white or
black-on-black. As for offenses classified as racial ``hate
crimes'' in 1997, the FBI reports that ``anti-white'' attacks
numbered 993 compared with 3,120 ``anti-black'' attacks. Smith's
killing spree ``doesn't surprise me at all,'' said Charles E.
Smith, president of the Kansas City, Mo., branch of the National
Association for the Advancement of Colored People. ``Racism has
nothing to do with class or formal education....
</P>
<P>
   ``You can get an education on paper but you need one of the
heart, an education of common sense and decency. It begins at home
on day one.''
</P>
<P>
   William L. Pierce earned a doctorate in physics. But that didn't
keep him from writing The Turner Diaries, a white supremacist
screed that is thought to have inspired Oklahoma City bomber
Timothy McVeigh.
</P>
<P>
   Vincent Bertollini and Carl Story amassed fortunes by building
computer-chip companies in California. And last fall, according to
news reports, they paid for the distribution of white supremacist
posters and videos to 3,000 homes in northern Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   Those who advocate racial violence may not always fall into the
traditional underclass, but in their own minds ``they still think
that they're victims,'' said Chip Berlet of Political Research
Associates.
</P>
<P>
   And, others contend, Ben Smith's rampage can serve as a lesson
to all Americans, as did the Colorado high school shootings.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no easy answers, no easy scapegoats,'' said Daniels,
author of White Lies: Race, Class, Gender and Sexuality in White
Supremacist Discourse.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all need to engage in a more open, sophisticated dialogue.
For a lot of white families, race is a taboo subject. Kids are
being told that race is no big issue, when obviously it is.
</P>
<P>
   ``And liberals who talk a big game about compassion and
diversity need to start looking at where they choose to live. So
many kids of all ethnicities live in an environment where they
rarely encounter other kinds of kids. I think you saw that in Ben
Smith's case, and you saw it in Littleton.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
