<HEADER>
A6365 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RACE-VIOLENCE-2TAKES-     07-11 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RACE-VIOLENCE-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECENT VIOLENCE PROVES IT'S TIME TO REVISE STEREOTYPE OF WHITE
SUPREMACISTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICK MONTGOMERY  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Picture a white supremacist. Some might see the stereotype that
author Jessie Daniels describes in a book on the topic: A
``beer-swilling, shotgun-toting, pickup driving, gap-toothed,
trailer dwelling, cousin-marrying'' half-wit.
</P>
<P>
   Make way for Benjamin Smith.
</P>
<P>
   The man who carried out last weekend's shooting rampage in
Illinois and Indiana was the product of affluence, quality schools
and white-collar parents in Midwest suburbia.
</P>
<P>
   Could he reflect, as some experts contend, a ``new generation''
of well-heeled hatred?
</P>
<P>
   When Smith, 21, revved up his Ford Taurus and began hunting down
members of minority groups, he defied a common portrait of white
supremacists drawn by sociologists decades ago. Here, apparently,
raged a racist driven not by ignorance or personal hardship but by
political ideology.
</P>
<P>
   Smith's upbringing, some point out, resembled that of the
hate-filled shooters at Columbine High School. In a word,
comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is disturbing when you can't distinguish these people from
the general population,'' said Idaho State University sociologist
James Aho. ``They could be your next-door neighbor.''
</P>
<P>
   As Don Black, a computer whiz who runs a white supremacist Web
site, told USA Today: ``We're not trailer-trash people with bad
teeth, or high school dropouts. We are not illiterate,
unsophisticated people.''
</P>
<P>
   Consider their recruiting tactics. On college campuses and the
Internet, groups such as the World Church of the Creator _ to which
Smith belonged _ circulate racist and anti-Semitic views with a
buffed-up, intellectual sheen, experts on hate groups say.
</P>
<P>
   One pamphlet of the World Church of the Creator shows the
group's 29-year-old leader, Matt Hale, in a dark suit and tie. The
literature uses selective statistics, biological research, IQ
scores and the quotes of Abraham Lincoln and Albert Schweitzer _
all intended to lend respectability to arguments that ``the white
race possesses more intellectual capability'' and that the
Holocaust is bunk.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities say Smith killed two persons and injured 12 in a
rampage aimed at Jews, blacks and Asians. While police chased him
in a stolen van late last Sunday, Smith killed himself.
</P>
<P>
   Smith was the son of a physician and a real estate agent in
suburban Chicago. He attended an elite public high school and then
the University of Illinois, where he studied computer science. He
left in early 1998 after being charged with attacking his
girlfriend and possessing marijuana.
</P>
<P>
   He then enrolled at Indiana University and switched his major to
criminal justice. He and Hale intended to become lawyers _ a
profession that many white supremacy groups are trying to steer
members into, according to experts.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, in an article he wrote for the World Church of the
Creator newsletter in March, said his ``racial awakening'' began in
eighth grade. That's when he ``was forced to learn about the Jewish
`Holocaust,' '' he wrote. ``The entire course was made to instill a
strong and lasting sense of white guilt....
</P>
<P>
   ``What set me into action was when I was forced to live in the
dorms'' at the University of Illinois, he continued. ``I was from a
well to do, mostly white neighborhood (with significant Jew
infestation), but now...muds were everywhere I looked. I could not
escape them.''
</P>
<P>
   The World Church of the Creator called Asians, Hispanics and
African-Americans ``muds,'' or ``mud people.''
The racial epithets and emotions are ancient. But the motivations
of hatemongers have been redefined in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1960s, sociologists relied on landmark studies by
researchers Daniel Bell and Seymour Lipset to explain the racist
and anti-Semitic viewpoints of the ``radical right.'' Most members
were found to be lacking in education and social standing.
</P>
<P>
   Experts concluded that economic distress caused racists to
``scapegoat,'' or to blame their own failures on minority groups
and alleged Jewish conspiracies.
</P>
<P>
   Today assumptions are shifting, said Leonard Zeskind, a Kansas
City, Mo., author who last year received a grant from the MacArthur
Foundation for his research into extremist groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``You take a demographic slice of white America and a
demographic slice of these extremist movements, they're going to
look very similar,'' he said. ``It's not economics that's
motivating a lot of these people, it's politics and ideology.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this post-Cold War age, what we have on our hands is an
ethic of ultranationalism worldwide,'' he said, pointing to ethnic
cleansing in Kosovo and militia activities in the United States.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
