<DOCNO> NYT19990711.0204 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-11 23:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6371 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-DODGERS-MARINERS-     07-11 0955
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-DODGERS-MARINERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS WIN IN FIGHT-MARRED GAME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Los Angeles Dodgers ended the season's first
half Sunday afternoon looking like they finally have started
something.
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of a 14-3 victory over Seattle that gave them four
consecutive victories heading into the All-Star break, the Dodgers
puffed out their sunken chests for an epic 15-minute scuffle that
had the Dodger Stadium crowd of 43,231 yelling for more.
</P>
<P>
   As the rumble rolled from the mound to second base to near the
Mariners dugout, it was the clear the teams were battling over much
more than a high-and-tight fastball by Frankie Rodriguez with two
outs in the sixth that nearly struck Mark Grudzielanek in the face.
</P>
<P>
   This was the season of frustration unfolding for two teams
expected to be better.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were fighting for a year that has never come together; they
were fighting for getting swept in the series,'' said coach Rick
Dempsey, one of seven ejected after the brawl. ``There was a lot of
energy on that field getting released.''
</P>
<P>
   And when players and coaches finished rolling around, a folk
hero came out of the dust: Trenidad Hubbard _ hitting machine,
martial artist and ... backup catcher.
</P>
<P>
   His five RBI were a career high and his emergency duty behind
the plate was his first appearance there since 1993, when he played
in the Houston Astros organization. He had never played there in
the big leagues, but starter Angel Pena injured his left forearm in
the fight and rested Todd Hundley was ejected for throwing punches
and obscene gestures at the Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   Although the fans went wild when Eric Karros followed
Grudzielanek with a shot into the left-field stands that capped a
five-run inning, they saved their best for Hubbard, who came in
from left field to put on the equipment to start the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   ``The place was really charged up after the fight,'' Hubbard
said. ``When they called me in from left field, I was like Austin
Powers. I said, `Yeah, baby.' ''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Dempsey, Hundley and Pedro Borbon were ejected
for the Dodgers. For Seattle, Jay Buhner, Jose Paniaqua, Damaso
Marte and Jose Mesa were thrown out. Because this was an
interleague game, the presidents from each league will punish their
clubs.
</P>
<P>
   More serious were the injuries. Seattle's reserve infielder
Charles Gipson suffered a separated right shoulder in the fight and
could be lost for the season. Mariners left fielder Brian Hunter
hyperextended his left knee, but is expected back after the break.
Pena bruised his left forearm and Dave Hansen needed stitches to
close a cut on his right pinky. Both are day-to-day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we'll be OK,'' said Dodgers manager Davey Johnson.
``The team is starting to play better, and that is a good sign for
the second half.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers enter the break last in the National League West, 10
games behind division leading San Francisco and one game back of
fourth-place Colorado. By winning four straight, they finished the
first half 39-47, their worst record at the break since 1987.
</P>
<P>
   The tension began Friday night, when Dodgers starter Ismael
Valdes hit two Seattle batters and Mariners right-hander Freddy
Garcia hit the leadoff hitter the next two innings.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, the Dodgers had a 6-3 lead in the fifth when things
started falling apart for the Mariners. Pena, who had a two-run
homer and RBI single in the first three innings, was on third with
one out.
</P>
<P>
   Hubbard popped to short, where Alex Rodriguez drifted over to
make a one-handed catch. But then he fell and the slow-footed Pena
scored from third. When Hubbard hit a bases-clearing double the
next inning, the scene was set.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez's first pitch sailed at the head of Grudzielanek, who
took a few steps toward the mound. Rodriguez started yelling, as
did first baseman David Segui.
</P>
<P>
   The benches emptied, but at first there was little action.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ran out there thinking Mark got hit,'' Todd Hollandsworth
said. ``It was only after I got out there that I heard he hadn't
been hit. By then all hell had broken loose.''
</P>
<P>
   The fighting often was fierce, with Segui throwing some big
punches in the middle of the pile. And no one was spared. Buhner
was tossed because players on the disabled list are not allowed to
participate in fights. Sheffield, who had the day off before
leaving for the All-Star Game in Boston, ran onto the field and was
struck in the head by Marte.
</P>
<P>
   That set off Hundley. ``I saw that and took off running,'' he
said. ``By the time I got there, guys were holding me back. Then
Marte hit me.''
</P>
<P>
   Gipson separated his shoulder trying to separate players.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was pretty intense in there,'' Hundley said. ``But when
you're on a team, you have to cover each other's backs. That Marte
really ticked me off. He was throwing sucker punches, then running
away, then coming back with more sucker punches. It was cheap and
pathetic. But we got him. I won't say who, but we got him.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Dodgers long man Jamie Arnold, who replays showed
pummeled Marte to the ground with two right-hand blows.
</P>
<P>
   Mariners manager Lou Piniella wasn't talking after the game.
Neither was Ken Griffey Jr., who broke out of 1-for-9 series slump
(seven strikeouts) with a two-run homer off Darren Dreifort (7-8)
in the third.
</P>
<P>
   ``When teams are frustrated, stuff happens,'' said starter Jeff
Fassero (4-9), who allowed six runs in three innings after throwing
eight scoreless innings against the Angels in his last start.
``Guys start yelling at each other, and something like this is
going to happen when you start doing that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
